<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros seek more than Central title
<TEXT>
<P>
   By FRAN BLINEBURY
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Now it becomes as much mental as physical.
It's not just the doing, but the believing.
</P>
<P>
   Expectation is, after all, the burden that has brought so many
contenders to their knees.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Astros have backed themselves into a corner with
three consecutive National League Central titles, we will see how
well they cope with one of the more difficult aspects of the game _
success.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, three division titles in a row raises the bar, and three
straight times of flaming out in the first round of the playoffs
brings an entirely different kind of atmosphere to spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tension,'' said Larry Dierker, the jangly, loose-jointed
manager who looks anything but tight standing behind the clubhouse
under a bright Florida sun in his new brick-red cap, white T-shirt
and a pair of baggy black shorts that are long enough to make him
look like a middle-aged NBA wannabe.
</P>
<P>
   It's mostly pitchers and catchers who will hold their first
workouts this morning, and for a short while the sound of baseballs
popping into leather gloves will have its usual therapeutic effect
after another winter's chill. But in a few days the regulars will
be here, and that's when you'll be able to feel the hum of tension
in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Not that easy
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody on our team underestimates how difficult
it is just to get into the playoffs three years in a row, what it
means to be able to go the distance, survive the ups and downs of a
season and come out on top each time,'' Dierker said. ``Maybe the
fans do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long way from April through September and there are so
many things that can go wrong, so many challenges. It's an
achievement, it really is, to have been able to get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having said that, we know it's not good enough anymore. Not
for our fans and not for us. The idea is to get into the playoffs
and then to go on, and that's where you definitely feel the raised
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   It's there, no question about it. It hangs in the air even on
the earliest days of spring training, and it is almost tangible, an
animal that stalks around the clubhouse growling its presence.
</P>
<P>
   As if losing three straight times in the playoffs weren't enough
of a burden, the Astros will be moving into a new home at Enron
Field, where everything from the tickets to parking to the hot dogs
will be more expensive. And you can be sure that added cost will
carry a price of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear the talk on the street, on the radio shows,'' Dierker
said. ``Since we're moving into a new ballpark, a lot of people
expect that there's so much more money to spend on the team. You
say you have to work within a budget, and it doesn't compute to
some. All they know is you've won before, and now you should win
more, go farther.''
</P>
<P>
   About 15 miles away from Osceola County Stadium down Highway 192
_ the schlockiest street in America _ the Atlanta Braves have their
camp at Disney's Wide World of Sports Complex and their own set of
different expectations and disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   Roll with the changes
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to say our goal as an organization is to get to where
the Braves are in the National League,'' Dierker said. ``They come
into each season with the full expectation that they should win
their division and they should get to the World Series, and they
usually do. But how many times have they won it all? Once? That's
their disappointment. Yet they come back each year and never seem
to lose their edge. They don't dwell on the past. They look ahead,
and they take care of business again.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the challenge facing the Astros, not looking back too
long at their failures in the postseason and not looking too far
ahead at another shot at October redemption. They are a different
team this season. Mike Hampton and Carl Everett are gone, and
Octavio Dotel and Roger Cedeno must show they can take their place.
Derek Bell is gone, and Moises Alou comes back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can afford to stand still and keep bringing
the same team back,'' Dierker said. ``If you do and still come up
short, you run the risk of being stagnant, and one day you find you
have to change it all. That's what happened to us in the early
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, I'd say look at the Braves. Over the years they've let
go of (Charlie) Leibrandt, (Denny) Neagle, (David) Justice, (Jeff)
Blauser, (Fred) McGriff, (Mark) Lemke and more. They identify the
guys who are the best players, keep the core and move on. It sends
a message. It says you always have to perform. It makes for a
creative tension. They expect to win. That's where we are now.''
</P>
<P>
   Full of great expectations and all of the pitfalls that come
with them.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
