<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS HOLD ON TO BEAT HEAT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Kendall Gill, his eyes wide open and his
thoughts racing, could not believe his good fortune. He had just
missed the rim completely on a heavily contested, somewhat
ill-advised layup and given the Miami Heat a chance to tie the game
with less than one minute left to play.
</P>
<P>
   But before he could get down on himself, he saw Tim Hardaway,
Miami's star point guard, driving into the lane against Stephon
Marbury. Gill, a student of basketball theft, knew a steal was
imminent. He was stunned at how easy Hardaway made it for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timmy just put the ball where I could get it,'' Gill said. ``I
don't know why the guys put the ball where I can get it or try to
even drive into me. I want to be like Deion Sanders. I don't even
want them to run offense towards me. Sometimes they do and they're
successful, but most of the time I try and make them pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill made the Heat and its exasperated coach, Pat Riley, pay
severely Friday night. The New Jersey Nets forward knocked the ball
away from Hardaway and into the hands of Kerry Kittles, who then
fed Gill for a breakaway dunk that gave the Nets a four-point lead
with 46.4 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Though three Miami timeouts followed, Gill's steal and slam
essentially ended the game, as the Nets closed out the Heat for a
91-84 victory before 16,494 appreciative fans at Continental Arena.
It was the Nets' second victory in as many meetings with the
Atlantic Division-leading Heat, and their third straight victory at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very satisfying win,'' said Nets coach Don Casey, whose
team broke a two-game losing streak to improve to 20-31. ``We held
the lead. We just hope this can become a constant.''
</P>
<P>
   As always, Riley, the former New York Knicks coach known for
putting his players through grueling practices, kept his cool on
the sidelines. But beneath his chic appearance, he was seething.
The Heat, now just one-half game ahead of the Knicks with a 31-19
record, lost to the woeful Chicago Bulls on Thursday. Four of
Miami's losses have come to the Bulls and Nets, who have just 31
victories between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night, we held Chicago to 36 percent shooting,'' Riley
said. ``Tonight, the Nets shot 38 percent and we lose. Right now,
our offense is stuck in the mud. Turnovers are the difference.
Turnovers and free throws.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat, which led by 22-12 midway through the first quarter,
but trailed, 50-41, at halftime and 70-63 heading into the fourth
quarter, committed 24 turnovers against the Nets and made just 11
of 17 free throws. Hardaway, who led Miami with 18 points, had six
turnovers, including three in the last 4 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Gill, ranked seventh in the league in steals, made five steals
to go with his 18 points and five rebounds. His defense, which
keyed the first-half surge that gave the Nets control of the game,
is a big reason Riley covets his services.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat, believing that Gill can successfully guard the Knicks'
Allan Houston in the playoffs, has tried to trade for him, but
Miami is not offering players who are enticing enough to the Nets.
Gill is in the last year of a contract that pays him $5.6 million
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Never lacking optimism, the Nets believe Friday night's victory
proves that they are indeed a playoff team, one that can beat
anyone in the Eastern Conference. The key Friday night was their
defense, which made 12 steals, and their heart, which enabled them
to overcome being outshot _ Miami hit 47 percent of its attempts _
and outrebounded dramatically (51-35).
</P>
<P>
   Instead of collapsing after building a lead, the Nets
persevered. Miami opened the fourth with a 12-2 run to go ahead by
75-72, but the Nets refused to wilt, as they had done against
Philadelphia, Atlanta, Washington, Seattle and numerous other
teams. Marbury, who played poorly throughout the first three
quarters, was huge in the fourth, hitting 5 of 6 free throws to
score nine of his 18 points. He hit two straight free throws to
give the Nets the lead for good, 82-80, then followed with a nifty
running jumper to push the lead to four with 1 minute 25 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Van Horn, who led the Nets with 19 points and 11 rebounds,
played one of his most aggressive games of the season. He attacked
the basket powerfully rather than attempting soft finger rolls, and
though many of his shots did not fall, he drew fouls and hit 7 of 9
free throws. Van Horn's sudden toughness also helped slow down
Alonzo Mourning, who until Friday night had been a Nets killer of
late. Mourning had averaged 26 points, 15 rebounds and six blocks
in his last four games against the Nets, but Friday night, with the
rookie Evan Eschmeyer and Jim McIlvaine pounding on him, he had
just 15 points, 11 rebounds and three blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a strong, quick guy,'' said Eschmeyer, who had five
points, five rebounds and a block in 12 minutes. ``You just have to
go out there and not back down. If you back down and you're scared
a little bit, he's going to kick your butt.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, the Nets did the kicking. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
