</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-WAGNER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Wagner to play it safe with elbow
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Billy Wagner was back in that spot again, the
same one he occupied in 1996 when he was told to move his
belongings to the minor-league clubhouse despite an eye-opening
performance in the big-league camp.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, Wagner was somewhat let down, especially
considering several veterans told him they thought he belonged on
the big-league club. But general manager Gerry Hunsicker's cautious
approach with prospects called for a little more minor-league
seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran pitcher Doug Drabek, who lockered near Wagner at the
time, put his hand on the young lefthander's knee and said: ``Don't
pout and don't whine. Bust your butt, and you'll be right back.''
</P>
<P>
   By midseason, Drabek looked like a prophet. Wagner joined the
Astros down the stretch in 1996, inherited the closer's role and
saved nine games, ending all thoughts of being a starter, the role
in which he flourished during his minor-league career.
</P>
<P>
   Four years and 101 saves later, Wagner was able to sit in that
same spot with a grin and an inner confidence that only comes with
a sense of belonging. The one-pitch wonder of 1996 will enter the
2000 season as the most feared closer in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to face him; I mean nobody,'' Astros catcher Tony
Eusebio said. ``Before, they knew they were going to get that
fastball, and they still could barely hit it. Now, he's got that
slider. Now, he's even tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, 28, has a tough act to follow if he intends to top his
1999 season. He was 4-1 last year with a 1.57 ERA and 39 saves,
earning him the Rolaids Fireman of the Year award in the National
League.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed runs in only seven of his 66 appearances, including
just one run after July 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are filthy numbers,'' Astros reliever Trever Miller
said. ``God gave him a gift.''
</P>
<P>
   The gift, of course, is Wagner's left arm, a lightning bolt
waiting to strike. Toward the end of last season, the electricity
in Wagner's left arm began to flicker, and it flamed out in the
final game of the Astros' Division Series loss to the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Astros manager Larry Dierker ordered Wagner to warm up in the
bullpen in anticipation of facing lefthanded slugger Ryan Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw three pitches in the bullpen, and I had to quit,''
Wagner said. ``It just didn't feel right. Who knows what would have
happened? Just holding the ball hurt. I never felt anything like
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner's strained elbow most likely would have prevented him
from pitching any more in the playoffs had the Astros advanced, and
the effects of recovery will linger into spring training. Although
Wagner will not be on a special program, he is not expected to see
as much game action as in past exhibition seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to baby him,'' Hunsicker said. ``He'll go
through the same routine as everyone else. We just may not be as
aggressive with him once the games start. We're going to keep an
eye on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner believes he needs only about five or six innings of work
this spring to be ready for opening day.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the good thing about closers,'' Hunsicker said. ``It
doesn't take them much work to get ready.''
</P>
<P>
   No one will have to force Wagner to be cautious. He realizes his
value to the team and is mindful of the fact his health is a key
ingredient to the Astros' success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've felt pretty good over the past couple days, but I'm still
going to take it real slow,'' Wagner said. ``It's something I'm
going to have to watch. I'm going to play it right. I won't overdo
it. I'm not going to be throwing two days in a row or doing
anything foolish like that. The point is to be ready by opening
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, the Astros open the season at Pittsburgh's Three
Rivers Stadium, where Wagner first noticed the pain in his elbow.
He wasn't able to close out the game, costing himself a chance at
the extra save that would have netted him 40 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   But Wagner is hardly one to fret over the one that got away. He
was too busy enjoying the best season of his career. In addition to
making the All-Star team for the first time, Wagner broke his own
major-league record for strikeouts per nine innings with 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about strikeouts until (setup man) Jay Powell
and those guys in the bullpen start talking about it,'' said
Wagner, who consistently throws 97 mph. ``When it's all said and
done, the numbers will speak for themselves, so I really don't pay
too much attention to them. To me, the real joy is just being in
the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
