<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FROGS-BOOTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATHOGENS CARRIED BY MUDDY BOOTS SUSPECTED IN
AMPHIBIAN  EXTINCTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A surprising new suspect was implicated Friday in
the hunt for what's causing global destruction of frogs,
salamanders and other amphibians: dirty boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say take only pictures and leave only footprints, but it
turns out those footprints may well be deadly,'' said Elizabeth
Davidson, a biologist at Arizona State University.
</P>
<P>
   She was part of a panel of amphibian experts Friday at the
annual meeting of the American Association for the Advancement of
Science, which continues through Tuesday in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   One waterborne virus that commonly infects amphibians can
survive out of water for at least a week, studies have shown. A
fungus may also be causing health problems for some amphibians.
</P>
<P>
   If these pathogens can travel in mud caked on boots, it's
possible that scientists and ecotourists who seek out the most
pristine places on the planet may unwittingly be hastening the
demise of rare species _ the very animals the scientists are
struggling to save.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very concerned about that,'' Davidson said.
</P>
<P>
   That's why she and other scientists have taken to washing their
shoes thoroughly in bleach after every trip into the field. The
experts are recommending that recreational hikers do the same,
particularly those encountering hard-to-reach streams and ponds. A
10 percent solution of ordinary household bleach is thought to do
the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually no place on Earth seems to be immune to amphibian
destruction, often on a scale far beyond known population swings in
nature. Dozens of species are now thought to be extinct since mass
die-offs that were first noted in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Many possible factors have been identified besides pathogens,
including DNA damage from ozone depletion, climate changes,
parasites, habitat loss and introduction of exotic predators. Most
experts now suspect the problem is caused by an interaction of
several factors, perhaps changing the host's biology to make
animals more susceptible to infection.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Blustein of Oregon State University is looking at the
possibility that some species lack a natural defense against
ultraviolet radiation, making them vulnerable where ozone is
depleted. Studies have shown sharp declines in fog cover even in
the depths of rain forests, possibly the result of global,
human-induced climate change.
</P>
<P>
   A complete answer to the puzzle seems to be a long way off.
Unfortunately, there may not be many amphibians left _ other than
perhaps the common bullfrog, which seems to thrive wherever it has
been introduced _ by the time science has the solution.
</P>
<P>
   So even if dirty boots _ and other sources of possible
contamination _ turn out to be a false alarm, scientists reason
that they have to take precautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're all scared of,'' said Marvalee Wake, the
head of the Department of Integrative Biology at the University of
California at Berkeley, who was in the audience at Friday's
session. ``It's truly a crisis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 0005EST &QL; 
