<SLUG> BC-GLF-NISSANNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWNE'S NICE WEEKEND CUT SHORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Olin Browne considers the PGA Tour's West Coast
swing to be the highlight of his season, and one can only imagine
how much more he would enjoy it if he could stick around for the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Browne, who didn't play golf until he reached Occidental College
at age 19, has had moderate success during his six full years on
the tour but missed his third consecutive cut Friday at the Nissan
Open.
</P>
<P>
   Browne birdied No. 9, his final hole of the day, to get back to
even par for the tournament but fell one shot short of the cut.
Browne, who shot a 1-under 70 on Thursday, birdied No. 1 and No. 5
but bogeyed No. 3 and nearly came apart soon after as he finished
on the front side.
</P>
<P>
   Bogeys on No. 7 and No. 8 put him at 1-over for the tournament,
and even the birdie on No. 9 could not save his week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love playing out here,'' said Browne, 40, who won the
Colonial last year and the Greater Hartford Open in 1998. ``This
course is great, and that's another reason why I'm a little steamed
at myself right now, because I could have played better.''
</P>
<P>
   Browne finished 51st on the tour's money list last year, and is
47th this year because of a strong start. He tied for 21st at the
Mercedes and tied for 34th at the Sony, both in Hawaii, and tied
for 16th at the Bob Hope Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   The next two weeks were not as kind. Browne failed to break par
in five rounds at Phoenix and Pebble Beach, and although he shot a
1-under 69 on Thursday, Browne left Southern California rather
displeased with his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the same story now for a few weeks,'' Browne said.
``Great shots, but no putter. I had that problem both days out
here, and the good shots don't mean much if you can't make the
putts.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as far as playing in Southern California, how much better
can you get?''
</P>
<P>
   Ace in the hole: Craig Stadler recorded the first hole-in-one of
the tournament when he aced the 175-yard No. 6 with a 7-iron.
</P>
<P>
   The shot likely allowed Stadler to stick around for the weekend.
The former USC All-American and 1996 Nissan champion shot a 1-over
72 in the first round. The ace put him at 3-under for the second
round, but he played the next 11 holes at par.
</P>
<P>
   On the par-4 No. 18, Stadler laid up with his second shot and
missed an eight-foot putt for par to finish at 1-under through two
rounds. Stadler displayed strong iron play throughout the second
round but became frustrated after missing birdie putts from six
feet or less on No. 9 and No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the future?: Two familiar faces made climbs at Riviera
on Friday, as Fred Couples and Corey Pavin, each two-time
tournament winners, put themselves in position for another possible
weekend run.
</P>
<P>
   Pavin, champion in 1994 and 1995 and a former star at UCLA, shot
a 6-under 65 on Friday to reach 4-under, five shots back of leaders
Bob Tway and Greg Chalmers.
</P>
<P>
   Couples, who won in 1990 and 1992, followed up Thursday's 1-over
72 with a 66 to tie him with Pavin. Pavin and Couples finished
first and second in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Riviera was not as kind to all its previous heroes. Couples,
Pavin, Stadler, Ernie Els (2-under) and Billy Mayfair (1-under)
made the cut, but Chip Beck (1988, 2-over), Mark Calcavecchia
(1989, 1-over), Nick Faldo (1997, 2-over) and Ted Schulz (1991,
3-over) all fell short, as did 1977 champion Tom Purtzer (2-over),
who will turn 50 next year.
</P>
<P>
   Movers and shankers: Brandel Chamblee matched Pavin for the
biggest move of the day by shooting a 6-under 65 after Thursday's
round of even par. Neal Lancaster, tied for third at 5-under after
the first round, missed the cut by three strokes after bogeying
Nos. 2, 5, 7, 12, 13 and 15 to finish the second round with an
8-over 79.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
