<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1866 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-ASSESS-2NDLD-WRI     02-19 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ASSESS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTENSIFIED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 ANALYSIS: BUSH'S MESSAGE HAS CHANGED AS McCAIN'S CHALLENGE HAS (CHANGES ``acerbic'' to ``combative'' in 4th graf) 
 (EDS: Second half of 4th graf rewritten; more complete quote in
11th graf; second half of graf 22 rewritten; direct quote added to
graf 27.) 
(lh) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas began his quest
for the presidency in a blaze of promises and good intentions,
carrying an emphatically articulated vision of the new image he
planned to establish for the Republican party and the new voters he
intended to woo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a uniter, not a divider,'' Bush said as he began a
nine-month trek to this critical juncture, and he repeated that
mantra each and every step of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Bush sang another melodious tune, too: that his campaign would
hit an indefatigably upbeat, positive note and lift people's
spirits, always making them proud. Party elders beamed, because
here, at long last, was a vibrant, youthful Republican presidential
candidate who could court voters across a wide range of the
political spectrum and match any Democrat in the sensitivity wars.
</P>
<P>
   But the trail took a twist here in South Carolina, a state that
has long smiled on traditional Republicans, and in the final weeks
leading up to Saturday's fiercely contested primary, Bush
frequently seemed harsh, combative and as deeply invested in the
status quo of Republican politics as his father or Bob Dole, the
party's nominees from the last three elections.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Sen. John McCain of Arizona humbled Bush with a
19-point victory in New Hampshire, Bush has been on the attack,
hammering away at McCain's record day after day, in news
conferences and radio and television commercials. And through much
of the time, McCain unleashed several blistering attacks of his
own.
</P>
<P>
   Bush simultaneously pursued a well-trod path of political
caution, announcing unequivocally that he would shore up the
conservative Republican base in South Carolina on the same day
earlier this month that he visited Bob Jones University, a
Christian school with a controversial and well-known policy
prohibiting interracial dating.
</P>
<P>
   And, over the last few days, Bush intermittently portrayed the
election here as a contest between the Republicans who favored him
and the independents and Democrats who wanted to throw a wrench
into the process by siding with McCain.
</P>
<P>
   It was a cunning method for turning out the Republican vote, but
it cast Democrats as enemies and provided a vivid reminder that
somewhere along the way, McCain had commandeered the perception of
being the Republican able to sow support in unlikely places.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, in the end, Bush's strategy will yield him a victory
here. But at what price?
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Friday, a reporter edged up to this
question, but Bush confidently dismissed any concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the beginnings of a long marathon,'' Bush said.
``We'll find out who can attract votes of independents and
Democrats in the long run,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, asked about McCain's stated desire to reinvent
the Republican party, Bush said, ``Reinvent it? I want to lead it
to victory. I want to be the person we nominate.''
</P>
<P>
   To a large extent, what happened to Bush in South Carolina was
the inevitable and unremarkable product of an extraordinarily tight
race. Like any candidate in a vigorous fight, he reached out to his
most reliable supporters, and he took on his opponent as directly
as possible.
</P>
<P>
   He and his advisers rejected the notion that their engagement of
McCain has been negative, saying that Bush simply responded to what
they viewed to as lines of argument by McCain that were unwarranted
and extreme. They cited, in particular, two television commercials
in which McCain compared Bush's trustworthiness to that of
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt compelled to defend his integrity,'' said Karen P.
Hughes, the campaign's director of communications.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Bush did not abandon the oratory he had used to date,
and he frequently touted accomplishments and ideals that were not
necessarily tailored to conservative voters' strongest interests.
</P>
<P>
   He almost never talked about the importance of improving
education without noting the particular strides that he said
Hispanic and black students in Texas had made.
</P>
<P>
   He answered every question he received about illegal
immigration, a source of intense vexation for many South
Carolinians, by reminding voters that many Mexicans streamed into
the United States simply to seek a better life for their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family values do not stop at the Rio Grande,'' he said during
perhaps a dozen question-and-answer sessions with voters here over
the last two and a half weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But that compassionate message was frequently eclipsed in the
public eye by seemingly contradictory signals that Bush might not
be willing to press his case to the point where it cost him any
votes on the right.
</P>
<P>
   It was not simply that Bush repeatedly declined to express
either approval of disapproval of the flying of the Confederate
battle flag over the South Carolina state capitol, even when Tim
Russert, interviewing him Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press,''
challenged him by saying: ``Lead!''
</P>
<P>
   It was that Bush met fresh questions about the flag with a
stern, displeased expression. And his answers seldom included pleas
for racial tolerance and healing.
</P>
<P>
   The visit to Bob Jones University fell into a similar category,
and it drew intense attention from news organizations that has yet
to let up.
</P>
<P>
   When it predictably came up at the Republican debate on Tuesday,
Bush argued that he had denounced the dating policy, making it
sound as if he had done so in his remarks at the school. In truth,
that stand was taken at a subsequent news conference miles away
from Bob Jones University, and only after a reporter questioned him
intently.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference this week, Bush answered a question about
whether his appearance at the university would hurt him in a
general election by saying that both his father, George Bush, and
Ronald Reagan had visited the school without electoral
repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Republican of the future leaned on logic and
examples from the past.
</P>
<P>
   That was also the case in some of his final appeals to
Republicans on the last day before the South Carolina primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow,'' he told an audience in Clinton this morning,
``South Carolina can send a strong message of what our party stands
for.''
</P>
<P>
   His next words boiled that position down to two core thoughts,
neither of which spoke to his initial rallying cry of compassionate
conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   ``A limited government,'' Bush promised, ``and lower taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Those pledges drew vigorous applause. Then again, they would
have elicited the same reaction 10 or 20 years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
