<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACEACHERN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMPLE THEMES OF DUTY, HONOR CARRYING MCCAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DOUG MACEACHERN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Rabbi Hesh Epstein, director of South Carolina's
larg est Jewish education program and assistant rabbi at Beth Sha
lom Synagogue, is puzzling over just what it is about this fellow,
John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Just now, you see, hundreds of members of his temple are clap
ping and cheering and foot-stomping _ under a big tent right here
in the parking lot of Beth Shalom _ in a display of almost
religious fervor curiously similar to the revivalist habits of
certain other South Carolinians.
</P>
<P>
   As we speak behind the tent, McCain has shifted into full cul
ture-meld mode inside. Bounding before this audience _ which
certainly understands stand-up, Catskills-quality comic schtick far
better than he does _ Mc Cain is laying out one-liners one after
the other. And he's killing 'em.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, we sold the movie rights to my book. My kids wanted
to know who would play me in the movie. I wanted Tom Cruise. They
wanted Danny De Vito.''
</P>
<P>
   Big roar. He's knocking them dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's giving the people exactly what they want to hear, which
is accountability,'' says Rabbi Ep stein, referring not to the
schtick, but to the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jewish community here, which is basically Democratic,
basically thinks he may be worth crossing over for.''
</P>
<P>
   So why is this so?
</P>
<P>
   In 16 years of following presi dential primaries, I have seen
rogues and rebels come roaring from nowhere to surprise their
party's Anointed Ones in this or that small-state primary. I have
seen angry, bellowing firebrands whipping up voter fury and tap
ping into this or that simmering discontent du jour.
</P>
<P>
   They've run the ideological gamut from populist conserva tives
like Pat Buchanan to liberal socialists like Jesse Jackson. But
every one of them has invariably been branded with the same iron,
bent into an ``L'' for ``Loser.'' And that is where this particular
hell-raising reformer parts com pany with all the others.
</P>
<P>
   If the Arizona senator wins Saturday here in South Carolina _
and his prospects at this moment are no worse than those of this
season's Anointed One, George W. Bush _ the chances become very
good he will be the Republican nominee for presi dent. And if he
wins the nomina tion, polls today are saying he will whip Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   So what is it about this fellow, John McCain? Wrong question.
</P>
<P>
   What has made this the most simmering-hot presidential show down
in decades is not so much about this white-haired former fighter
jock who so seriously irks so many of the leaders of his own party
and state.
</P>
<P>
   It's actually quite simple: John McCain embodies commitment to
duty and honor and all of the sometimes infuriatingly manly _ yes,
manly _ qualities of which Bill Clinton is the living antithe sis.
That is why he has super charged this contest.
</P>
<P>
   The issues? Bah. Sometimes I suspect McCain cobbled together his
campaign finance-reform package and his bottom-up tax relief plan
strictly to tick off the party hierarchy. And guess what? It
worked. They're all so mad about this busted Bush corona tion they
could spit, as South Carolinians say.
</P>
<P>
   No, the right question to ask about why this seemingly impos
sible event may occur is this: What is it about American voters
that is making them need this fellow now?
</P>
<P>
   This is a particularly difficult question for many Arizonans to
answer. We know too much about John McCain. Or think we do.
</P>
<P>
   We know intimately the squab bles between McCain and Ari zona
GOP leaders. We know about his rift with former protege Grant Woods
and about his links to the empathy-challenged likes of Fife
Symington. We know about his heavy-handed use of power and about
his temper. Oh heav ens, do we know about the tem per. We know
about the national media and about how far, far different their
cozy view of Mc Cain would be if only they knew the guy like we do.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is the rest of America does not, and never will,
care about those matters.
</P>
<P>
   Here is an illustration of how America is coming to view John
McCain and why that view actu ally may propel him toward the
presidency:
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, which holds its primary election next Tuesday, the
same day Arizona does, there is a woman in her mid-70s who came to
this country from Can ada over 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Having held onto her green card and lived as a resident alien
all those years, she has never voted for anyone in her life. But in
January, she became an Amer ican citizen at long last, and
immediately registered to vote. Guess who she's bound and deter
mined to cast the first vote of her life for?
</P>
<P>
   You go, Mom. You go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 0014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
