<DOCNO> NYT20000219.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1869 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CASENATERACE-REPUBLIC     02-19 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASENATERACE-REPUBLICAN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPBELL HOPES TO CAPITALIZE ON INDEPENDENCE IN UPHILL RACE
FOR  SENATE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARK SIMON 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has taken Tom Campbell eight years to get to this point _ a
near-lock on the Republican nomination for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   It is no accident.
</P>
<P>
   Since his first run for the Senate in 1992, Campbell has worked
hard to promote his distinct mixture of conservative and moderate
politics and to quell the antipathy of GOP conservatives, who once
actively spurned him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between 1992 and 2000, I've done a lot to try to learn about
my state, be a better representative and be in a position where I
can win,'' Campbell said in an interview with The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I preserved my moderate positions on social issues, and the
open primary creates a chance for a person like me to win the
Republican nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, he has been aided in no small degree by Democrat
Sen. Dianne Feinstein, his likely opponent in November.
</P>
<P>
   Her formidable incumbency discouraged many high-profile
Republicans from running against her _ and left Campbell facing two
lesser-known primary opponents, who trail him substantially in
money and in public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   He also stands to benefit from the open primary, which he
strongly supported three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those who think I did that for my own purposes,'' he
said. ``(But) that is not the case. It is true that I was concerned
that both parties were dominated by their more extreme wings, and
that is remedied by the open primary.''
</P>
<P>
   His quest for the Senate began eight years ago. After two terms
in the House of Representatives representing the mid-Peninsula,
Campbell sought the Republican nomination, losing the primary to TV
commentator Bruce Herschensohn by 60,176 votes _ little more than 2
percent of the total votes cast.
</P>
<P>
   In that campaign, Herschensohn and entertainer Sonny Bono cuffed
Campbell about, dismissing him as a liberal in conservative's
clothing for his support of abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   He was elected to the state Senate in 1993 and then returned to
Congress in a 1995 special election for a South Bay congressional
seat directly south of the one he won in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, he was laying the groundwork for another run for
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, he was the leading backer of the open primary
initiative, the law that now allows voters to cast ballots across
party lines in all primary elections except the presidential.
</P>
<P>
   With the open primary, Campbell said he is free to define
himself as a unifying force in the party _ a true independent with
a maverick style and a record as a fiscal conservative and social
moderate.
</P>
<P>
   He has shown his independence by voting to censure then-Speaker
Newt Gingrich, a vote that cost him in his caucus, and to impeach
President Clinton, a vote that angered many of his South Bay
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said his approach to government is philosophically
rooted in the Republican sentiment that the least government is the
best government.
</P>
<P>
   He said that is why he kicked off his campaign by calling for a
national sales tax to replace the income tax _ a sales tax that
would be levied on Internet sales.
</P>
<P>
   That's also why he has called for allowing local governments to
adopt programs in which drug addicts would be given free drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not talking about spending a dime of federal money,''
Campbell said. ``I'm talking about getting somebody into treatment
is more likely if they're coming in for treatment. Should the
federal government stop a city or a county that wants to try this?
No,'' said Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   That he is willing to talk frankly about such matters is a
measure of his independence and his political honesty, Campbell
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My record shows I do not run from difficult decisions or try
to take the easy way out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All of which put Campbell where he is today _ well ahead of two
GOP primary opponents who are casting about for a way to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego County Supervisor Bill Horn and Riverside state Sen.
Ray Haynes have made Campbell the issue in the campaign, each
arguing that he is not a true Republican, nor a true conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes said Campbell ``goes out of his way to slap the
conservatives in the party'' by taking pro-tax, pro-abortion
positions and by backing the open primary initiative that diluted
conservative influence within the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he thinks the party ought to be going in a different
direction. He certainly doesn't work with conservatives,'' Haynes
said.
</P>
<P>
   But neither Haynes nor Horn has been able to raise money to
compete with Campbell _ he has a 6-to-1 fund-raising lead over Horn
and a 10-to-1 lead over Haynes.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes recently took the extraordinary step of sending an e-mail
to 30,000 supporters, begging them to send him money. A subsequent
e-mail said his backers had responded, but not well enough.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional conservative sources of money ``are just
quiet,'' Haynes said.
</P>
<P>
   Horn, a successful rancher, put $300,000 of his own money into
his campaign, but he has spent little of it.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes said it may be that the conservative leadership is
willing to let Campbell take his shot and lose the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tired of being blamed for losing elections. Let them
lose one,'' Haynes said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Campbell has spent most of the primary
contemplating how to scale the mountainous lead Feinstein has in
public opinion polls, which show her ahead by a margin of nearly 5
to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell has just begun a statewide media advertising buy in all
of the major TV markets. The goal is to build up his name
recognition. Campaign officials are convinced that much of
Feinstein's lead is based on her wider recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can close against Sen. Feinstein substantially simply by
increasing my name identification,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   And should lightning strike and Feinstein be selected the
Democratic vice presidential nominee, Campbell would be running
against an incumbent seeking two offices at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would help because she would essentially be running for an
office in which she did not wish to serve. That would be difficult
... (and) I would be in a better position to win,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even if he fails to catch Feinstein and loses the Senate
race, Campbell's eight years of spadework leave him well positioned
for the future.
</P>
<P>
   With the dearth of GOP statewide officeholders, Campbell could
finish a losing Senate race with a statewide fund-raising base and
voter recognition that could put him in a top-tier position to
challenge Democratic Sen. Barbara Boxer when she is up for
re-election in 2004.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 0014EST &QL; 
