<HEADER>
A1871 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MILLIONAIRE-SHOW-COLU     02-19 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLIONAIRE-SHOW-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: GET-RICH SHOWS LEAVE WOMEN HOLDING THE REMOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS to ``Jeopardy!'' in 6th graf) 
 (mk) 
 By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   We already have the first winner in the Who Wants to Be a
Millionairess Contest, which was announced only last week in this
space. Readers were asked to redress the gender problem on ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire'' _ 90 percent of the contestants are
male _ by devising a female-friendly game show.
</P>
<P>
   The winner, of course, is Fox television, which triumphed in the
Nielsen ratings on Tuesday with ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire?'' The program was denounced for presenting an
offensively sexist stereotype of women, but for some reason it was
watched by more women (10 million) than men (7 million). The next
day so many women applied to be contestants that the Web site
crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, though, this show may not be for everyone. There
are probably some women in America unwilling to run off and marry a
rich man sight unseen (just as there are even some guys unwilling
to marry someone after seeing her in a bathing suit). Some women
could be especially reluctant to play if they thought their current
husbands would be watching.
</P>
<P>
   So the contest continues for another get-rich-quick game, and it
may be a good idea to learn a lesson from Fox's success. The lesson
is that the enlightened new era of complete sexual equality is not
yet here.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't been heeded by the ``Millionaire'' producers, who
have tried to be fair by giving men and women the same computerized
tests by telephone. But this equality seems to be unfair to women,
as I heard from an array of would-be contestants like Andrea Carla
Michaels.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first game show I haven't been able to get on,''
said Michaels, a San Francisco trivia buff who has been on
``Jeopardy!,'' ``Win Ben Stein's Money'' and other shows. She
phones in daily to take the ``Millionaire'' test, but she's been
stymied by the qualifying questions.
</P>
<P>
   Each question requires that four things be put in order. You may
have to arrange four European countries from west to east. Or, to
use an example encountered by Michaels, you may have to list the
following four movies in chronological order: ``Thin Red Line,''
``Green Card,'' ``Yellow Submarine' and ``Blue Velvet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seemingly nonsexist, right?'' Michaels said. ``I've seen all
of them, can name the stars, who directed them, can speak at length
about Andie McDowell's studio apartment in New York complete with a
rooftop greenhouse, or how Isabella Rossellini was with David Lynch
at the time, so why did he leave her so naked out there, etc.
</P>
<P>
   ``But tell you which came first, `Blue Velvet' or `Green Card'?
Zero idea. That is a very male way to think about a film. Women
could do fine with the straight trivia questions that are actually
on the show, but most of us can't get through the qualifying
rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Her complaint resonated with Dr. Helen Fisher, an anthropologist
at Rutgers University who surveyed male-female brain differences in
her 1999 book, ``The First Sex: The Natural Talents of Women and
How They Are Changing the World.'' The ordering question requires
what Fisher calls step thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both men and women practice step thinking, but men do more of
it,'' she said. ``They're more likely to compartmentalize, get rid
of extraneous data and proceed in a straightforward path. They make
faster decisions because they consider fewer variables. Women tend
to collect more data and assemble it into more complex patterns _
what I call web thinking. They're better at generalizing and
synthesizing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire'' could be fairer if it dispensed with the
ordering questions, especially the geographical ones, which play to
men's spatial skills. But the program, like other trivia game
shows, would still probably appeal to more men than women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Straight trivia questions seem boring to a lot of women
because they're so simple,'' said James M. Dabbs, a psychologist at
Georgia State University who has studied testosterone's role in
focusing men on simple, competitive tasks. ``Men needed to focus on
one thing when they were fighting each other for mates. They
evolved for fast, energetic, explosive action, panache, and short
lives. Women evolved for enduring relationships and the long
haul.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's marriage competition might have been gloriously moronic
and tasteless, but it was still more complex than a trivia game.
Courtship is more complicated than geography. The challenge is to
find a still more intricate game. Our researchers hope to
field-test, perhaps in the spring, a prototype that does not
require anyone to wear a bathing suit or marry a motivational
speaker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
