<SLUG> BC-AMOS </SLUG>
 -KAN  
 Founder of cookie company visits Kansas City to promote literacy  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICTORIA SIZEMORE LONG  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Wally Amos, the founder of Famous Amos
Cookies, visited students of Knotts Elementary School in Kansas
City on Friday promoting another kind of goody _ literacy.
</P>
<P>
   Amos, the national spokesman for Literacy Volunteers of America,
spoke with students and read to them early in the day, then talked
to parents Friday evening about becoming actively involved in their
children's education and activities.
</P>
<P>
   Amos read to the children from the books The Giving Tree by Shel
Silverstein, The Crayon Box That Talked by Shane DeRolf, Wilma
Unlimited: How Wilma Rudolph Became the World's Fastest Woman by
Kathleen Krull, and That's Good! That's Bad! by Margery Cuyler.
</P>
<P>
   He also talked to the students about how important they are as
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal mission has been to help build self-esteem, to let
children know how special and important they are and that anything
is possible,'' Amos said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   He said he emphasizes the same message to parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them to love themselves,'' he said. ``If a parent has
low self-esteem, that can spread to their child.''
</P>
<P>
   Amos said he also encourages parents to read to their children
every day, even if only for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, he will talk about overcoming adversity at a 1 p.m.
workshop at Unity Temple on the Country Club Plaza. The workshop is
open to the public. There is no cost, but donations will be
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Amos is widely credited for his entrepreneurial spirit and for
being a positive role model to others. He has become a popular
motivational speaker, sharing his message of self-respect and
perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   With the financial backing of friends such as Bill Cosby and
Helen Reddy, Amos started his cookie business 25 years ago on
Sunset Boulevard in Hollywood after leaving the entertainment
industry, where he was a theatrical agent.
</P>
<P>
   Finding the entertainment business a ``feast or famine''
environment, Amos opted for a more stable one. Turning a weekend
cookie-baking hobby into a business, Amos saw cookie sales hit $10
million in 10 years. But, like many small companies that experience
rapid growth, Famous Amos went through serious growing pains in the
mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   After the company changed hands several times, Amos left in
1989. He rejoined the company last year as the brand's
spokesperson, hired by Keebler, which purchased Famous Amos in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Amos will be involved in promoting events and
activities to celebrate Famous Amos Cookies' 25th anniversary as
well as continuing to promote family literacy and dropout
prevention.
</P>
<P>
   He is working with KCPT, Channel 19, to develop a show called
``Read Aloud With Wally Amos.''
</P>
<P>
   Funding for preproduction work, which will include the
development of two half-hour pilot episodes, has been provided by
the Kauffman Foundation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
