<HEADLINE>
IRRATIONAL WORLD OF THE MARKET TODAY  
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Two events this week illustrated how far
afield the stock market has wandered from real-world value.
</P>
<P>
   When Wal-Mart reported a 23 percent surge in net income for its
fiscal fourth quarter that ended Jan. 31, the company's stock
slipped more than a point Tuesday on concerns about the retailing
giant's ability to sustain such heady gains.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter that the results even surpassed analysts'
expectations. As Wall Street ruminated further on Wal-Mart's
prospects, investors continued to hammer the stock. In three
trading sessions, Wal-Mart's stock price lost nine points, or more
than 15 percent. It was a case of no good deed going unpunished.
</P>
<P>
   Could such a thing happen in a rational world? Wal-Mart is a
magnificently profitable Dow Jones industrial average blue-chipper.
It has rewritten the book on retailing and set the standard by
which all others in its industry are measured. Its outlook is good
from both domestic and international perspectives. Then, wham!
Doubts about its ability to top spectacular fourth-quarter growth
numbers translate into a mindless trashing of the company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   This unfortunate turn of fortune for Wal-Mart was especially
scary given what was happening in the loss-ridden New Economy
high-tech Wonderland of dot-com mania. The technology-laden Nasdaq
was going its merry way to a another record high in Thursday's
trading.
</P>
<P>
   In the Old Economy, meanwhile, Wal-Mart was just one instance of
bad things happening to good companies. Thursday's close saw the
Dow Jones industrial average at 10,515. This meant the venerable
indicator remained in what Wall Street considers a correction mode
because it was still down more than 10 percent from its record high
of 11,723.
</P>
<P>
   The absurdity of what's occurring was underscored Thursday when
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan went to Capitol Hill to
brief Congress on the central bank's view of the economy. As
Greenspan's testimony was being aired on CNBC, the screen's
accompanying stock market indicators provided a live report on Wall
Street's reaction.
</P>
<P>
   As the Dow industrials slumped and the Nasdaq indicator pushed
higher, the message was clear: The Fed's apparent intention to keep
raising interest rates until it sees slower economic growth will
cause the real-world economy to sink under the weight of
increasingly expensive borrowed capital. As it does, real-world
companies such as Wal-Mart will be challenged to sustain the sort
of supercharged profit growth that justifies higher stock
valuation.
</P>
<P>
   The dot-com Wonderland, however, isn't burdened by any such
real-world value considerations. It doesn't depend all that heavily
on borrowed capital to sustain its money-losing operations.
Although its enterprises often chew up equity capital at a
prodigious pace, there are always enough venturesome believers to
finance money-losing expansions.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a time, no doubt, when real-world problems affect
even the dot-com phenomenon. It won't come, though, until a
Fed-induced liquidity crunch creates severe shortages of all types
of investment capital.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone interested in what happens at capital-crunch time need
only bone up on the demise of Japan's economy since 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 0023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
