<HEADLINE>
NOBEL PEACE PRIZE WINNER MAKES DEMANDS ON BEHALF OF PRISONER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY SANCHEZ  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A Nobel Peace Prize winner is voicing three
demands on behalf of American Indian prisoner Leonard Peltier:
clemency, a congressional hearing and prompt attention to his
failing health.
</P>
<P>
   Rigoberta Menchu Tum, who won the Nobel for her human-rights
work in Guatemala, had visited Peltier on Friday at the U.S.
Penitentiary in Leavenworth, Kan., where he is in his 24th year of
serving two life sentences for the murders of two FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that she felt a moral debt to Peltier, Tum spoke of links
between indigenous people in Guatemala and Peltier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't found the correct key, path or door to free him
yet, but I really believe we are going to be able to free Leonard
Peltier,'' she said in a press conference at the Bruce R. Watkins
Cultural Heritage Center.
</P>
<P>
   Tum and other human-rights advocates met with U.S. Justice
Department officials this week in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Besides pressing for executive clemency, they want medical
attention for Peltier's jaw, which has been painfully stuck open
half an inch, the long-term effect of tetanus he contracted as a
child. His food is blended so he can eat without chewing, said Gina
Chiala of the Lawrence-based Leonard Peltier Defense Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Tum's Guatemala City foundation works to fight injustices
suffered by indigenous people worldwide. Until recently, the
foundation has largely been a voice against injustices, but it had
not done many formal investigations, Tum said. That focus is
changing, she said, and Peltier's case will be one her group will
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Peltier has many supporters worldwide who believe he was
unfairly convicted in a government attempt to avenge the deaths of
the agents and deflect criticism of FBI interference in the
sovereign lands of the reservation where the murders occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice has not been served here,'' Tum said. ``What has been
served here is revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Tum expressed frustration Peltier's case has languished for more
than two decades in the United States, but she also spoke to the
necessity for patience when trying to find the truth when the
rights of indigenous people are involved.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, years after the 34-year civil war in her country
ended, a U.N. truth commission substantiated what many believed _
the CIA-backed Guatemalan Army had committed 93 percent of the
atrocities there, mostly against Mayans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 0025EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000219.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1876 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CRASH-SACRAMENTO-SFCH     02-19 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-SACRAMENTO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARGO JET IN CRASH HAD OTHER FORCED LANDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL WALLACE and LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ The Emery Worldwide Airlines cargo jet that crashed
killing three crew members in Sacramento this week had emergency
engine shutdowns twice in the past three years, according to
federal aviation safety reports.
</P>
<P>
   The reports of the aircraft's earlier mechanical problems came
to light as investigators continued to comb for clues where the
Emery DC-8 plunged to earth Wednesday near Mather Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The reports, part of the Federal Aviation Administration's
Incident Data System, show that in May 1997, the No. 1 engine of
Emery DC-8 N8079U ``flamed out'' during a night flight out of
Ontario Airport in Southern California, forcing the plane to make
an emergency landing.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was injured in the incident, but no cause was ever found
for the sudden failure.
</P>
<P>
   In another episode in February 1996, the DC-8 was flying from
Los Angeles to Montgomery, Ala., when it was forced to make an
emergency landing in Wichita, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   According to the FAA report, an engine-fire warning alarm went
off, and the crew was forced to shut down the No. 2 engine. After
discharging two fire extinguishers, the alarm continued.
</P>
<P>
   When the plane landed, the system tested normal. According to
the FAA, the fire alarm had failed a test three days before the
emergency landing.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of Wednesday night's accident is still under
investigation, and it will take months to determine precisely what
caused the DC-8 crash.
</P>
<P>
   Killed in the accident were pilot Kevin Stables, 43, of Berlin,
N.Y.; co-pilot, George Land, 35, of Placerville; and flight
engineer Russell Hicks, a 38-year-old Sparks, Nev., resident.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, investigators from the National Transportation Safety
Board, the agency conducting the probe, said they have made a
preliminary examination of the aircraft's voice recorder and are
having an exact transcript prepared in Washington, D.C..
</P>
<P>
   They also said they have taken aerial photographs that
reconstructed the path of the doomed plane, recovered a wingtip
lost when the plane clipped the awning of a two-story building
before crashing into a car lot, and determined that the tail of the
plane did not strike the ground on takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   Within moments of the accident, the possibility was raised that
the crash had been caused by a shift in the cargo inside the
aircraft, making it impossible to control.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, safety board officials said a possible cargo shift
remains a focus of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're carefully examining the wreckage, to look at any devices
used to tie the cargo down to the deck,'' said George Black of the
National Transportation Safety Board during a briefing.
</P>
<P>
   The investigator in charge, Greg Fieth, said some of the parts
have already been recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've found some bear clamps (devices used to secure cargo),
found various parts of the floor, but we haven't found the entire
deck and total number of clamps.''
</P>
<P>
   Emery's cargo-handling methods have come under considerable
criticism in the past few years. The Air Line Pilots Association,
which is engaged in contentious negotiations with the $2.4 billion
freight carrier over the association's first contract, has written
the FAA repeatedly to suggest that the company loads its aircraft
unsafely.
</P>
<P>
   Since Wednesday's crash, however, the union has declined comment
on Emery or its practices, saying making any public statements
would be inappropriate because the union is a party to the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Rocco Sacci, a spokesman for Emery in Redwood City, said the
company is prohibited from commenting on the crash or any FAA
inspections while the investigation is under way. But he
categorically denied a widely publicized statement by a former
Emery pilot, Steven Weinstein, alleging that the airline had been
grounded on numerous occasions because of problems with cargo
stowage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FAA has never, ever grounded an Emery aircraft for any
reason at any time in our 54-year history,'' Sacci said. ``We
absolutely deny his statement.''
</P>
<P>
   During Friday's briefing, Black said he was aware of the union's
allegations and the National Transportation Safety Board is looking
into them _ with a degree of skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of opinions on how things are operated,'' he
said. ``I think it's significant that that's coming from a union.
They have one set of interests, and the other parties have other
concerns. So we have to weigh all of that and validate it before we
can reach any sort of a conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   A review of the FAA's database system shows that there have been
34 serious incidents or accidents involving Emery Worldwide
Airlines aircraft in the past 12 years, but none of the previous
occurrences caused fatalities and none involved shifting cargo or
improperly secured materials aboard planes.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen of the incidents were attributed to errors by air crew
or ground personnel; four were related to other causes, and 15
resulted from mechanical failures ranging from blown tires to a
loss of hydraulic pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the mechanical problems may be tied to maintenance
practices. In one 1998 case, for example, while preparing for
takeoff from Cox International Airport in Dayton, Ohio, another
Emery DC-8's main cargo door opened for reasons that have never
been explained. Despite the problem, the aircraft took off before
FAA investigators were able to inspect the door and related
systems.
</P>
<P>
   As the plane was lifting off, the tower told the crew that their
cargo door was open. When the plane made an emergency landing, the
cargo door slammed into the fuselage and the crew had to wrestle
with the landing gear in order to control it.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the accident, Emery officials blamed the
aircraft's crew for failing to follow procedures on takeoff, while
the crew said the cargo door and its emergency light malfunctioned.
</P>
<P>
   The type of aircraft in this week's crash, the DC-8, has been
involved in relatively few accidents. A review of the safety
board's safety database shows only 10 DC-8 accidents have occurred
since 1996. Despite the small number of crashes, several have been
deadly. A total of 11 people died in two of the incidents, and four
others received minor injuries in another.
</P>
<P>
   One of the DC-8 accidents involved an Emery aircraft, but nobody
was injured in the mishap.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA's aviation incident data system shows only three
accidents in the past dozen years caused by shifting cargo in
commercial flights, but the FAA's records may be misleading.
</P>
<P>
   When a Fine Airlines DC-8 carrying cargo crashed near Miami in
1997, the safety board issued a report that severely criticized the
carrier for slipshod practices in stowing and securing cargo.
</P>
<P>
   Three flight crew members, a security guard and a motorist died
in that crash. The safety board specifically cited Fine for
allowing the aircraft to be loaded in such a way that it could not
be controlled by the crew.
</P>
<P>
   After the accident, the safety board conducted an intensive
review of Fine Air's operations and found ``problems ... in the
area of weight and balance control, to include ground handling,
weighing of cargo, security of cargo on pallets, accuracy of
individual pallet weights and condition of pallets and nets used to
restrain cargo.''
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded that its findings were ``an indication of a
systemic problem at Fine Airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 Fine Airlines DC-8 crash is not included in the FAA
incident data system.
</P>
<P>
   (This article was reported and written by Gledhill in Sacramento
and Wallace in San Francisco.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
