r a BC-URBAN-KAN &LR;      02-19 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URBAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSAL WOULD OFFER `NEW URBANISM' IN KANSAS CITY'S NORTHLAND  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFFREY SPIVAK  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The largest housing plan proposed in Kansas
City in more than a half-century was filed at City Hall this week,
offering a rare opportunity for the suburbs to replicate cozy
old-style neighborhoods like Brookside.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, encompassing roughly 2.5 square miles near Hodge Park
in the Northland, embraces features from a bygone era that are
becoming trendy again around the country: front porches, back
alleys, town squares and apartments on top of shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll make this section of the Northland a very unique place,
something Johnson County has not been able to offer,'' said Kansas
City Councilman Ed Ford, from the Northland.
</P>
<P>
   The project is called the Shoal Creek Valley, and it's being
proposed by a group affiliated with the Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-day Saints in Utah. It covers 1,700 acres from Northeast
76th to Northeast 96th streets, between Interstates 435 and 35.
</P>
<P>
   The group on Thursday filed a master plan that divides the
acreage into 10 districts, including a business park, townhouses
geared to retirees and more typical suburban-style housing around a
golf course. About a quarter of the project is devoted to old-style
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In size and scope, the project is so unusual that the group also
worked with city planners to create an entirely new zoning
classification, covering ``master planned communities.''
</P>
<P>
   If it is all built in the next 20 to 30 years, Shoal Creek
Valley could be home to 15,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   It represents the region's first large-scale attempt at
so-called ``new urbanism'' or neotraditional development, which
offers homes and shops in a close-knit village setting that
promotes walking as much as driving. The trend is aimed at
Americans who, according to a growing legion of studies, are
dissatisfied with their suburban neighborhoods' sense of community.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the church-affiliated development group is willing to take
its experiment only as far as the marketplace will accept it. If
neotraditional home-building has a hard time selling, developers
can switch to more commonplace cul-de-sac subdivisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know yet whether the market is going to say this is a
good thing,'' said Mark Staples, manager of the Shoal Creek Valley
Development Co., which is buying the land from a Mormon
Church-owned affiliate. ``We believe the demand is deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people want alleys and detached garages, this is one of the
few places to go. If they don't want it, then the plan is flexible
enough to do what's typically been done.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoal Creek Valley, generally east and south of Hodge Park, is
one of the largest blocks of land under one ownership in the
region. As such, it bedeviled Kansas City planners for years.
</P>
<P>
   As the pace of development surged throughout the Northland
during the 1990s, subdivisions surrounded and leapfrogged over the
Mormons' land. At one point, a delegation of city leaders even
visited Utah to spur some action.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the church's real estate officials were ready to
act, city planners had a master plan.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS is Kansas City's master land-use plan, adopted in 1997,
that advocates clustering homes, shops and offices close together
instead of in autonomous zones that are common in suburban areas.
One part of FOCUS' Northland Plan, for instance, calls for ``a
compact development pattern, structured around vibrant, mixed-use
centers.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was basically the inspiration for Shoal Creek Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted this to develop for a long time,'' said Vicki
Noteis, the city's planning director. ``It's a great example of the
FOCUS plan. This shows there is another way to develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can overstate the significance of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoal Creek Valley is believed to be the largest
residential-commercial project undertaken in Kansas City since J.C.
Nichols started the Country Club district, encompassing the Country
Club Plaza and Brookside, in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   The new project also is one of the largest attempts at
neotraditionalism in a major city.
</P>
<P>
   There are just 14 such developments being planned or constructed
that exceed 1,700 acres, according to the Congress for the New
Urbanism, a San Francisco group that tracks these projects. And
only two others are planned within the limits of a big city _
Orlando, Fla., and Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is an excellent project, one that really combines
the new technology of housing but goes back to the more traditional
Brooksidelike model,'' Mayor Kay Barnes said. ``I think it is going
to be a tremendous project.''
</P>
<P>
   The development group's inch-thick plan provides a map showing
the project's possibilities:
</P>
<P>
   At the far north, off the northeast corner of Hodge Park,
there's a typical suburban subdivision, complete with winding
streets. And across Shoal Creek Parkway, there are large-lot,
high-priced homes around a 200-acre golf course. These subdivisions
emulate the suburban style already built near the park.
</P>
<P>
   South of Missouri 152, though, the new development takes on its
neotraditional character.
</P>
<P>
   East of Shoal Creek Parkway, there's a district called The
Village. Streets are laid out in a grid, and developers talk about
narrower lots, homes with front porches, maybe even detached
garages with apartments on top.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood shops nearby aren't laid out in a strip but
clustered across the street from another park.
</P>
<P>
   West of Shoal Creek Parkway is where space is set aside for a
corporate center, a business park and a town square, labeled The
Commons. This is where a public library and community center could
bookend a Plazalike, low-rise shopping and office district, where
the buildings would be adjacent to the streets instead of set back
with parking lots in front.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people really want are relationships _ of usable open
space, or the possibility of their child walking to school, of
their grandfather as he gets older having the possibility of living
in their neighborhood,'' said site planner Donald Brandes Jr. of
Denver. ``This is something greater than a single-use subdivision.
We're going to connect you to a greater community.''
</P>
<P>
   The city approval process is expected to take months. After
that, the next steps are for the development group to begin putting
in some main thoroughfares and find builders willing to tackle the
old-fashioned concepts. And that's something City Manager Bob
Collins is eager to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interested to see how the building community will respond
to this,'' Collins said. ``Some of them are going to have to change
the way they build.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
