<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1884 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-NOHO-LAWSUIT-LADN     02-19 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOHO-LAWSUIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBBER CRIED OUT FOR HELP, WITNESS SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JESSE HIESTAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   North Hollywood bank robber Emil Matasareanu cried out for help
three times as he lay handcuffed, writhing in a pool of blood as
police chatted casually, a woman who witnessed the scene testified
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Dora J. Lubensky said Matasareanu's increasingly loud tirade of
curses and pleas included a demand that police ``shoot me in the
head.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Help me' three times - he was shouting more all the
time,'' Lubensky told the U.S. District Court jury, which is
considering whether police allowed Matasareanu to bleed to death
Feb. 28, 1997. ``He looked uncomfortable and kept moving and the
officer tapped him with his foot.''
</P>
<P>
   Matasareanu lay in the street for about an hour and died of 29
gunshot wounds before paramedics arrived. Lubensky, 69, said she
witnessed it all from her house, about 30 feet away, in the 11800
block of Archwood Street.
</P>
<P>
   Police have said it was too dangerous to send an ambulance for
Matasareanu out of fears that his body might be rigged with
explosives or that other robbers might be on the loose.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lubensky, 20 minutes after the hulking robber was
shot down about 10 a.m., the officers guarding him appeared relaxed
and remained that way past 10:45 a.m. when Matasareanu stopped
moving, leading Lubensky and another witness to assume he had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were walking around casually, talking to each other -
just talking and looking for shells,'' Lubensky said. ``He was
bleeding heavily and no one gave him any attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Lubensky's testimony came after Dr. Marshall Morgan, emergency
medical center director at the University of California, Los
Angeles, Medical Center, said Matasareanu could have been saved if
he had had received medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bleeding was not tremendously rapid,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Two now-retired officers and a former police chief are being
sued, along with the city, by attorney Stephen Yagman on behalf of
Matasareanu's children, Alexander, 4, and Emil Jr., 8.
</P>
<P>
   Yagman's federal civil rights suit accuses former officers James
Vojteck and John Futrell of allowing Matasareanu to bleed to death
in an act of ``street justice'' after the gunman robbed a Bank of
America on Laurel Canyon Boulevard and, with an accomplice, wounded
17 people with machine gun fire.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also seeks damages against the city and former police
Chief Daryl Gates, who is accused of encouraging such alleged
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   From her front room, Lubensky said she could see Matasareanu
fire his final burst of machine gun fire at police.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stopped shooting, fell to his knees, lowered his arms and
brought them back up again and started shooting again,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she said, he fell to his knees and raised both arms
to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   About that time, motorist William Marr, who was wounded in the
head when Matasareanu commandeered his car on Archwood Street, came
to her porch, Lubensky said, prompting her to call 911.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:07 a.m., an ambulance arrived and treated Marr, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Starting about 10:10 a.m., she stood outside her house for
almost an hour, focusing almost exclusively on the robber and his
movements to see if he was still alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was talking, moving his head and body; he was shouting
obscenities,'' followed by, ``Shoot me in the head,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lubensky said she could not hear what police said in response.
</P>
<P>
   Lubensky said she went inside her house briefly on two
occasions, each time returning to see if Matasareanu was still
moving.
</P>
<P>
   Matasareanu was officially pronounced dead at 11:10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys said they plan to call a medical expert who
will refute Morgan's conclusions that the wounds were survivable.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan testified Friday that he had no expertise to judge how
police handled the crime scene after the shootout.
</P>
<P>
   But under questioning by Futrell's attorney, Bradley Gage,
Morgan said he did not believe Futrell, who was assigned to guard
Matasareanu, did anything to cause the robber's death.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan also said he did not believe Futrell prevented others
from giving him medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   In his estimation, Morgan said it might have taken up to 45
minutes from the time paramedics were dispatched to help
Matasareanu to the time they could have brought him to a hospital.
They would probably arrive on scene within 10 minutes to begin
life-saving care, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Matasareanu had a heart condition, it was not severe
enough to be a contributing factor in his death, Morgan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
