u s BC-HKN-RANGERS-AVALANCHE     02-19 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-AVALANCHE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PODEIN'S HAT TRICK KEYS AVALANCHE'S VICTORY OVER THE RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The sagging New York Rangers needed a victory at
Madison Square Garden Friday night. Trailing by a goal after two
periods, they would probably have settled for a tie. But try as
they might, the Rangers could not find a way to beat Colorado
goalie Patrick Roy in the final period, and they wound up losing to
the Avalanche, 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   When Colorado's Shjon Podein completed his first hat trick with
just 2 minutes 37 seconds to play, he put the finishing touch on a
game that kept the Rangers sagging, if not staggering.
</P>
<P>
   With 22 games left in the regular season, the Rangers are eighth
in the Eastern Conference standings, but their hold on the final
playoff berth is slipping. Friday night's loss left them 0-3-1 in
their last four games, 1-4-1 in the six games since Brian Leetch
returned to the lineup and 3-7-2 since they won 9 of 10 games in 21
days last month.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-game experiment with Adam Graves at center, coach
John Muckler reverted to using the lines that had powered the
Rangers through a January spurt before the team sputtered this
month.
</P>
<P>
   The Czech Connection line of center Petr Nedved and wings Jan
Hlavac and Radek Dvorak remained. Graves skated at left wing with
Mike York at center and Theo Fleury at right wing. Alexandre Daigle
returned to the third line after being a healthy scratch Wednesday
night in Florida. And Tim Taylor centered the fourth line between
Eric Lacroix and Mike Knuble.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were looking for production from a line other than
the Czech line, which had scored six of the Rangers' last nine
goals before Friday night. When the Rangers were winning 9 of 10
games from Jan. 5 to Jan. 25, including a span of seven straight
victories, all four lines were scoring. Lately, they had become a
one-line team.
</P>
<P>
   Not Friday night. Through two periods, the Czech line did not
register a shot on goal. Graves, meanwhile, celebrated his return
to left wing with his first goal since Feb. 2. It came 7 minutes 28
seconds into first period.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was Graves' 18th, tying him with Nedved and York for
the team lead. It came on a deflection of a pass from York, who was
motoring down the right wing. Graves deflected the puck through the
legs of Roy.
</P>
<P>
   The lead did not last long, however. Podein scored the first of
his three goals at 10:00 of the first period. The goal snapped a
13-game scoring drought for Podein, who was able to capitalize on a
mistake by Daigle.
</P>
<P>
   Every time Daigle has been on the ice lately, it seems, the
other team has scored. Before Podein scored, Daigle skated past a
loose puck in the neutral zone and failed to set up a 2-on-1 break.
Instead, the puck went back into the Rangers' zone, and when Daigle
and John MacLean fought each other for the puck, it eventually was
gathered by Podein, whose shot from the slot beat Mike Richter on
the glove side.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury had a chance to give the Rangers the lead again at the
end of the first period. Graves hooked Peter Forsberg off the puck
at center ice on a Colorado power play, setting Fleury up for a
short-handed breakaway. When these teams met in Denver on Nov. 5,
Fleury beat Roy on a breakaway, steamrollering the goaltender in
the process.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Fleury chose to pull up just off the goal mouth.
Fleury, who is in one of the worst slumps of his career, faked Roy
by moving the puck quickly from his forehand to his backhand
repeatedly before finally trying a forehand shot. Roy stopped it
with his glove.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury ended up smashing his stick at the other end of the ice
at the end of the period in what has become his customary response
to his bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was the Avalanche that took a 2-1 lead at 10:33 of
the second period on Podein's second goal of the game and eighth
this season. The play unfolded from a strong cycle by Podein's
line.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Aaron Miller jumped to the play to retrieve a puck
along the right boards. Podein took control of the puck behind the
Rangers' net, circled clockwise to just off the right post, and let
loose a wraparound shot that deflected off Richter and into the
net.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was held in check for most of the first two periods,
Nedved did draw a hooking penalty on Chris Drury at 11:37 of the
second to set up the Rangers' tying goal. It came from Kevin
Hatcher, who wristed a shot from the top of the slot through heavy
traffic and off the right post for his fourth goal. It came at
13:34 of the period, with just three seconds left in the power
play. And it evened the score at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   But Podein's line struck again at 17:58. He and Dave Reid broke
in on Richter on a 2-on-1 with Stephane Quintal back. Reid wanted
to pass to Podein to give him a chance at a hat trick.
</P>
<P>
   But Quintal played the pass. So Reid scored on a backhander to
give Colorado a 3-2 lead. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
