r s BC-CAR-RACINGSAFETY-TEX     02-19 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-RACING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLENT WRECKS CHALLENGE RACING'S SAFETY STANDARDS
</HEADLINE>
 SAFETY-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ Texas Motor Speedway general manager Eddie Gossage
was not there the day Bobby Allison's car nearly cleared a catch
fence at the Talladega Superspeedway in May 1987. But he does have
a piece of memorabilia from that event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was working for Bobby Allison at the time, and I got his
helmet from that race in my office,'' Gossage said.
</P>
<P>
   Images of Allison's wreck returned yesterday after a wild, fiery
crash involving Geoffrey Bodine and 10 other trucks at the Daytona
International Speedway during the Daytona 250 NASCAR Craftsman
Truck Series race.
</P>
<P>
   In a wreck that was eerily similar to Allison's, Bodine suffered
several broken bones, and nine fans were injured from flying
debris. The race was delayed nearly 21/2 hours while crews repaired
a 50-foot stretch of damaged catch fence.
</P>
<P>
   Wrecks like this are not unusual at Daytona and Talladega in
Winston Cup or Busch Grand National competition, but some were
concerned because the wreck occurred near fans along the
frontstretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give credit to a couple of things,'' Gossage said.
``The fence did its job. The truck did its job, and the safety
standards in place really performed excellent. \RThe fence\S did
what it was exactly designed to do, to keep the race truck, in this
instance, on the racetrack side of the fence.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodine's truck careened off the concrete wall in the tri oval,
or frontstretch section, of the 2.5-mile banked superspeedway and
flipped several times, catching fire. The wreck damaged a 150-foot
section of Daytona's 13-foot, wire mesh catch fence, with steel
poles snapping out of the concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Four fans were treated at the infield care center and released.
Five others were transported to Halifax Medical Center, where three
were treated and released. Two spectators were undergoing surgery
last night _ one with a fractured left arm and another with a
facial laceration.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third time at a major race in less than two years
where spectators were injured. And fan safety has been on the minds
of motorsports officials since two incidents in open-wheel racing
in 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Truck circuit is scheduled to make a stop at TMS on June 9,
and the Winston Cup circuit makes its yearly stop April 2. Gossage
said he does not expect NASCAR to implement any changes to its
safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't relate this accident \Ryesterday\S to the Michigan
and Charlotte accidents,'' Gossage said. ``I think it will be
analyzed and overanalyzed, and you have to be real careful
separating what is proper and what is not proper. You need to learn
from every single accident that takes place.''
</P>
<P>
   Six spectators were killed and several were injured by flying
debris at a Championship Auto Racing Teams event in Michigan in
July 1998 and an Indy Racing League event at Lowe's Motor Speedway
in Concord, N.C. in May 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the incident at Lowe's Motor Speedway, all
Speedway Motorsports Inc. tracks, including TMS, that hosted IRL
events raised their catch fences to 20 feet with a 6-foot overhang.
But Daytona's fences were not raised because the track does not run
open-wheel events.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Allison's wreck, restrictor plates were mandated
for Winston Cup events at Daytona and Talladega. The trucks did not
have restrictor plates, like Winston Cup and Busch, but were still
reaching speeds close to 190 mph. At Texas Motor Speedway, the
trucks reached speeds near 180 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Until yesterday, no fan had been injured at a NASCAR race since
Allison's wreck, when a woman lost an eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dealing with an inherently dangerous business ...
speed,'' Gossage said. ``It is not necessarily unique that an
accident like this happened. It was a pretty horrifying accident.
But Geoff Bodine drove Winston Cup cars without restrictor plates
and is a former Daytona 500 winner. We are not talking about a guy
who has questionable experience and skill.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 0119EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000219.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1894 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CUBAN-SPY-3RDLD-WRITE     02-19 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-SPY-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRATION OFFICIAL IS CHARGED AS SPY FOR CUBAN GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS grafs 4 and 13 with Cuban response.) 
 (HLW) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A high-ranking U.S. immigration official was charged in
federal court on Friday with spying for the Cuban government, after
federal officials say he was caught in an elaborate sting passing
on what he thought was classified information about a Cuban's plan
to defect to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Mariano M. Faget, (pronounced fah-HAY) who was born in
Havana and left Cuba in his teens, is a senior official in the
Miami field office of the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
Faget, who is 54, was arrested here late Thursday. The immigration
service and the Federal Bureau of Investigation say they caught him
last week passing along to an otherwise unidentified ``Cuban-born
New York businessman'' false information they had fed him about a
Cuban intelligence agent's plan to defect to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Faget was charged with violations of the Espionage Act and lying
to federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban Interests Section in Washington, in a statement,
denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Private individuals have been convicted of spying for Cuba, but
federal officials said they knew of no prior instance of an arrest
of American government official.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here for 24 years,'' said Terry Nelson, an FBI
spokesman, ``and I can't recall ever arresting a government
official _ especially an official with such access to immigrant
records.''
</P>
<P>
   As section chief for adjudications and the third-ranking officer
in the Miami office, Faget had access to classified files and the
authority to treat applications for political asylum. Thus he was
in a position to tell Havana of the plans of Cuban nationals to
defect and subject them to retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is continuing and officials said they did not
know of defections Faget might have blocked. ``It's too early to
tell if he did any damage, or what kind of damage he did,'' said
Carlos Zaldivar, a lawyer in the Miami office of the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Faget, who was scheduled to retire in March, made a telephone
call, recorded by the FBI, on Feb. 14 to the New York businessman,
then visiting Beijing. In the call, Faget said he had nothing new
to report about the Cuban spy.
</P>
<P>
   In an affidavit filed with the charges against Faget, Joe
Franklin, a agent for the FBI in Miami, wrote: ``The businessman
concluded the call by asking Faget, `You're still not leaving until
next month, right?' Faget answered, `Until next month. Yes. We have
time.'''
</P>
<P>
   The arrest is likely to stir the pot of Cuban-American
relations, already boiling because of the custody battle over
6-year-old Elian Gonzalez, who survived his mother's drowning when
she fled Cuba with him in November. Elian's relatives here are
fighting in court for custody against the wishes of his father in
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I found out about this, I laughed,'' said Jose Basulto,
president of Brothers to the Rescue, a Cuban exile group that
supports the relatives. ``I'm sure there are many more spies out
there, hundreds, even thousands. This should really come in handy
for Elian's situation.''
</P>
<P>
   In the statement , the Cuban Interests Section called the
allega- tions ``a colossal and false slander,'' and said, ``We are
sure that it is no coincidence that these false accusa- tions are
surfacing during a critical moment for the return of little Elian
to his father.''
</P>
<P>
   The cases are unrelated and investigation of Faget began more
than a year ago, the officials said. Maria Cardona, a spokeswoman
for the immigration service, said Faget ``has never been involved
in the Elian Gonzalez case.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference here and in a court affidavit, immigration
and FBI officials and U.S. Attorney Thomas E. Scott described a
year of investigating Faget after suspicions were raised by a
routine investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, investigators say, they observed Faget meeting with a
Cuban intelligence officer for 90 minutes at Pitchers Bar at the
Miami Marriott Hotel and with a second officer for two hours in a
secluded area of the lobby of the Hilton Hotel in Miami. Faget
never disclosed the meetings to his superiors, the investigators
reported. He also was not authorized to meet the agents on
immigration service business, but the government did not report
whether the men discussed immigration matters.
</P>
<P>
   If found guilty on all the charges, he faces at least 10 years
in prison and a $250,000 fine. Faget, who is being held in the
Federal Detention Center here, could not be reached for comment,
and no one answered the phone at his home. A woman at the office of
his lawyer, Joel Kaplan, said Kaplan was unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Faget spent 34 years with the immigration service, climbing the
ranks from an entry level clerical job. In 1971, official records
show, he married Pitty Sanchez, who is also called Maria and is 52.
To all appearances, they live modestly in a white, two-story tract
house in the Amaretto subdivision in Kendall, southwest of Miami.
They bought the house in July 1998 for $134,000 and took a mortgage
of $107,000.
</P>
<P>
   Late on Friday, a green Hyundai sedan was parked in the
driveway, and The Miami Herald had not been retrieved from the
lawn. Children skating in the cul-de-sac said they often saw a man
and woman coming and going but that the couple exchanged no more
than the occasional greeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
