<HEADER>
A1896 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MUGABE-NYT &LR;      02-19 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MUGABE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A REBUKE FOR MUGABE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Feb. 19:
</P>
<P>
   When Zimbabwe achieved independence from white minority rule in
1980 in what had been Rhodesia, its newly elected leader, Robert
Mugabe, held out the promise of transforming a state that was not
only racist but brutally authoritarian. Many hoped he could make
Zimbabwe a model for what was then still an apartheid-ruled South
Africa, on its southern border. The former guerrilla leader made
progress in dismantling the legacies of racism, but he maintained
the machinery of authoritarianism that he inherited from Rhodesia's
last white leader, Ian Smith, including sweeping emergency powers.
</P>
<P>
   It has been two decades since independence, and Mugabe has long
since grown accustomed to autocratic power. He presides now over a
corrupt, sclerotic and repressive state that is rapidly driving
Zimbabwe into economic ruin. But Mugabe's disappointing dominance
of Zimbabwean politics is now under attack by his countrymen. This
week they convincingly defeated a constitutional referendum that
would have strengthened his executive powers and allowed him to
confiscate white-owned land without compensation. The vote was both
a stinging rebuke to Mugabe's leadership and a victory for
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling opposition Movement for Democratic Change is led
by trade-union activists, church leaders and domestic human rights
organizations. It cuts across racial, ethnic and class divisions.
It had abundant ammunition with which to attack Mugabe's
leadership: fuel shortages, 60 percent inflation, more than 50
percent unemployment in urban areas and pervasive corruption. His
costly military intervention in Congo is deeply unpopular.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum did not signal the demise of Mugabe's government.
It still enjoys extensive powers of patronage and coercion, as well
as a monopoly on broadcast media. But Mugabe now faces the prospect
of elections for Parliament in April in which his dominant ZANU-PF
party will probably encounter its toughest challenge since
independence. He is expected to seek a fifth five-year term as
president in 2002. He has reason to cling to power. In today's
climate of prosecutions against former heads of state, he could
face criminal liability, both at home and abroad, for abuses
committed by his security forces.
</P>
<P>
   The precipitous decline of Zimbabwe's economy and fears of
political turmoil could undermine the hard-won stability of its
closest neighbors and trading partners, notably Mozambique and
South Africa. The United States and other democracies can help by
using their influence to discourage Mugabe from manipulating the
democratic process. This week he sounded a conciliatory note and
promised to ``respect the will of the people.'' Perhaps he has
gotten the message that his countrymen have lost patience with his
autocratic rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
