<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1898 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKC-CRAWFORD-SPI &LR;      02-19 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CRAWFORD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND EMPLOYEE LINKED TO GIFT-GIVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS and TED MILLER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A second employee of Seattle businessman Barry
Henthorn's telecommunications company has been connected to an NCAA
investigation into favors and gifts provided to Michigan basketball
player Jamal Crawford, sources told the Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   The employee, Charles McLennan, who works out of Henthorn's
Innovative Communications Technologies offices on Sixth Avenue,
refused to comment when asked by the P-I about his role in
delivering a 1988 Mercedes to Crawford at Michigan late last year.
</P>
<P>
   When Crawford tried to register the car on campus, university
authorities launched an inquiry into who provided the car and
discovered Crawford's relationship with Hen-thorn. McLennan's name
surfaced this week when a source with business connections to
Henthorn told the P-I that McLennan had talked about delivering the
car, valued at about $12,000.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA is investigating Henthorn, who provided cash, jewelry
and cars to Crawford, starting when Crawford was at Rainier Beach
High School. On Thursday, the NCAA interviewed Henthorn's former
administrative assistant, Darcienne LeRoue, about three loans she
cosigned with Crawford at Hen-thorn's request.
</P>
<P>
   The loans, totaling $10,097, were used to buy a 1985 Chevy
Blazer, gold jewelry and provide cash to Crawford. LeRoue is suing
Henthorn in King County District Court contending she wasn't fully
reimbursed for the loans and that Henthorn coerced her into signing
them to conceal his identity from the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA investigation will have to consider whether the actions
of Henthorn and his employees violated Crawford's status as an
amateur or if Henthorn was acting as an agent. The NCAA also could
rule that Henthorn was acting only as a quasi-guardian for the
freshman basketball player.
</P>
<P>
   Henthorn previously told the P-I he is confident he will be
vindicated, and maintains he has no interest in becoming an agent
for Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   However, McLennan's actions, which fall outside of his duties as
an employee of ICT, further show that Henthorn employees acted in
the interest of Crawford on multiple occasions.
</P>
<P>
   When first contacted Thursday by the P-I, McLennan refused to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can ask me questions all you want. I'm not going to answer
them,'' he said. ``You're going to print what you want anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The P-I later called McLennan at the ICT offices and tried to
ask him about the delivery of the Mercedes, but he did not respond.
</P>
<P>
   McLennan, who also represents Henthorn's cellular phone service,
was known to have attended Crawford's basketball games and
practices when the player was at Rainier Beach, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   After finding out about the Mercedes, Michigan suspended
Crawford for one game and reported the car to the NCAA. The NCAA
added five games to the suspension and ordered Crawford to return
the car and repay Hen-thorn about $15,000. It then launched a new
probe in Seattle because of the P-I's discovery of the loans and
Henthorn's ``Academic Assistance Foundation,'' a non-profit
organization apparently set up to help Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford's suspension is due to expire Thursday. If the NCAA
hasn't completed its investigation by then, the university will
have to determine whether to allow him to play that night against
Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   Henthorn has repeatedly denied the foundation had begun
operation, even though the P-I obtained documents, including a
scholarship acceptance agreement, that used the foundation's name.
Henthorn called the brochure a ``mock-up'' and wouldn't comment on
the acceptance agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford has told Michigan officials that, with the permission
of his mother, he lived in Hen-thorn's Edmonds home in high school.
Before the revelations about the loans and foundation, university
officials tried to show that Henthorn was essentially Crawford's
guardian.
</P>
<P>
   Henthorn has asserted throughout that his only motivations were
to help Crawford graduate high school and attend college.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
