<HEADLINE>
LAKERS GAMER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ It should have been enough that Shaquille O'Neal
carried the Los Angeles Lakers on Friday with the usual array of
dunks, rebounds and swats. But against the scrappy, frenzied
Orlando Magic, it took another, extraordinary dimension of O'Neal's
repertoire to steal a game here.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, it took an extraordinary steal.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were down by two with 17.4 seconds to go, and a loss
looming as the Magic had possession. Then O'Neal skipped in front
of Ron Mercer's inbounds pass at midcourt, slapped the ball away
from Michael Doleac, chased it down and threw down a one-handed jam
at the other end to send the game into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   It was near pandemonium on the Laker bench, and total shock for
the Magic, who never recovered from the jolt. O'Neal scored seven
points in the extra period as the Lakers pulled out a 107-99
victory, their sixth ina row.
</P>
<P>
   How giddy was O'Neal? Enough to give himself a new nickname for
the 10th time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``My new name,'' he said, ``is `The Big Felon,' because of my
stealing ability.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was almost out of reach, and I knew that they were
going to try to throw it to Doleac. He stepped out, and I just
stepped in front of him. And luckily I got it, tapped it and ran it
down. ... It was a sweet moment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal also had 39 points, 16 rebounds, five assists, three
blocks and another impressive free-throw performance _ 9 for 13,
including 3 for 4 in the fourth quarter and a 3-point play in
overtime. (His streak is now 41 of 54 _ 75.9 percent _ over four
games.)
</P>
<P>
   But it was The Steal that saved the Lakers (40-11) on a night
when no one could stop Magic guard Darrell Armstrong (24 points)
and no one could find Kobe Bryant (season-low 11 points).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was funny,'' Bryant said of O'Neal's steal. ``I didn't
expect it _ what the hell is he doing? ... That's the first time
I've ever seen a7-footer hop in the passing lane. ...He got the
steal pretty quickly, which really caught me off-guard, then when
he was chasing the ball, like the first two steps, it looked like
he was in slow-mo.''
</P>
<P>
   On the strength of O'Neal and a rejuvenated Glen Rice (26
points), the Lakers built as much as an 11-point lead and were up
86-81 with 1:32 remaining in regulation after Robert Horry hit a
20-footer.
</P>
<P>
   But a Mercer tip-in and a Pat Garrity 3-pointer tied the game
with 45 seconds left, and the LakUfrI1e
</P>
</TEXT>
