<SLUG> BC-GLF-NISSANSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN STARTING TO FIND THE GOING A BIT SMOOTHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Casey Martin doesn't think he ever will be viewed
simply as just a member of the PGA Tour, but the spotlight has
dimmed on the Guy With the Cart.
</P>
<P>
   During Friday's second round of the Nissan Open at Riviera
Country Club, there were no photographers or television cameras
chronicling his every move as they did at January's Bob Hope
Chrysler Classic. Martin was allowed to play golf with no
distractions, and his solid, 3-under-par 68 left him only six shots
off the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attention has definitely died down, which it should,'' he
said. ``I'm not the story right now. It should be the guys who are
playing. Hopefully, I'll get in contention and get a little
attention that way. But right now, there's no reason for me to be
getting stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin was !ital!the!off! story at the start of the season. He
had had won the right to ride a cart during tour events because a
circulatory condition in his right leg _ Klippel-Trenauny-Webber
Syndrome _ makes it painful to walk. The PGA Tour appealed the
decision, and a court ruling is expected within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He has played in three events, missing the cut twice. He has
only $6,400 in earnings for his tie for 69th at the Phoenix Open in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Martin hit the ball beautifully Friday and missed only one
fairway his first hole of the day but inconsistent putting
continued to be his nemesis. He missed three birdies inside 10 feet
and two attempts for par inside eight feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been hitting a lot of good shots,'' he said. ``I'm just
not making a lot of putts ... I haven't been this year.''
</P>
<P>
   But things are looking up, on and off the course. Martin is
expected to join Terry Jastro's staff of Jack Nicklaus Productions,
which produces events like the Wendy's Three-Tour Challenge, Diners
Club Matches and Shell's Wonderful World of Golf.
</P>
<P>
   He also made his share of putts Friday, with birdies from four
feet on the fifth hole, eight feet on nine, five feet on No. 13 and
a curling, downhill 15-footer on the 451-yard 18th.
</P>
<P>
   Martin even showed his impressive length off the tee by driving
just off the green on the 315-yard 10th hole. He chipped to within
two feet and made it for birdie.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is feeling more refreshed after deciding to skip last
week's event in San Diego and is more confident in his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better now, a little bit,'' he said. ``I needed a
break. I'm playing the next two weeks (Tucson and Doral), and that
would have been six in a row, and that's not reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither was the earlier media spotlight, he said, despite
expecting the worst and getting it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is getting out here and getting adjusted to that,''
he said. ``I knew it and I was prepared for it, so it wasn't a
shock. If my life had to be like that every day like down in Palm
Springs, that would be tough. I couldn't keep playing with as much
attention as I had the first couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never going to be totally where I'm looked at as a normal
guy, but hopefully more so I can just get out here and play well
... feel like I'm capable. I think the cart thing will fade a
little bit, but not totally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm prepared for it to never totally go away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
