<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-SHARKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS SETTLE FOR TIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Mighty Ducks insist it's too early
to label any game a must-win, but Friday's game against the San
Jose Sharks was as close as it gets at this point of the season.
</P>
<P>
   So what do the Ducks do? They play one of their most
unsatisfying ties in years, blowing two leads and settling for a
4-4 tie before 16,868 at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Ruslan Salei nearly became the unlikely hero when he scored at
12:16 of the third period to give the Ducks a 4-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Anaheim, desperately trying to stay close in the Western
Conference playoff race, couldn't hold that lead as San Jose tied
the game with 2:22 left when Niklas Sundstrom knocked in a rebound
that Ducks goalie Guy Hebert couldn't control.
</P>
<P>
   A victory had seemed certain when the Ducks took a 3-1 lead into
the third period against a Sharks team that was 0-18-1 when
trailing after 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But things suddenly got silent at the Pond when Tony Granato set
up young defenseman Scott Hannan for his first NHL goal at 2:28 of
the period to cut the Ducks' lead to 3-2. There was more silence at
5:16 when Vincent Damphousse, from behind the goal line, banked a
shot off Hebert's pads to tie the game 3-3. The goal was
Damphousse's first in 24 games.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose came into the game with a 6-12-3-5 record in its last
21 games and the the Ducks seemed to smell blood from the
beginning, even though it took them over 26 minutes to break
through.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim had five power plays and outshoot the Sharks 14-2 in the
first period, but they had nothing to show for it until Matt Cullen
scored on an inside-out move at 6:08 to give the Ducks a 1-0 lead
on their 19th shot of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Cullen was knocked down at the San Jose blue line but swept the
puck to Ted Donato, who got it to Kip Miller. Miller then set
Cullen up with a mini-breakaway and the Anaheim center scored his
career-high 12th goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks made it 2-0 on their 21st shot, just nine seconds
after Ronnie Stern took San Jose's sixth minor penalty of the game.
Oleg Tverdovsky made a perfect shot-pass and Teemu Selanne,
positioned at the left post, tipped home his 24th goal of the year
at 6:38.
</P>
<P>
   The goal extended Selanne's point-scoring streak to 13 games and
it marked the 10th consecutive game that the Ducks have scored on
the power play, one short of the franchise record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
