<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS QUICK TO STAND UP FOR RODMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Mavericks knew the Dennis Rodman questions were
forthcoming, so they braced themselves accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Mavericks won 10 times in their previous 13 games
before Rodman arrived on the scene. Yes, the Mavericks are 0-2 with
Rodman in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Mavericks beat up the Detroit Pistons _ 106-97
without a suspended Rodman _ the questions were bound to pop up and
hit them with the same impact as a Rodman headbutt.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over, as if it was rehearsed, the Mavericks players
repeatedly said they're a much better team with Rodman on the
court. Over and over, they defended owner Mark Cuban's decision to
give The Worm one last turn in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   And they all say it's just going to take some time before Rodman
become the smooth operator he is expected to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to integrate a guy into a team, and after two games
decide that he's hurt our team,'' guard Steve Nash said. ``I think
that's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis eventually is going to be very good for us. It's just a
situation where it's a coincidence \Rthat the Mavericks are winning
without Rodman\S, and nothing should be made more of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Cedric Ceballos said he saw some situations during the
Pistons' game where Rodman would have been a factor on the boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got some key rebounds when they got offensive rebounds,
and he probably would have taken care of that,'' Ceballos said.
``But he's here to help us out, and he's definitely going to help
us out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We scrambled and did some things to help us win the
\RDetroit\S ballgame, and scored in the fourth quarter. It was the
same situation in those other two games; we just didn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard Erick Strickland said he expected the question of the team
being better off without Rodman to crop up as soon as the Mavericks
beat the Pistons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of figured that probably was going to happen,''
Strickland said. ``But we can't worry about that. We just have to
go out and try to win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman was at practice yesterday after serving a one-game
suspension for not leaving the court in a timely fashion after he
was kicked out of Tuesday's game against Milwaukee. And he was
talking about talk show host Jay Leno, who is keeping a tab on how
many days it takes before Rodman has an ``incident'' on or off the
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jay is a very good friend,'' Rodman said. ``He's always tried
to keep me out there. Just the other day he called me and asked me
to come on the show. So I might go on his show next week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jay Leno Show'' is taped Monday through Friday. Monday the
Mavericks are scheduled to play in Indiana and arrive home early
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday the Mavericks are scheduled to practice for Thursday's
game against Utah, and they also have a home game a week from today
against Denver. So, if Rodman plans to travel to California, next
week, that might be a tricky proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the Mavericks knew what they were getting when they
signed the power forward/actor/wrestler/promoter, didn't they?
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what he brought to our team,'' All-Star guard Michael
Finley said. ``Without him \R against Detroit\S everybody had to
take it up a notch _ from rebounding, to outscraping them and doing
all of the little things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We played over 40 games without him, and it's tough for any
player who didn't play for a year,'' forward Dirk Nowitzki said.
``He just has to learn our system and learn our games, how we
shoot, when we shoot, where we shoot and where the rebounds go. I
think if he does that he'll fit in great.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
