<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS MISS CHANCE TO HURT COYOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ For most of this season, the Stars chased the Phoenix
Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   They trailed them by this much or that much in the Pacific
Division until finally catching them before the All-Star break,
starting to pull away after it, and then had a chance to really
take control with a victory last night.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't, losing 4-3 instead. Instead of jumping to a
six-point lead , the Stars' advantage in the division dwindled to
two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would've been a real shot to them,'' Stars center
Mike Modano said. ``But again we always find a way to make it
interesting coming down the stretch. It's going to be one of those
fights to the bitter end to try to salvage points and stay right
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The frustrating part was the Stars had them. The Coyotes were on
the ropes after Modano scored the game-tying goal at 9:52 of the
third period. His was the third goal, which had ensured them
victory in 43 consecutive games until last night.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes winger Dallas Drake made sureit didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Drake unleashed a quick shot that slipped between Ed Belfour's
elbow and stomach with 2:55 remaining in the game. Belfour allowed
four goals on 20 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it wasn't one of my better performances,'' said
Belfour, who hasn't had too many bad ones this season. ``We just
broke down a little defensively. I didn't come up with the saves I
normally do. I put pressure on myself to make those saves, and I
didn't make them tonight. So I guess I'll have to take the blame
for this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, a little of the blame should also go to the rest of the
defense. Not even the return of captain Derian Hatcher could save
them.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher said he felt slow in his first game back after being
sidelined for nine weeks with a lacerated calf muscle. When asked
what the hardest part was after being gone so long, though, Hatcher
didn't hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said they deserved a better fate. He
figured the Stars had three breakdowns all night and the Coyotes
got three goals out of them. The Stars allowed the Coyotes one
solid scoring chance in the third period and they capitalized on
it.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes were playing desperate. Truth be told, they were
desperate. Their 2-0 loss to the Stars right before the All-Star
break was gnawing at a lot of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came into our barn and they schooled us on how to play
defense,'' Coyotes winger Shane Doan said. ``Tonight, we came here
and knew we had to get some points.''
</P>
<P>
   Doan scored the first of his two goals at 8:26 of the first
period. Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor answered at 9:33. Drake
scored at 17:29 of the first period, but Stars rookie Roman
Lyashenko answered at 6:47 of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were then able to kill 6:32 of Coyotes' power plays,
including 1:26 of a 5-on-3. They did. But 33 seconds after the last
kill, Doan scored for a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Four times, the Coyotes took leads. Three times, the Stars tied
it.
</P>
<P>
   The final Stars goal _ that tied the game at 3-all _ was a
beauty, displaying the type of player Modano has been for the past
month. Lyashenko sent him a pass just as he was crossing the blue
line. Modano danced past Coyotes defenseman Todd Gill, zeroing in
on goalie Sean Burke, who shadowed Modano, following him to the
near post. Modano, however, simply threaded the puck inside the
other one at 9:52 of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars looked to have everything going for them except for
the one thing the Coyotes had been carrying since the All-Star
break _ fear.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes didn't really talk about it but the unspoken filled
the room before the game. They knew if didn't win, they were in
trouble in the race for first place in the Pacific and the much
more favorable seed that comes along with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's huge,'' Coyotes center Jeremy Roenick said. ``You know a
six-point deficit with only 25, 26 games left, against this team is
tough. This is going to make it rather interesting.'' nn
</P>
