<SLUG> BC-BKC-CSUN-MONTANASTATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE ROLLS TO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOZEMAN, Mont. _ Hey, how about it. A strategy that worked
perfectly. Not too soon.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to go in the paint and score. Pick up fouls. Then
go back in again. And again.
</P>
<P>
   The Cal State Northridge men's basketball team didn't fail
against Montana State on Friday night, pummeling the Bobcats 86-62
in front of 3,522 at Worthington Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a term for our guys, sometimes we go to the `E.W.O.
Offense,'which is the easy way out,'' CSUN coach Bobby Braswell
said. ``We tend to go away from being strong and aggressive
(inside) and we want to shoot a bunch of jump shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal was to come in and establish the inside game. To work
hard. To make (the Bobcats) have to defend us on the inside, and
hopefully covert some of that and put pressure on them on the other
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Northridge did that, getting a combined 38 points from forwards
Jeff Parris, who had a team-leading 17, Hewitt Rolle (12) and Andre
Larry (nine).
</P>
<P>
   Northridge broke a two-game losing streak and improved to 7-5 in
the Big Sky Conference, 15-8 overall. CSUN also doesn't have any
regular-season road games left, and it is 9-0 at home this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, physically and in the standings, we needed a win
bad,'' said Parris, who was aggressive but under control; he didn't
foul out for the first time in three games. ``All the other games
(on the losing streak) we were making stupid mistakes. In past
games, those negative things affected us.''
</P>
<P>
   Not this time. CSUN never allowed Montana State (12-14, 4-9) a
chance to breathe. The reeling Bobcats, who have lost five in a
row, suffered through their worst loss against CSUN in the series'
14-game history that spans 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter to us how many we win by,'' Braswell said.
``Our goal is that we just play well, that we play hard with a lot
of good energy. That we play together, unselfish and we play smart.
We haven't always done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Encouraging signs were everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN shot 56 percent its best percentage from the floor since a
sizzling 68 percent performance at Idaho State on Jan. 8. The
Matadors had 25 assists and only 15 turnovers, while forcing the
Bobcats into 20 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge wasn't this dominant since a 76-57 win at Sacramento
State on Jan. 27. At one point, CSUN led MSU 80-52.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, (this game) gives us confidence,'' said Rolle, who
tied for the team lead in rebounds, with six. ``Confidence to go
home and do what we have to do. We needed this.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN, already flying high with a 16-point halftime lead (42-26),
made four of its first five shots to open the second half and led
50-26 with a little over 18 minutes left. The Matadors didn't score
their 50th point in Thursday night's overtime loss at Montana until
the 5:55 mark of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Montana State helped CSUN build a big lead with awful shooting;
the Bobcats made only three of their first 14 shots and the
Matadors led 27-7 only 11 minutes into the game.
</P>
<P>
   It got worse for MSU. Junior forward Jason Lazosky, tied for the
team lead in scoring, picked up his third foul with 5:14 left in
the half. Twenty-four seconds later, Larry slammed home an
alley-oop pass from Markus Carr and Northridge led 35-15.
</P>
<P>
   Lazosky, who averages 14.6 points per game, got his fourth foul
less than a minute into the second half and finished with five
points in just 15 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
