<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS COME IN MANY FORMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You follow Tiger Woods around Riviera Country Club
for the same reason you never missed Nolan Ryan when he came to
town and you never miss Mark McGwire. And it's not to watch a
four-hit shutout or a smartly executed hit-and-run.
</P>
<P>
   You come to witness a chapter in history.
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon, at Riviera's 13th hole, Ryan's no-hitter was
broken up and McGwire's fly ball died at the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Just as his gallery, packed five-deep along the narrow yellow
ropes, sensed he was gathering momentum after an early birdie,
Woods came apart on the fourth hole of a day that had begun at the
10th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can relate to that,'' a young man beside the green said
after Woods, forced to scramble, left a chip on the fringe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad, you can relate to every bad shot they hit,'' his son
replied.
</P>
<P>
   Woods ran his chip _ an attempt to save par _ 6 feet past the
flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, Louis,'' the dad said, rapping his boy on the top of his
Yankees cap, ``when he hits a bad shot he doesn't throw his club
and roll around on the ground.'' Touche!
</P>
<P>
   Woods missed the uphill bogey putt to the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The !ital!one!off! hole we see,'' the mom of the family
groaned, ``and he gets a double bogey.''
</P>
<P>
   There would be no 59 Friday. No dramatic charge to the lead of
the Nissan Open, either. No perfect game, no home run over the
roof.
</P>
<P>
   That double-bogey 6 left Woods six strokes off the lead around
lunchtime. Later birdies on the first and eighth holes gave him a
1-under-par 70 for the day and a 4-under total of 138. He'll begin
the weekend in a tie for 24th, five strokes behind co-leaders Bob
Tway and Greg Chalmers.
</P>
<P>
   As evening fell, he was talking about all the makeable puts that
slid past the hole or lipped out, talking about trying to ``get
myself in the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, especially by the standards of a player who's
won six of his past seven tournaments, he is in the tournament.
Look at the names on top of him on the leader board.
</P>
<P>
   The top six _ Tway, Chalmers, J.P. Hayes, Jeff Freeman, Tom
Scherrer and Bradley Hughes _ have eight PGA Tour victories in
their careers; Tway accounts for seven of those. Tiger has 17.
</P>
<P>
   None of the leaders has won a tournament since Hayes in the
rain-shortened Buick Classic at Westchester Country Club in New
York in 1998. Tiger has won 10 since then.
</P>
<P>
   He might blow past them all by Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   He ought to be breathing on them right now.
</P>
<P>
   That double-bogey wrecked the day _ for Tiger and most of the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The 13th is one of Riviera's more treacherous holes because of
the gully to the left of the fairway. But that's not what got Tiger
in trouble. His iron from the tee stopped in the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   His 9-iron approach shot drifted into the gallery to the right
of the green and came to rest under somebody's backpack. He
insisted he didn't try to be too fine when he chipped to the
smallest part of the green and came up short.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a good lie at all (in the rough),'' Woods said,
``one of those lies where it could have come out soft like it did
or it could have come out jumpy and hot and go over the other side.
I just tried to play a nice little one up there, somewhere on the
green ... I definitely wasn't trying to get cute at all.''
</P>
<P>
   At less than his best, Tiger is worth watching anyway, if only
to chart the perfectly focused athlete's response to blown
opportunities. Missed birdie putts produced, variously, a putter
flip at the 12th green, an exasperated spread of the arms at the
14th, a jab at the ground at the sixth, a putter flip back over his
head at the seventh, and an indeciferable mumble at the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   After each disappointment, though, he'd stare back up the
fairway, into a space free of fans and photographers, and gather
his emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just really frustrated with the putts not going in,''
Woods said. ``The only thing getting on my nerves is the ball not
going in the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Tiger trivia: The double bogey was his first of 2000, his
worst hole since a triple bogey in November during the World Golf
Championships in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   More Tiger trivia: He !ital!won!off! that tournament in Spain.
</P>
</TEXT>
