<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS BLOWOUT DROPS SONICS FROM FOURTH TO SEVENTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ At one point this season, the Sonics seemed
offended they weren't scheduled more for national television.
</P>
<P>
   This is hardly how you change the minds of programmers.
</P>
<P>
   In one of their rare appearances on TNT this season, the Sonics
continued a trend of recent weeks: They played poorly after a big
victory, this time in a 118-85 pasting by the up-and-coming
Sacramento Kings Friday night in ARCO Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics weren't in tune to the fast-breaking Kings, lacking
enough energy and shooting touch to avoid having a two-game winning
streak severed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In front of people around the country, to come out and play
like this is a shame,'' Sonics guard Brent Barry said. ``The
upsetting thing is we talked about being the more focused team and
not having these lapses. ... To come down here and not be
competitive leaves a bad taste in your mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the national exposure, the game was important because
Seattle entered the game just a game ahead of Sacramento for the
fourth seed in the Western Conference playoff standings. The loss
dropped the Sonics to seventh in the West.
</P>
<P>
   These teams could meet in the first round of the playoffs, and
the difference between the fourth and fifth seeds could come down
to which team wins the season series.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento has beaten Seattle twice this season. The teams have
two games remaining on the schedule, one each at home, and the
Sonics need to win both games to make tie-breaker rules relevant.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem Friday was containing Sacramento's 3-point
shooters. Another issue for the Sonics was matching the Kings'
bench power _ the Kings' reserves outscored the Sonics, 56-22.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle shot just 35 percent for the game and turned the ball
over 18 times, makingthe Kings look dominant in every facet of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about us missing shots,'' Sonics forward Vin
Baker said. ``I'm worried about us playing defense this late in the
season ... especially with us trying to position ourselves for the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help matters that Sonics point guard Gary Payton
followed his best offensive game as a pro with one of his worst. He
made just four of 19 shots, a performance compounded by a weak eye
from beyond the 3-point stripe.
</P>
<P>
   Payton missed six of seven 3-pointers and finished with 13
points in 41 minutes. His futile shooting came two days after he
lit up KeyArena for a career-high 41 against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't expect our Superman to carry the load every night,''
Barry said. ``We've got to have other guys contribute. Gary can't
win every game. But I'll be damned if he doesn't try.''
</P>
<P>
   With Payton struggling, Baker and Barry stepped up. Barry scored
a team-high 21 points and Baker added 19 points and eight rebounds.
However, the Sonics had little else offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Missing shots is one thing. Playing defense is another,''
Sonics center Horace Grant said. ``If you don't play defense and
you miss shots, you're going to get blown out every time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings hardly looked as though they had suffered a tough loss
at Utah the night before. Sacramento was high octane while the
Sonics, who hadn't played since Tuesday, seemed to run on fumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thought they were going to be fatigued because they
played Utah,'' Grant said. ``They wanted the game more than we did.
I mean, they aren't known as a great defensive team, but we made
them look good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics trailed just 29-23 after the first quarter, but let
the game slip away in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 31-28, the Sonics were outscored 31-16 the rest of the
period. Sacramento made its 62-44 halftime lead hold up by beating
the Sonics in transition and forcing turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics made one minor run, scoring the first 10 points in
the third quarter to cut the Kings' 18-point lead to 62-54 with
9:03 left. But Chris Webber stopped the outburst with a 19-foot
jumper in front of the Sonics' bench.
</P>
<P>
   Webber then tipped in his own miss after a Sonics turnover, and
the Kings pounced again. Sacramento raced to an 82-61 lead just
before the end of the third.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Anderson's 3-pointer with 3:14 left in the fourth buried
the Sonics under a 101-79 deficit. Sacramento's biggest lead was 34
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a lousy game,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal said.
``Give them credit, but we didn't do what we had to do to hang
around.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 0248EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
