<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-CHANGES-1STLD-WRITE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGE COMING SLOWLY TO TRADITION-BOUND SOUTH CAROLINA 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (REMOVES information about flag in 15th graf) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ The freeways through South Carolina would be
indistinguishable from anywhere else were it not for the Church of
Christ-sponsored signs from God and the billboards for Maurice's
Gourmet Piggie Park Bar-B-Q.
</P>
<P>
   The trees are bare from winter, McDonald's are omnipresent and,
but for the lack of snow, the view from the bubble of the campaign
bus is much the same as it was in Iowa or New Hampshire, the last
two proving grounds in the 2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But the political terrain is fundamentally different in this
state where the Civil War began, where abortion is regarded by many
as murder and where the political spectrum ranges from fiscal
conservative to religious conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Politics in South Carolina, locals like to boast, is a blood
sport.
</P>
<P>
   In 1902, the lieutenant governor gunned down the editor of the
State newspaper in broad daylight on Main Street. The prosecutor,
who could not find a jury that would convict, was a fellow named
Thurmond, whose son Strom has been elected to public office _ as
state senator, governor and U.S. senator _ in every election since
1933.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is South Carolina. `Change and reform' is not our
motto,'' said Michael Graham, a Republican consultant who claims to
have come from a rural town where he spent his ``formative years
running from large hairy people named `Bubba,' many of them
women.''
</P>
<P>
   But the image of South Carolina as a backwater state is
outdated. Sumatra coffee and Grgich Hills chardonnay are easily
found in the capital Columbia. Cotton and tobacco are no longer
king, long ago replaced by manufacturing and tourism as the state's
top businesses.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of GOP19 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  South Carolina attracted $42 billion in capital investment during
the 1990s, evidenced by newly constructed office parks and
warehouses toward the west, in the foothills of the Blue Ridge
mountains. Toward the coast, the arrival of thousands of retirees
has driven up real estate costs in Charleston and resort towns such
as Hilton Head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are changing,'' said Don Fowler, who teaches a course
on Southern politics at the University of South Carolina and until
last year was the chairman of the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler said he recently received an invitation to a gay/lesbian
political event, which ``you just wouldn't have seen 10 years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The influence of television, the growing black vote and the
rising number of outsiders have made South Carolina less distinct
from the rest of the nation, Fowler said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the stereotype of South Carolina persists for a reason.
</P>
<P>
   The Confederate flag, the emblem of a cause lost 135 years ago
and a symbol of hatred and racism to many, still flies atop the
statehouse. Bob Jones University, the state's largest liberal arts
college, bans interracial dating and only started allowing blacks
in 1971. The Citadel, a state-financed military school, began
admitting women just four years ago and only after pressure from
the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Those traditions are strong enough that Texas Gov. George W.
Bush made a visit to Bob Jones University his first South Carolina
campaign stop after the New Hampshire primary two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   And no Republican candidate has dared to challenge the flying of
the Confederate flag, which was raised in 1961 to mark the
centennial of the beginning of the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ``What other state would be fighting this flag issue but one of
these deep south States?'' asked Fowler, adding with a smile that
Democrats will be able to exploit it in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of GOP19 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The Republican position on the flag ``is like giving us a nice,
warm cream puff on a silver platter,'' Fowler said.
</P>
<P>
   The national media's focus on race has bred resentment from
South Carolinians who feel they are being maligned. The race
question is more complicated than the stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Pait, like a majority of South Carolinians, believes
the Confederate flag should come down from the statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's offensive to many blacks,'' said Pait, who is white.
</P>
<P>
   Pait, an administrator at Bob Jones University, also says that
the school's ban on interracial dating is an appropriate safeguard
against the blending of God-created races.
</P>
<P>
   ``God did that to keep us from coming together,'' Pait said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could say this until I'm blue in the face, and no one
believes us, but this policy is not based on racism or hate.''
</P>
<P>
   As a political matter, the stop at Bob Jones is sure to haunt
Bush if he wins the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that no one from South Carolina told him not to go
there says something about this state,'' said Graham, who believes
that the behavior of national politicians pandering to the
conservative vote in South Carlina dooms them in the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you really want to be president, lose South Carolina,''
Graham advised.
</P>
<P>
   But therein lies the rub.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Atwater, the late guitar-playing Republican operative famous
for his scorched-earth politics, helped turn his native South
Carolina into a must-win state along the GOP primary trail. Since
the Palmetto State primary in 1980, no Republican has won the
nomination without first winning here.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who writes a weekly political column, describes the
state's GOP as having three factions: the Old Guard (``fiscal
conservatives who will have a drink''), the Right Guard
(``Evangelicals'') and the Off Guard (``anti-establishment kooks
who think the Confederate flag is important.'')
</P>
<P>
   He also repeated the words of a Palmetto State senator from the
mid-1860s: ``South Carolina _ too small to be a republic, too large
to be an insane asylum.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 4 of GOP19 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 0307EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000219.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 03:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1938 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-DUCKS-REWRITE-LAD     02-19 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS SETTLE FOR TIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Mighty Ducks insist it's too early
to label any game a must-win, but Friday's game versus the San Jose
Sharks was as close as it gets at this point of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Win and the Ducks pull within three points of both San Jose and
Edmonton as they desperately try to stay in the thick of the
Western Conference playoff race. Lose and they fall seven back of
the Sharks and remain five back of the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   So what do the Ducks do? They play one of their most
unsatisfying ties in years, blowing two third-period leads and
settling for a 4-4 draw before 16,868 at The Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about running in place. Instead of picking up two points on
the Sharks and Oilers, they settle for just one to pull within four
of the eighth-place Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim made all of the flashy plays, scoring on a great
individual moves, but the Sharks did the dirty work banging home
three ugly goals on only six shots in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had learned something,'' said Teemu Selanne.
``Going to the third period ahead 3-1 ... you can't do what we did.
It's a pretty sad story. We have to learn how to play with the lead
in our building ... what are you going to do, you just have to
learn.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks held the Sharks without a shot for 12 minutes to start
as well as a 12-minute span in the second. They outshot San Jose
21-4 over the first 30 minutes and 36-20 in the game, but the
Sharks salvage a tie when Niklas Sundstrom scored with 2:22 left in
regulation. Sundstrom's third goal in his last 31 games, followed
Vincent Damphousse's first in 24 games at 5:16 of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a heck of a game and it's unfortunate that two
mistakes end up in our net,'' said Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg, who
did his best to put a happy face on the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was may be the best game we've played in 2-3 weeks,'' he
said. ``We have to take the good things. If we look at the big
picture, we should be confident.''
</P>
<P>
   But the big picture didn't look so bright to the players, who
let a valuable point slip through their grasp.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of positives,'' said Ted Donato. ``But at this
time of the season it's all about the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's Ruslan Salei nearly became a unlikely hero when he
scored at 12:16 of the third period to give the Ducks a 4-3 lead,
but Anaheim couldn't hold that lead either, as San Jose tied the
game with 2:22 left when Sundstrom knocked in rebound that Ducks
goalie Guy Hebert couldn't control.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert, coming off a sub-par performance against Calgary on
Wednesday had another rough night, especially when Damphousse's
shot from behind the goal line bounced off his glove and into the
net to tie the game 3-3 at 5:16.
</P>
<P>
   A victory had seemed certain when the Ducks took a 3-1 lead into
the third period against a Sharks team that was 0-18-1 when
trailing after 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But things suddenly got silent at The Pond when Tony Granato,
who assisted on all three goals in the final period set up young
defenseman Scott Hannan for his first NHL goal at 2:28 of the
period to cut the Ducks' lead to 3-2. The silence was even more
deafening when Damphousse scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a bad goal, you should never score from there,'' said
Hartsburg.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose came into the game with a 6-12-3-5 record in its last
21 games and the the Ducks seemed to smell blood from the
beginning, even though it took them over 26 minutes to break
through a wall otherwise known as Shields.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim had five power plays and outshoot the Sharks 14-2 in the
first period, but they had nothing to show for it until Matt Cullen
made the San Jose goalie look human with an inside-out move at 6:08
to give the Ducks a 1-0 lead on their 19th shot of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks made it 2-0 on their 21st shot, just nine seconds
after Ronnie Stern took San Jose's sixth minor penalty of the game.
Oleg Tverdovsky made a perfect shot-pass and Teemu Selanne,
positioned at the left post tipped home his 24th goal of the year
at 6:38.
</P>
<P>
   The goal extended Selanne's point-scoring streak to 13 games and
it marked the 10th consecutive game that the Ducks have scored on
the power play, one short of the franchise record.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks were totally dominating the Sharks, but San Jose took
advantage of a rookie mistake by defenseman Vitaly Vishnevsky to
pull within a goal at 15:33. Vishnevsky cross-checked Damphousse to
give the Sharks a two-man advantage for 1:30. Four seconds after
the two-man advantage expired Owen Nolan banged home his 36th goal
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks regained the momentum and appeared to have put the
game away at 17:18 when Kip Miller left a drop-pass for Tverdovsky,
who scored his second highlight-reel goal in as many games.
Tverdovsky drove to the net, went from forehand to backhand, faking
Shields out of position and tucking in his ninth goal of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The trend for the period was set early when Shields was tested
twice on the Ducks' first power play. He passed both exams with
flying colors, stopping Steve Rucchin's goal-mouth deflection and
Paul Kariya's point-blank follow up just over a minute into the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks' first shot _ a 120-foot one-hopper by Gary Suter _
wasn't recorded until there was 7:42 left in the period. By that
time the Cullen had missed the net on a two-on-one feed from
Selanne, Miller's wraparound bid was turned aside by Shields and
Selanne was stopped from the right circle on a Anaheim power play.
</P>
<P>
   Shields and the Sharks continued their escape act in the second
half of the period. Rookie defenseman Brad Stuart made a great play
to block Miller's pass on a three-on-one Anaheim break. Shields
then made sure the teams went to the dressing rooms tied by
stopping Kariya and Fredrik Olausson on power play chances in the
final minutes of the opening period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
