<HEADER>
A1961 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      02-19 1483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Feb. 20:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PUTIN-PROFILE (St. Petersburg, Russia) _ After half a year as
prime minister and a month as acting president, Vladimir Putin
remains largely unknown. But what is known _ his career in the KGB,
his tough suppression of Chechnya, his ascetic habits _ point in
many ways to an updated version of the Yuri Andropov model. By
Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Chechen guerrillas shot down a
Russian military helicopter on Friday in mountains near southern
Chechnya's Argun gorge, killing 15, Russian government and Chechen
rebel sources said Saturday. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   WESTBANK-BEES (Tulkarm, West Bank) _ There is a quiet cult of
the bee in the land of milk and honey, and beekeepers, be they
Israeli or Palestinian, are the high priests of the hive. It was
only a matter of time, then, before the bees of the Holy Land
became ensnared in the tangled web of the peace efforts. By Deborah
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-SCANDAL (Tokyo) _ When a popular news magazine reported
this week that the secretary to the prime minister, Keizo Obuchi,
had improperly acquired stock in a telecommunications company that
later skyrocketed in value, the political opposition smelled blood
and attacked. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-POLITICS (Seoul, South Korea) _ Two years into his
five-year term as president, Kim Dae Jung is locked in a
surprisingly ugly fight for his political life. By Howard W.
French.
</P>
<P>
   HONG-KONG-XINHUA (Hong Kong) _ On Thursday, the New China News
Agency threw its annual spring festival reception. Always a must
for Hong Kong's elite, this year's party had an added attraction.
For the first time in half a century here, China's state news
agency, known as Xinhua, was no longer operating under cover. By
Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA-MAID-ABUSE (Bangkok, Thailand) _ Almost every day now
in Malaysia, people are reading newspaper accounts of foreign
domestic helpers who have been abused by their employers. The
revelations of these secret crimes have horrified a society that
sees itself as kind, hospitable and soft-spoken. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-DEVELOPING-NATIONS (Bangkok, Thailand) _ A U.N. conference
on developing nations concluded Saturday with expressions of good
will but no real narrowing of the differences that split a meeting
of the World Trade Organization in Seattle in December. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-ELECTION (Tehran, Iran) _ Early results from Iran's
elections indicated Saturday that the country's reform-minded
president, Mohammad Khatami, may have a solid majority behind him
in the parliament to make good on his promises of creating a more
liberal society after 21 years of rule by puritanical Islamic
clerics. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SILICON-VALLEY-POOR (San Jose, Calif.) _ With all the new money
floating around, the most expensive housing market in the country
and the densest concentration of investment capital in the world,
there is no other place in the country that offers a starker
example of the growing gap between the rich and poor. By Evelyn
Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   CORPORATE-TAX-DODGES (Undated) _ With incomes rising sharply,
particularly among the wealthy, Americans are paying a lot more in
federal taxes than they did before the economic expansion of the
last decade. Not so, American corporations. Their profits are
growing even faster than Americans' incomes, yet the taxes they pay
have begun to fall. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   GENE-CONFLICTS (Undated) _ With the biomedical revolution in
full swing, academic scientists who lack industry ties have become
as rare as giant pandas in the wild. But as Congress begins to
investigate lapses in federal oversight of gene therapy
experiments, lawmakers, bioethics experts and federal regulators
say they are troubled that so many researchers have a financial
stake in companies testing their discoveries _ companies whose
fortunes, along with those of the scientist, can rise and fall on a
single product. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   CATS-CLOSING (New York) _ After almost 18 years, $380 million in
sales and untold gallons of makeup, ``Cats,'' the longest-running
production in Broadway history, will close on June 25. By Jesse
McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   DC-DEATH-PENALTY (Washington) _ Federal prosecutors are pressing
for the death penalty against a man charged with murdering three
employees at a Starbucks coffee shop here in July 1997, clearing
the way for the city's first death penalty case in nearly 30 years.
By John Files.
</P>
<P>
   IDAHO-MEMORIAL (Boise, Idaho) _ Greg Carr's native Idaho is a
state well-known for its spectacular wild beauty. But, he said, it
also has a reputation as a haven for racists, an unfortunate
distinction generated by white-supremacist groups that congregate
in northern Idaho and exacerbated by the fact that it is one of the
least ethnically diverse states in the nation. So Carr, the former
chairman of Prodigy Inc., last year issued a ``challenge grant'' to
the people of Idaho to raise money for a human-rights memorial that
might represent a step toward counteracting the image. By Sam Howe
Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   SOJOURNER-STATUE (Northampton, Mass.) _ Seven years into a
project to honor the rights advocate Sojourner Truth with a bronze
statue, organizers are finding themselves in the middle of a
dispute over fairness.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD-OVERSIGHT (Los Angeles) _ In a vote seen as a crucial test
of the city's commitment to change and oversight of the city's
police force, the Los Angeles Police Commission has ruled that an
officer's shooting of a mentally ill homeless woman last year
violated department policy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MICH-REPUBS (Lansing, Mich.) _ After battering each other for
two and a half weeks in South Carolina, Gov. George W. Bush and
Sen. John McCain will crisscross Michigan for the next two days
campaigning for the big state's primary on Tuesday. Worried by
polls showing the race too close to predict, Gov. John Engler of
Michigan, an early supporter of Bush's, has organized one of the
largest political mobilizations ever in the state. By Keith
Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-LABOR (Undated) _ The leaders of the AFL-CIO said this
weekend that they would continue pushing union members to campaign
all-out for Vice President Al Gore even though he has reiterated
his support for President Clinton's trade deal with China. By
Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS _ NAACP opposes compromise on flag; More
turmoil for Reform Party; Cheese Heads in North Carolina? By B.
Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, several political stories dealing with the
Republican primary in South Carolina will move later in the day or
after polls close:
</P>
<P>
   SC-REPUBS (Columbia, S.C.) _ The lede-all. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   SC-REPUBS-ASSESS (Columbia, S.C.) _ An analysis of the results
of the Republican primary. What they mean. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   SC-REPUBS-SCENE (Dateline TK) _ People, places, voices.
</P>
<P>
   SC-BUSH (Dateline TK) _ George W. Bush's day and his reaction to
the results of the South Carolina primary. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   SC-MCCAIN (Dateline TK) _ John McCain's day and his reaction to
the results of the South Carolina primary. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Charleston, S.C.) _ $50 million man of the people.
By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ New economy, old story. By Paul
Krugman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-SPORTS-NYT-BUDGET _ A rundown of sports stories will move by
1 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
