<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRY-MILLIONAIRE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RICHER OR RICHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By JENNY LYN BADER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's not fair that you didn't get to ask me all those
questions, and I didn't get put on the spot.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Multimillionaire Rick Rockwell, ne Richard Balkey, last week
on the hit Fox TV special ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   Even the groom felt the show was imbalanced. The would-be brides
answered all the questions; he answered none.
</P>
<P>
   Memo to the folks at Fox: In the spirit of equal time, you need
a sequel with the bridal contestants doing the asking!
</P>
<P>
   After all, the program didn't let on that Rockwell, a real
estate developer and motivational speaker worth $8 million, is also
a former B-movie actor and comedian. Or that in 1982 he told jokes
for 30 hours, making the Guinness Book of World Records for
``longest continuous comedy routine.''
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. With on-air revelations like these, ratings
would soar. Plus you should face up to the fact that it's not
single women without rich husbands who are desperate. Networks
without Regis Philbin are the desperate ones. Just imagine: ``Who
Wants to Be a Gold-Digger? Part II: The Bride Strikes Back'' . .
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: So. Are you really a multimillionaire? How much
of your net worth is liquid? Or is this only, like, on paper?
</P>
<P>
   Multimillionaire: I'm heavily invested in high technology right
now.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: Aren't you concerned that high-tech is
overvalued?
</P>
<P>
   Multimillionaire: I also own a lot of small-cap stocks. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: Hmm. You're not one of those suitors who thinks
the Russell 2000 Index is going to surge?
</P>
<P>
   Multimillionaire: I'm hoping.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: Oh, dear. I usually drop those after the second
date. OK. If you were to invest in an Asian country right now,
would it be A) Japan, B) China, C) Singapore, or D) none of the
above?
</P>
<P>
   Multimillionaire: C.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: Good. How long do you think it would take you to
evaluate my investment portfolio?
</P>
<P>
   Multimillionaire: (surprised) You have an investment portfolio?
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: Of course I do! I'm an experienced gold-digger!
(consulting teal index cards) Next question: I understand you're a
success object. You have a second home and a decent wardrobe. I
gather you're an attractive guy, though I can only see the back of
your head silhouetted in the purple shadows in your ``Wizard of
Oz'' booth. So the girls and I have been trying to figure out, um,
what your problem is. Why you can't find a wife. So, why are you
here?
</P>
<P>
   Multimillionaire: I resent that. You're here, too!
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: I told you, I'm a fortune-hunter. And my best
friend Marcia is always making fun of me for liking men who give me
presents, so she sent my picture in as a little joke. (To camera)
Marcia, if you're watching now, you're dead meat. (To
multimillionaire) What's your excuse?
</P>
<P>
   Multimillionaire: (miserable) See, I'm a motivational speaker
and by the time I get to a date I'm so burned out from talking I
have nothing left to say. Women find me boring. (He bursts into
tears.)
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: Oh, God, you're the crying type too. No wonder
you're not married.
</P>
<P>
   Multimillionaire: You're not either!
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: That's because I'm picky.
</P>
<P>
   Multimillionaire: (incredulous) If you're picky, how can you let
the Fox network choose for you?
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: I find the Fox Network to be very selective!
Have you seen those boys on ``Party of Five''? Besides, I don't
have the resources to do the kind of background check they did.
They screened you for diseases and past marriages and Swiss bank
accounts and criminal records and _ Fox accomplished in two weeks
what would take an average woman two years!
</P>
<P>
   Multimillionaire: I hadn't thought of it like that.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: I hear before you became a real estate investor,
you did stand-up comedy in clubs. This whole thing could be a
publicity stunt for you. Would you promise me you'll never do
stand-up again? And you'll never mention me in a comic monologue?
</P>
<P>
   Multimillionaire: What about if I get invited to do, like,
Letterman?
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: Acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Multimillionaire: I promise. Though, damn, you'd make great
material.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: How would you justify your purchase of me to our
children?
</P>
<P>
   Multimillionaire: What do you mean?
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: I mean, when our neighbor pops this tape in the
VCR and little Billy asks you, Daddy, did you really buy Mommy on
TV?
</P>
<P>
   Multimillionaire: I'll say we had a very special romance.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: Can I get more light on him, please?
Technicians! And can we see a little more flesh? Did you bring a
bathing suit?
</P>
<P>
   (MULTIMILLIONAIRE is stripped and put on display. REGIS PHILBIN
appears.)
</P>
<P>
   Regis: You've used up your ``50/50'' and your ``Ask the
Audience.'' You can either marry him or call your ``Lifeline.''
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: I'd like to call Marcia.
</P>
<P>
   Regis: Marcia is on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia: (blubbering) I am so sorry. I'll never send your picture
anywhere again.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: I forgive you.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia: Don't do it.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: But he might buy me some stuff. And the diamond
is really pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia: So what? He's a former comic, he can't talk on dates,
and his portfolio isn't diversified! Look, you should totally meet
this other guy I was telling you about.
</P>
<P>
   Regis: I need your final answer.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: (still on phone) What's this other guy like?
</P>
<P>
   Marcia: Well, he doesn't have money, but you would love his abs.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: But I'd get to keep the car.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia: You are a mercenary freak. (Marcia hangs up.)
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: OK, Reeg. I do.
</P>
<P>
   Regis: You do. That's your final answer?
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: Yes. It's my final . . . (bursts into tears) No!
Why do I always meet losers? Even on national TV! Pre-screened,
creatively frustrated, incapable-of-making-small-talk losers?
</P>
<P>
   Regis: Maybe you should be a contestant on our next show: ``Who
Wants to Go on a Long Vacation by Herself?''
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring bride: Would I get to keep the car?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 1122EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
