<HEADLINE>
CHECK YOUR DOORS: BREAKING IN, HACKER-STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By GINA KOLATA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first one rattled the doorknob at 3 a.m. Wednesday morning,
trying to see if the door was open. The next came by an hour later,
then one at 8 a.m., another at 10:30 and yet another at noon. At 1
p.m. a particularly determined intruder arrived, trying entrances
that most people would not even think about. The final attempt of
the day came at 3 p.m., but like all the rest, it was unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   The fortress these thieves were trying to enter? A simple home
computer, hooked up to the Internet with the cable modem service
(at)Home.
</P>
<P>
   The owner happens to be a computer security expert, who wants to
remain anonymous so hackers will not see his system as a
tantalizing challenge. He knows about the attacks because his
computer has a fire wall, which keeps intruders out and tells him
when they have come by. Yet he was nonplussed by the number of
attacks on that single day last week. ``I think it's fairly
typical,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others agree. ``It's called doorknob rattling,'' said Steven
Bellovin, a researcher in Internet security at AT&AMP;T Laboratories in
Florham Park, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Computers are under constant random attacks from hackers around
the world who are looking for open doors, or ports, enabling them
to sneak in. For many hackers, the goal is simply to enter someone
else's computer. Others, like those who launched the recent attacks
on commercial Web sites, are criminals who quietly entered other
people's computers and planted programs that they later triggered
en masse, tying up Amazon.com., Buy.com, eBay, CNN.com and other
sites. But it is a strange sort of crime, since the owners of the
invaded computers probably were unaware of the foray, computer
security experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Internet users who are connected through telephone lines are of
less interest to intruders because they are assigned a different
address each time they dial in. Thieves who do break in have a hard
time succeeding at it again.
</P>
<P>
   But people who are always connected to the Internet through
cable services offered by (at)Home or Road Runner or the high-speed
DSL lines provided by telephone companies are a different story. So
are companies and universities that hook everyone up via their own
high-speed networks. The advantage is that these systems are 10 to
hundreds of times faster than using an ordinary telephone line. The
disadvantage is that your computer's address is usually fixed and
easy to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``The addresses used by (at)Home are public, they're well
known,'' said Bellovin. ``It's very easy to scan all the addresses
for (at)Home and see which ones might be hooked up to cables and on
all the time and which ones might have certain open doors.''
</P>
<P>
   The same is true for other commercial cable companies as well as
university computers. ``A lot of universities have networks that go
to every dorm room,'' he added. ``It is very easy to scan the
address space and find the open servers and go in.''
</P>
<P>
   How often you see doorknob rattlers come by may depend on how
good you are at detecting them. Some computer experts say they see
attacks on a regular basis. Bellovin, who also uses (at)Home, says
his system averages two attempted break-ins a day. Ira Winston,
director of computing at the University of Pennsylvania, said he
detects an attack at least once a day on his home computer.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Smith, a computer science professor and expert on
network security at the University of Pennsylvania, protects his
computer by closing and locking all of its doors. That makes it
more difficult to use, but he doesn't care. ``I'm paranoid about
security,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Other owners set up fire walls that act as electronic stockades.
But most people who are at risk do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a target-rich environment,'' Bellovin said, borrowing a
phrase from the military. Computer factories may ship their PCs
with their doors unlocked, and many users are blissfully unaware of
the cruising doorknob rattlers, which include not just the
teen-ager next door, Smith said, but foreign governments.
</P>
<P>
   Today the trend is toward high-speed cable connections and DSL
lines and toward personal computers connected by networks, said
William Arbaugh, a computer security consultant in Baltimore who
worked at the National Security Agency. The stage is set for
break-ins, he said. And while there are countermeasures, nothing is
100 percent secure.
</P>
<P>
   A colleague at the NSA, he said, ``used to say that the only
safe computer was one buried in a safe in the ground with a marine
guard and the power turned off.''
</P>
