<SLUG> BC-LADN-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Sunday, February 20 and thereafter. For questions about stories,
please contact Elizabeth Ferry at the Daily News at (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   BONDS-RAMPART (Los Angeles) _ Los Angeles Mayor Richard
Riordan's plan to float bonds to pay for settlements in the Rampart
scandal is just the latest in a long line of
pay-later-for-debts-now plans that the city has concoted.
Meanwhile, the County Board of Supervisors will vote Tuesday on a
measure to condemn the city for using tobacco money to pay off the
LAPD scandal. By Rick Orlov. (Will move in the ``a'' national and
``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   DRUMS-CAMP (Los Angeles) _ Inside the white brick classroom
adorned with construction paper cutouts of gangbangers and
athletes, teen-age boys sit in plastic chairs, waiting for the
drums. What makes this gathering unique is that the participants
are wards of Camp Karl Holton, a juvenile probation camp in a
remote corner of the San Fernando Valley. Organizers and psychology
experts say it is one of the first such programs in the nation. By
Jason Kandel. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California
news files.)
</P>
<P>
   VICIOUS-DOGS (Los Angeles) _ This ain't the Westminster Dog
Show. Dogowners bring their pooches to the Sepulveda Basin
Off-Leash Dog Park to frolic and get in some good exercise. But
owners know to be on guard with a sturdy stick and a tight leash to
ward off the vicious breeds that may take on their pet. Dog fights
are all too common at the park, neighbors and visitors of the dog
park say. Alan Goldman, the owner of ``Joy,'' a Corgie and Lab
mixed dog were both hospitalized after a pit bull attacked the dog
this week. Checking for stats at this dog park and others in city
for number of dog fights and injuries to people. By Lisa Van
Proyen. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news
files.)
</P>
