r a BC-DRUMS-CAMP-LADN     02-19 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUMS-CAMP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG OFFENDERS MARCHING TO A DIFFERENT DRUMMER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON KANDEL 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Inside the white brick classroom adorned with
construction-paper cutouts of gangbangers and athletes, teen-age
boys sit in plastic chairs, waiting.
</P>
<P>
   The bald, goateed Steven Angel, a sessions drummer who recorded
songs with legendary guitarist Jimi Hendrix, removes several
colorful drums from a large bag and begins to pass them around the
room.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone gets a drum and brief instructions, then Angel screams,
``Go crazy!''
</P>
<P>
   Like a drag racer at the starting line, rumblings turn to
thunderous pops.
</P>
<P>
   And then it's quiet. The teens laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tap into their emotions,'' Angel said. ``Through
drum therapy, I see them saying, Yeah, this is the way I should
feel. I should feel like a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Drumming has been a popular method for people to bang out their
frustrations, work as a team, or, well, just make some noise.
</P>
<P>
   But what makes this gathering unique is that the participants
are wards of Camp Karl Holton, a juvenile probation camp in a
remote corner of the San Fernando Valley. Organizers and psychology
experts say it is one of the first such programs in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   And because of the calming effect it seems to have on these
young people, law enforcement officials are taking a liking to drum
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``These sessions are a probation officer's dream,'' said L.A.
County Probation Department spokesman Kenneth Kondo. ``When they
are done drumming, we notice a change in attitude. They are not as
aggressive. They aren't as angry.''
</P>
<P>
   In two-hour sessions some Sundays, 15 teen-age boys beat and
whack the drums with plastic mallets until their hands turn raw, or
until they are too tired to do anything else.
</P>
<P>
   But some experts believe the casual sessions are not doing any
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venting anger doesn't reduce aggression, it increases it,''
said Brad Bushman, a professor of psychology at Iowa State
University who has conducted two studies on the effects of taking
out aggression. ``The best-case scenario of venting anger - through
drum therapy, punching a pillow, hitting a punching bag and yelling
and screaming - is that it doesn't work at all. The worst-case
scenario is that it does more harm than good.''
</P>
<P>
   Other experts and participants have a different view.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteer drummer Angel says drum therapy helps bring out the
child in these sometimes hardened juvenile delinquents, many of
whom are serving several months at the camp on various weapons
possession, theft and burglary charges.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent session, 15 teens, wearing brown and tan and
camouflage fatigues, walked single file into an elementary
school-size room. As a probation officer ushered them in, some of
the teens took seats and moved them next to their buddies moves to
which the probation officer objected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want them to think that they are in control,'' Kondo
said, as the probation officer ordered them into other seats.
</P>
<P>
   The young men complied and simmered into submission, while their
probation officer sat at the back of the room, keenly watching them
while cradling a walkie-talkie.
</P>
<P>
   Angel and music program instructor Fletcher Beasley set up a
microphone at the front of the room and began passing out the
small, colorful canvas drums.
</P>
<P>
   As the boys got their drums, some began hitting them. Others
pounded them. Beasley captured their attention.
</P>
<P>
   After introducing a television producer and her cameraman who
were documenting the session for a youth violence series, he said,
``Make as much noise as you want to. There are probably not many
opportunities to make as much noise as you want around here.''
</P>
<P>
   The session began with the primal beating of the drums. Then
Angel led the group through several exercises - one in which he led
a drum solo and they followed, another in which each teen led his
own solo and others followed, and then solos with chanting. At one
point, Angel led them on an anger exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them to think of someone who hurt you, or an experience
that recently happened that caused you a lot of anger, and release
the emotion on the drum,'' he said. ``With their eyes closed, they
visualize the person on the drum, and as they hit the drum, the
image starts fading away as the emotion is released. It's much
healthier to release their anger on an inanimate object.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the session, a few visibly tired teens could
barely tap their drums, while others had set their drums on the
floor to beat them. One youth was nursing blisters with toilet
paper he had been given. Two youths were ordered to leave the room
early for taunting a boy from a rival gang.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts, like Janice Held, a Los Angeles marriage and
family therapist, disagrees with Bushman's theory that venting
anger fuels aggression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will grant him that there might be some accuracy to that,''
said Held, who participated in a recent session with Angel and
follows his work regularly. ``If you hold things back and then have
a spurt of anger, you probably will not have improved the
situation. However, it's incredibly essential to release energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The words that (Angel) uses as part of the drumming
subconsciously build self-esteem at the same time as he's allowing
them to release their energy.''
</P>
<P>
   While it has yet to be seen what long-term effects, if any, the
drumming will have on the teens, 14-year-old Anthony, who was doing
10 months on a gun possession charge, knows one thing's for
certain. ``The thing about beating up the drums,'' he said, ``is
that it can't hit you back.''
</P>
<P>
   A reticent Jose, 15, who said he was serving nine months for
carrying a .38-caliber handgun, was tired after the session.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to go in and go to sleep,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
