r a BC-BONDS-RAMPART-LADN     02-19 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONDS-RAMPART-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS ASSAIL MAYOR`S PLAN TO ASSERT TOBACCO SETTLEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   From health care advocates to taxpayer watchdogs, Los Angeles
Mayor Richard Riordan faces stiff opposition to his plan to bond
the city's long-term share of the national tobacco lawsuit for cash
now to settle Los Angeles Police Department scandal cases.
</P>
<P>
   With some $10 billion in bonded city debt, some questioned the
fiscal responsibility of the plan to sell bonds on $300 million due
over 25 years for $100 million in cash up front, and the loss it
represents to the city in future years.
</P>
<P>
   Others questioned whether the city should take steps now to bond
the money or wait to see how much will be required after the first
Rampart Division liability cases go to trial, probably next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know the full scope of what we will be facing,'' said
Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas. ``A good point is to look at the
Rodney King case and what happened with that settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   King, whose 1991 beating in Lake View Terrace precipitated the
earlier police scandal, had sued the city for $54 million. In the
end, he received less than $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a handle on what the real number will be,''
Ridley-Thomas said. ``This could be less or it could be just the
tip of the iceberg of what we will face.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials have given a preliminary estimate of losses of up
to $125 million from the cases known so far, involving 99
individuals. But many believe the cost could go much higher.
</P>
<P>
   Former anti-gang Officer Rafael Perez told investigators of the
shootings, beatings, planting of evidence and lying in court
against gang members. An internal review is under way and a report
on the LAPD's operations is scheduled to be released March 1.
</P>
<P>
   One of the concerns voiced over Riordan's proposal to use the
tobacco settlement money is the high cost. For that $300 million
coming to the city over 25 years, it would get around $100 million
in cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think that's bad policy,'' said Jon Coupal of the
Howard Jarvis Taxpayers Association. ``This money should be used
for purposes related to tobacco and health. It strikes me as
horrible public policy to use that money for more public debt.''
</P>
<P>
   The city already has more than $705 million in voter-approved
debt and an additional $1.2 billion that is not voter-approved
debt. It pays $248 million a year to cover the interest payments on
those bonds.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the city has $7.7 billion in revenue bonds - which
are paid off from fees or other programs, such as sewer, water and
power.
</P>
<P>
   One city analyst, who asked not to be identified, said a
preliminary look at the mayor's proposal raises the issue of the
cost to get the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city can issue judgment bonds for 5 percent,'' the analyst
said. ``The mayor's plan would cost 6.5 percent in interest. That
point and a half can add up to a lot of money when you're talking
about $300 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Mayor Noelia Rodriguez said Riordan is open to other
suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor is looking for creative ideas,'' Rodriguez said.
``The tobacco money seems like a good idea because it's
uncommitted. The one thing the mayor is concerned about with this
is that the city not cut back any programs or stop new
initiatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said the mayor also has proved his ability to cover
shortages from his first days in office when his budgets had to
deal with shortfalls in the hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, Riordan is going into uncharted
territory with the potential damages from the Rampart corruption
scandal and other demands on the city treasury.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the city is looking at another judgment bond to
cover part of the costs in a $40 million settlement for police
overtime from the 1992 riots.
</P>
<P>
   City Controller Rick Tuttle, whose office was involved in
developing the city's debt policy to keep it below the level of 15
percent of the general fund, said he wants to review the mayor's
proposal more closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to have more of a sense of the details, but what we
have to look at is if this is the most effective way to cover the
debt,'' Tuttle said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the mayor is getting pressure from the health
community to use the funds for tobacco education purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Reynolds, an heir to the R.J. Reynolds Co. and an ardent
anti-tobacco activist, said he believes the proposal to use the
money for lawsuit settlements is emblematic of similar situations
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to speak out and make a very clear case that this is
just politics being played out here,'' Reynolds said. ``We find it
curious that in the settlements nowhere is it required that the
money be used for health or tobacco education programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said the demands on the city require the city to have
flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of health and education programs that already
are going on from the state, the county and the federal
government,'' Rodriguez said. ``What we have to look at is how to
maintain our services.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County Supervisor Michael D. Antonovich also
criticized Riordan's proposal, pointing out that the city earlier
decided to use the dollars to install curb cuts for handicapped
access at intersections, and for tobacco enforcement activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outrageous,'' Antonovich said. ``Those funds are to be
used to help those impacted by the Americans with Disabilities Act
and for education and health programs related to the abuse of
tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tobacco tax dollars are not a Fort Knox the city of Los
Angeles can use for a nonhealth-related mistake they have made.''
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Gloria Molina also disagrees with Riordan's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``She believes the tobacco settlement money was intended for
health care and should go for health care,'' said her spokesman,
Miguel Santana. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer Troy Anderson contributed to this report
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
