<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2059 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-PUTIN-PROFILE-4TAKES-     02-19 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUTIN-PROFILE-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN RETAINS SOVIET DISCIPLINE WHILE STEERING TOWARD REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (A Special Report)  
(Eds: For those wishing to use an abridged version, the first take
can stand as is.) 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ Nine years ago a sea of Russians
celebrating the collapse of a communist-backed coup jammed the
traffic circle outside Moscow's KGB headquarters and stripped away
icons of dictatorship, including a bust and plaque honoring the
late spymaster and Soviet ruler, Yuri Andropov.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 20, in a little-noticed ceremony at entrance 1A of the
old headquarters, workers put them back _ on the personal order of
Prime Minister Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   To Westerners, it seemed a curious tribute: a gesture of respect
from a self-proclaimed democratic reformer to a chief of an
infamous machine of repression. Now that Putin is acting president
and the runaway favorite to win a full term in presidential
elections next month, it is a bit unsettling, too.
</P>
<P>
   But in a country that believes in a strong hand at the tiller,
there was logic to the affinity. Andropov was not simply a shadowy
terror chief propping up a disintegrating totalitarian state; he
was also a leader who recognized that the Soviet system had to be
reformed _ not to make it democratic and Western, but to make it
great and powerful.
</P>
<P>
   He began with draconian discipline in the streets and a
crackdown on vodka. After half a year as prime minister and a month
as acting president, Putin _ his ambitions, his methods, his
intentions _ remains largely unknown. But what is known _ his
career in the KGB, his tough suppression of Chechnya, his
statements, his ascetic habits _ points in many ways to an updated
version of the Andropov model.
</P>
<P>
   He may have little use for Andropov's Soviet system, and a
greater appreciation for law and order and the value and efficiency
of Western-style business. But he has shown himself a man every bit
as intolerant of Russia's disarray, and as determined to do
something about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did the Soviet Union break up?'' he asked in a December
interview, then answered himself: ``Because things were allowed to
happen; laxness. And if we continue like this, Russia will fall to
pieces, and it will happen so quickly you and I cannot even
imagine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there will be a real tragedy, much bigger than we are
seeing today in the north Caucasus. Much bigger,'' he said. ``You
can imagine what will follow if we see the Russian Federation fall
apart, a nuclear power. We do not have the right to be lax; we do
not have the right.''
</P>
<P>
   The unanswered question is what he intends to do about it. Putin
advertises himself as a democrat. He says that a free press is an
essential deterrent to tyranny; that Russia's only dictatorship
should be ``a dictatorship of laws,'' that Russia is committed to
``fundamental political rights and human liberties.''
</P>
<P>
   But his six months in the Kremlin present a far muddier picture.
In prosecuting the war in Chechnya, Putin has proved not just
indifferent but belligerent toward international criticism of
Russian behavior there. His aides have used both financial and
police levers to cow critics of that war in the press, even
fingering some skeptical reporters as potential collaborators with
the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently for the purpose of skewering Putin's potential rival,
former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, deputies aligned with Putin
struck a power-sharing deal with the Communist Party in the Russian
parliament, shunning democratic forces. The acting president has
talked of fiscal, legal and social reforms, but his presidential
agenda remains vague.
</P>
<P>
   What he has offered are gestures _ like mandatory military
education in schools _ that hint at a streak of nationalism and a
bent for strong, centralized rule.
</P>
<P>
   Putin clearly has an intellectual grasp of democracy and of what
he has called the ``historic futility'' of communism. He is a
veteran of an intelligence service in which, as an agent in East
Germany in the 1980s, he could witness the reality of socialist
economics and Soviet rule.
</P>
<P>
   But his defining characteristics seem to be a passion for order
and a desire to see Russia rise from the ashes.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew H. Murray, a former U.S. Senate aide who has worked with
investors here for the last decade, frequently negotiated with
Putin when he worked with foreign businesses. Murray called Putin
very tough, mentally swift, immaculately prepared and ingenious at
navigating Russia's labyrinthine bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a `khozayin,''' a tough taskmaster, Murray said. ``He
knows how the pieces of this society fit together. He knows how to
take care of people. And he knows how to get results.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great potential on the part of the West to
misinterpret Putin,'' Murray added. ``You shouldn't mistake a lack
of an economic worldview for a lack of economic purpose. He has a
purpose: to get Russia back on its feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Igor Antonov, a retired KGB officer who claims to have worked
with Putin, and carries a tattered snapshot which appears to prove
it, agreed in a long conversation last week that Putin and Andropov
shared some traits. But Westerners seeking a clue to Vladimir
Vladimirovich Putin's style of leadership, he said, might look to a
more familiar ruler, an iron-fisted democrat and abrasive
nationalist of the 1950s and 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, Vladimir Vladimirovich is most like De Gaulle,''
Antonov said. ``I don't know if that's good or bad. But in my
opinion, he is close to this.''
</P>
<P>
   By comparison with many of his countrymen, Putin seems almost
monkish. He does not smoke. If he drinks, it is rarely. He seldom
shows anger and does not make snap decisions. He regularly works
16- and 17-hour days. He is a practicing Orthodox Christian _ his
mother secretly arranged for his baptism when he was a baby _ and
actually delivered a Christmas Eve sermon to reporters last month
outside a Moscow church.
</P>
<P>
   He holds not just one diploma _ a distinction shared among
Kremlin predecessors only by Mikhail Gorbachev _ but two: a law
degree from Leningrad State University and a doctorate in economics
from Russia's oldest technical university. He speaks some English
and such impressive German that he can imitate dialects. He holds a
black belt in judo and played handball in high school. He is a
runner, an avocation roughly as common among his predecessors as
break dancing.
</P>
<P>
   When President Boris Yeltsin named Putin chief of the Federal
Security Service, the domestic successor to the KGB, in 1998, he
sought to promote him to general, the rank held by all espionage
chiefs. Putin, who only rose to lieutenant colonel during his own
KGB days, would have none of it, saying he had not earned the rank.
</P>
<P>
   ``His most outstanding trait, I would say, was his fighting
spirit and his strong will to achieve his goals,'' said Pavel
Koshelev, a college classmate and fellow KGB officer who wrote a
recommendation for Putin's application to join the agency. ``In
general, he exercised total control over himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Anatoly Sobchak, a former mayor of St. Petersburg and, early on,
Putin's mentor, said Yeltsin and Viktor Chernomyrdin, who served
the longest as prime minister under Yeltsin, would relax ``by going
to the baths, by going hunting, by heavy drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For Putin and his team, the new people who are now coming into
the government, they don't drink or smoke, they don't go hunting,
and if they go to the baths, it's only to wash, and not to get
drunk or be with girls. They're entirely different people _ not
only by age, but by upbringing and behavior.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Early Education: Physical Training And an Elite School
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Putin's upbringing was not atypical. He was born Oct.
7, 1952, in St. Petersburg, then Leningrad, the only child of a
factory foreman and his wife who were, it is said, decorated war
veterans. Like countless Russians and the vast bulk of
Leningraders, he spent his first decades in a communal flat, where
he shared a carved-up apartment with two other families.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Putins were not poor. His father's job, at a shop
that made experimental parts for devices conjured up at a
neighboring institute, was highly specialized. It probably paid
well for the time: unlike many Soviet women, Putin's mother did not
work.
</P>
<P>
   Although small for his age _ he remains short and wiry today _
Volodya Putin was enrolled in martial arts classes by his parents.
By the time he entered secondary school No. 281, at age 16, he was
a top-ranked expert at sambo, a Russian combination of judo and
wrestling dating from the 1930s, and able to handle schoolyard
fights, one teacher said, with devastating results.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Putin was no academic weakling, either. School
281 was a college-preparatory institution for ninth- and 10th-grade
students _ the Soviet system ended at grade 10. It was the only
school in Russia stressing chemistry, and only students with
near-perfect grades _ straight ``fives,'' with perhaps one four _
could get in.
</P>
<P>
   Graduates were guaranteed a spot in the city's most prestigious
technical university. Putin planned to be a chemist, but it was not
long before he discovered that his true interests lay elsewhere.
The education at an elite school like No. 281 was not ordinary. The
director encouraged teachers to shun lectures and rely on debates
and even arguments to impart their lessons. The school's most
popular instructor, a literature teacher named Mikhail Dimenkov,
peppered his course with samizdat _ banned literature circulated
underground in carbon or handwritten copies. The history teacher,
Tamara Stelmakhova, staged discussions on whether Nikita
Khrushchev's promise to build a true communist state within 20
years was realistic.
</P>
<P>
   In this environment, Volodya Putin was drawn to humanities and
softer sciences like biology, where he scored steady fives. His
math and chemistry grades fell to threes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke to his father about this,'' Putin's biology teacher,
Raisa Polunina, now 68 and retired in a tiny third-floor flat
outside the city, said in an interview. ``He said his son was so
goal-oriented that he already knows what he wants _ and between us,
why should he be expending so much energy on chemistry and math
when he is going to do something else?''
</P>
<P>
   In teachers' and students' memories _ made rosier, perhaps, by
time and his rise to prominence _ Putin was the steadiest and
hardest-working of all: the boy everyone called when the school
radio station broke down, as it often did; the one who made weekly
current events reports to class and, several times, to the entire
school; the sole boy who agreed to dance with girls in an
interschool competition because the honor of No. 281 was at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Putin played music by the Beatles and other Western rock bands
on the school radio station. He attended after-school
get-togethers, though he held none in his flat. He was well-liked
by girls, who apparently admired his athleticism and quiet
competence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to say that we had a lot of time for recreation,''
said Alexander Matveyev, a classmate. ``After high school
graduation, we still would meet sometimes over the weekend at each
other's places. We danced, talked about our life; had a party.
Still,'' he said, ``Putin was a little more adultlike than the rest
of us. It was clear that he was a responsible person who wanted to
make something of himself.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, Putin enrolled at Leningrad State University, one of
the more prestigious Soviet institutions, where he majored in civil
law and studied German.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin didn't have much free time at school, and when he did,
he spent it on sport,'' said Koshelev, who first met him there in
1970. ``While he's not a big man, he has fantastic reactions as a
judo and karate expert. He was my instructor at the KGB school for
karate, and he impressed us all with the inner strength he
exuded.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   KGB Career: A Plum Position In a Gentler Time
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Putin was Leningrad's judo champion. A year later, he
graduated with honors from the university. Sobchak, who taught
civil law to Putin and presided over the oral examination for his
diploma, says today that his student acquired not just a solid
education, but an appreciation of democratic rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere at the university was free-thinking, democratic
and dissidentlike,'' Sobchak said during a long talk in his St.
Petersburg law office. ``It is not necessary to convince him that
we need to have a market economy, to respect private property and
the rule of law. It's already his professional credo, one he
acquired while he was at the university.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobchak, like many others, has much to gain by burnishing
Putin's reputation. He lost his bid to become governor of the St.
Petersburg region in 1996, and subsequently was accused of major
corruption _ accusations that drove him into virtual exile in
western Europe until his return to St. Petersburg last year.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Putin did soak in some un-Soviet customs. But Soviet law
was drenched in ideology, and the law school was considered a
finishing school for future government workers _ not exactly free
thinkers. At the same time, former students say, the faculty was
peppered with older professors with an almost prerevolutionary
attitude toward the law. And the students, many of them children of
the victims of Stalin's repression, were relatively progressive,
interested in _ and allowed to experiment with _ foreign films,
music and opinions.
</P>
<P>
   The KGB also trolled the Leningrad law school, looking for
future spies, but it was extremely selective. Of the 100 or more
students in the class of 1975, it picked but one.
</P>
<P>
   Yuri Andropov's KGB was anything but free-thinking. Andropov
himself helped crush Hungary's 1956 revolt, ran the agency during
the 1968 suppression of Czechoslovakia's ``Prague Spring,'' and
popularized the Soviet practice of imprisoning dissidents in
psychiatric hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   But by the 1970s and 1980s, the KGB _ while still feared and
fearsome _ was no longer the tool of Stalin, sending millions to
their deaths in the gulag. It still had ears everywhere and was
vigilant for any sign of dissidence, but those who knew their place
and their limits could stay out of the KGB's web.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a mood in the country,'' said Polunina. ``If you
weren't touched by Stalin's repression, it was like it never
happened. The KGB had become helpers of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   For many, it also was a coveted career choice, a club of elite
Soviets given superior education and a unique chance to sample the
forbidden world _ if only to fight it. And so when recruiters
offered a job in the service in 1975, Putin accepted instantly.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he owned a new car, which he told disbelieving friends he
had won in a lottery. Putin was schooled in espionage in Moscow,
but passed much of the next decade in Leningrad.
</P>
<P>
   After briefly working in counterintelligence, he joined the
KGB's First Chief Directorate as a foreign intelligence agent,
focusing on Western visitors and, presumably, handling informers
who passed through the region to drop off information or receive
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's superiors were reluctant to send him abroad, Antonov,
his KGB co-worker, said last week, because he was single. But
sometime in the early 1980s, Putin married Lyudmila, a specialist
in English and French some eight years his junior. In 1985, the KGB
sent him to East Germany. He became Adamov, director of a
German-Soviet friendship society in Leipzig, living in a
two-and-a-half-room apartment in Dresden. His office in a two-story
brick villa was across the street from the sprawling Stasi
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's real work is partly a matter of speculation. His KGB
co-worker, Antonov, said that he remained a foreign agent,
traveling frequently to the West to gather information and manage
informers. Others have suggested _ Antonov calls it ``rubbish'' _
that Dresden was an espionage backwater where Putin's main job was
to keep tabs on an East German population growing increasingly
restive under the nation's Stalinist dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the winds were changing. In 1985, Andropov's
protege, Gorbachev, came to power and began his perestroika, and
suddenly communist regimes across Eastern Europe were tottering.
</P>
<P>
   At least part of Putin's work in Dresden may have involved
preparation for the collapse. According to some published accounts,
he worked with seven other KGB agents on an operation code-named
``Luch,'' Sunbeam, aimed at creating a network of spies separate
from the one then shared with East Germany's intelligence agency.
The notion was to maintain a stable of agents that could survive a
collapse of East Germany's government.
</P>
<P>
   That fall, however, came swifter than anyone imagined. By
December 1989, the Berlin Wall had fallen and East and West Germany
were on their way to being reunited under a democratic government.
Putin has yet to give his own public account of these events.
</P>
<P>
   Antonov, who did not serve in Dresden but claims to have
remained close to Putin through the 1980s, said Putin's principal
reaction to East Germany's collapse was not ideological. He
realized that the walling off of the two Germanys was fated to end.
The major regret, rather, was that the end was quick and chaotic,
and not managed better in the interests of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Political Climb: From Mayoral Aide To Kremlin Post
</P>
<P>
   Putin returned to Leningrad with a bronze medal from his Stasi
co-workers and took up work in the international affairs department
at his old university, a job that was really a cover under which to
continue intelligence work.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he heard from Sobchak, who had quit teaching to become the
first mayor of a newly renamed St. Petersburg. Putin became his
external affairs aide, charged with recruiting foreign companies
and promoting business. In a city embracing capitalism, he became
the man to see, in no small part because it quickly became clear
that he got things done.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he was deputy mayor, and by Sobchak's description, ``my
most reliable, responsible and hard-working assistant.'' Antonov,
no admirer of Sobchak, said Putin told him that he quit
intelligence work for politics because government work offered a
prospect ``to make something happen'' at a critical period in
history.
</P>
<P>
   In Sobchak's administration, Putin made the law his specialty.
He excelled at unraveling the Gordian knots of Russian bureaucracy
and building an infrastructure _ highways, telecommunications,
hotels _ to support foreign investment. He also became known as an
exacting, workaholic taskmaster who gave underlings one chance _
two, at most _ to reach a goal. He seldom stayed at receptions and
city functions longer than a half-hour, preferring to slip away to
his desk.
</P>
<P>
   Co-workers said his anteroom was perennially jammed with
callers, usually foreign investors, and that his meetings always
ran beyond schedule. ``Putin is the kind of guy who wants to listen
to everything you have to say,'' said Alexander Kostrykin, an aide
in his office from 1992 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   His success is hard to measure. St. Petersburg never realized
Sobchak's grand ambitions to become Russia's financial capital;
Putin's plans for a world trade center fell through in 1995;
through much of the 1990s, the city struggled.
</P>
<P>
   But in fairness, Putin started from scratch. and St. Petersburg
today appears prosperous _ in part, some say, because of the
economic foundation he laid. Sobchak and others say Putin had a
major hand in every significant foreign investment in St.
Petersburg in the early 1990s, from Coca-Cola to Credit Lyonnais to
Dresdner Bank to NEC, the Japanese electronics giant.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Bazhanov, a St. Petersburg banker, first met Putin in
1995 at the Davos international economic forum. When Bazhanov later
asked the city to help find his bank an office, Putin produced _
and promptly asked the bank to sponsor the purchase of $500,000 in
equipment for city hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, the American investment adviser, described a 1994
instance in which a Russian government agency sought to seize a $9
million donation by a U.S. charity _ until Putin personally
persuaded the former prime minister, Chernomyrdin, to push
legislation through Russia's parliament thwarting the agency's
plans. Putin extracted his own payment for the favor: a hefty
donation of sterilization equipment to a city medical clinic to
slow the spread of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's very professional; very disciplined,'' Murray said.
``And in the end, you got a result. Usually at the end, you don't
know if someone's looking for a bribe. But that's not Vladimir
Putin.''
</P>
<P>
   Nina Odling, a senior analyst at St. Petersburg's Leontieff
Center for Social and Economic Research, said, ``Everyone in
government in Russia has skeletons in his closet. But Putin was one
of the more honest and decent people in the St. Petersburg
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin was literally tossed out of St. Petersburg politics in
1996, when Sobchak lost his political campaign, which Putin shaped.
Alone among top aides, he resigned after the loss. ``Better to be
hanged for loyalty than rewarded for treason,'' he told friends.
</P>
<P>
   He was rewarded anyway, with a Kremlin job some say was arranged
by another reformer from St. Petersburg who is now his deputy
finance minister, Aleksei Kudrin. That job, in 1997, kicked off a
rise in Kremlin politics which, by any definition, has been
meteoric.
</P>
<P>
   Should it continue after the March election, as seems likely,
Russia's De Gaulle may well give the West even greater headaches
than did France's. Putin appears every bit as dry-eyed about the
merits of liberal democracy and one-superpower worlds as he was
about the demise of East Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he is, like De Gaulle, an authoritarian leader longing
to restore the greatness of the state, has yet to be fully
answered. Putin himself was oblique when he last pondered the
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who does not regret the passing of the Soviet Union
doesn't have a heart,'' he said in a recent interview. ``And anyone
who longs for its restoration doesn't have brains.''
</P>
</TEXT>
