u p BC-MICH-REPUBS-2TAKES-(T     02-19 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-REPUBS-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN GOVERNOR PRESIDING OVER HUGE EFFORT FOR BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANSING, Mich. _ After battering each other for two and a half
weeks in South Carolina, Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain
will crisscross Michigan for the next two days campaigning for the
big state's primary on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Worried by polls showing the race too close to predict, Gov.
John Engler of Michigan, an early supporter of Bush's, has led one
of the largest political mobilizations ever in the state.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has a low-budget operation here and is relying heavily on
media coverage and the Internet to get his message out, in a
showdown that pits the buzz of his popularity against one of the
most formidable political machines left in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Republican owners of small businesses say party officials have
asked to use their offices as phone banks to appeal for Bush
voters. County executives and other local party leaders have been
writing thousands of letters to get out the vote. And Republican
state legislators have been recording radio advertisements for Bush
in their districts.
</P>
<P>
   Engler is hoping that his approach to politics still works. He
said the push for votes in this primary exceeded efforts in the
general elections of 1992 and 1996, and was the biggest since his
first campaign for governor, in 1990, when he beat a Democratic
incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's somewhat chilling, actually, to see the McCain campaign
be so obsessed with their press relations and their media strategy
that it overwhelms all of the old, traditional political campaign
aspects,'' Engler said in an interview at his office here, across
the street from the state capitol.
</P>
<P>
   McCain campaign officials say that 2,000 people have volunteered
over the Internet to help in Michigan, but they have set up only a
handful of phone banks and are hoping that most of the volunteers
will distribute pamphlets, put up signs and make phone calls from
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll concede the organization battle,'' said Michael Hudome,
McCain's top adviser on the Michigan primary.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high here for Engler personally and for
Republican governors across the country. Engler is a top adviser to
Bush and was the only governor on Bush's exploratory committee
before Bush, the Texas governor, announced his presidential
candidacy. Term limits require Engler to leave office at the end of
his current term, his third, and there has been much speculation
that he would have a role in a Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   Support for Bush coalesced early last year among Republican
governors, many of whom saw the Texas governor as a superior
alternative to candidates from the Republican-controlled Congress,
which was ensnared then in President Clinton's impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   But if Engler fails, the image of all Republican governors will
suffer, said Curt Smith, the chief operating officer of the
conservative Hudson Institute, based in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has put his prestige on the line, and he has put his
organization on the line,'' Smith said, ``and if he can't deliver,
the perception might be in Washington that these governors are
popular at home but can't deliver for others.''
</P>
<P>
   Engler predicted that Bush would win the primary here by 4 or 5
percentage points, and said the vote would show that Republican
governors, rather than a Republican senator like McCain,
represented the best hope for wooing Republicans, Democrats and
independents alike in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``In reality,'' Engler said, ``it's the governors in the
Republican Party who have, without question, enjoyed substantial
success in the '90s and who have been bringing millions more
Americans into the Republican Party, far more than the McCain
campaign has brought in, in its short life. Through our
performance, we've earned not only a seat at the table but a very
important role in setting some of the direction of the party.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Engler said he wanted to finish his term and declined to
speculate further on his own political future, other than to rule
out a bid for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters say Bush is slightly ahead of McCain here, but that
the outcome will depend on turnout. In past Republican primaries
here, the turnout has tended to be 10 percent to 12 percent of
registered voters, about two-thirds of whom are in the party and
the balance of whom are Democrats, independents and Republicans who
vote only occasionally. McCain can win if he can increase turnout
to 15 percent _ close to 1 million people _ by attracting more
independents, Democrats and Republicans who vote infrequently, said
Ed Sarpolus, a pollster here at EPIC/MRA, which does a lot of
polling for media organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 100,000 voters on Tuesday will be Republicans who seldom
vote in primaries but will vote for Bush at the request of the
Engler organization, Sarpolus estimated. That could be roughly
equal to the number of Democrats who vote in the Republican
primary, he added.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A few liberal Democrats have urged their supporters to vote for
McCain to punish Engler for stripping Detroit of some its control
over schools and courts. But Michigan's Democratic leaders have
disavowed this tactic, and pollsters have predicted that the effect
would be statistically insignificant. Engler has tried to galvanize
his supporters by attacking the limited Democratic efforts.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Engler has spent his 10 years as governor, as well as most of
the 1980s, as president of the state Senate, assiduously attending
fund-raisers and other events for Republican chairmen in each of
Michigan's 83 counties. He is also a feared figure in state
politics, with a reputation similar to that of Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani of New York for remembering his friends and punishing his
enemies in budgets and other legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Engler has been using all his influence to make sure that
local Republicans organize the grass-roots effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is when the Engler machine, or establishment, kicks in,''
said L. Brooks Patterson, Oakland County executive. ``We have
resources, I think, that McCain doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Gil Cox, the chairman of a large law firm in Troy, Mich., said
that he had agreed to a request from Oakland County Republicans to
turn over the firm's headquarters this weekend to volunteers who
would make phone calls asking Bush supporters to make sure they
voted.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been asked to do this for local races, but this is the
first time we've been asked for a presidential race,'' Cox, a
Republican, said. His firm, Cox, Hodgman &AMP; Giarmarco, represents
many Michigan cities in liability cases, including cities with
Democratic administrations. But Cox said that the decision to help
had been made ``because it's a good thing for the community'' to
increase voter turnout.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Michigan's secretary of state, Candice S. Miller, said she had
arranged for 560 volunteers to work this weekend in shifts on 300
phones at local businesses to get out the vote for Bush in Macomb
County in Detroit's northeastern suburbs, her political base.
``We're approaching this not as if this were a presidential
campaign but as though there were county commissioner campaigns all
over the place,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the McCain campaign has a total of just 25
volunteers who will be making calls from their homes in Oakland and
Macomb Counties, two of Michigan's three largest counties.
</P>
<P>
   There is a precedent for Engler's activity. William G. Milliken,
a moderate Republican who was Michigan's governor from 1970 to
1982, campaigned energetically at the last moment for Bush's father
in the Republican primary in 1980 and essentially cast the primary
as a referendum on himself.
</P>
<P>
   Despite having lost a string of earlier primaries, and despite
trailing Ronald Reagan in Michigan polls by up to 12 percentage
points several days before the vote, Bush won the primary by 25
percentage points. The victory helped him secure the vice
presidential nomination at the Republican convention eight weeks
later in Detroit, an important step on the path to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Milliken, who remains one of the most popular politicians in the
state despite having been retired for 18 years, endorsed McCain on
Thursday, saying that he admired his courage. But in a sign of the
weakness of McCain's organization in Michigan, Milliken said after
the endorsement that he had never heard from the senator or his
staff, even though McCain was scheduled to campaign on Monday in
Traverse City, the small city in northern Michigan where Milliken
lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
