<HEADER>
A2106 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-IRAN-ELECTION-NYT &LR;      02-19 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY TALLIES SHOWS REFORM CANDIDATES GAINING IN IRAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ Early results from Iran's elections indicated
Saturday that the country's reform-minded president, Mohammad
Khatami, may have a solid majority behind him in the Parliament to
make good on his promises of creating a more liberal society after
21 years of rule by puritanical Islamic clerics.
</P>
<P>
   The only counts completed, however, were in some provinces
outside Tehran, the capital, where a final tally is not expected
for some time. The ballots are being counted by hand, and in big
cities like Tehran, each ballot may contain up to 30 handwritten
candidate names that must be deciphered and sorted.
</P>
<P>
   According to some political analysts, the preliminary results
that have dribbled out of the provinces showed that hard-liners who
have resisted Khatami's drive for social reforms won just one seat
out of four in Iran's small towns and rural areas. The big winners,
they said, were candidates who had identified themselves as
outright reformers and those who called themselves
middle-of-the-road moderates but back Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   Sayed Hossain Marashi, the deputy campaign manager for the
moderate Servants of Construction Party, said he had received
unofficial results showing that about 25 percent of the votes
outside of Tehran went to his party. An additional 20 percent, he
added, went to the left-wing Islamic Iran Participation Front,
which includes Khatami's brother and well-known liberal writers,
and most of the rest went to candidates who ran under the combined
banner of the two groups in many provincial cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised because the predictions had been that up to
one-third of the votes would go to the conservatives,'' Marashi
said. ``Still, they will still be an important factor in the
Parliament, even if they don't get more than 25 percent of the
seats, because the other 75 percent is not one unified bloc.''
</P>
<P>
   While those who ran under the moderate banner support Khatami on
some issues, many are known to be hesitant to move too quickly to
loosen the conservative clergy's grip on matters dealing with the
courts and the country's many competing security forces, which do
not answer to the president. They also differ from the more leftist
reformers on the economic policy needed to create jobs and
investment in Iran _ issues that many Iranian voters said were
priorities in an overwhelmingly young country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the people in the middle who think about modernization
of the country along progressive lines,'' said Marashi. ``We are
not conservatives, and we don't want to be part of the left because
we don't agree with them that the economy should be
government-controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   The lead figure for the moderates in Tehran was the former
president, Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
   There was no official announcement on the size of the turnout,
and private estimates varied widely, from about 67 percent,
according to Marashi, to a hefty 88 percent, according to the
reformers' camp.
</P>
<P>
   As with previous Iranian elections for the Parliament, it may
take analysts some time to sort out the political orientations of
the winners. Many candidates in Tehran ran as aspirants from
specific parties, but outside the capital many more were associated
with loose coalitions of parties with little in common but their
stated support for either Khatami or more conservative symbols from
Iran's past, like Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a big win for his supporters, Khatami may still have
an uphill struggle to achieve some of the systemic changes he has
advocated, including reforming the judiciary and guaranteeing a
free press.
</P>
<P>
   All legislation must be approved not only by the Parliament, but
also by a 12-man Guardian Council that has traditionally opposed
reforms that would give Iranians freedom of choice in what they
read, what they wear and how they behave in public and in private.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Khatami shares power with Ayatollah Ali Khameini,
who holds the post of supreme leader and embodies the clergy's
domination of Iranian politics, security and foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leader has always respected the vote of the majority of
the people,'' said Ahmad Bourghani, a leader and parliamentary
candidate of the reform Participation Front. ``I think he will
cooperate with Khatami because he has been generally supportive in
the past of the president's programs, even though he sometimes
raises questions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
