<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2110 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WESTBANK-BEES-ART-770     02-19 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WESTBANK-BEES-ART-770(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMONG MIDEAST BARRIERS, THE TINIEST OF PASSIONS: THE BEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TULKARM, West Bank _ There is a quiet cult of the bee in the
land of milk and honey, and beekeepers, be they Israeli or
Palestinian, are the high priests of the hive.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a matter of time, then, in a place where passion and
conflict are so entwined, before the bees of the Holy Land became
ensnared in the tangled web of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``No bees, no peace,'' read the Hebrew placards at a recent
demonstration at an Israeli checkpoint in the West Bank, protesting
an epidemic of hive thefts by Palestinians. It was called the
Beekeepers Revolt.
</P>
<P>
   Looking like astronauts in their white protective gear, dozens
of Israeli beekeepers briefly blocked a key entrance to Israel from
Palestinian territory. With their hives.
</P>
<P>
   They said the theft, of 2,600 hives in the past year, is
threatening not only their livelihood, but _ given the centrality
they attach to the bee _ the land of Israel itself. If Israeli
lawmakers don't pay greater attention to this phenomenon, they say,
they will bring their hives to the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, if worse comes to worse, we will release the bees,'' said
Roni Feldman, a 65-year-old, fourth-generation beekeeper who makes
an unlikely candidate for apiarist-terrorist. ``This is a struggle
for our existence, and I would dare say, since the flowers and the
orchards are so dependent on the bee, for the future of Israel
itself. That last part is what people don't seem to realize.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian beekeepers share this kind of rapture:
without the bee, we are nothing. For the Israelis, it is a Zionist
thing. For the Palestinians, it is religious _ a whole sura, or
chapter, Number 17, of the Koran, is devoted to the bee _ and
nationalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey is a holy product of the Holy Land,'' said Osman Arafat,
the leading beekeeping expert in the West Bank, who decided against
naming his company ``Arafat Bee Productions'' so as not to alienate
potential customers who oppose his namesake, the Palestinian
leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' Arafat continued, ``it is definitely a growth industry
with huge potential for our future state.''
</P>
<P>
   The effect of peacemaking on bee-keeping was probably not
contemplated by the signers of the Oslo interim peace agreement of
1993. But there has been a profound effect, and the story is not
only one of conflict but of accommodation and cooperation, too. And
it underscores that there is nothing abstract about peace between
Israelis and Palestinians, who live elbow to elbow and share the
same land, acre by acre, honeycomb by honeycomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, there is no such thing as a Palestinian or
an Israeli bee,'' Arafat said. ``They fly freely over checkpoints,
linking us through nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Feldman's 25-year-old son, Ziv, who wears his hair in a ponytail
and majors in communications at Tel Aviv University, sees it
differently. ``Bees don't like to mix with those who are not from
their hive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Arafat and other Palestinian beekeepers graduated
from a five-day training seminar administered by the Israeli
Agriculture Ministry in Netanya, Israel. Outside the hotel where
the seminar was offered, Israeli beekeepers, not including Feldman,
protested. But the Israelis' complaint is not really with their
colleagues, the true professionals like Arafat, who holds a
master's degree in beekeeping from Belgrade, Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   It is with the thieves themselves, with the Palestinian police
who do not crack down on thieves, and with the Israeli officials
who do not pressure them on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   Theft of cars and of agricultural products, from tractors to
bees, increased sharply after the Palestinians started taking
control of territory in the West Bank. Palestinian thieves became
able to disappear into Palestinian-ruled land without fear of
apprehension. A lot of the thievery involves collaboration between
Israeli and Palestinian criminals, the authorities say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of theft is one of cooperation,'' said Samir Mouadi,
Israel's deputy agriculture minister for the West Bank. ``But it is
the cooperation of negative elements on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Car theft was attacked by a joint operation of Israeli and
Palestinian police. So far, though, hives have been largely
ignored, even though some government officials understand the
primacy of the bee.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli agriculture officials estimate that 80 percent of the
stolen hives made their way to the West Bank. That represents a
direct loss of only about $600,000 to the nation's beekeepers, who
tend 80,000 hives. But, as Feldman says, ``the smallest bee is
indeed a huge factory,'' and every hive contains thousands.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Feldman's bee-keeping venture is a typical Israeli story. It
starts in Odessa in 1882.
</P>
<P>
   His great-great-grandfather was offered a deal he couldn't
refuse: the trade of a farm in what later became Nes Tziona,
Israel, for his place in Russia. The property was right near the
Western Wall in Jerusalem, he was falsely told. So after arriving
at the desolate ruin of a farm in the middle of nowhere, he
immediately turned around and returned to fetch 10 other religious
families so he could be ensured of a prayer quorum, or minyan.
</P>
<P>
   They started Israel's honey industry, whose history is soon to
be honored in a bee-keeping museum near Feldman's home in Nes
Tziona. The new immigrants were shown their first hives when they
asked locals about the boxes bumping on the sides of their camels.
And the rest is apiary history, despite the fact that Feldman's
great-great-grandfather quickly discovered he was allergic to bees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say that I believe I was actually conceived among bee
hives,'' Feldman said. ``And that from age zero, I grew up chasing
bees. I'm a Jew, so bees are not my religion. But close. If I'm not
stung several times a day, I don't feel alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Feldman contends out that bee-keepers are ``high-quality''
Israelis, many of whom served in elite units of the army. Indeed,
the lore of the beekeeper, in ancient times or pioneering days,
infests Israeli literature.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One recent example is the bee-keeping protagonist in ``The Blue
Mountain,'' by Meir Shalev, an endearing character who calls his
wife ``the queen bee.''
</P>
<P>
   When a small-time beekeeper was wiped out by theft in December,
Feldman, who owns about 1,500 hives, was radicalized, he said. He
is right-wing, and skeptical about peace, but most of the other
beekeepers live in the farming collectives and kibbutzim belong to
the dovish Labor Party. Still, they think the government is
sacrificing their livelihood on the altar of peace _ unwilling to
make a fuss.
</P>
<P>
   The Jerusalem Post supported the bee-keepers in an editorial
last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Halt unneighborly theft,'' it said. ``Addressing the plague of
agricultural theft does not conflict with the peace process. It is
part of the more fundamental process of learning to live together
as neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   In the deserted woods of Bet Jamal near Bet Shemesh in Israel,
Feldman, his son, his son-in-law and a Palestinian worker recently
visited some of their hives. They all donned gear from head to toe
before they lifted the honeycombs from their wooden boxes, checking
to make sure the queen bee was still buzzing and that the others
were swarming and healthy.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Palestinian beekeepers in this West Bank town,
many of whom keep their hives in their backyards, visited their
bees without any protective clothing whatsoever. ``We Palestinians
are not afraid of the landmines all around us,'' Arafat said. ``Why
should we be afraid of little bees?''
</P>
<P>
   To sit in a living room here with the Tulkarm Beekeepers
Association, beneath a chandelier whose amber crystals look like
dripping honey, is to absorb an incredible passion for an ancient
livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's best student, Adnan Hanoun, 37, keeps a sample of an
old-fashioned mud hive in his workshop on Paris Street. But it is a
piece of history, only. High-tech has come to the honey business
even here, where it is a fledgling industry of some 20,000 hives,
and Arafat owns an artificial bee insemination machine.
</P>
<P>
   Hanoun's connection began during the Gulf War, after he had
graduated from Bir Zeit University near Ramallah with a degree in
business administration. Locked in his town by Israeli
high-security measures, he started reading a how-to guide on
bee-keeping, then went on to train with Arafat and in France. He
has since surpassed his teacher in the amount of honey he can
extract from a hive.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when their businesses, which produce mostly for local
consumption, are getting off the ground, the Palestinian beekeepers
feel stung by the thievery issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be frank, we as Palestinian bee producers are hurt doubly,
maybe even more than the Israelis victims,'' Hanoun said. ``First,
because we cannot compete with the stolen product. Second, because
we are suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians said they were thrilled by the Israeli seminar,
offered in the midst of this controversy. While some Israeli
beekeepers protested outside, they bonded with others inside, they
said, trading notes on bee nutrition and bee medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no need for a common language,'' Arafat said. ``The
common language was the language of bees.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
