u i BC-KOREA-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      02-19 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREAN FIGHTS FOR COALITION AND HIS AIMS AS A REFORMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ Two years into his five-year term as
president, Kim Dae-jung is locked in a surprisingly ugly fight for
his political life _ or at least to avoid having the remainder of
his term turned into an ornamental presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The depth of his predicament was driven home the other day when
one of South Korea's leading politicians compared the president,
who took office as a reformer with a long history of opposition
dissent, to Mao Tse-tung.
</P>
<P>
   What was shocking was not so much that comparison to Mao but
that the critical comment came from Kim Jong-pil, the president's
erstwhile prime minister and nominally one of his most important
allies.
</P>
<P>
   The 74-year-old president may be a hero of the long struggle
against military dictatorship in his country, and more recently,
the engineer of a resuscitation of his country's economy that has
impressed international financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   But on April 13, he faces elections for the national assembly
that almost everyone in South Korea _ including Kim himself _
agrees will be decisive. ``It will have a definitive influence on
things,'' Kim said in an interview. ``The ruling party must win in
this election in order to continue its reforms, and to make Korea a
leader in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim's two years in power have eroded the aura of the reformer
that was a ticket to his popularity. Now, many grumble that he has
adopted much of the imperial style of his authoritarian
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Kim still speaks strongly in favor of democratization and human
rights, noting, for example, that the press enjoys a ``freedom
unknown in the past,'' or that last year, for the first time in
living memory, South Korea's fearsome police used no tear gas to
put down demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   But opposition politicians and independent observers alike say
that his government has taken an increasingly vindictive approach
to critics and perceived political enemies. The cases most often
cited include tax prosecutions and other legal harassments of the
owners of the newspaper Joong Ang Ilbo and the head of Korean Air.
</P>
<P>
   The news here last week was dominated by the government's clumsy
attempts to arrest a lawmaker, Chung Hyung-keun, on charges that he
defamed the president. Claiming that the arrest was illegal, Chung,
a high-ranking intelligence official during South Korea's
dictatorship, barricaded himself with supporters in the
headquarters of the opposition Grand National Party.
</P>
<P>
   Recently Kim has come under heavy criticism by opposition
conservatives for his policy of engagement with North Korea, the
so-called Sunshine Policy, which some have called a sellout for
allowing a lucrative market in tourism with the North.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Kim is becoming more like Khomeini and less like
Mandela,'' said Park Shinil, assistant to the director of the Grand
National Party, the leading opposition group.
</P>
<P>
   Others dismiss comparisons like these as greatly overdrawn, but
offer criticisms of their own. ``In terms of dealing with the
North, or handling the nation's economy, the president has achieved
tremendous successes,'' said Lee Seog-yeon, secretary-general of
the Citizens' Coalition for Economic Justice, a leading
nongovernmental organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``But internally, in terms of human rights, political reform and
social justice, his performance has been below expectations,'' said
Lee. ``He has become so fixated on winning the elections that he
only seems to listen to the voices of his confidants rather than to
the wishes of the Korean people.''
</P>
<P>
   The April legislative elections may still be nearly two months
off, but South Korea has already become a political hothouse. Kim's
newly renamed Millennium Democratic Party barely holds one-third of
the 299 legislative seats. It is in coalition with a party headed
by his former prime minister, but that coalition is distinctly
fragile.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Jong-pil stepped down as prime minister a month ago to head
the coalition's election campaign. Then his name appeared at the
top of a list of reputedly corrupt politicians circulated by a new
coalition of civic groups that wanted those politicians excluded
from the election race.
</P>
<P>
   The former prime minister's supporters now suspect the president
of outmaneuvering their man, getting him to relinquish his office
and then encouraging an embarrassing attack on his reputation. A
breakup of President Kim's coalition, or a poor electoral
performance in April, Kim says, would mark the end of the reform
era in Korean politics. ``Only with a mandate can we promote our
agenda of a new human rights law, a new anticorruption law, a new
national security law and legislation to further democratize this
country,'' Kim said. ``We must win these elections.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 1419EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
