<HEADER>
A2125 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AUSTRIA-PROTEST-NYT &LR;      02-19 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISE OF FAR RIGHT PARTY BRINGS OUT LARGE PROTEST IN VIENNA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ Apparently unbowed by rain, tens of thousands
of people gathered in the streets of Vienna on Saturday to protest
the formation of a government that includes Joerg Haider's
anti-immigration Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration, organized by human-rights groups and attended
by artists and intellectuals from throughout Europe, was by far the
largest since the coalition government took office two weeks ago.
But it elicited only contempt from Haider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who who were in power for the past 30 years, the Social
Democrats, cannot stand to lose,'' Haider said Saturday. ``That is
why they try to mobilize the population, and if that does not work,
even pay people to go out and protest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Social Democrats angrily rejected the charge that anyone had
been paid, and Haider produced no evidence to support his
allegation. The demonstration appeared to be drawn from a very
broad swath of Austrian society, including artists, state
employees, factory workers, professionals and students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am here to show the Austrian government and also the
international community that not all Austrians are Nazis,'' said
Martin Hochegger, a psychologist from Graz. ``I do not believe that
Haider is a Nazi, but he is a racist, and that is unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   The formation of a government made up of the Freedom Party and
the conservative People's Party of Wolfgang Schuessel has provoked
outrage in Europe because it has appeared to legitimize the far
right. Haider has made occasional remarks praising aspects of the
Third Reich, before recently denouncing Hitler's regime as
``barbaric.''
</P>
<P>
   Several demonstrators said that while it was a good thing for
Austria's long-blocked democracy to have a change after three
decades of government by a coalition of Social Democrats and
conservatives, this particular change was abhorrent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was proud to have an Austrian passport, and now I am
ashamed,'' said Agnes Schmidt, who moved here from her native
Hungary 30 years ago and took Austrian nationality. ``Even if we
needed change, we did not need this one.''
</P>
<P>
   No estimate of the number of demonstrators was immediately
available; organizers had said they expected as many as 200,000
people. Those attending include Bernard-Henri Levy, the French
philosopher, and Michael Friedman, a leading member of the German
Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators marched under banners saying ``Resistance''
and ``Never Again,'' and it was clear that the arrival of Haider's
party in power had abruptly politicized what had been a largely
apolitical Austrian youth.
</P>
<P>
   The government has vowed to cut the public sector, deregulate
Austria's highly bureaucratic economy, promote capital markets and
generally bring something resembling a Thatcherite revolution to
this country. These economic aims have provoked almost as much
alarm among Austrians as Haider's anti-immigrant or revisionist
declarations. Several banners said, ``No to social cutbacks,'' and
a large labor union presence was evident.
</P>
<P>
   Anna-Maria Maio, a lawyer, said the Freedom Party justice
minister, Michael Kruger, aimed to cut jobs in the justice
department and courts throughout Austria. ``I cannot accept this
any more than I can accept a justice minister who is against
foreigners,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Maio added that she was married to an Italian in the Tyrol area
of Austria and had frequently encountered racism, although she said
the situation had improved in recent years. ``From my private life,
I have learned what racism is, and there is no question that Haider
stirs up racism in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Posters for Haider's last election campaign showed fair-haired
Austrian girls as emblems of the threatened essence of the country,
while other posters in Vienna appeared to equate black people with
drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Schuessel, the chancellor, dismissed the importance of the
demonstration. ``Those from the old left, the generation of 1968,
can have a good romp with the young and the Internet generation,''
he said. ``Then we will return to normality and get on with the
work that has to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   But it appeared from the breadth of the demonstration, and the
strong presence of powerful unions, that the work of the
conservative government will be arduous, both in its efforts at
home and its attempt to overcome a hostile international
environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
