<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Feb. 20, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A shift in the weather pattern across the nation will become
more evident Sunday as dry and milder air begins to dominate the
region east of the Rockies. Meanwhile, clouds and precipitation
will be more widespread in the West. The jet stream will start a
retreat from the East, but it will be impeded by a fresh surge of
polar air into the upper Great Lakes which will move into New
England on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   An expansive high-pressure system over the lower Mississippi
Valley will control the weather over the South. The clockwise
circulation will draw cooler air into the Southeast. The leading
edge of the cool air will reach into Florida with scattered
showers. The return flow of warmer air into the southwest Plains
will be accompanied by thickening clouds. Showers will develop in
the Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Milder air will move into the northern Plains and eastern
Rockies. This warmth marks the beginning of at least several days
of well above seasonal readings. As the warmer air progresses into
the Midwest, it will encounter cold air over snow-covered terrain.
The result will be some flurries.
</P>
<P>
   The disturbance which brought showers to southern California on
Saturday will move into the southern Rockies with valley showers
and patches of snow in the mountains. A larger and more powerful
disturbance will near the California coast with moderate to heavy
rain in northern sections and showers farther south. Snow levels
will decrease in the Sierra and southern Cascades. The Northwest
will turn dull, but stay seasonably mild. Showers will arrive at
night. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Train of Showers &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the Ohio Valley were drenched Friday as a complex
winter storm spun its way through the region. Evansville, Ind.,
measured a February record of 3.38 inches of rain in less than 24
hours. A swath of showers, with a link to Gulf moisture, developed
near the Ohio River and kept reforming over the same parts of
southern Indiana and western Kentucky. This elongated train of
showers is more common in the warm season, but when atmospheric
conditions are ripe and a rich supply of moisture is available,
like the Gulf of Mexico, then this ``training'' can happen at any
time of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
