<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2134 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      02-19 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAACP OPPOSES COMPROMISE ON S.C. FLAG  
 MORE TROUBLE FOR THE REFORM PARTY  
 THE POWER OF CHEESE IN NORTH CAROLINA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Minn., N.C.)  (nk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ The Confederate battle flag issue was here when
the Republican presidential candidates arrived months ago to begin
campaigning for Saturday's primary. And it will still be here when
they depart, as politically contentious and seemingly intractable
as ever.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates have been asked repeatedly whether the banner
should be hauled down from atop the Statehouse, no small decision
in a state in which ``The War'' remains very much on some minds.
</P>
<P>
   The two leading candidates, Sen. John McCain of Arizona and Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, saw the question as a sure-fire loser
whatever answer they offered. So they skittered away, saying the
flag's fate was not for outsiders to decide.
</P>
<P>
   That struck the third candidate, Alan Keyes, the black
conservative commentator, as rank wishy-washiness _ not the kind of
wash McCain and Bush had in mind as they skittered. He demanded
that the flag be taken down.
</P>
<P>
   It still flies. And the debate rages on as the candidates take
their leave.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jim Hodges, a Democrat, proposed on Monday that the state
Legislature approve moving the flag to a site near the Statehouse
on which there is a large statue of Gen. Wade Hampton, a Civil War
hero. Standing with the governor when he announced the plan were
numerous business and community leaders who are concerned about the
impact of the dispute on the state. Standing there, too, were 22
state legislators, nine of them black.
</P>
<P>
   Given the makeup of that gathering, it appeared the governor's
proposal, with its nod to both sides in the fight, might have the
kind of backing needed to end the impasse. Such a compromise had
long seemed to many South Carolinians to be the best way to get the
flag off of the Statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   But now the Hodges plan appears to be in some trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People,
which has called for an economic boycott of South Carolina until
the flag comes down, says the compromise is inadequate and
unacceptable. What is more, some black leaders say state NAACP
officials have begun warning black legislators, many of them weary
of the flag issue and eager to move on, to vote against the Hodges
plan or risk political retribution.
</P>
<P>
   One NAACP ally, state Sen. Darrell Jackson, told The State
newspaper of Columbia on Thursday that the group's leaders minced
no words in demanding that black legislators put up a solid front
of opposition to the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leadership said to them emphatically,'' Jackson said,
``that anybody that supports it, they would consider them against
them.''
</P>
<P>
   For Reform Party, More Turmoil
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of last weekend's rowdy free-for-all in
Nashville, Tenn., where Ross Perot forces snatched back control of
the Reform Party from allies of Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota, a
move is afoot to draft Perot for a third run for president.
</P>
<P>
   The effort is being led by Jim Mangia, the party's national
secretary, who was a leader of last week's Perot putsch. He says it
is critical that the party have a competitive race between
candidates this year if it is to survive and grow, and he argues
that Perot, the party's founder, is the man who can make it
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   To many Reformers, the ``draft Ross'' call has a ``stop Pat''
sound, Pat being Pat Buchanan, the only big name still proclaiming
or hinting at an interest in the party's nomination, now that
Ventura and Donald Trump have said they want no part of the party.
To Ventura and Trump, Buchanan is a political extremist, not a
reformer, and they believe his nomination would finish off what is
left of an already badly shattered party.
</P>
<P>
   As for Perot and Buchanan, they had seemed to be on good terms
until Mangia began his draft effort, though Perot had not endorsed
Buchanan. In fact, after Jack Gargan, Ventura's man, was ousted as
Reform Party chairman last Saturday, the Perot supporters installed
Pat Choate as the interim chairman. He was Perot's running mate in
1996 and, until he took the interim chairman's job, was helping run
Buchanan's presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Perot is not commenting on the draft effort, at least not yet.
But if Perot jumps in, Buchanan vows to fight. He has been working
the party's grass roots in recent months and has built up enough
support that his backers made the difference the Perot faction
needed for the Nashville takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Do not look to Russell Verney, Perot's closest political adviser
and his spokesman on party matters, to explain away all this
confusion. He is talking up Sen. John McCain of Arizona as the
possible Reform nominee, arguing that McCain espouses the closest
thing to a real reform message this election year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could be both the Republican nominee and the Reform
nominee,'' Verney says.
</P>
<P>
   But Cheese Heads In North Carolina?
</P>
<P>
   The American Diary Association was casting about for a new way
to promote cheese when the bright idea hit. Why not run a
television spot keyed to the election season?
</P>
<P>
   So the advertising people went to work and came up with a skit,
now showing nationally, in which a fictional presidential candidate
named ``Hayes'' refuses an offer to try a piece of cheese in a
campaign appearance. The crowd is outraged.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes' opponent, a fictional fellow named ``Taylor,'' calls a
news conference and declares his love for cheese. Flashbulbs pop
and scribes scribble and Bob Dole _ he of real political and
advertising fame _ calls Hayes ``a doofus.''
</P>
<P>
   The closing scene finds Hayes back in his campaign headquarters,
alone and deserted _ a cheesy guy. The lights dim and an announcer
intones, ``Ah, the power of cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, indeed, for it turns out that in the 8th Congressional
District in south-central North Carolina, there just happens to be
a genuine race involving two fellows named Hayes and Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   The district's incumbent congressman, Robin Hayes, a Republican,
is in a down-to-the-wire contest with Mike Taylor, a Democrat who
almost captured the seat two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Aware that many 8th District voters have seen the cheese
commercial, both candidates are working ``pro-cheese'' references
to it into their speeches, with Hayes boasting that his wife hails
from Wisconsin and Taylor promising to be a ``Gouda'' legislator.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on here?
</P>
<P>
   Pure coincidence, dairy association officials insist. They say
the characters in the commercial were named for two advertising
agency employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 1447EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
