<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2135 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-IDAHO-MEMORIAL-NYT &LR;      02-19 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IDAHO-MEMORIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDAHO SEEKS A MORE TOLERANT IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOISE, Idaho _ Greg Carr's native Idaho is a state well known
for its spectacular wild beauty. But, he said, it also has a
reputation as a haven for racists, an unfortunate distinction
generated by white-supremacist groups that congregate in northern
Idaho and exacerbated by the fact that it is one of the least
ethnically diverse states in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   So in an unusual example of the burst of philanthropy now going
on among Internet-era executives, Carr, the former chairman of
Prodigy Inc., last year issued a ``challenge grant'' to the people
of Idaho to raise money for a human rights memorial that might
represent a step toward counteracting the image.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Idaho seem to have responded, raising about
$750,000 over four months and more than meeting the $500,000 goal
that Carr set as a baseline for him to kick in $500,000 toward the
project.
</P>
<P>
   And, it was announced here recently, construction will begin
this spring on the Idaho Anne Frank Human Rights Memorial, to be
built along the Boise River Greenbelt near the city's public
library.
</P>
<P>
   ``Idahoans are good people, and this response is evidence of
that,'' said the 40-year-old Carr, who resigned from Prodigy, the
online services company, to pursue philanthropic matters full time,
including establishing the Carr Center for Human Rights Policy at
the John F. Kennedy School of Government at Harvard. ``Sadly, it
really only takes a very few people, a tiny group, to give the
entire state a bad image.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for a 175-foot-long wall of granite panels with
quotes and images from human rights figures, including Nelson
Mandela, Martin Luther King Jr. and Margaret Mead.
</P>
<P>
   There will also be a life-size statue of Frank and a bronze
model of the diary that she kept as she and her family hid from the
Nazis in an Amsterdam, Netherlands, attic. Frank, who would have
turned 70 last year, died at 15 of typhus in the Bergen-Belsen
concentration camp, a few months before the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The donors came from across Idaho, offering amounts that ranged
from the $50,000 contributed by Hewlett-Packard Co. and Albertson's
Inc., the supermarket chain, down to the $23 collected by a young
girl who sold bookmarks to be used in reading Frank's diary, one of
the most widely read books in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the memorial will help project Idaho as a far more
tolerant place _ or, more important, help make it so _ remains to
be seen. Many people here are confident that it will.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of little things to change perceptions,'' said
the state controller, J.D. Williams, a Democrat. ``I would describe
this as a big little thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, though, say it is only the first step in a long process,
or even worry that having a human rights memorial to point to will
divert people from harder actions.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Baker, a professor of sociology at Boise State
University, who has written two books on race relations in Idaho,
said that Hispanic people in the state, many coming here to work in
agriculture, are routinely viewed as ``second-class citizens'' by
the majority. Efforts to give them stronger wage or
working-condition protections are routinely beaten back in the
Legislature, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is much more problematic than an image issue,'' he said.
``There is institutionalized racism here, and nobody even wants to
talk about it.'' That said, though, Baker added that he strongly
supported the human rights memorial as a way to help spark
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Idaho is undeniably far from diverse. Of its 1,228,684 people,
just 88,284 are Hispanic and 7,158 _ barely half of 1 percent _ are
black, according to Census Bureau figures.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany Hardy, who moved with some trepidation from New York
City last year to become executive director of the Idaho Black
History Museum, which opened last March, said she found more
friendly curiosity than xenophobia.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an outsider, all I had ever really heard about Idaho was
the Aryan Nation and potatoes,'' said Hardy, who is black.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take away the potatoes, and that's a pretty negative
image,'' she said. ``But since I've been here, I've found that
that's not fair. I talk to a lot of people who've lived here all
their lives and they simply don't know about blacks. They've never
been around black people, but they want to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the Anne Frank theme for a human rights memorial
emerged after nearly 50,000 people, including schoolchildren from
all over the state, attended the international Anne Frank in the
World exhibit when it came to Boise in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Peterman, executive director of the Idaho Human Rights
Education Center, said the memorial was expected to open sometime
in the fall. Describing an outpouring of checks and letters that
had come in , she said: ``The vast majority of people here want to
do something together that will really speak louder than the few
voices of those groups. I think this memorial will send that
message, loud and clear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
