<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2142 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-LABOR-945(2TAKES     02-19 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-LABOR-945(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR LEADERS SUPPORT GORE DESPITE STANCE ON CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The leaders of the AFL-CIO said this weekend that they would
continue pushing union members to campaign aggressively for Vice
President Al Gore, even though he has reiterated his support for
President Clinton's trade deal with China.
</P>
<P>
   Persuading Congress to reject the China accord has become
organized labor's No. 1 legislative goal this year, and some labor
leaders are voicing fears that Gore's support for the deal could
cause many rank-and-file union members to sour on the vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Gore told labor leaders meeting in New Orleans that
any trade agreements he negotiated as president would have strong
labor and environmental protections. Some union officials took that
to mean that Gore was unenthusiastic about the China deal, which
does not contain such protections.
</P>
<P>
   But after some administration officials and corporate executives
criticized Gore for seemingly undermining the deal, he sent a
letter to a powerful business group reaffirming his support for the
China accord, and his aides said his remarks had been
misinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
   John J. Sweeney, the AFL-CIO's president, said that even though
he was unhappy with Gore's stance on the China deal, labor would
back him enthusiastically. The AFL-CIO, which represents 13 million
union members, endorsed Gore for the Democratic presidential
nomination last October.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's picking up a lot of momentum with our members,'' Sweeney
said in a telephone interview on Friday night. ``We were confident
when we started down this path that he was the right person and the
best candidate, and that's just been reconfirmed for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Several labor leaders said Gore's speech to the AFL-CIO's
executive council resonated with them on many issues other than
China, like Social Security and the need for legislation that would
make it easier to unionize workers.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, who has transformed organized labor into a more potent
political force, is walking a fine line in trying to mobilize union
members to fight the China deal while somehow keeping them
enthusiastic about Gore. Even many of Sweeney's union allies say
this will be hard to pull off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think China raises the legitimate issue that no candidate is
perfect on our issues,'' said Andrew Stern, president of the
Service Employees International Union. ``If I were this
administration, I wouldn't hold this vote now. It will not generate
enthusiasm among union members, and certainly among parts of the
labor movement it's going to be incredibly debilitating.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern said he had told Gore to urge President Clinton to delay
the vote and instead focus on issues popular with union members,
like safeguarding financing for Medicare and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, shortly after the AFL-CIO endorsed Gore, the
Clinton administration reached its trade deal with China, a move
that will help pave the way for China's entry into the World Trade
Organization. The deal calls on China and the United States to
remove barriers to each other's trade.
</P>
<P>
   Business executives have praised the deal, saying it will
increase American exports, create jobs and force China to follow
world trade rules. But union officials have condemned it because it
does not require China to improve its performance on human rights
or worker rights.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders fear that once China joins the World Trade
Organization, it will use its influence to block efforts to
persuade the organization's members to include labor protections in
future trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors have helped cement labor's support of Gore
despite his stance on the China accord. For one thing, his
Democratic rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley, and the two leading
Republican presidential candidates, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
and Sen. John McCain of Arizona, all support the deal.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Gore has repeatedly called for inserting
enforceable labor, environmental and human rights provisions into
the fabric of future trade agreements, rather than relegating such
provisions to unenforceable side agreements. That has convinced
many labor leaders that he will take a more pro-labor stance in
trade negotiations than President Clinton has.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Al Gore is supporting the president and the China trade
agreement, he was very clear at our convention as to where he will
stand on trade agreements when he is the president,'' Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   Some business leaders who support the China deal say that Gore
has been trying to walk a tightrope in dealing with trade _ and
that when he spoke to the AFL-CIO on Thursday, he fell off. They
say he apparently tried to signal his ambivalence about the China
deal by telling labor leaders, minutes after he had said he
supported the deal, that as president he would negotiate accords
more to labor's liking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was trolling for votes and grass-roots support,''
said Bruce Josten, executive vice president of the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce. ``It's unfortunate, to be quite honest, that he did this
right when this is being teed up in Congress. He's running for
president, and they had endorsed him earlier, and for any Democrat
to win the presidency, you have to keep intact that important union
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Josten said he considered the AFL-CIO's opposition
short-sighted, because blocking the deal will reduce the number of
export-related jobs. He noted that China will join the World Trade
Organization whether or not Congress approves the agreement. If the
deal is rejected, he said, American companies will continue to face
trade barriers in China, and European and Japanese competitors will
have an advantage in exporting to the world's most populous nation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many lawmakers say they expect Congress to vote on the China
accord this spring or summer, although some union officials and
Democratic lawmakers say it would be best to delay the vote until
after the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats in Congress will feel intense pressure to vote
for the agreement, from business leaders as well as President
Clinton. But if they do, many union members could turn against them
in a year when the Democrats hope to regain control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a vote on China is potentially devastating for the
Democrats,'' said Mike Mathis, director of government affairs for
the Teamsters union. ``In our case, our general president, Jim
Hoffa, is going to be out front on this trade issue, and it's going
to be a real selling job for us to have our general president
pushing the importance of defeating this trade agreement and then
ask our members to vote for Al Gore. The only way to do that is to
say, `If he's president, he will be a better president on trade
than whoever the Republican is.'''
</P>
<P>
   Josten said he was upset by Gore's remarks, because if the vice
president was questioning the deal, that might give wavering
Democrats political cover to oppose it. Nonetheless, he said, he
was confident that Congress would approve the accord.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders say they plan to spend at least $9 million
lobbying for the deal, while the AFL-CIO is planning an advertising
campaign to pressure wavering members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their dismay with the Clinton administration's trade
policies, the International Brotherhood of Teamsters and the United
Auto Workers have bucked the union tide and not endorsed Gore. The
Teamsters' executive board is scheduled to meet on Feb. 29 in
Orlando, Fla. Teamster leaders say that a majority of the board is
leaning toward Gore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
