<DOCNO> NYT20000219.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2147 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ENVIRONMENT-LAWSUIT-N     02-19 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENVIRONMENT-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ENVIRONMENTAL SUIT WITH THE ROLES SWITCHED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ko) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. _ The pretrial litigation has reached the
five-year mark with depositions and arguments ever growing in
Dickensian stacks dense enough to make the judge cry out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This court has been submerged,'' complained Judge James
Michael here in U.S. District Court. ``No more of these 180-page
briefs,'' he ordered the battery of lawyers as he applied a firm
hand to one of the more enigmatic environmental lawsuits inching
its way across a highly valued corner of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The suit involves a group of preservationists in a rustic
antebellum enclave of Louisa County and two strip mining companies,
but not in the usual configuration.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it is Historic Green Springs Inc., the nonprofit
group of preservationists, that is being sued after decades of
aggressively using the courts to help create a 11,000-acre land
trust of 18th century working farms and Civil War plantation
houses. The trust was set up 30 years ago as a federal National
Historic Landmark. Through conservation easements, the local
property owners agree not to develop their land.
</P>
<P>
   The enclave of more than 250 privately owned 18th and 19th
century homes, barns and slave quarters 25 miles east of
Charlottesville survives as one of the little noticed jewels of the
rolling Virginia countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fighting for our survival,'' said Rae H. Ely, a founder
of the Green Springs land trust, which is being accused by one of
the mining companies, Virginia Vermiculite Ltd., of participating
in an antitrust conspiracy in having accepted a gift of 1,400 acres
of vermiculite-rich land for the trust.
</P>
<P>
   The gift was unexpectedly made by the second mining company,
W.R. Grace &AMP; Co., which ended its plans for an elaborate
strip-mining project on the land and yielded the acreage as an
unusual gift after years of fighting the tenacious Ely and her
neighbors in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   In the civil suit, conducted largely behind closed doors in the
name of protecting trade secrets, Virginia Vermiculite is demanding
the award of most of the Grace gift plus $20 million in damages,
contending that the donation to the land trust amounted to an
unfair monopoly of a rare mineral, vermiculite, which is used as an
insulation material.
</P>
<P>
   Grace , rejecting that argument, stands accused alongside the
Green Springs trust, while major preservation groups like the Land
Trust Alliance and the National Trust file friend of the court
briefs.
</P>
<P>
   Preservationists fear that the suit, if successful, could chill
future donations under federal programs that protect more than
700,000 acres of historic areas around the nation from industrial
development by the use of conservation easements and pledges to
keep the land configured for agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to destroy us,'' said Ely, contending that the
lawsuit had no merit but was being pursued in a costly effort to
break the trust, which she said had no paid staff, had exhausted
its resources and was more than $150,000 in debt from the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Ely is a fierce defender of the land as she squares off against
her chief antagonist, Robert Sansom, a former environmental
official in the Nixon administration who is head of Virginia
Vermiculite.
</P>
<P>
   Sansom's company has been mining a smaller strip at the edge of
the trust and is suing to gain the valuable Grace gift as a
resource he contends is vital for the nation's interests. ``It's
the finest reserve of vermiculite in the United States, the biggest
and highest quality,'' Sansom said.
</P>
<P>
   Sansom paid a battle-weary compliment to Ely after this and
years of earlier legal clashes over mining rights. ``She never
sleeps,'' he said. He argued that the district was not threatened
by the suit and rejected the argument that a defeat of the trust
would essentially open the other 10,000 acres of the National
Historic Landmark to relentless development pressures.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Sheehan, who as part of the trus thas restricted
development of Prospect Hill, his small plantation inn, disagreed.
``If you can successfully challenge supposedly iron-clad easements,
then the whole thing falls,'' he said. ``What I have sacrificed is
not for me or my children. It's for 100 years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Spirits are running high among the Green Springs homeowners,
whose holdings range from the humblest working farms to Henry
Taylor's family homestead, a gleaming mansion called Westend that
dates from 1847. ``Virginia Vermiculite is aiming to destroy the
historic district,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The vehemence of the struggle contrasts with this region's tone
of Virginia courtliness, a quality personified by Michael, who
keeps a sharp edge to his drawl as he prods the lawyers to work
harder and faster. ``You all aren't doing very much in the way of
geein' and hawin','' he observed, employing the mule driver's
vernacular to the case that is only now attracting wider notice of
the quiet beauty and simmering conflict at Green Springs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
