<HEADER>
A2151 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LAPD-OVERSIGHT-NYT &LR;      02-19 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAPD-OVERSIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES BOARD RULES POLICE SHOOTING WAS WRONG 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a vote seen as a crucial test of the city's
commitment to change and oversight of the city's police force, the
Los Angeles Police Commission has ruled that an officer's shooting
of a mentally ill homeless woman last year violated department
policy.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 3-2, the commission concluded that the woman,
Margaret Mitchell, had not posed an imminent danger and that
alternatives had not been exhausted before she was killed. In doing
so, the commission accepted the recommendation of its civilian
inspector general, Jeffrey Eglash, over that of Police Chief
Bernard C. Parks. Parks had argued that the shooting should have
been found within the department's policy guidelines even if the
tactics leading to it were faulty.
</P>
<P>
   The commission voted on Tuesday after more than a year of debate
over the inspector general's role in department affairs and
questions about the commission's independence from the police chief
and Mayor Richard J. Riordan, who appoints commission members and
is a strong backer of Parks.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago a city attorney determined, for the first time,
that the civilian commission, and not the police chief, was the
head of the department. Still, there is growing conflict over
whether the commission should have the ultimate say in a
department-wide examination started following accusations of
corruption and brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Some city leaders believe that the commission and the inspector
general should be given the chance to review the examination and
determine whether the changes it recommends are adequate to correct
deficiencies. Other leaders and civil rights advocates believe that
an outside commission _ similar to the Christopher Commission
convened in the wake of the Rodney King beating _ should be
appointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor supports the police commission,'' Deputy Mayor
Noelia Rodriguez said on Wednesday. ``They've done their job,
they've looked at the facts and they've voted on the matter. This
shows that they are independent.''
</P>
<P>
   But the narrow vote, and the rarity of the civilian panel
overruling the police chief, has others reluctant to proclaim a new
day in the troubled police force. ``The fact that this has happened
once in most of our memories does not mean that it signals the
police commission is truly independent,'' said Ramona Ripston, the
executive director of the American Civil Liberties Union chapter
here, which is calling for an appointed commission to oversee the
changes. ``There's too much evidence that they're not
independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, 54, a college-educated onetime bank teller rendered
homeless by mental illness, was shot last May after brandishing a
foot-long screwdriver at two officers who approached her to ask if
the shopping cart she was using had been stolen. The commission
unanimously agreed that the officer who killed Mitchell, Edward
Larrigan, had used flawed tactics leading to the shooting: He did
not take the screwdriver when he had an opportunity, he did not use
nonlethal options and he did not keep a safe distance from her.
</P>
<P>
   But it was divided over whether the shooting was within
department guidelines. In the majority opinion, three commissioners
said the evidence, including Mitchell's 102-pound frame, did not
support the officer's belief that he had been in imminent danger.
But the two dissenting commissioners found that Mitchell's conduct
justified the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitchell case has given rise to a new debate over how police
commissioners assess the validity of police shootings. In the past,
shootings have been examined in three parts: tactics leading to the
incident, drawing of the weapon and the use of force. The approach
allowed officials to criticize parts of an incident without
condemning it entirely. The Mitchell case is leading some to
question whether it is possible to find a shooting within policy
guidelines if the tactics that led to it were faulty.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Martin, Riordan's chief of staff, told the commissioners
that the question was a policy issue that deserved public debate
and should not be applied to the Mitchell case. Some commissioners
reportedly interpreted that instruction as lobbying by the mayor's
office for them to adopt Parks' position. Martin adamantly denied
that the mayor's office had lobbied the commissioners to reach a
certain conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The commission recommended ``administrative disapproval'' of the
shooting, meaning the case will now go to Parks for disciplining of
the officer. Punishment could range from from an official reprimand
to dismissal from the force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 1513EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000219.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2152 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      02-19 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic  
 THIS STORY ALSO MOVING IN THE ``L'' CATEGORY 
 RETRANSMITTING FOR THOSE WHO MIGHT HAVE MISSED IT. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``COLORS OF THE MOUNTAIN'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Da Chen (Random House, $25)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is that rarity in these times, a truly marvelous book. Da
Chen was born in 1962, in a tiny town in southern China, and his
memoir begins with his childhood stories of life during the
Cultural Revolution. Chen's grandfather had been a wealthy
landlord, reason enough to incur relentless mistreatment for him
and his family (he lived with Chen's parents and their five
children), as well as the loss of their house, land and most
possessions. Food was scarce, humiliation was waiting around every
corner, and the future seemed without promise. And yet, the view
through young Chen's eyes is remarkably cheerful, made so by his
curiosity and pugnacity and by his parents' enduring dignity in the
face of their dreadfully altered lives. This big-hearted and
sometimes even humorous story is written in simple, evocative
prose, and it ends as Chen leaves for college in Beijing. It's a
moving moment, but not the book's first _ we were misty before we
got past the dedication. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``THE BRETHREN'' &QL; 
 &UR; By John Grisham (Doubleday, $27.95) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to mock a rich man, but we must give Grisham credit:
He doesn't take the advance and run. His new novel is inventive and
unpredictable, and very different from any of his previous books.
It focuses on three judges who are incarcerated in a
minimum-security prison for sins ranging from tax evasion to
driving drunkenly over two hikers in Yellowstone. In jail, they
preside over a ``court'' in which inmates file grievances against
each other (witnesses are expected to lie, and verdicts are quick
and without appeal). The judges also run a mail scheme in which
they pose as young, nubile inmates, bait wealthy men on the
outside, then blackmail them for the gay sex talk in their letters.
Trouble brews when they target Aaron Lake, U.S. congressman from
Arizona and the presidential candidate backed by the powerful
director of the CIA. Everyone's sleazy here, and the efforts at
damage control are complex and entertaining. When this one lands on
the bestseller lists, the honor will be deserved.  &QL; 
 &UR; ``MATCH WITS WITH MENSA'' &QL; 
 &UR; (Perseus, $19.95) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We have found our omnipotence, and it is in vocabulary _ we will
stomp all challengers into the ground. It was the only subject in
this book at which we showed any prowess, but thank God there was
something. The editors say they have assembled more than 800
puzzles. We were struck by the inordinate amount of yakking that
precedes them. You must wade through much discussion of a category
_ trivia, analogies, logic etc. _ and a sometimes lengthy list of
acknowledgments before you get to the tests themselves, which makes
us think that Mensa members need rest between bouts of mental
exertion. We were also struck by how much Mensa members _ to be
one, you must score in the top two percent of the population on any
standard intelligence test _ like to look at themselves in the
mental mirror. But we digress. Here is what the editors consider to
be a ``warm-up'' trivia question: ``Domenikos Theotocopoulus is
better known as who?'' The answer is El Greco, the painter. We
looked it up.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``THE WHITE DEATH'' &QL; 
 &UR; By McKay Jenkins (Random House, $23.95) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins calls John McPhee his mentor, and you can see McPhee's
influence in the way Jenkins comes at his subject _ avalanches _
from all sides. His main path is the story of five young climbers
who died in an avalanche on Mount Cleveland in Montana's Glacier
National Park in 1969. He mixes the personal stories of those young
men with fascinating information about snow, mountains, rescues and
survival. He shows us how terrifying it is to be caught under snow,
not knowing which way is up (the only way to tell, he says, is to
spit _ whichever way it falls, you should dig, if you can move, in
the opposite direction), how you increase your chances for survival
if you remember to shut your mouth (many victims are found with
their mouths full of snow), how your chances plummet if you are not
rescued within minutes. Dogs have found people alive in 15 feet of
snow, sniffing them out by their individual scents. Each living
person smells different, Jenkins says. All corpses smell the same.
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 1515EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000219.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2153 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AUSTRIA-CHANCELLOR-NY     02-19 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-CHANCELLOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISOLATION OR NO, AUSTRIA WON'T CRAWL, SAYS ITS CHANCELLOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ Wolfgang Schuessel has only to gaze from his
window at the creamy Hapsburg palaces to know that the tumult of
history is no stranger to this town. But seldom has a modern
Austrian leader been as lonely as he is, or as angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is going to bring this government down from the
outside,'' the conservative Austrian chancellor said in an
interview. ``We stand firm, a small, independent country. Isolation
may last days, weeks or even one year, but we are not going to come
crawling and asking for favors.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacket off, bow tie, as ever, on, Schuessel looked indignant, a
man much maligned in a quaint country of comfortable cafes that
scarcely looks like a danger to Europe or the world.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of Austria's isolation lies in Schuessel's decision
this month to form a coalition government with the Freedom Party of
Joerg Haider, a right-wing populist who has made isolated, later
regretted, statements praising aspects of Hitler's rule. The
European Union downgraded its relations with Austria.
</P>
<P>
   This decision by 14 governments of the European Union against
the 15th member has provoked a furious debate about the meaning of
national sovereignty in a unifying Europe and about whether the
demands of what appears to be an emerging new international order
that its proponents say is based on morality can take precedence
over the democratic expression of a people's will.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly referring to France and Germany, the two countries most
vehement in their denunciation of him, Schuessel asked, ``Is this
the start of some new procedure that two big states tell other
European Union members what governments they should have?''
</P>
<P>
   In elections last October, Haider's Freedom Party took 27
percent of the vote, fractionally more than Schuessel's People
Party. The coalition, which ended 30 years of increasingly stalled
Social Democratic-led government, has 104 seats in the 183-member
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The untransparent, unfair and counterproductive methods used
against us are unacceptable,'' Schuessel said. ``The European Union
took six months to impose the first timid sanctions on Slobodan
Milosevic. And yet in three days, it imposes sanctions on a member
of the family.''
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor, who spent five years as foreign minister and so
knows all the ministers who have now turned against him, continued:
``I did not take Haider's past statements lightly and I would never
have formed this government without a strong and credible apology
from him. I would not have done this if I did not feel I could now
trust Haider. Watch us. There will be no shadows.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Schuessel's assurances, his invitations to one and all
to visit Vienna and his joint statement with Haider on the eve of
the government's formation promising an Austria in which
``xenophobia, anti-Semitism and racism'' have no place, France and
Germany have kept up a steady verbal assault.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer has
accused Schuessel of taking ``a false route,'' and French President
Jacques Chirac has spoken of an Austrian ``rupture'' of the
European Union's contract.
</P>
<P>
   Their statements have reflected a growing determination to turn
a union that was long essentially a trade bloc into an ever closer
political community with some aspects of a federal state, one bound
by a shared determination to ensure that Europe puts its terrible
20th century firmly behind it.
</P>
<P>
   This sudden acceleration of Europe's push for integration has
polarized the Continent, prompting widespread enthusiasm most
frequently articulated by French intellectuals and uneasiness in
some, mainly conservative quarters.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week with the German weekly Die Zeit,
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, a Social Democrat, said the
principles applied in Austria would also apply in Italy, if
necessary. ``Europe would have to intervene if neo-fascists were
again sitting at the Cabinet table. We cannot allow ourselves to
lower the standards we have set.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder was referring to the fact that the rightist National
Alliance led by Gianfranco Fini joined a government in 1994,
setting off an indignant reaction in Italy. Foreign Minister
Lamberto Dini said Fini was not Haider and accused the German
chancellor of a ``superficial, unjustified and arbitrary''
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, a political and legal minefield has been opened.
Schuessel, 54, said, ``We need procedures, we need transparency, we
need rules of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Several European ministers advised him to reconsider his
decision to ally with Haider, Schuessel said. But he received no
prior warning of the European sanctions, which include a freeze on
bilateral relations and a refusal to receive Austrian ambassadors
at anything above ``technical level.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, reflecting its ambitions, the European Union revised
its treaties to allow the sanctioning of member states in which
there are ``serious and persistent'' breaches of principles of
liberty, democracy and respect for human rights. Nobody has accused
Austria of any such transgressions, let alone persistent ones.
</P>
<P>
   But Haider's past reference to Nazi concentration camps as
``punishment camps,'' his praise of Hitler's labor policies and his
party's racist anti-immigration electoral posters have awakened
ghosts that Europe is determined to suppress, even if Haider has
never passed from words to deeds.
</P>
<P>
   Schuessel contrasted the European reaction with that of the
Clinton administration, whose approach he described as
``reasonable, moderate, positive and showing an understanding that
what matters are deeds.'' He said he had spoken more than once with
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   The United States briefly withdrew its ambassador and registered
its distaste for Haider's party, but has not imposed any punitive
measures. Schuessel said his government was determined to meet
certain ``American benchmarks'' laid down to measure progress on
issues like compensating Nazi-era slave laborers.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of immigration, the chancellor said the Freedom
Party had been obliged to drop the demands of some of its members
that there be ``zero immigration'' and that Austria would continue,
as it had in recent years, to restrict immigrants to a quota of
about 10,000 a year, plus about 10,000 seasonal workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our posture is to be open in a limited way,'' he said. ``The
United States is a land of immigration, but it is a huge continent.
Austria is a tiny country and cannot be a land of immigrants in
that way. This has nothing to do with xenophobia. It is merely a
practical point of view.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
