</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARYSHNIKOV0220-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Baryshnikov practices his modern moves in the seclusion of an
exotic nature preserve
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Passy
</P>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There are 7,500 acres of wide open space at
the White Oak Plantation _ and not an inch seems wasted.
</P>
<P>
   If you're lucky enough to receive an invitation to this posh
retreat, just north of Jacksonville, you can spend your day however
you choose. Canoeing on a secluded lake. Bowling in a private
two-lane alley. Even watching rhinos make love.
</P>
<P>
   Or, if you're Mikhail Baryshnikov, you can dance as long as your
52-year-old body will allow.
</P>
<P>
   It's all a little too bizarre _ the world's most heralded ballet
star of the last quarter-century in this remote northern Florida
paradise, a corporate hideaway-turned-cultural oasis where the rich
and famous congregate and rare breeds of animals laze in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can live here all year-round,'' says the Russian-born
Baryshnikov, known as Misha to virtually all the plantation's 350
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Although Baryshnikov has a house in suburban New York, he
escapes to White Oak whenever he can. He's here for some of the
same reasons that have drawn other big-name celebrities, from
President Clinton to Colin Powell to Julia Roberts. He plays a
little golf on the nine-hole course. He rides horses with his four
children. He travels the grounds in his lovingly restored 1957
Buick.
</P>
<P>
   But White Oak is far more than Baryshnikov's favorite vacation
spot: It's also where he comes to work. The sprawling plantation is
the birthplace of the company he founded 10 years ago: the White
Oak Dance Project. The troupe, which performs two programs this
week at the Kravis Center, has been at the heart of his transition
from ballet legend to modern-dance impresario.
</P>
<P>
   A MACHINE WAITING TO MOVE
</P>
<P>
   White Oak, even more than New York or Russia, is Baryshnikov's
spiritual home.
</P>
<P>
   You can sense as much when you make the long drive from the
small town of Yulee _ population 19,000 _ through the dirt roads
that lead to the plantation. His studio sits in the most clustered
part of the property, next to a series of buildings that house
everything from conference facilities to a state-of-the-art gym. An
oversized wooden structure that blends into the background of
countless pine trees _ ironically, there are few white oaks _ it's
far larger than the typical urban dance space. The windows let in a
pure, cool light one associates more with New England than North
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Clad in baggy sweats, Baryshnikov is already waiting alone in
the studio a little after 10 a.m. Regardless of the repeated
surgeries he's endured to fix what a three-decade career has
wrought, his 5-foot-7-inch torso remains like that of a
bantamweight champion, all compressed strength, a machine waiting
to move. His dog, Maggie, a doormat of a boxer, stays constantly at
his side _ until the dancers arrive and he directs her into a
corner with a sharp command. ``She was chasing a deer the other
day, and she's not herself,'' Baryshnikov says by way of apology
for her sluggish behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Baryshnikov's seven-member company rarely spends much time at
White Oak anymore, although he remains a frequent visitor. The
current rehearsal period, which started in late January and runs up
to the Kravis engagement, is the longest the ensemble has been at
the plantation in years. But there's something about each visit
that clearly feeds the company's soul. Unlike New York, where so
many dance groups are based, White Oak is a place with no agenda,
no politics, no spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know if I would have had enough patience with
New York,'' Baryshnikov says, mulling the question of whether he
could have started White Oak elsewhere. ``New York doesn't need
another dance company.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does White Oak necessarily need Baryshnikov and the White
Oak Dance Project. But there's a reason for their presence.
</P>
<P>
   The plantation is the brainchild of the late Howard Gilman, a
New York arts patron who struck up a friendship with Baryshnikov
right after he defected to the West in 1974 and became the ballet
world's poster boy. Not so incidentally, Gilman was also heir to
the Gilman Paper Co., based near White Oak in St. Marys, Ga. The
family had owned the 7,500-acre North Florida estate since 1938 but
considered it little more than a rustic hunting camp. When Gilman
took over the company, he envisioned the plantation as something
else. In the '70s, he began turning the property into one of the
world's most private play yards _ complete with 15 residences,
pools, game rooms and movie theater _ to woo potential clients. He
also complemented that mission with a conservation program that's
the envy of many a first-class zoo, protecting about 400 animals,
including giraffes, tigers, okapis, cheetahs, wolves and Florida
panthers. ``Most guests think we're like a Jurassic Park,'' says
Ricky Bridges, a White Oak supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   THE LOCAL VIEW
</P>
<P>
   Ask the locals what they think of White Oak, and you'll get a
range of responses. Those in high places are unabashedly
supportive. ``It is wonderful,'' says John Mead, an active member
of the chamber of commerce who owns a frame and trophy shop in town
and has been to the plantation for special events. Since entrance
is strictly by invitation, he secures a few guest spots and sells
them at a premium of $75 to benefit a local charity. ``That was a
bargain,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Others maintain a sense of skepticism about the place _ and all
the powerful folks who pass through it. ``A lot of people come
here, kings and all that crap,'' says Trisha Gose, who runs the
Down Home Market just a couple of blocks from the downtown traffic
light (yes, there's only one). She claims a girlfriend of hers who
works at White Oak even scored a marriage proposal from a member of
some visiting royal family.
</P>
<P>
   But do the locals know that Baryshnikov is in their back yard?
Some do, some don't. And, sad to say, a few have trouble
recognizing the name. ``It's in the back of my head somewhere,''
says the clerk at the Holiday Inn Express that sits a few miles
from the plantation's gate. Perhaps that is part of the reason the
notoriously media-shy Baryshnikov likes to come here. In New York,
he can't walk down a street without being recognized. At White Oak,
he's an unknown _ and with all its creature comforts, he doesn't
have to bother with a trip into town. Nights are often spent in the
company of the dancers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watch some stupid TV shows,'' he says between bites of a
cheeseburger during lunch at the plantation's small cafeteria. ``We
were watching ``The Sopranos'' the other day. Fabulous, fabulous
show.''
</P>
<P>
   It's as if Baryshnikov has the run of the place. Ask the guy
with the clipboard at the entrance if you might be able to see some
of the animals after visiting the dance studio and he says, ``If
you can get with Misha, he might hook you up.'' Other employees
talk of the dance legend as if he were family _ which he
practically is considering the time Baryshnikov has spent here with
his four children (one by former flame, actress Jessica Lange).
``My children grew up here, they started to swim, they started to
ride horses here,'' Baryshnikov says.
</P>
<P>
   It's a life of privilege _ all White Oak visitors stay for free
_ and Baryshnikov must sense it as he asks an attendant to arrange
for a group outing or has a golf pro give him pointers on his
swing. (''It's my time, instead of going to the psychiatrist,'' he
jokes of the latter.) But there's also a sense that what he has at
White Oak, he's been given through friendship and loyalty. ``He was
the closest friend. He was like older brother,'' Baryshnikov says
of Gilman, speaking as always with a thick Russian accent. ``He
knew how much I loved the place.''
</P>
<P>
   AN HONEST PERSPECTIVE
</P>
<P>
   Gilman, who died in 1998, must have also known that Baryshnikov
needed space and isolation to pursue his adventurous, full-throttle
foray into modern dance. And his foundation's commitment remains as
strong today. When Baryshnikov started White Oak, it followed a
nine-year stint as artistic director of the American Ballet
Theatre. It was Baryshnikov's last great run as a ballet dancer,
even though he used the company as a platform to branch into
contemporary work. The more snide critics suggested the move was
because he could no longer handle the physical stress of ballet.
But Baryshnikov insisted it was because modern work offered a more
honest perspective. (''Mannered art'' is how he once described
ballet.) White Oak, which he began in 1990 as a partnership with
``enfant terrible'' choreographer Mark Morris, would be his new
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Gilman) said, why don't you guys come, and I will build a
studio for you,'' Baryshnikov recalls of the company's origins.
(That first makeshift dance space was replaced in a few years with
the current elaborate studio, which even Baryshnikov admits is ``a
little too big.'') In a way, the idea harked back to the earliest
days of modern dance, when pioneer Ted Shawn brought his charges
into the woods and experimented with the concept of movement as an
earthly expression. Baryshnikov also liked the inherent isolation:
Free from the distractions of the city, his dancers, an all-star
group of professionals in their 20s and 30s from other modern and
ballet companies, would become a true unit. ``The idea was to get
together ... have fun, have some hard work and a lot of bonding,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, the concept remains basically that. What's
changed, however, is the company's reputation and outlook. White
Oak is no longer the new kid on the modern block; it's an
established powerhouse, one of the few arts organizations of any
kind that doesn't have to seek nonprofit status to pay its way. (Of
course, there's Gilman's largesse to thank partially for that.) And
its scope of choreographers has expanded well beyond Morris,
although he continues to remain an important contributor. Among the
major names Baryshnikov has wooed to White Oak are Lar Lubovitch
and Paul Taylor, but lesser-known, young choreographers are also
part of the mix. (Baryshnikov has toyed with the idea of doing a
piece by Lake Worth's Demetrius Klein, a recent Guggenheim fellow;
for now, he's planning a joint program with Klein's company in
Hollywood, Fla., this spring.)
</P>
<P>
   In essence, White Oak is something that modern dance has never
truly had: a repertory company with emphasis on the current scene.
``I rarely, rarely bring back (works). It's much more interesting
to do something new,'' Baryshnikov says. And it has something even
rarer to the genre: the power of celebrity. Although decisions
about programming and touring are made by the entire group of
dancers, it would be naive to think this company would be where it
is today without Baryshnikov, who by his mere presence has made
modern dance acceptable to mass audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, that idea has started to wear thin in recent years _
and the company is having to raise money for a project in the fall,
a first in its history. Even the Kravis dates have yet to sell out,
a marked contrast to Baryshnikov's first visit to the West Palm
Beach center (with Twyla Tharp) in 1993. But to Baryshnikov's
credit, he's stuck to his vision, plugging a few audience-friendly
works into the mix, but refusing to shy away from more daring
material. ``If the audience is interested in dance, they will get
there somehow,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Yvonne Rainer, one of the choreographers recently
invited to the North Florida studio to create a piece for the
group. A member of the avant-garde Judson Dance Theater in the
'60s, Rainer left dance in 1975 to pursue a filmmaking career. What
drew her back to the stage? Baryshnikov, naturally. ``I said to
Misha that more people will see this dance than who saw 15 years'
worth of my work from 1960 to 1975,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   PATIENCE NOT A VIRTUE
</P>
<P>
   But a day at Baryshnikov's studio, which has also been used by
other prominent dance groups, is not a star-studded affair. It's
the business of dance as usual. There is no company class per se,
just a quick, no-nonsense warm-up. Whether at the barre or standing
on the floor, Baryshnikov relays a few movement ideas to his
company, and the members respond accordingly. There is nothing
high-pressured about his manner _ he asks rather than orders.
``Shall we do the 'rond de jambe' ?'' he says at one point,
referring to the circular movement of the legs. But with that
sullen stare _ his blue eyes seemed burned into their sockets _
it's obvious he doesn't suffer many mistakes. Patience is not one
of his signature virtues. ``Hey, what's cooking in there?'' he says
sharply when a couple of dancers take too long during a bathroom
break.
</P>
<P>
   After the warm-up, Baryshnikov freely hands over the company to
Rainer, who runs through her challenging 45-minute work, a dense
mix of abstract movement, death-bed speeches and the occasional
running in circles. In keeping with White Oak's democratic design,
Baryshnikov shares the stage equally with five other dancers, at
one point jostling with them in a scene that could have been lifted
from a New York subway during rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   Baryshnikov's star presence does pose a challenge, Rainer
admits: Do you ignore it or acknowledge it? For the most part, she
chooses the former. But she does give him an extraordinary solo, a
slow-movement section in drag that suits the thought-provoking
dancer he's become. And she tosses in a revealing line for one of
the other dancers, who points to Baryshnikov and asks the audience
if they're looking for him: In perfect post-modern fashion, she
subverts the crowd's expectations into part of the theatrical
experience. Rainer explains it all by offering this apt summation
of White Oak: ``It's not the Misha show, although it is the Misha
show.''
</P>
<P>
   THE STUDIO IS THE STUDIO
</P>
<P>
   It's a situation not lost on the dancers, either. Many can
recall their feelings of humility when they were contacted by
Baryshnikov about working with the company. But the feelings don't
last: He's just a man, after all. ``I had the image of who he was,
but then I met him, and he was so personable and easy-going and
relaxed. I just immediately forgot,'' says Rosalynde LeBlanc, the
newest member of the company. ``He seems to create an atmosphere
where everybody evens themselves out.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the opportunity to come to White Oak affect the
process, the dancers insist. Oh, there are the not-so-small details
of staying at a private getaway, including being fed gourmet meals
(tonight's dinner features homemade venison sausage, roast Cornish
game hen and a honey pecan tart) and having a staff on call. The
dancers joke that they leave the plantation just so they can remind
themselves what it's like to open their wallets. But the studio is
the studio. ``The time you spend ... is spent with the
choreographer's mind, and that's true whether it's a New York
studio or here,'' says Emily Coates, who left a promising career
with the New York City Ballet to dance for White Oak. ``These other
things are just this added luxury.''
</P>
<P>
   As the day draws to a close, the luxury indeed becomes an
afterthought. Baryshnikov is now just another observer in the
studio, watching the group rehearse a different Rainer work, to be
performed later this year. He is quiet, almost melancholic,
reflecting that he would like to join the company in the piece,
except ``there's a few elements which my knee wouldn't allow.'' But
after watching him throughout the long morning, where he also
rehearsed John Jasperse's hyperkinetic ``See Through Knot'' without
breaking into a sweat, it's hard to believe he's past his prime.
During lunch, he offers a blunt assessment of what it means to be a
52-year-old dancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not things to do with the physical,'' he says. ``I can
still dance with them in difficult pieces ... It's an internal
realization. You have to prepare your exit somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   At White Oak, Baryshnikov has been able to dance _ and think.
It's all too easy to see the plantation as a place where an aging
former ballet star gets the royal treatment. But the remote setting
has clearly freed Baryshnikov's mind and, in turn, allowed his
still graceful body to work what wonders it can. Here, the final
curtain has been placed on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
