<HEADER>
A2159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-JETER-ART-N     02-19 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-JETER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETER SEEKS IMPROVEMENT, RIGHT DOWN TO THE CORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Mike Buddie played with a skinny kid in Class A
baseball seven years ago, so frail, Buddie recalled, that it seemed
he might break in half if a runner slid into him.
</P>
<P>
   That seemingly fragile youngster has been at work again in this
last off-season, adopting another weight-training program _ this to
increase the strength in his legs and his middle body, his physical
core. Buddie laughed at his memory of Yankee shortstop Derek Jeter,
compared with what Jeter looks like now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went from being Kevin Garnett to Shaquille O'Neal,'' said
Buddie, referring to the CD-thin forward from the Minnesota
Timberwolves and the mountain range of a center for the Los Angeles
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter has gained 18 pounds since the end of last season, pushing
his weight to 203 pounds, but the increase is not apparent in the
usual manner. It's a baseball cliche to arrive in spring training
with massive biceps, with a chest and neck muscles puffed up, and
Jeter has worked out his upper body, too. But he doesn't have that
extra-large look. He is still lean, but just appears stronger, in
the upper, middle and lower portions of his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get stronger,'' Jeter said. ``I'm not trying to
win any body-building contests.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankee Manager Joe Torre said: ``Oh, wow, he's gotten big. He's
gotten big, and he's been able to maintain his flexibility, which
is wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter's agent, Casey Close, had long encouraged the shortstop to
consider the training regimen taught and tendered at the
International Performance Institute in Bradenton, Fla., less than
an hour from here. Boston shortstop Nomar Garciaparra developed his
strength program there, actually living at the institute one
off-season, and now dozens of baseball players and athletes from
other sports have begun working out there.
</P>
<P>
   Prepared to begin his off-season training in earnest, Jeter, 25,
visited the facility last December with Russ Orr, the Yankees'
strength and conditioning coordinator for the minor leagues. In
consultation with the Yankees' staff, Jeter added elements of the
institute's program to his own, going through them on a daily basis
at the Yankees' minor league facility here, aided by Orr.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it's going to do is help you through the course of a
season,'' Jeter said. ``When you lift weights, you get stronger,
but the season is so long, you want to be as strong in September
and October as you were at the beginning of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter, who weighed 195 at the start of 1999, lost about 10
pounds during the season, and felt weaker. He wants to maintain his
weight better, to maintain his long-term stamina. This off-season,
he began training his lower body, his legs, for the first time.
Some of that training is standard leg work, squat-lifting free
weights.
</P>
<P>
   Other parts, adopted from what the institute emphasizes, work to
increase the explosive movements. A sandbag weighing anywhere from
15 to 30 pounds is placed on Jeter's shoulders, like a collar
around his neck, and he lunges forward, to the sides, backward,
repeating the movements over and over, to increase the strength in
his legs.
</P>
<P>
   The results become apparent particularly in August and
September, said Luke Wilcox, a Yankees outfielder who has worked
out at the institute for the last three off-seasons. The baseball
season tends to sap leg strength, and suddenly, Wilcox said, he has
found the spring in his legs in those last months to chase down a
distant fly ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, you overlook your legs in terms of playing,''
Jeter said. ``People go and lift and try to get big arms and a big
chest, and they sort of forget about their legs. This year, I'm
trying to use my legs more when I hit, and hopefully, it'll help.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter has also concentrated on increasing the strength in what
is referred to by strength coaches as the core, the abdomen and
flanks, the area that connects the upper torso to the hips. To do
this, he will lean against a physioball _ imagine a superstrong
beach ball _ with weights in each hand, and as he moves, the middle
body is forced to provide the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, took Jeter on a
tour of Yankee Stadium right after Jeter signed with the team out
of high school, and remembered Jeter being frail. ``He's so much
stronger,'' Cashman said.
</P>
<P>
   For a hitter, additional strength can translate into more bat
speed; more bat speed means the hitter can wait extra milliseconds
to swing. That's more time to determine if the pitch is going to be
in the strike zone, more time to identify whether it is a slider
moving outside or a fastball running high, more time to decide
whether to swing at all, or whether to attack.
</P>
<P>
   And once Jeter hits the ball, the additional bat speed means he
will hit the ball harder and longer. Buddie, a right-handed
pitcher, has been shagging fly balls during Jeter's batting
practices for almost eight years now, and figures that he is
driving the ball an additional 30 to 40 feet, ``at least.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter rarely used to drive the ball to left field in batting
practice, Buddie said, but Jeter has become an all-field hitter as
he has gained strength and experience. The other day, Jeter took
batting practice with Tino Martinez and Darryl Strawberry on a
spacious practice field at the Yankees' minor-league facility, in
less than ideal conditions for long-distance driving: a batting
practice pitcher throwing the ball at diminished speeds, a
crosswind and Jeter's timing at the plate not being optimal at this
time of year.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he launched towering shots over the fence in left
and left-center field, hammered the ball against the black screen
that extends some 20 feet above the fence in dead center, and
reached the fences in right-center and right repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   What the others have noticed here this spring, since Jeter began
the program to strengthen the muscles in his middle body, is how
much more explosively he is turning on the ball. Imagine a rubber
band in three segments: With the newly developed core, it's as if
Jeter has strengthened the middle part of that rubber band, the
part that twists and then releases explosively.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as two years ago, Jeter's home run potential was
talked about in terms of 15 to 20 a season; last spring, those
estimates changed to 25 a year. Now, after slugging 24 home runs in
1999 _ and not at the expense of his batting average, which
increased to .349 _ reasonable baseball scouts and executives tend
to talk about Jeter hitting 30 to 40 home runs a year, even while
remaining an opposite-field hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Gwynn, the San Diego outfielder with 3,067 hits in his
career, stopped at second base during the 1998 World Series and
told the right-handed-hitting Jeter to just keep doing what he has
always done: lining the ball to right-center and right field. Jeter
is cognizant that this has made him successful, and he has been
careful not to stray from his basic approach. But he is trying to
refine what he does well, through strength training.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee pitcher David Cone said: ``He could stay in New York and
do a thousand endorsement deals. He chooses to stay in Tampa and
work on his game. He's clearly not satisfied with his success; he
wants more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
