<HEADER>
A2160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-BREAST-CANCER-NY     02-19 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BREAST-CANCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TREATMENT OF ADVANCED BREAST CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Feb. 20:
</P>
<P>
   Women who suffer from advanced, intractable breast cancer have
been confronted with discouraging developments over the past year.
Thousands had hoped that, after all else failed, an arduous
procedure known as a bone marrow transplant might save them. But
four major clinical trials reported last May found that women with
advanced breast cancer who were given bone marrow transplants fared
no better than women given conventional chemotherapy. This month, a
well-publicized study in South Africa that appeared to show some
benefit of the bone marrow transplant was acknowledged to be a
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Even discouraging results from well-conducted studies are
helpful in the fight against the disease. This is particularly true
in the case of the controversial transplants. For years now,
desperately ill women have sought out this therapy _ which involves
removing some of the marrow, hitting the patient with high doses of
toxic drugs and then replacing the marrow _ even though there has
been no scientific evidence that it is effective. Under pressure
from patients, hospitals and lawmakers, insurers have been paying
for these very costly and difficult treatments, with the result
that few women have been willing to participate in clinical studies
in which some would be assigned to a control group and get
conventional treatments. In the last decade, as many as 30,000
breast cancer patients may have received bone marrow transplants
while only 1,000 participated in studies designed to test whether
the procedure works.
</P>
<P>
   The desire of very sick patients to try even an unproven therapy
is understandable. But had more women been enrolled in the studies,
answers about the effectiveness of the treatment might have been
achieved earlier. The resources spent on this treatment might have
been better directed to other approaches. The National Breast
Cancer Coalition, an advocacy group, concluded that this treatment
does not benefit women with breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is reason to continue with more clinical trials
because there may be subsets of patients for whom this treatment is
effective. Recently, Aetna/US Healthcare, a prominent insurer,
decided to stop covering bone marrow transplants for breast cancer
patients, though other insurers will still do so. But Aetna will
continue to pay for the treatment if it is provided in a federally
approved clinical trial. Other companies, including a coalition of
major insurers in New Jersey, are agreeing to pay for experimental
cancer treatments in clinical trials. That is a sound step toward
finding answers for breast cancer and other diseases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 1522EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
