<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DIALLO-LAWYERING-NYT     02-19 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIALLO-LAWYERING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNTOWN CRITICS PAN DIALLO LAWYERING
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the hallways of the sprawling Manhattan Criminal
Courts Building, lawyers have long made a sport of griping about
judges' decisions, gossiping about their colleagues' performances
and engaging in Monday morning trial quarterbacking. Over the last
two weeks, the focus of courthouse chatter has turned northward, to
the trial of four New York police officers accused of killing
Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Without knowing all the facts of the case or seeing every moment
of prosecutors' and defense lawyers' performances, the shotgun
opinions of Manhattan lawyers border on speculation. And surely,
the lawyering in Albany is no worse and perhaps better than much of
the lawyering in Downtown Manhattan. It is simply more public.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a series of impromptu interviews last week, Manhattan
defense lawyers and some judges contended that the lawyering on
both sides had at times been mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   Both camps have had impressive moments, courthouse veterans
said, but prosecutors have lacked passion and defense lawyers have
made amateurish mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, criticism focused on the defense team of Stephen
Worth, John Patten, Steven Brounstein, James Culleton and Bennett
M. Epstein.
</P>
<P>
   Worth and Patten first erred, some critics said, by asking
questions of a prosecution witness that allowed her to testify that
she had heard someone say, ``OK, OK, we just want to say this,''
after the shooting. That statement could lead jurors to suspect a
police cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers' decision then to call Schrrie Elliot as a defense
witness was ``a rookie mistake,'' critics said. Elliot saw the
shooting but did not want to testify for the defense, and because
of earlier court decisions and her refusal to meet with the defense
lawyers, they did not know exactly what she would say when she took
the stand. Their move violated a cardinal rule of trial lawyering,
critics said: Never ask a question without knowing the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Elliot ended up giving an account that was so potentially
damaging to the officers that the defense team had her declared a
hostile witness and cross-examined her to undermine her
credibility. ``It appears to be a mistake that there is no good
explanation for,'' said David Stern, a Manhattan defense lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Another lawyer said it would have been wiser to let the officers
_ and no one else _ tell the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you've got Mother Teresa looking out the window, you
don't need anyone other than the cops,'' the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   And some critics contended that the defense did a poor job
coaching the four officers on their testimony, which the critics
said was sometimes hard to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Several lawyers and court officers expressed skepticism about
the officers' account of the first moments of their encounter with
Diallo outside his Bronx apartment building. The men testified that
they had used the words ``please'' and ``sir'' and had identified
themselves as New York police officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police don't talk that way,'' said Frank Rothman, a Manhattan
defense lawyer. ``They don't speak that way in that neighborhood,
especially in a potentially dangerous situation.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, prosecutors have also erred, lawyers
contended, delivering a sometimes flat performance and failing to
hammer away at their argument that Officers Sean Carroll and Edward
McMellon, who each fired 16 shots at Diallo, acted recklessly. The
two other officers, Richard Murphy and Kenneth Boss, fired four and
five shots, respectively. The issue of recklessness could prove
pivotal as jurors consider the lesser charges of manslaughter or
criminally negligent homicide. The officers are charged with
second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said the prosecution's cross-examination of Carroll, the
first defendant to take the stand, was lackluster and too brief.
And once prosecutors failed to knock Carroll off balance, they
appeared to lose steam in their other cross-examinations, lawyers
said. Several said they were surprised that prosecutors did not
cross-examine the defense's final witness, a police procedure
expert.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Ricco, a Manhattan defense lawyer, said one of the
prosecutors' biggest errors was failing to raise the role that race
might have played in the shooting. He and other lawyers said the
issue hanging over the trial was whether the four white police
officers were more suspicious of Diallo because he was black.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should have been dealt with more honestly,'' said Ricco,
referring to the race issue. ``When that occurs, the community has
more confidence in the verdict, whatever it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Kuby, a defense lawyer in the Manhattan courthouse on
Thursday afternoon, agreed that both sides' performance had been
mediocre at times. But he pointed out the folly of legal
handicapping, and noted that no one had any idea what the most
important audience _ the jury _ was thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a serious problem with treating criminal trials as a
sporting event,'' he said. ``In a sporting event, you know the
score by looking at the scoreboard, but in a criminal trial if you
try to be a sportscaster, you put undue emphasis on certain events.
You're always surprised by what the jurors find relevant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 1541EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
