<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-MARBURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPECIAL BIRTHDAY FOR MARBURY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Home for Stephon Marbury was never
really the icy terrain of Minnesota where he started his National
Basketball Association career and spent the first two-and-a-half
seasons of his career.
</P>
<P>
   When he forced his way out of there last season, conspiring with
his agent, David Falk, to create a way to bring him back to the
metropolitan area where he had grown up and forged his schoolboy
legend, he left behind few friends and no regrets. Still, after a
hard year spent with the Nets since the trade that brought him
here, Marbury admits to some pangs of emotion, feelings that will
surely resurface when he returns to face his former team for the
first time on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Nets struggles this season, Marbury would hear of
Kevin Garnett's dominating opponents out West, and suddenly
Minnesota did not seem so cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss playing with Kevin,'' Marbury said. ``I miss playing
for Flip Saunders. I loved playing basketball in Minnesota. It was
great playing ball there. The fans are unbelievable. The coach is a
great coach. He knew exactly what he wanted. He knew what he was
doing. It was fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin McHale put the team together, put the right pieces into
the team to make a championship team. It was fun. But I just wanted
to come back home.''
</P>
<P>
   His return to Minnesota comes in the Nets' only nationally
televised appearance of the season. It also falls on his 23rd
birthday, providing him with the likely, but unwanted, gift of an
arena filled with fans booing his every move and a team that most
likely remembers how he forced his way out of town. It will be more
frigid inside the arena than outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's ironic, very ironic,'' Marbury said. ``National TV on
my birthday. It's like, `Let's see him have a bad birthday.'''
</P>
<P>
   Marbury dismisses the notion that this appearance in the Target
Center will be any different than any other game, reminding anyone
who asks that he has already returned to Madison Square Garden as
an enemy and that it cannot be worse than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to win, like I want to do every day,'' he said.
``I know it's going to be a different situation, but nothing like
the Garden. I play according to the game. I play the same way every
time I go on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   At the trading deadline last year Marbury was dealt to the Nets,
along with Chris Carr and Milwaukee's Elliot Perry, in a three-way
deal that sent Sam Cassell, Chris Gatling, Brian Evans and the
Nets' first-round pick in 1999 to Milwaukee, and Terrell Brandon to
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The deal broke up the dreams that Marbury and Garnett would
replace Utah's John Stockton and Karl Malone as the next great
inside-outside tandem. Each has continued to flourish without the
other, with Garnett averaging 23.2 points a game, 10th-best in the
NBA, while Marbury is 13th at 22.3. Garnett is fourth in the league
in rebounding at 12 a game and Marbury is eighth in assists with
8.4 a game.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury, who counts Garnett among the few friends he left behind
despite the rumors of alleged jealousy regarding Garnett's
contract, does not believe that his former teammates will hold a
grudge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're looking at me like that,'' Marbury said.
``They know I'm the same way. They're coming at me. I'm coming at
them. They already know that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Marbury is enjoying life close to his home, a quick drive
from the Brooklyn neighborhood where he grew up and then starred at
Lincoln High, it is the basketball things that sometimes make him
wonder.
</P>
<P>
   But even though he speaks wistfully of Garnett's skills and
Saunders' coaching, he never voices his doubts about his current
teammates or coach. During the Nets' dreadful 2-15 start, he was
criticized for his play for the first time in his career and
alienated teammates by taking the floor for a practice with the
words ``33 Alone'' inscribed on his sneakers. But he never
reconsiders the decision he made to force the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' he said. ``Never. When I make a decision, I
think about it before I do it. When I do it, that's it. It's done.
That's how I feel, and I stand on my decision like I stand on my
word. That's all you got in this world. People trust you from what
you tell them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
