<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-HOUSING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY SPENDS TOO MUCH ON OFFICERS' HOUSING, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Texas)  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Defense Department has been spending too much
money on housing for high-ranking officers, according to the
department's inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   The Army, Navy and Air Force have repeatedly surpassed the
annual spending limits imposed by Congress for the maintenance and
repair of officer housing in the last three years, the inspector
general said in a newly published report.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Congress gave the services larger budgets for special
repairs, they exceeded the allowed amounts, the report said. Other
violations cited in the report include the repair and maintenance
of residences with money set aside for other uses.
</P>
<P>
   The report, released at the end of January, comes when the
Defense Department is seeking more money to improve the housing of
its rank-and-file service members. Poor housing is one of the major
reasons people leave the military.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration proposed this month increasing the
Pentagon's housing budget by $3 billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Although the amounts spent on housing for admirals and generals
are relatively small, the report said the military failed to comply
with congressional instructions and the policies of the Department
of Defense.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has been concerned about the issue since last May, when
the Navy and the Air Force reported improperly financed repairs on
several large homes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Navy said it had financed $5.7 million worth of
repairs to the homes occupied by three admirals using money
intended for other purposes between 1992 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's report examined generals' and admirals'
houses, which are the most expensive to maintain in the Defense
Department's housing system.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1980s, Congress has limited spending on repair and
maintenance to $25,000 a year for each of these residences. If a
service thinks a project will require more than $25,000, it must
get congressional approval for the extra financing.
</P>
<P>
   The study by the inspector general examined 79 of the military's
882 homes for top officers. One of the largest violations was at
Fort Belvoir in Virginia, according to the report. In fiscal 1997,
the Army spent $47,230 to renovate one house, almost double the
limit allowed by Congress, without seeking congressional approval,
the report says.
</P>
<P>
   In another violation, the Navy sought congressional approval for
a large renovation project last year in Corpus Christi, Texas, but
went beyond the approved budget without notifying Congress, the
report says. The project received a budget of $258,600 and reported
spending $257,999. But the report says spending eclipsed $295,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy and the Air Force have already taken action to correct
some of the violations, but the inspector general still recommended
that each of the three services begin complete investigations of
the incidents cited in the report.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Army and the Air Force said they would follow the
report's recommendations and begin investigations. But the Navy
said it saw no need to investigate further.
</P>
<P>
   In a written response to the inspector general, the Navy said it
was already ``investigating potential violations'' and had taken
steps to correct previous ones.
</P>
<P>
   It also said that many of the residences occupied by
high-ranking officers ``are historic treasures that require
extraordinary efforts to maintain in a condition suitable for
simple habitation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
