<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2169 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OLD-MURDER-ART-NYT &LR;      02-19 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-MURDER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1985 DISAPPEARANCE FINALLY REACHES COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.D., Nev.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT13 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ko) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fourteen years ago, prosecutors say, Dr. Robert Bierenbaum
committed a murder that for more than a decade would stand as the
perfect crime. They say he killed his young wife in the couple's
Upper East Side apartment, rented a plane and dumped her body into
the Atlantic Ocean. She was never found.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, when a female torso washed up on a remote
beach on Staten Island, it was mistakenly thought to be that of
Gail Katz-Bierenbaum, and the body was buried and mourned by the
Katz family.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after a decade of inaction on the case, prosecutors have
charged Bierenbaum, 44, with second-degree murder, contending that
circumstantial evidence and missteps by the wealthy plastic surgeon
in the years since his wife's disappearance will prove his guilt.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, Bierenbaum ``absolutely and unequivocally''
denied the charges, and his lawyer, Scott Greenfield, accused
prosecutors of engaging in ``rampant speculation, character
assassination and flagrant hearsay.'' He also suggested that
Katz-Bierenbaum might have killed herself, died at the hands of a
paramour or run off with one. Prosecutors responded that
Katz-Bierenbaum's lovers had nothing to do with her disappearance
and would even testify against the surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Katz, the missing woman's brother, said he hoped
Bierenbaum would finally be held accountable. ``I really, for
myself, believe that he did this,'' said Katz, who was 15 when his
older sister disappeared. ``I can't even look at him now.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor left New York in 1990 and has since remarried,
fathering a daughter and building successful plastic surgery
practices in Las Vegas and then North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is expected to be held this fall, and in it, a
Manhattan jury will learn the details of an Upper East Side
marriage that on its surface was the picture of promise, but in
truth was troubled, violent and adulterous, prosecutors say. The
panel will be asked to determine whether Gail Katz-Bierenbaum, who
was never found, is alive or dead. And it must decide whether her
now graying husband was a hapless victim of circumstance or a young
criminal genius.
</P>
<P>
   The case began unfolding at 8:30 p.m. on July 8, 1985, when
Robert Bierenbaum walked into the 19th Precinct station house on
the Upper East Side and reported his wife missing. Bierenbaum said
he had last seen his wife at their home the previous morning,
according to the police report.
</P>
<P>
   Katz-Bierenbaum was described by her husband as in ``good''
physical condition but ``poor'' mental condition. And the police
report said that she had had a history of mental illness and that
she had ``had argument with husband.''
</P>
<P>
   A follow-up police report said Bierenbaum reported ``that he had
been fighting with his wife over the weekend'' and that he had last
seen her when she left their apartment on July 7. He also reported
that she was suicidal and that the couple had undergone marriage
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   The case was assigned to the missing persons bureau. When
Katz-Bierenbaum failed to turn up five days after she was reported
missing, the police reinterviewed her husband.
</P>
<P>
   The substance of this interview is likely to be the foundation
of prosecutors' circumstantial case. During the interview, a
detective asked the doctor, then a resident at Maimonides Medical
Center in Brooklyn, if he had ever tried to strangle his wife.
Bierenbaum responded abruptly that ``he did not want to talk about
it,'' according to the police report. The detectives then asked
about ``an incident with a cat.'' Bierenbaum responded with ``the
same abrupt answer,'' according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had threatened to jump out of a window during an
argument, he said yes, but again said he did not want to talk about
it. Detectives then asked the young surgeon if he knew anyone named
Ken or Anthony, an apparent reference to Katz-Bierenbaum's lovers.
Bierenbaum replied that their ``names are in her book.''
</P>
<P>
   And as the interview ended, according to the police report, the
young doctor told the detective, ``This don't look right and people
are going to start to wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   The series of bizarre and violent incidents referred to in the
interview are the central reasons Katz-Bierenbaum's family cite for
their long-running suspicions about the doctor. In a fight just
before the couple's 1982 marriage, Bierenbaum tried to drown the
couple's cat in a toilet after complaining that his fiancee cared
more about the cat than about him, said Alayne Katz, the missing
women's sister.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, on Nov. 8, 1983, Katz-Bierenbaum filed a complaint
with the police stating that her husband had strangled her to the
point where she lost consciousness. Two weeks later, Michael Stone,
a psychiatrist counseling the couple, drafted a letter that he
wanted Katz-Bierenbaum to sign to release him from liability should
anything happen to her.
</P>
<P>
   The letter stated that Katz-Bierenbaum was aware Stone had told
her ``that for reasons of my own safety'' she should no longer live
with her husband. It referred to ``the unpredictable nature of my
husband's physical assaults'' and warned that, ``If I do not heed
this advice, I must accept the consequences, including the
possibility of personal injury, or death, at the hands of my
husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Alayne Katz said her sister showed the letter to her mother but
never signed it.
</P>
<P>
   The police also later discovered that Bierenbaum had rented a
single-engine Cessna and took a two-hour flight the day his wife
disappeared. According to records from Essex County Airport in
Caldwell, N.J., the young surgeon flew over the waters of the
Atlantic Ocean between Cape May, N.J., and Montauk Point, N.Y., for
two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Because the disappearance was considered a missing persons case
at first, the couple's apartment, the doctor's car and the plane he
had rented were not searched until 18 months after
Katz-Bierenbaum's disappearance. No traces of blood, hair or any
evidence of a murder were found.
</P>
<P>
   After the case languished for a decade, prosecutors reopened the
investigation in 1997 because of the lingering suspicions of Andy
Rosenzweig, a former police detective who had become chief
investigator in the Manhattan district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators went to Las Vegas, where Bierenbaum lived from
1990 to 1995, and to his current home in North Dakota, interviewing
former girlfriends, friends and fellow doctors, according to court
papers.
</P>
<P>
   In court, Daniel Bibb, an assistant district attorney, said the
surgeon had given inconsistent explanations for his wife's
disappearance in the years since.
</P>
<P>
   Bierenbaum's lawyer argues the prosecution has no body, no
confession and no case. He accuses them of engaging in a ``public
witch hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   The missing woman's brother and sister say they want answers
from their former brother-in-law and finally some sense of closure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thought that he has been free all this time, and has a
wife and a child and has been practicing, it's extremely
upsetting,'' said Steven Katz. ``His life has gone on, but from
that point forward my family's life stopped.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
