u s BC-CAR-DAYTONA-ART-NYT &LR;      02-19 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARRETT IS AHEAD OF THE FIELD BEFORE DAYTONA STARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The thrill is far from gone. After a
hectic off-season in which he had to fulfill commitments virtually
every day, Dale Jarrett says he is eager to begin defense of his
NASCAR Winston Cup Series championship. And why not? Robert Yates
Racing, for whom Jarrett drives, may have made his job easier.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Yates lured five of Jeff Gordon's Rainbow Warriors to
work his pit and hired eight members of Ricky Rudd's crew, and then
Rudd himself as the team's second driver.
</P>
<P>
   So, it was not a big surprise when Jarrett qualified for the
pole position in Sunday's Daytona 500, the initial Winston Cup race
of the season, and Rudd qualified second. The last time one team
had a front row starting monopoly at Daytona came in 1992, when
Junior Johnson Racing had Sterling Marlin on the pole and Bill
Elliott next to him.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's guys were not able to capitalize, with both going out
in a wreck on the 92nd lap. It may take such rotten luck to keep
the Jarrett-Rudd combination out of the top five.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep looking ahead at what's going to benefit you
down the road,'' Jarrett said. ``If we just sit still, people are
not only going to catch us, they're going to surpass us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, at 43, embraces what a superior support system can do
for a driver. He won his Winston Cup title at 42, after 16 years of
trying.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have that team around you, it doesn't matter how
good you are,'' he said. ``There are probably better people out
here that are better race car drivers than I am, but I'm in a
better position than they are. You got to have the whole package to
make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett should feel even better about his pole position because
he drives a Ford, and never mind that this is a restrictor-plate
race (restrictor plates slow cars by cutting down on the flow of
air into the carburetor). Both Ford and Chevrolet came out with new
models this season, and then NASCAR made rules changes regarding
shock absorbers and springs.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet's front end has had more aerodynamic difficulties than
Ford's. Chevy owners asked for relief through another change in the
shocks-springs rules, but NASCAR said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a Ford can set out there and run faster by itself than a
whole pack of cars, then there's something way wrong,'' said
Richard Childress, who owns two Chevrolets. ``It's such an
unbalanced field right now. We feel the deck is stacked against
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Childress said he has learned never to underestimate Dale
Earnhardt, one of the sport's legends. Yet even Earnhardt is
feeling overmatched.
</P>
<P>
   After Earnhardt finished 11th in his qualifying race on Thursday
_ following 10 straight years of winning his heat _ he singed
NASCAR's ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took NASCAR Winston Cup racing and made it some of the
sorriest racing,'' he said. ``They took racing out of the hands of
the drivers and the crews. We can't adjust and make our cars drive
like we want. They just killed the racing at Daytona. This is a
joke to have to race like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Elliott, 44, in particular dazzled with his qualifying
victory on Thursday. He says he has the best car he has brought to
Daytona since finishing second in the Winston Cup standings in '92.
``We've come light years in the last month, and if anything, that's
an understatement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett does not have to be convinced. ``Bill is one of the best
at drafting. We always hear a lot about Dale Earnhardt being one of
the best, but Bill knows as much about the draft as anybody here.
And man, his car looked great.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, 28, driving a Chevy and breaking in a new crew chief,
does not seem to be drawing much attention as a serious contender
this week, despite his three Winston Cup titles in five years and
two Daytona 500 victories over the last three years. But the
resolve is clearly there.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I told the guys in the garage, `We don't have to come out
and do great things,''' said Gordon's crew chief, Robbie Loomis.
``What we need to do is work together well as a team and give him a
good, solid foundation. Then put Jeff Gordon in the car and he'll
take care of the rest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
