<HEADLINE>
GREENS AT RIVIERA ARE GIVING WOODS FITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PACIFIC PALISADES, Calif. _ Tiger Woods trailed by five shots
going into Saturday's third round, a deficit which, in his
universe, can disappear at light speed over a few holes. Yet if
Woods does not rally and win the Nissan Open, he can legitimately
point to the Riviera Country Club's greens as his nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   Poa annua grass is synonymous with bumpy and inconsistent
putting at Riviera and other stops on the PGA Tour's west coast
swing. A stretch of hot weather can smooth out poa annua greens,
which would help if these tournaments were played in July. Every
player has missed his share of putts, of course, but Woods' luck
has been rotten even by low standards.
</P>
<P>
   In the first round, he couldn't find the hole on at least a half
dozen putts no longer than 10 feet, including three attempts that
hit the cup. In the second round, two more tries lipped out and
some others appeared struck well enough to fall. Woods still
managed to shoot 68-70, but he left several birdies and possibly
the lead on the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't make any putts,'' Woods said, including second-round
laments for his playing partners Hal Sutton and Steve Pate. ``I
think we as a group easily had double-digit lipouts. We didn't hit
bad putts. They just didn't go in. That's really frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   They weren't the only ones suffering, although most players
simply endured missed opportunities rather than cursed lousy
putting strokes. Sutton put together a bogey-free 67 and pulled to
within three shots of the leaders, Bob Tway and Greg Chalmers.
Still, things are haywire on the greens last week. Despite carding
Friday's low round, a six-under-par 65, Brandel Chamblee said he
was baffled when missing three attempts inside 4 feet. On Thursday,
Nick Faldo, who read these greens well enough to win the 1997
Nissan Open, five-putted No. 11 for a quadruple bogey 9.
</P>
<P>
   It's clearly feast or failure at Riviera. With the lead at nine
under par, the cut at one under and 39 players within five shots of
first place, birdies obviously are plentiful. With Woods lurking,
the chance for a dramatic finish also exists. Also five shots
behind and not yet out of contention were Jesper Parnevik, who
ranks second to Woods on this year's PGA Tour money list, and Vijay
Singh, who ranks sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, it wasn't supposed to be Woods' week here. Bumpy
poa annua greens aside, the length of Riviera's back-nine par-5's,
564 yards at No. 11 and 576 yards at No. 17, provided him with less
of an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Par is 68 for him on just about every golf course,'' said Neal
Lancaster, who ballooned to a 79 Friday, after an opening-round 66,
and failed to make the cut. ``Not with a course like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure from Woods' winning streak was supposed to catch up
with him. But Woods was not worried about his length on the par-5's
nor the continued glare of the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing getting on my nerves is the ball not going in
the hole,'' he said. ``That's the only thing that really bothers
me. The media and the fans, that's just part of playing well, but
it's frustrating when good putts don't go in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
