<SLUG> BC-OBSERVER-NY-GOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: FRATRICIDAL COMPETITION IN NEW YORK'S GOP
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ELEANOR RANDOLPH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although nobody wants to talk about it on the record, New York's
Republicans are quietly agonizing over the intrigue and backbiting
among the state's top party leadership. Gov. George Pataki, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, Joseph Bruno, the state Senate majority leader,
and William Powers, the state party chairman, are contenders in a
struggle for the dominance once exercised by Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   This feuding _ in some cases a rekindling of old hostilities, in
others an effort to establish a new power base _ comes at a
particularly bad time for the state's Republican regulars. New
York's presidential primary, set for March 7, has already left its
embarrassing mark on the state party nationally, after Pataki and
Powers tried unsuccessfully to keep Sen. John McCain off the New
York primary ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle at the top threatens the party's unity and strength
in a critical election year, not merely for the presidential and
U.S. Senate races, but also for choosing legislators who will map
voting districts for state and federal offices for the next decade.
If done with political expertise, these maps can be drawn to keep
the draftsmen, and their party, in power.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage, the most open combatants are Pataki and Bruno.
The longest-running discord, patched on occasion for public
appearances, is between Pataki and Giuliani. And the least
understood, and in some ways most intriguing, part of the mix is
the relationship between the governor and Powers, an early backer
of Giuliani and a friend of Bruno.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno's conflict with Pataki began surfacing last year when the
the Senate majority leader bucked the governor on several issues,
including health care and reforming the state's sleazy lobbying and
gift-taking system in Albany. Suddenly the governor was asking
Bruno's colleagues whether they were satisfied with how the
majority leader was conducting his business. At the same time,
several state workers with ties to Bruno mysteriously lost their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno's allies were furious, spreading the word that the
governor was on a power trip, trying to control every political
move made by Republicans and, they charged, making a mess of it.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Benjamin, dean of the college of arts and sciences at the
State University of New York at New Paltz, suggests that the
governor is trying to send a hard and clear message that he has
taken over as the state's top elected Republican. As the powers of
D'Amato fade, the powers of his protege, Pataki, gain strength.
Benjamin said: ``Firing the employees is a way of saying to Bruno:
`I'm in charge now. Here are the new facts and you are going to
have to live with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing struggle between Pataki and Giuliani offers an
almost weekly twist. Most recently, the mayor embarrassed the
governor by saying the New York presidential primary should be open
to candidates other than George W. Bush, including the mayor's
friend, McCain. The resulting steam leaking from Pataki's office
could have relieved the heating crisis in several upstate counties.
</P>
<P>
   It has been labeled a coincidence, but shortly after Giuliani
broke ranks by criticizing the primary, he began to face the
renewed possibility of competition within his own party. Rep. Rick
Lazio, a Republican from Long Island, had wanted to run for the
Senate this year. But he harnessed his ambitions a few months ago
to make way for the mayor. Suddenly, Lazio is reminding the
political world that ``I have not closed the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki quickly dismissed any possibility that he was behind the
return of Lazio, but the timing, as one Republican suggested
privately, sent a signal from the governor to the mayor just the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Behind all these veils is Powers, a reclusive figure credited in
state party circles with pulling the party out of the hole created
in 1990 when a GOP gubernatorial candidate lost by a landslide and
left behind $1.5 million in party debt. After almost a decade of
pushing and financing Republican candidates at every level, Powers
wants Giuliani to win the Senate race, a yearning that has, on
occasion, put him at odds with Pataki. No doubt there are also
strains between the two over their disastrous failure to deliver an
uncontested primary to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's national reputation clearly suffered from this debacle.
Allies who once dreamed of a Pataki vice-presidential nomination
are now setting their sights on a Cabinet appointment in a
Republican administration. Still, the big unanswered question is
whether the state's feuding Republican leaders can muster enough
party unity to mount a massive voter turnout for Giuliani in his
race against Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
