u s BC-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT &LR;      02-19 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRADA'S FIERY OWNER STIRS CREW WITH WAVES OF ANGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ Resplendent in a cream linen suit, the
fashion scion Patrizio Bertelli _ husband of the clothing designer
Miuccia Prada, financial wizard behind the fabulously successful
Milan, Italy-based company that bears her family name, and the
latest in a long line of multimillionaires to challenge for the
America's Cup _ stood ankle deep along a shaggy, green bluff while
sheep grazed in the lush, adjacent meadow.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the potential for a dry-cleaning disaster, Bertelli was
ebullient. It was two weeks ago and, moments earlier, he had taken
possession of the Louis Vuitton trophy, emblematic of the
wonderful, dramatic victory his Prada America's Cup challenge had
completed the previous afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Bertelli had bankrolled the $55 million campaign from his own
deep pockets, and his crew had vanquished San Francisco's America
One syndicate in a thrilling series to earn the right to face Team
New Zealand in the America's Cup finals. The racing was scheduled
to begin this weekend, but was curtailed by a frustrating lack of
wind on Saturday; only in yacht racing are the games canceled
because the weather's too nice.
</P>
<P>
   The literal and figurative center of attention, Bertelli had
been busy arranging a group photo of his 130-strong sailing team
and their families: gesticulating, commanding, getting it right. To
his left and to his right, tanned sailors casually posed in the
standard yachtsman's garb of white trousers and blue blazers.
</P>
<P>
   As conductor of this maritime orchestra, the linen-clad Bertelli
had earned the right to tack away from the occasion's collective
crew uniform. It was more than a symbolic moment for, in his dress
and in his firm, omnipotent management style, Bertelli was apart
from the others.
</P>
<P>
   He has also been known to flash a temper. In fact, his pot
boiled over on the day that America One came storming back from a
3-1 deficit to take a 4-3 lead in the five-of-nine-race
challenger's finals. When the Prada boat returned to the docks, the
54-year-old Bertelli was waiting. And his advice for the skipper,
Francesco de Angelis, and the tactician, Torben Grael, was loud and
pointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was terribly angry,'' said a reporter from one of Italy's
largest daily newspapers who witnessed the outburst, and who spoke
on condition of anonymity, fearful of incurring Bertelli's wrath.
``He's from Tuscany, and you must understand these people. One
minute they are smiling. The next they are on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Bertelli is proud of his Tuscan connection and, while he does
not dispute the summation of the personal characteristics of those
who hail from the region, he also points out that the Prada
campaign has dispelled a myth about another purported trait of its
natives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tuscans tend to be pretty disorganized,'' he said. ``We've
proven we can organize and undertake a project of this size, and do
it to international or Anglo-Saxon standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Bertelli's talent for and dedication to organization have turned
Prada into a billion-dollar concern. In many ways, it has been an
unlikely success story. Miuccia Prada took over her family's ailing
luggage business in 1978 and joined forces with Bertelli, a belt
manufacturer, two years later. With Bertelli serving as chief
executive officer and his wife in the role of chief designer, their
alliance has been magical.
</P>
<P>
   A competitive amateur sailor who successfully campaigned his own
boats in the offshore racing scene in the 1970s, Bertelli was lured
into the cup wars by Argentine naval architect German Frers, with
whom he was contemplating the commission of a large cruising yacht.
Frers insisted that Bertelli was the perfect man to lead an Italian
challenge, and Bertelli almost immediately agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the aftermath of a cup challenge can be hazardous
to the health of Italian tycoons. Maurizio Gucci, who led the
Italia syndicate in 1987, was later assassinated after his former
wife, Patrizia Reggiani, took out a contract on his life. And Raul
Gardini, who bankrolled the 1992 cup challenger, Il Moro de
Venezia, committed suicide a year later in the middle of a
financial scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But Bertelli is in it for the long run. Asked whether he would
return to New Zealand and try again if this attempt at the cup
ultimately proves to be unsuccessful, he said: ``Yes. We'll wait
and see until what happens after the finals, of course, but I'm 99
percent certain.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether he returns to cup competition as the defender or as the
challenger, in either case his style will continue to be
straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   ``He rolls into things like a tank,'' Bruno Trouble, who heads
up the challenger's series, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Gardini and I know Bertelli and I like them both,'' he
added. ``But Gardini had much more glamour and panache. That's not
Bertelli's style. He's not really doing it the Italian way.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Bertelli's doing it his way. And as the sailors aboard Prada
are learning, there really is no other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
