<SLUG> BC-BBO-MILLER-HALLOFFAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARVIN MILLER'S FAME IS SUBJECT TO INTERPRETATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
(Eds: Allen Barra is a sportswriter in the New York area.) 
 By ALLEN BARRA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ask people connected with baseball and they will say that Marvin
Miller, the man who founded the Major League Baseball Players
Association and the man who brought free agency to baseball,
belongs in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Red Barber once called Miller, along with Babe Ruth and Jackie
Robinson, ``one of the three most important men in baseball
history.'' Arthur Ashe felt that Miller ``did more for the welfare
of black athletes than anyone else.'' Bob Costas said that, with
the possible exception of Branch Rickey, ``there is no nonplayer
more deserving for the Hall of Fame than Marvin Miller.'' Even team
owners like George Steinbrenner and former executives like Buzzy
Bavasi endorse Miller's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   The players themselves are unanimously behind Miller. Jim
Bunning, a U.S. senator from Kentucky and Hall of Famer, said,
``The Hall of Fame is about players, and Marvin did more for the
players than anyone else.'' Tom Seaver called Miller's exclusion
from the hall ``a national disgrace.'' Hank Aaron wrote that
``Miller should be in the Hall of Fame if the players have to break
down the doors to get him in.''
</P>
<P>
   Some are wondering if that's what it might take to get him in.
If Miller is not tapped by the veterans committee on Feb. 29 _ and
speculation is that the choice will be Sparky Anderson, the former
Cincinnati Reds and Detroit Tigers manager _ then the
behind-the-scenes rumblings that surround the issue may break out
into one of the Hall of Fame's biggest controversies. Or, as Brooks
Robinson, the Hall of Fame third baseman and member of the board of
directors, put it: ``Too many of us who want this to happen have
let it slide for a long time. This year, we're going to ask the
right questions and find the right answer to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The question, it appears, will focus on rule 6(b) of the ``Rules
for Election to the National Baseball Hall of Fame by members of
Baseball Hall of Fame Committee on Baseball Veterans.'' According
to the rule, ``Baseball Executives and/or Managers and/or Umpires
who have been retired from organized baseball as Baseball
Executives and/or Managers and/or Umpires for at least five years
prior to the election'' are eligible.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, does Miller qualify?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, definitely not,'' a veterans committee member said. ``It
says `baseball executive,' and Marvin Miller was not a baseball
executive.''
</P>
<P>
   To which a former player on the veterans committee said:
``That's ridiculous. The rule says `baseball executive,' not
`executive employed by major-league baseball.' Marvin Miller was
the executive director for all the players in baseball, not just
the players of just one team. The players are baseball. If Marvin
Miller isn't a real baseball executive, who is?''
</P>
<P>
   For some, the interpretation of rule 6(b) is the stumbling
block.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the interpretation of the rule that matters,'' said
Leonard Koppett, the sportswriter and a veterans committee member,
who favors Miller's candidacy. ``The board of directors make the
rules, and we can't put Marvin on the ballot until the board
interprets the rule and tells us it's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jeff Idelson, vice president for communication and education
of the Hall of Fame, said: ``There is nothing in rule 6(b) to
prohibit Marvin Miller's candidacy. If Leonard Koppett or anyone
else puts up his hand and said, `Let's rule in Marvin Miller,'
they'd have to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Holtzman, another sportswriter on the veterans committee,
said, ``That's not my understanding of how the process works.''
</P>
<P>
   And who is on the screening committee? The Hall of Fame will not
say except that the screening committee is made up of veterans
committee members
</P>
<P>
   So why hasn't the screening committee brought Miller before the
veterans committee for the three-fourths approval vote that would
put Miller in the Hall of Fame?
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody on the screening committee,'' a veterans committee
member said, ``always has a hang-up about rule 6(b).''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you know,'' Dick Moss, a player agent who was Miller's
former legal counsel at the players association, said, ``why people
who have tried to sort through this years ago screamed in
frustration and walked away.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people trying to sort through it now might feel the same
way. Joe Morgan, the Hall of Fame player and ESPN broadcaster, who
is a member of the hall's board, devoted a section in his recent
book, ``Long Balls, No Strikes,'' to advocating Miller as a Hall of
Famer, said. ``I didn't even know about the screening committee,''
Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   But even those who know about it are not sure how it works.
``It's my understanding,'' Seaver said, ``that the screening
committee is only there to help the veterans committee. I am not
aware that it's necessary to have the screening committee present
someone before the veterans committee in order for a vote to be
taken.''
</P>
<P>
   There are those who see Miller's exclusion as more than the
result of mere confusion; they view it as intentional obfuscation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What some baseball executives tell the press,'' a veterans
committee member said, ``and what they say to each other when the
doors are closed are two different things. The Hall of Fame is a
private organization run by the owners of major-league baseball.
There are a great many men on those committees who have vivid
memories of the stomping Marvin Miller gave them in every labor
battle. Do you think those men are going to roll out the red carpet
and ask him into Cooperstown? If anything is going to be done about
this, the push is going to have to come from the players themselves
and the players association.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks Robinson concurred. ``This is our fight,'' he said,
``and, frankly, it's our fault Marvin isn't in the Hall of Fame.
We've wasted too much time waiting around for this to happen. It's
time we got together and said: `Look, we want this to happen. Does
this rule exclude Marvin Miller, and, if so, let's change it.'
Marvin Miller taught us all to stand up for ourselves. It's time we
took the responsibility and stand up for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
