<HEADLINE>
THREATENED STRIKE AT APOLLO MAY AFFECT GORE-BRADLEY DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stagehands gathered outside the Apollo theater in
Harlem on Saturday and threatened a walkout, two days before a
scheduled Democratic presidential debate at the historic theater.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations broke off at midnight Friday after members of the
Apollo Theater Foundation and the union, Local 1 of the
International Alliance of Theatrical Stage Employees, which has
2,350 members in New York, failed to agree on a new contract and
additional payment for night-shift workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They insulted our intelligence at midnight,'' said Jim
Claffey, a business manager with the union. He promised a strike
unless the Apollo foundation gave the union a signed agreement
before Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A strike and resulting picket line will likely throw the
scheduled 90-minute debate between Vice President Al Gore and
former Sen. Bill Bradley on Monday into chaos. The debate is to be
televised live on CNN at 9 p.m. and moderated by its anchorman,
Bernard Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vice President Gore would not cross a picket line,'' said
Peter Ragone, a spokesman for Gore. ``We hope that this issue can
be resolved, as we would like to debate.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Bradley, Michael Powell, would not comment on
whether Bradley would cross the picket line. He said only, ``We
don't think there's going to be a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Field, a spokeswoman for CNN, said, ``We're going ahead
with the debate as scheduled,'' and added that CNN was not
researching other sites.
</P>
<P>
   Apollo officials could not be reached for comment and did not
respond to messages left on the theater's answering machine
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Union organizers at the theater, at 253 W. 125th St., said
Saturday that the stagehands had worked without a contract since
last September, were not paid extra for working the overnight, or
lobster, shift and said the Apollo's management had discriminated
against them for union activities.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble began, they said, in August 1998, when the
stagehands joined the union and held a five-week walkout. Charles
Richardson, a shop steward who had worked at the Apollo for 10
years and helped organize the stagehands, said he was fired in July
1999 for having a bad attitude but claims he was really being
punished for his union activities.
</P>
<P>
   The 33 stagehands do electrical, carpentry and audio work and
are paid $20 to $35 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Sprauve, an assistant shop steward, who took over
Richardson's duties, said: ``We can't get responses to grievances.
We get no return phone calls. We're still getting no respect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
