<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF-SEASON FOR ROCKIES GENERAL MANAGER WAS AN EXHAUSTING ONE  
 JUST THE FAX  
 GONE BUT NOT FORGOTTEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The caller solicitously inquired about the general manager's
health. Was he all right, was he feeling OK? Yes, Dan O'Dowd
replied, puzzled at the question. Well, he was told, you haven't
made a trade for five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   O'Dowd laughed. ``It hasn't been for a lack of trying,'' he
said. ``It's getting harder now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Rockies' new general manager was so active in the
first four months of his tenure that he could have suffered
exhaustion. He made six trades, including a three-way deal, that
brought the Rockies 13 players. He also signed five free agents and
he claimed one player on waivers. Eleven players who were with the
team before rosters expanded in September are gone. Approximately
15 newcomers could be on the team's opening-day roster, maybe more
if O'Dowd succeeds in executing another trade or two.
</P>
<P>
   Easily the busiest team in the off-season, the Rockies arrive in
spring training as the most changed team in the major leagues. When
they hold their first full-squad workout Wednesday, under a new
manager, Buddy Bell, of course, they will not be able to tell the
players without a scorecard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope all the jerseys come in with names on them,''
O'Dowd said.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle, Tampa Bay, Texas, the Chicago Cubs and the New York
Mets were other teams that had an active winter. No team, of
course, made a more significant move than the Cincinnati Reds, who
snatched Ken Griffey Jr., one of the best players ever traded.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies, who had regressed since reaching the playoffs in
their third year of existence, finished in last place last season
with the National League's highest batting average and the highest
earned run average, demonstrating that their hitters could not
overcome their pitchers' mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   O'Dowd, however, did not simply overhaul the pitching staff; he
restructured the team's hitting element, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team came off three poor seasons,'' O'Dowd said.
``Something had to be done. It just wasn't working and wasn't going
to work.''
</P>
<P>
   For their first seven years, the Rockies relied on power. They
tried to beat their opponents into submission. For two successive
seasons, they had three players with 40 or more home runs. No more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to change an offense,'' O'Dowd said, ``that was based
on a hit, a walk and a three-run home run to one that we hope will
feature going deeper into counts, working the pitcher more, having
better at-bats. We wanted to get more of a pure hitter. We
sacrificed power, and we might have to add some later on.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the Rockies are looking for higher on-base
percentages to go with their fewer home runs. ``You need a high
on-base percentage,'' the new general manager said. ``If you have a
high slugging percentage and a low on-base, you're going to get
beat eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   So O'Dowd traded Vinny Castilla and Dante Bichette, who last
season hit 30 percent of their home runs and drove in 26 percent of
their runs, who in seven seasons in the Rockies slugged 403 home
runs and drove in 1,436 runs. Jeff Cirillo, from Milwaukee, will
replace Castilla at third base, and Jeffrey Hammonds, from
Cincinnati, will take over from Bichette in left field. Tom Goodwin
is the new center fielder and Brent Mayne is the new catcher.
</P>
<P>
   On the pitching side, which he wanted to stock with people who
could throw strikes, O'Dowd shed pitchers who started half of the
team's games last season. He retained Pedro Astacio and Brian
Bohanon, and they will be in the rotation this season with three
pitchers of a group of five newcomers _ Rolando Arrojo, Masato
Yoshii, Scott Karl, Manny Aybar and Jose Jimenez, who pitched a
no-hitter for St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Other off-season acquisitions will compete for spots in the
bullpen _ Stan Belinda, Rick Croushore, Julian Tavarez, Mike Myers,
Billy Taylor. Gone are Curtis Keskanic and Dave Veres, who between
them relieved 136 times last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had to make changes here,'' O'Dowd said. ``But
things just kind of unfolded. One piece fit another piece and led
to another. We didn't go into this off-season thinking we were
going to do all this. I've been around the game long enough to know
we made some good decisions and we made some bad ones. I think our
analysis was good and our thought process was good, but that
doesn't mean you made the right decision every time.''
</P>
<P>
   The decisions the Rockies made weren't based wholly on getting
this particular player or creating a certain kind of offense. It
was imperative, O'Dowd said, to create flexibility in the payroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to establish some type of long-term strategic plan that
tied into the payroll,'' said O'Dowd, formerly the assistant
general manager of the Cleveland Indians. ``In Cleveland it was the
foundation of everything they've been able to do there. Here we had
eight players tied up with $54 million. It would have been even
higher in 2001. Now the payroll will wind up at around $60 million
for 25 players.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
