</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: 25 players.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mariners Make Moves
</P>
<P>
   Before the Mariners reluctantly traded Ken Griffey Jr., they
signed themselves into the favorite's role in the American League
West, adding five free agents _ first baseman John Olerud, a
versatile Mark McLemore, the starting pitcher Aaron Sele, the
reliever Arthur Rhodes and the noted Japanese reliever Kazuhiro
Sasaki.
</P>
<P>
   While the Mariners were adding, the Rangers were subtracting. In
the process, they tried to transform their team from one that had
relied on hitting to one that will try to win with pitching.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers traded or lost as free agents players who drove in a
third of the runs they scored last season. Juan Gonzalez and Todd
Zeile are the most prominent of that departed group. The defending
division champions also lost an 18-game winner, Sele, but they
gained three left-handed starting pitchers, Kenny Rogers and Darren
Oliver as free agents, who began their careers with Texas, and
Justin Thompson in the Gonzalez trade.
</P>
<P>
   Using money but not androstendione, Tampa Bay bulked up this
winter, signing Greg Vaughn (95 home runs the past two seasons) and
trading for Vinny Castilla (191 the past five). The Devil Rays also
signed Gerald Williams to be their leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays, who also signed two pitchers, Juan Guzman and
Steve Trachsel, had one of the weakest hitting teams in the league
last season, and that weakness, their 25 percent plunge in
attendance in their second year and the success of their expansion
partner Arizona, prompted them to alter their plans and try to make
the team more potent and attractive.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs were much more active this winter than last, because
they assured Don Baylor they would be. Baylor is their new manager,
and because he had his pick of jobs he would not have gone to the
Cubs if they had planned to maintain the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs signed catcher Joe Girardi and shortstop Ricky
Guttierez and traded for Eric Young, Damon Buford and Ismael
Valdes. Unlike last year, they appear to be serious about
contending.
</P>
<P>
   Just the Fax
</P>
<P>
   Postscript to the Ken Griffey Jr. trade:
</P>
<P>
   In the first month of Jim Bowden's three-month effort to get his
favorite player in all of baseball, the Cincinnati general manager
sent a proposal to Pat Gillick, the Mariners' general manager, by
fax. Gillick called Bowden about an hour after he received the fax
and said: ``You have a major security problem. Someone has stolen
your letterhead and forged your name on the most ridiculous
proposal I've ever seen in my life. You should look into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said he would. An appropriate passage of time later, the
Reds' general manager called Gillick and said: ``You're right.
Obviously the proposal that was faxed to you the Reds would never
consider doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes even general managers have to have some fun in their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Gone but Not Forgotten
</P>
<P>
   Last December, when he was still employed by the Mets, Bobby
Bonilla issued a warning. If he did not play more regularly than he
did last season, he said, he would become a distraction and cause
trouble for the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're all going to love me next year,'' Bonilla told
reporters. ``In the millennium, there will be some fireworks. I
want to play.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bonilla was asked if he would try to create difficulty for
General Manager Steve Phillips and Manager Bobby Valentine if he
did not play, Bonilla said: ``Oh, yeah. Oh, yeah. Oh, yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   Mets officials, of course, were outraged at this threat of
deliberate trouble-making. Bonilla is gone now, but Valentine is
still the manager.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, then, what those same team officials must have thought
when they read this comment from Valentine last week. He was
responding, in an interview with Jack Curry of The New York Times,
to his status as a manager in the last year of his contract with no
guarantee of continued employment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was looking for a headline story,'' Valentine said, ``I'd
watch for that one day we had a long practice that didn't go well
and I find out there's something wrong at home, and someone gets to
me as soon as I get into the office. Ask me the wrong question at
the wrong time and that guy will have one heck of a story.''
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought that Valentine would have borrowed
anything from Bonilla?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
