<HEADLINE>
FLIGHT PLANS OF THE FEATHERED VARIETY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just off the Clearview Expressway in Bayside, Queens,
Aline Euler has created a welcoming back yard. From a sprawling
sycamore, three bird feeders hang, one full of the premium thistle
seed that attracts finches. There are sunflower hearts for the
chickadees and, a few trees to the left, a suet feeder that
attracts downy woodpeckers and starlings.
</P>
<P>
   An electric cord runs under the snow to the house, to keep the
water in the birdbath from freezing. Two birdhouses await spring
guests. With a notebook and field guide in hand, Euler carefully
counts the arriving guests.
</P>
<P>
   Euler is one of thousands of bird-watchers participating in the
Great Backyard Bird Count this weekend, collecting statistics about
which species are showing up at feeders, lawns and bushes around
the United States and Canada. The project is in its third year,
sponsored by the Cornell Lab of Ornithology and the National
Audubon Society.
</P>
<P>
   Over the entire weekend and through Monday, observers count the
number of birds they find per day in at least half an hour of
observation, and submit their numbers, via the Internet, to the
North American count. The Web site, www.birdsource.org, shows a
running tally of how many birds were counted, with breakdowns by
state and province.
</P>
<P>
   With the statistics, ornithologists will be able to study how
this winter's weather has influenced bird populations, and whether
migrating waterfowl species are moving as far north this year as
last. Birders are asked to pay careful attention to house finches,
which have suffered recently from conjunctivitis, an eye infection
that hinders their ability to feed. With information from the bird
count, ornithologists hope to be able to map the spread of the
disease, which might be contracted from other birds at feeders.
</P>
<P>
   Euler spreads birdseed instead of salt or sand on her front walk
when it is icy. As a reward, the trees above her home are filled
with birdsong, even late on a frosty Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are what she calls the ``typical New York
birds'' _ pigeons, starlings, house sparrows _ around the feeders.
But soon a trio of American goldfinches, drab in their winter
feathers, alight on the thistle-seed feeder, and a pair of red-wing
blackbirds pick at the suet. Other days, other seasons, Euler has
spotted a migrating indigo bunting, a red-bellied woodpecker and a
hooded warbler.
</P>
<P>
   One of her more exotic visitors was a sharp-shinned hawk, which
helped itself to some of the songbirds she feeds. She knew it was
the nature of the species, and tolerated it, so long as it kept to
house sparrows.
</P>
<P>
   Euler, who is the education director at Alley Pond Environmental
Center in Douglaston, Queens, is hoping her yard can be certified
as an official Backyard Wildlife Habitat by the National Wildlife
Federation. She also plants flowers and bushes to attract
butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so relaxing to come out and watch them here,'' she said
as she sat in her enclosed porch, with its large windows installed
specifically for bird viewing. ``We like to be next to nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Dunne, vice president of natural history information at the
New Jersey Audubon Society, said that birding was the second
favorite American outdoor pastime, after gardening, and had grown
in popularity during the last decade. Of the country's 54 million
birders, 80 percent never leave their back yard, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Euler keeps a vigilant eye on her feeders, and groaned in dismay
when a black and white cat crossed her yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really like to see cats,'' she said. ``They really
decimate the birds.'' She does not use pesticides on her garden or
lawn, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame because a lot of the birds we had in the past we
don't see as many of,'' she said. ``We used to have lots of jays,
but we don't anymore, I think because of pesticide use.''
</P>
<P>
   Observing such trends is important, she said, so that causes can
eventually be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very important, because it provides people with
an understanding of what birds reside here in urban areas,'' Euler
said. ``Many people believe that birds are the barometers of the
health of the environment _ canaries in a coal mine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 1617EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
