<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS CONTINUES FOR THE RAVENS  
 A BETTER HELMET IN THE WORKS  
 GOOD PLAYER, GREAT MONEY  
 SEVERAL TEAMS SHOW AN INTEREST IN GRAHAM  
 THOMAS' CHILDREN AND HIS PENSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   These days have been busy, and stressful, for the Baltimore
Ravens' owner, Art Modell. ``I've aged 40 years in the last two
weeks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason his pulse has been racing is because of good news.
Last week, his team signed free agent tight end Shannon Sharpe,
after re-signing some key free agents like quarterback Tony Banks _
and spending $12.5 million in signing bonuses. There is no question
about it: Baltimore should be considered a sleeper as a Super Bowl
contender next season.
</P>
<P>
   But of course there is another reason Modell has been getting
little sleep lately: Ray Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   When the team's best linebacker is accused of a double murder,
that is sure to lead to many sleepless nights for all involved,
especially the families of the two dead men.
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League, however, is a business. As
horrible as the situation is, the sport goes on. And the Ravens
find themselves in a difficult situation. On one hand, the team
believes Lewis is innocent, but on the other, it must prepare for a
future that may not include an All-Pro player.
</P>
<P>
   In the grand scheme of things, when two people are stabbed to
death, as happened in Atlanta after a Super Bowl party on Jan. 31,
and another, Lewis, faces the possibility of spending the rest of
his life in prison, what happens on a football field seems trivial.
But the Ravens still have a season to prepare for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving forward, getting ready for next year,'' Modell
said. ``This has not been easy for anyone. We may have some tough
choices. But this organization is moving full steam ahead. We
signed Shannon Sharpe. We re-signed Tony Banks.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of Lewis, 24, the Ravens may face some serious choices.
Lewis, who was released on $1 million bond in Atlanta last Tuesday
and returned home to Maryland, has asked for a speedy trial, but
there is a possibility that it could be delayed until after the
season starts. If that is the case, would the Ravens, or the NFL,
allow Lewis to play?
</P>
<P>
   The league would almost certainly not allow a murder suspect to
play. Ravens officials say privately that they could be forced to
sign a free-agent linebacker to replace Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore and the NFL, at least for now, do not want to suspend
Lewis, because such an act may prejudice a jury when he is tried.
That is different from the case of former Panther Rae Carruth. The
league suspended Carruth before his murder trial, mainly because he
fled from authorities after it became clear that he was a suspect
in the shooting of a pregnant girlfriend. Carruth is being held
without bail in Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens may also face a salary-cap problem. Lewis is due more
than $3 million this season. If Lewis' case goes to trial, and he
is found guilty, would this year's salary, and future ones, count
against the cap? Again, the league does not yet have the answer.
But the question is critical to Baltimore. There is little room to
spare for teams in terms of the $62.172 million cap.
</P>
<P>
   These questions seem small considering what is at stake for
Lewis, and that two men were killed, but to the Ravens, what
happens in the next few months can affect the franchise for years
to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping for the best,'' Modell said, ``and we're prepared
for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   A Better Helmet
</P>
<P>
   Last season, San Francisco quarterback Steve Young was hit so
hard in the head that he lay on the turf, crumpled, unconscious, as
his teammates watched in horror. It was one of several concussions
sustained by Young over his long career. The hit renewed a debate
about head injuries and prompted calls for the NFL to better
protect its players.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, within the past year, the league has intensified its
research into head injuries and helmet technology. Now, several
league officials say, specialists have developed technology for a
new helmet that may lower the risk of concussions.
</P>
<P>
   Results from the studies will be discussed with teams at the
Indianapolis scouting combine next week. It is possible that a new
type of helmet could be introduced in time for next season,
although it seems more likely that it would be used in several
years.
</P>
<P>
   One thing seems certain: The NFL believes this new technology
can help its players.
</P>
<P>
   Good Player, Great Money
</P>
<P>
   There have been a number of unusual free-agent signings this
off-season, including Joey Galloway ending up in Dallas and Bruce
Smith leaving Buffalo for Washington. One of the more interesting
scenarios involved the Tennessee offensive lineman John Runyan. His
case shows just how much a team is willing to overpay for a player
it considers a great talent.
</P>
<P>
   Runyan is a 26-year-old tackle with Pro Bowl credentials, and is
a good run blocker and a talented pass protector. But by no means
is he a great player _ just a good one. The Titans offered him $27
million over six years. Runyan declined, and instead went to
Philadelphia, who gave him $30 million over six years.
</P>
<P>
   This is the problem with free agency. Sometimes teams lose all
perspective and get tunnel vision, locking on a good player and
paying him as if he were a future Hall of Famer.
</P>
<P>
   A few years from now, Runyan may question why he left a Super
Bowl team for the Eagles. There is a good chance that the Titans,
with a good young quarterback and running back, will remain at a
top level while Philadelphia stays mired in mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in Graham
</P>
<P>
   The former Giants quarterback Kent Graham, cut by the team this
month, is finding interest from a number of NFL teams. He has
received an offer from the Cincinnati Bengals, and in the next few
weeks is scheduled to visit Jacksonville, Pittsburgh and Detroit.
The Tampa Bay Buccaneers are deciding between Graham and Neil
O'Donnell as a backup to Shaun King.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' Children
</P>
<P>
   Few NFL players were as highly thought of away from the field as
Derrick Thomas, the Kansas City star who recently died as a result
of an automobile accident. He donated not just his time to charity,
but also hundreds of thousands of dollars as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs have long been extremely fond of Thomas. Now the team
is dealing with a potentially awkward situation involving the
pension fund and estate of Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas had at least six children with five different women,
according to several football officials. Thomas had taken care of
the children financially, and when he died, several of the mothers
contacted the Chiefs and inquired about his financial situation.
One of the issues involves Thomas' pension fund. The way his
pension works is that the six children would divide $3,000 a month
for four years, then $1,500 a month until they turned 19.
</P>
<P>
   It is likely that Thomas provided other means to take care of
his children in addition to the pension fund. Some officials are
concerned about possible fights _ and lawsuits _ over Thomas'
estate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 1624EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
