<DOCNO> NYT20000219.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2197 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BANK-LOST-BOX-ART-NYT     02-19 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-LOST-BOX-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAGIC OF GENERATIONS OF A FAMILY DISAPPEARS IN THE SAFETY OF A
BANK VAULT
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Every month, like clockwork, Alla Kozirovskaya would
leave her tiny apartment in Brighton Beach and walk to the bank to
visit her dead mother. It was such a comforting routine.
Kozirovskaya, 62, would sign in at the bank, wait for a clerk to
retrieve her safe deposit box, and then open it up and run her
bent, wrinkled fingers over a single ring, a single bracelet and a
single brooch.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother had worn this jewelry for decades, as had her
mother's mother, and their mothers before them. The jewelry was all
that remained of the family's prosperous roots in czarist Russia,
all that had survived the gloom of communism, the turmoil of two
world wars and the family's escape to the United States in 1990.
When Alla Kozirovskaya touched the brooch, she might remember how
her mother smiled. With the ring, she might recall a song. This was
the best kind of magic.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 5, Alla Kozirovskaya and her husband, Yakov Kozirovsky,
made the monthly trip to their bank, a Dime branch on Coney Island
Avenue in the Brighton Beach section of Brooklyn. And that is how
she discovered that her mother's beautiful jewelry had mysteriously
vanished from the bank.
</P>
<P>
   That morning a bank official politely informed her that there
was no record of her owning a safe deposit box. Nothing in the
computer. Nothing in the files.
</P>
<P>
   The news seemed so impossible that Kozirovskaya hardly knew what
to say. As her own records showed, she had rented her box on April
7, 1994 _ a week before the death of her 87-year-old mother,
Yelizaveta Krush _ and had paid the $32.48 rental fee each year
since. Her last receipt showed she was paid up through April 7,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Kozirovskaya pulled out a small, worn envelope that held her
keys to the box. She showed them to the bank official along with
the box number, 3359, which she had written on the envelope. More
bank officials came. They led her into the vault where the safe
deposit boxes are kept. She went to the spot where her box had
always been.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hole, no doors,'' she said. ``And inside this hole,
our empty box.''
</P>
<P>
   Kozirovskaya, who once taught Russian literature in Kiev but now
is battling cancer, said she began to cry. The bank officials, she
said, tried to reassure her. They said everything would be fine,
that there had to be some reasonable explanation. They promised to
call when they found her items, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks later, she is still waiting for a phone call, an
explanation of what happened to the magic that she left in that
box.
</P>
<P>
   So far, all the bank has produced is a one-page form stating
that on Jan. 3 _ two days before Kozirovskaya went in to check on
her heirlooms and only weeks after she had last visited them _ bank
employees opened safe deposit box 3359 because a computer indicated
it was vacant and had no owner.
</P>
<P>
   The form said the employees found nothing inside.
</P>
<P>
   Kozirovskaya's son, Victor Kozirovsky, hired a lawyer to write a
letter to the bank, asking about the missing jewelry. He said the
family has yet to hear back. Kozirovskaya also told her story to
Marsha Rapaport, an aide to state Sen. Seymour P. Lachman, who
represents Brighton Beach.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Rapaport said that she heard an identical tale
from another elderly woman who kept bonds and other valuables in a
box at the same Dime branch, which holds 6,500 safe deposit boxes.
When the woman went to check on her box in December, Rapaport said,
the bank told her it had no record of her owning a box. Other
families in the Russian community of Brighton Beach have reported
similar incidents, Rapaport and Kozirovskaya said.
</P>
<P>
   Rapaport said she suspected the items' disappearance had
something to do with the fact that a nearby Dime branch was
recently closed and merged with the Coney Island Avenue branch.
``The move-over and confusion was really horrendous,'' said
Rapaport, adding that she, too, has yet to receive a response to a
letter she wrote the bank seeking an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Robert P. Weaver, vice president of public relations for Dime
Savings Bank of New York, said in an interview on Wednesday that he
could not discuss what happened to Kozirovskaya's safe deposit box
because ``the facts are just starting to come in.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, the bank is investigating both Kozirovskaya's
case and that of the Dime customer who lost her bonds in December.
He said senior bank officials had not heard of other cases. ``We're
working really hard to come up with a quick and fair resolution to
this matter,'' Weaver said, declining to say whether the bank
suspected either foul play or a simple bureaucratic mix-up.
</P>
<P>
   If Kozirovskaya's heirlooms are gone for good, she is in a
difficult position. She did not insure her mother's jewelry, mainly
because she thought the pieces were safely stored away in a bank
vault. Her only record of ownership, her mother's handwritten will,
was in the safe deposit box, too, she said.
</P>
<P>
   As for value, she acknowledged that she did not possess any
written appraisal of their worth or even their composition. Some of
the stones looked like rubies, some like diamonds, but that is
about as much as she can say for certain.
</P>
<P>
   During the family's trip out of Russia, she said, they had been
offered about $100,000 for the jewelry. As much as they could have
used the money, the offers were rejected because, for the family,
the jewelry represented something of greater value _ their
collective survival and heritage as Russian Jews. For Kozirovskaya,
the monthly trips to the bank were the sentimental equivalent of
visiting her mother's grave, a way to reconnect with fragments of
memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every month I check, and then I see, and then I remember my
mother,'' Kozirovskaya said, at first fighting back tears, and then
giving in to them. She struggled for the English words to describe
her incredulity that something like this could happen here, in a
country she admires for its efficiency and fair play. ``I never
believe it will be in America. In bank. In safe box.'' The magic,
she said, is gone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
