<HEADER>
A2198 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-RENOVATIONS-REAL-NYT &LR;      02-19 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENOVATIONS-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENOVATIONS: A FIXER-UPPER GETS ITS FIXER-UPPER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TRISH HALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even in this real estate market, when many houses and
apartments generate instant bidding wars, some properties sit
around a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes deals are made but fall apart. Sometimes co-op boards
are resistant to the buyers who are offered and reject one after
another. And sometimes the place is so daunting that even the
fearless walk away.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened with a four-story, four-bedroom house on
Degraw Street in Brooklyn, between Clinton and Court Streets on the
border of Cobble Hill and Carroll Gardens. It is a vital
neighborhood, with hundreds of charming old town houses and a hip
commercial strip on nearby Smith Street.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like an easy sell. But when Michael Bruno first saw it in
January 1998, even he wasn't interested, and he had renovated other
homes, including one in Chicago and his family's apartment in
Brooklyn. The stairs were falling away from the wall, the marble
mantels were tilting, the floors sloped and there was a big hole in
the living room ceiling. He figured it was beyond him, in terms of
both time and money.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bruno, 40, was intrigued. ``No one would buy it,'' he
says. ``Everyone in the neighborhood had seen it, and every general
contractor said, `Don't buy it.''' The house had been on the market
for about six months.
</P>
<P>
   One day, driving back into the city at the end of the weekend
with his wife, Rebecca Stevens, 39, and their two young sons,
Victor, 3, and Kohler, 6, he simply made an announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm driving down the expressway coming back from Sag Harbor
and I say, `Rebecca, I hate my job. I'm quitting, and we're buying
that bombed-out house.'''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Bruno was the vice president of Cynthia Rowley, the
clothing designer, and he and his wife, an artist and a teacher at
St. Ann's, a private school in Brooklyn, lived in Brooklyn Heights
in a two-bedroom co-op apartment.
</P>
<P>
   He knew that they could never afford the house unless he worked
as the general contractor and also made many of the repairs
himself.
</P>
<P>
   The house was still available; one bid had collapsed after an
engineer delivered a negative report, and two other bids seemed to
be meeting the same fate. So six months after first seeing the
house, Bruno and his wife offered $510,000, about $140,000 less
than the asking price.
</P>
<P>
   After a few months, their deal went through. Maybe it helped
that they chose an optimistic engineer who said that no single
project in the house would cost more than $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   They closed in January 1999 and spent the next month frantically
doing the cosmetic work that would make it livable, filling three
Dumpsters with garbage. Although Stevens was less enthusiastic than
her husband, she didn't resist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found it much more intimidating than Michael had,'' she
says. ``It was big, and the stairs were falling down, and it was
dark and dank.''
</P>
<P>
   But the process, she says, has not been nearly as awful as she
feared, in part because by the time they moved in, the children's
room was ready.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, Bruno has done many repairs on the house,
with help from his father, Al, who worked as a carpenter as a young
man. Now retired from his later job as a construction manager and
living in Chicago, he visits New York for a week at a time, his son
says, ``working 12 hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bruno has also saved money by searching for
bargains. Someone in the neighborhood, for instance, said he would
charge $2,400 to strip the paint from four sliding pocket doors.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to afford that, Bruno found someone in Baltimore to do
the work for $600. He said that contractors who toured the house
estimated it would cost at least $250,000 to renovate; he figures
he will spend about $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Still, its flaws drive him crazy. ``Our house really sags,'' he
says. ``You can jack it up,'' but because of the stress on the
walls and ceilings and the brittleness of old materials, the lovely
leaf-shaped plaster moldings would be cracked and ruined. And so he
plans to rip the floors out, level them from below and put in new
wide-plank oak floors.
</P>
<P>
   On a cold day, he enters the house and immediately lights
candles that are grouped in the living room fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love lighting fires,'' he says; he bought the house partly
because every room has a fireplace. Whether they work, he doesn't
know. This summer, he plans to have them inspected and have at
least one of them made functional.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens says she loves the house now because it gives them room
for relatives to visit and space for their boys to roam. It is
cozy, too, especially in the living room, with its yellow walls,
enveloping red couch and paintings by Stevens on the walls.
</P>
<P>
   But she says she doesn't know whether they will live there for
three years or 20. ``The thing with Michael is, you never know,''
she says. ``It's his creative, artistic outlet.''
</P>
<P>
   And he doesn't disagree. ``She's right,'' he says. ``I'm always
looking for a house.'' If one turned up with a sunny back yard, he
might make the leap again.
</P>
<P>
   But this house has been more than just a project. It actually
led to his new career.
</P>
<P>
   While redoing the bathrooms, Bruno made a number of visits to
Ann Sacks in Manhattan, a showroom where he picked out tumbled
marble, a bowl sink and glass tiles. One day, a customer had a
question, and he found himself answering.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, he had gotten interested in something that turned
out to be compelling, and before he knew it, he became a salesman
for the company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
