<SLUG> BC-SC-REPUBS-TURNOUT-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS TURN OUT IN LARGE NUMBERS IN SOUTH CAROLINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ With an enthusiasm that party officials say
they have never seen in a primary, voters of all political creeds
thronged the polls Saturday to choose a Republican presidential
candidate, many of them giddy at the thought that their choice
might determine the party's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Polling places around the state reported long lines and the
potential for a record turnout. J. Sam Daniels, the executive
director of the state Republican Party, said the overall turnout
would certainly exceed 300,000 and might reach 400,000, far more
than the 276,000 who voted in the Republican primary of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout in polling places in traditionally Democratic areas _
many open for the first time, because of a federal lawsuit filed by
Democrats _ was far higher than normal.
</P>
<P>
   But there were also large numbers of voters in Republican areas.
In Forest Acres, a primarily Republican suburb of Columbia with
large numbers of independents and so-called Reagan Democrats,
nearly a quarter of all 1,600 registered voters in one precinct had
voted by 10:20 a.m. Most of those standing in line said they were
voting for Gov. George W. Bush, but there were also many bumper
stickers for Sen. John McCain and for Alan Keyes in the parking
lot.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the lawsuit, which charged that the Republican Party
had closed many polling places in black and other Democratic areas
in 1996, there were hundreds more polling places than ever before
open this year. The suit was settled last week when the party
agreed to provide volunteers or pay state workers to open every
possible polling place, but the large number of inexperienced poll
workers caused problems throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   In Greenville, a conservative bastion of Bush support, 21
polling places that were scheduled to open were closed because
volunteers did not show up, Daniels said. This infuriated the
McCain campaign, which has been relying on support from Democrats
and independents. McCain's aides charged that some precincts in
Democratic areas had been kept closed to suppress votes for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had thought the court had clearly dictated that all polling
sites should be open,'' McCain said on his bus Saturday morning.
``I believe there should be a full investigation. I don't know what
to say. It's so disappointing to hear this.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels said there had been no political intent in the closings,
for which he blamed inexperienced volunteers. Only three of the
closed polls were in black or Democratic areas, he said; the others
were in solid Republican districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some voters have been inconvenienced, but we have done
everything humanly possible to let them know where to vote,'' he
said. ``It's not political at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside Greenville, however, there were few reports of problems.
In Lexington County, a suburban area west of Columbia, all the
polling places opened as scheduled, and voting was substantial even
in Democratic areas.
</P>
<P>
   At the Brookland United Methodist Church in West Columbia, a
traditionally Democratic area, workers had expected about 139
voters for the whole day, based on past turnouts in Republican
primaries. But by noon, with seven hours left to vote, there had
already been 120 voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been involved in politics since I was 15, and I've never
seen this many voters for a primary,'' said Tommy Windsor, the
county's Republican chairman. ``This is approaching
general-election levels, and we've never had that before.''
</P>
<P>
   Turnout was much lower in black areas, although there was a
trickle of voters in the community center in Martin Luther King Jr.
Park near downtown Columbia. Black voters make up about 60 percent
of the state's Democratic Party, and many have said they are not
interested in either of the leading Republican candidates.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One black woman at the center who would not give her name said
she voted for McCain because her husband was a veteran and liked
the senator's war record.
</P>
<P>
   In Ward 4 of Orangeburg, a black precinct about 40 miles south
of Columbia, only 13 people had voted as of 1 p.m., compared with
19 people who voted in 1996. But in white areas of town, turnout
was quite heavy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exceptionally high even for a general election,'' said
Dan Peck, a volunteer poll manager for Wards 7 and 10 in
Orangeburg, who predicted nearly 50 percent participation in his
areas. ``I suspect that it's due to the very, very close race
between the two men.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
