<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAMENSKY AND FLEURY PROVIDE MORE GRIEF THAN GOALS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Theo Fleury, the frustration has increased to the point
where broken hockey sticks have turned into obscene gestures. For
Valery Kamensky, the frustration stems from what he perceives as
not enough ice time.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Rangers, the source of their frustration this season
can be traced directly to the lack of production from both Fleury
and Kamensky, the team's two biggest free-agent signings last
off-season. So far, they have been the Rangers' two biggest busts.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury and Kamensky were supposed to be the stopgaps in the
Rangers' rebuilding process. They were seen as the two players
whose offensive capabilities would hasten the Rangers' return to
respectability _ and the playoffs, allowing the organization to buy
a little time while it awaits the arrival of Jamie Lundmark and
Pavel Brendl from the junior leagues. (The stunted development of
Manny Malhotra, who has spent much of his sophomore season in the
National Hockey League in street clothes, is another question
altogether.)
</P>
<P>
   But after a 4-2 loss to Colorado at Madison Square Garden on
Friday, Fleury _ who was stoned by Patrick Roy on a first-period
short-handed breakaway _ admitted that he has been in a season-long
slump. A four-time 40-goal scorer over his first 11 NHL seasons,
Fleury has just 13 goals this season, none on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   Kamensky, meanwhile, who scored 26 or more goals four times over
his first eight NHL seasons, has just eight this season.
</P>
<P>
   If Fleury and Kamensky were performing to their capabilities, no
one would be speculating about the job security of either Coach
John Muckler or Neil Smith, the team president and general manager.
But they aren't. And the Rangers' tenuous hold on the eighth and
final Eastern Conference playoff spot gets looser with each passing
day.
</P>
<P>
   The frustration for Fleury hit a new low Friday night, going
beyond the smashing of his sticks on the ice. Saturday Fleury
admitted he directed an obscene gesture at the Garden crowd that
was booing him in the third period after he again failed to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just frustrated more than anything else,'' Fleury said.
``I just heard the boos. Hopefully I score three goals tomorrow and
that will be the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleury had ample opportunities to tie the game in the third
period with the Rangers trailing, 3-2. But he could not beat Roy,
his teammate for a few months last season, from the left side of
the net on two good chances. And so afterward, Fleury had to face
the same questions he has heard all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting the opportunities,'' said Fleury, who has made an
effort to shoot more lately. ``And eventually, it's going to go in.
Hopefully, that will be the start of something.''
</P>
<P>
   But will it be too late for the Rangers, if and when Fleury
finally does regain his scoring touch? This is a player who has
averaged 34 goals a season over his NHL career. This season, he is
on an 18-goal pace. When asked if he had experienced anything like
this before, Fleury said: ``Never. Never. Thirteen goals? That's
not good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Muckler said: ``You always feel he's going to break out of it.
So far, he hasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The short-handed breakaway was most frustrating of all. In
Denver on Nov. 5, Fleury had steamrolled Roy to score a breakaway
goal. This time, he pulled up and tried numerous dekes from the low
slot before Roy made a glove save on Fleury's forehand shot. At the
time, the score was tied, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I score that goal, it's a huge momentum boost for our
team,'' said Fleury, who responded by destroying his stick. ``I
want to do those things. It's just not going in. I'm as
disappointed and frustrated as anybody. I know why I'm here, and
it's not happening. That's what's really eating me up inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, what's eating Kamensky up is the way he is being
used by Muckler. When asked Friday why his reconstituted line with
Alexandre Daigle and John MacLean played so well offensively in the
third period after being invisible for most of the first two,
Kamensky said: ``Because we sit the first two periods. Look at the
ice time. That's why.''
</P>
<P>
   Muckler might point to the minus-2 rating that each player on
the line had as to why they sat for most of the first two periods.
But it was not the first time Kamensky complained about his lack of
ice. The problem is, he is not doing enough with the time he has
received.
</P>
<P>
   And the inability of both Fleury and Kamensky to score is
threatening to overshadow the moves the Rangers have made this
season _ like the acquisition of Radek Dvorak _ and the progress of
the rookies Jan Hlavac, Mike York and Kim Johnsson as the Rangers
wait for the rest of their future to arrive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 1641EST &QL; 
