u s BC-BBA-YANKS-RIVERA-NYT &LR;      02-19 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RIVERA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVERA LOSES RULING ON SALARY BUT TAKES IT IN STRIDE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Mariano Rivera was in the middle of doing sit-ups
just past noon Saturday when Rick Cerrone, the New York Yankees'
director of media relations, told him he had lost his arbitration
decision. To Rivera, it was a $2 million conversation: The
arbitrators ruled he will earn $7.25 million for the 2000 season,
rather than the $9.25 million for which he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, thank you,'' Rivera said politely, without stopping his
sit-ups. Sweat dripped down the sides of his face as he continued
through several more sets of sit-ups. He did not stop to gripe to
teammates, or reflect. He did not whine or complain. ``It's good
for me either way,'' he said, as he walked off the field. ``I'm
happy with the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera wanted more money, undoubtedly; he rejected a four-year,
$36 million offer from the Yankees that might have been increased
if there had been more progress in the negotiations. But within an
hour of the decision, Rivera joked with teammates, accepting their
good-natured barbs with laughter. When the bullpen coach Tony
Cloninger asked if Rivera was going to take him to lunch, the
Yankees' closer held up a hand and replied, ``Can't afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   When reporters approached him joylessly to ask about the
decision, Rivera began to chuckle. ``It's like somebody died in
here,'' he said. ``I'm not upset at all, and I have to concentrate
on what I have to do this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in a loss, Rivera's arbitration award was the largest in
baseball history, surpassing the $5.3 million Jack McDowell was
awarded in 1994, also in a losing case. Rivera, who saved 45 games
in 49 chances last year and is arguably the best closer in
baseball, defeated the Yankees in arbitration last year, winning a
salary of $4.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees discussed a long-term contract with Rivera's
representatives in January, and even in the minutes leading to the
hearing here Thursday. The Yankees' offer stood at $36 million over
four years _ and they may have been willing to increase that by $2
million or $3 million _ and Rivera's representatives reduced their
asking price, proposing a deal with a base salary of $39 million,
in addition to what the Yankees considered substantial incentives.
Feeling their offer fair, the Yankees' officials rejected that
proposal, and the arbitrators, Howard Block, Elisabeth Neumeier and
Alan Symonette, heard the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' contention was that their offer of $7.25 million
would still make Rivera the highest-paid closer in the game, for
although San Diego's Trevor Hoffman signed a four-year, $32 million
deal, he actually will make $6.6 million in salary this year before
any bonuses. Rivera's agent, Jim Bronner, noted that before this
year Rivera's salary has virtually matched that of the shortstop
Derek Jeter. Rivera made $550,000 in 1997, Jeter $540,000; Rivera
and Jeter both earned $750,000 in '98; Jeter made $5 million last
year, Rivera $4.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that Jeter settled his case at $10 million for this
year, Bronner argued, and he was also a valuable member of the
Yankees' team, why should a disparity exist now?
</P>
<P>
   As Rivera waited for the decision Saturday morning, the Yankees'
principal owner, George Steinbrenner, appeared near the practice
field to watch; once that happened, David Cone mused later, it was
probably a bad sign for Rivera. ``Heard anything about the case?''
Cone yelled to Steinbrenner. ``Mariano's nervous over here.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner yelled back, ``Cone, you old union guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner did not learn of the decision until Cone passed on
the news in the clubhouse later, and Steinbrenner immediately
walked to Rivera, placed hands on either of his shoulders and
assured him nothing would change; Rivera nodded his head and
smiled.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner said afterward that the team would continue to try
to explore a long-term deal with Rivera _ ``Our people will be
talking to them,'' he said _ but that may not be the case
immediately. After getting hammered by decisions involving Rivera
and Jeter in arbitration last year, the Yankees might very well
withdraw their long-term offer, something club officials certainly
will discuss in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   But Rivera intends to get back to baseball. ``The money,'' he
said, ``will take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
