</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWNTOWN-PHILLY-REAL-1035(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILADELPHIA: A SPECULATIVE DEVELOPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID J. WALLACE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The first speculative office project in almost a
decade is under way in downtown Philadelphia, as a 20-story
building atop a commuter railroad hub is about to be stripped down
to its steel skeleton.
</P>
<P>
   When the renovation at the southwest corner of 16th Street and
John F. Kennedy Boulevard is complete, its owners say the building,
Four Penn Center, will be a brand-new structure using the steel
framework of its predecessor. It will be the first office project
since 1992 that was begun without tenants already signed to leases
for a significant part of the building.
</P>
<P>
   Leggat McCall Properties LLC, of Boston, bought the building for
$12.3 million in December from the government of Singapore,
according to the contract of sale filed with the office of the
city's recorder of deeds. Leggat McCall said it had budgeted an
additional $70 million for the reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown office space, in short supply after two strong years of
leasing activity, has been further depleted by the removal of 15
older office buildings from the city's inventory. Six have been
converted to hotels; the rest have been converted into apartment
houses, with developers taking advantage of a 10-year tax-abatement
program.
</P>
<P>
   These and other losses have depleted 10 percent of what had been
in 1990 the city's 40.5 million square feet of office space,
according to Grubb &AMP; Ellis, the real estate services company. As of
Dec. 31, Grubb &AMP; Ellis reported, the downtown office vacancy rate
was 9.5 percent, compared with 13.1 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   At Four Penn Center, work began this month on asbestos removal,
said C. Craig Guers, a Leggat McCall senior vice president, and the
building is expected to reopen in the spring of 2001 with 400,000
square feet of space. The building, which sits above the tracks and
platforms of Suburban Station, a hub for regional rail and subway
lines, is just two blocks from City Hall and the municipal and
criminal courts.
</P>
<P>
   Guers said he expected annual rents in his building to be about
$26 a square foot, nearly 20 percent less than the rents of up to
$32 asked in the city's newest buildings, most of which were
completed between 1989 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   There are advantages to not trying to build a new structure,
however. ``I shave 12 months off the project by the steel already
being in place,'' he said. ``Brand-new construction, including
approvals and design, would be a 30- to 40-month process. We're
doing this in 15 months and we feel that's a manageable time frame
and economical because the West Market Street corridor has a 7
percent vacancy rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Guers estimated that the renovation, including new building
systems, wiring, elevators and climate controls, would cost about
$155 a square foot, adding that he looked for midsized law firms to
be among his tenants.
</P>
<P>
   He said he knew that some had leases expiring in the coming year
because they had signed leases with him a decade ago, when he
worked at other Penn Center buildings as a development manager for
Radnor Corp., the former real estate development arm of Sun Oil Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Downtown rents were in the low $20s two years ago,'' Guers
said. ``Then, in 1999, absorption set a record for the decade and
vacancy dropped by 25 percent in about six months. Leggat McCall's
biggest strength is in renovation _ we do it from Boston to
Washington _ and our people went through the building and figured
out how to make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Leggat McCall has new construction projects in the Philadelphia
suburbs, including Plymouth Meeting, Pa., and Mount Laurel, N.J.,
that stress quick construction in established markets where there
is room for relatively small buildings.
</P>
<P>
   While his company is willing to take small risks for small
rewards, he said, it is not willing to overextend itself on huge
projects involving large loans. Now, Guers said, there is a greater
emphasis than in the city's last building boom in the late '80s on
smaller, more efficient buildings closer to amenities such as
hotels, shops and restaurants and outfitted with premium systems
such as high-speed telecommunication and computer wiring.
</P>
<P>
   The Four Penn Center project is a major step in recovery for a
city still shaking off the hangover of excess space that lasted
from 1992 to 1996, said Wayne Fisher, senior vice president at
Grubb &AMP; Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   For most of those years, the city had a surplus of office space
that led to price cutting and costly incentives to lure tenants as
brokers worked to sublease or re-lease space vacated by takeover
targets such as Conrail.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, most of Conrail's operations were split between two
other rail carriers, CSX and Norfolk Southern. It then became a
small regional freight carrier in selected cities _ primarily in
the Northeast, but including Detroit _ and subleased 100,000 square
feet of its former 850,000 square feet of office space. CSX has
sublet an additional 650,000 square feet, 250,000 square feet of it
to PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   Merger announcements unsettled an otherwise positive real estate
leasing picture. Peco Energy Co., the region's electric utility, is
merging with Unicom Corp., a Chicago electric utility.
</P>
<P>
   And SmithKline Beecham, a pharmaceutical company that last year
opened an additional 215,000-square-foot building adjacent to its
598,000-square-foot headquarters two blocks north of Four Penn
Center, has agreed to merge with Glaxo Wellcome, a British
pharmaceutical corporation. No decision has been made on the site
of the Glaxo-SmithKline headquarters, according to Thomas Johnson,
a SmithKline spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Over 1.3 million square feet of downtown office leases were
signed in 1999, a record year, more than double the city's average
of 553,000 square feet per year, said Fisher of Grubb &AMP; Ellis. The
flurry of leases leaves many potential tenants for Four Penn Center
already committed elsewhere, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rents aren't spiking the way they are in Boston or
Washington,'' he said. ``But we're getting a steady 10 percent per
annum or about $2 extra per square foot. All the background
statistics say now is the time if you were ever going to do a
renovation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Among the risks Fisher identified was a shrinking pool of
prospective tenants looking to lease more than 100,000 square feet
of space; the likelihood that Philadelphia will not repeat the
stellar pace of 1999 and the constant exposure to mergers and
acquisitions, which might open up space in otherwise fully rented
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-building Penn Center complex, which has a total of
about 5 million square feet of space, extends from 15th to 19th
Street, between Market Street and John F. Kennedy Boulevard. It
occupies the former site of the old Pennsylvania Railroad's massive
rail station and elevated tracks, which were demolished in the
1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Begun in 1953, the Penn Center development initiated a shift of
office construction from the city's geographic center of Broad and
Market streets to the Market Street corridor as far west as 22nd
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Even at a modest 20 stories, Four Penn Center is not
overshadowed by the majority of its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   This is because, for more than half a century, developers
observed a self-imposed 500-foot restriction on the height of their
office towers so that they would not rise higher than the 548-foot
City Hall, which is topped by a bronze statue of William Penn. But
in 1986 the restriction was scrapped with the completion of the
945-foot 1 Liberty Place tower.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the office buildings in the central business district
built before that date have changed ownership in the last five
years, Guers said. The Four Penn Center building has been empty for
two and a half years since its last tenant, Reliance Insurance Co.,
moved into a tower several blocks north.
</P>
<P>
   One of the greatest challenges for developers, said Glenn
Mueller, managing director of Legg Mason Real Estate Research in
Baltimore, is finding tenants that are viable over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real risk is not in whether you can rent it today but
whether the company will be around two or three years from now,
because of the Internet and merger-and-acquisition activity,''
Mueller said.
</P>
</TEXT>
