<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BROOKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS WELCOME BROOKS TO CAMP WITH OPEN WALLETS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ Each of Al Leiter's 162 strikeouts cost
him $100 last year, and the New York Mets left-hander was happy to
pay it.
</P>
<P>
   The money went to a charity sponsored by the country singer
Garth Brooks, who was sincere during a spring training tryout with
the San Diego Padres last year. So Leiter made the donation gladly,
and welcomed Brooks warmly Saturday when he reported for work at
Mets camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talking to San Diego guys, he took it seriously,'' Leiter
said. ``Had we heard grumblings that it was just a fun fantasy camp
for him with San Diego, there would have been a little different
perception in the Mets organization.''
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old Brooks was at Thomas J. White Stadium by 7:45
a.m., before almost all of his new teammates. He took part in
batting practice, immediately after Mike Piazza, and fielding
drills, using a glove he got from Toronto pitcher David Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Turk Wendell invited him to go fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole goal here is that people see my respect for the game
is unequaled, and my love for the game is equal to any fan's on the
other side of the fence,'' said Brooks, who will leave during the
final week of exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   The other aim for Brooks is to promote his charity, the Touch
'Em All Foundation, which gives money to children's organizations.
Players make performance-based donations, which corporations and
celebrities match. The Mets are donating $100,000, as is
eSuperstars.com, a new charity-based Internet auction site for
which Mets manager Bobby Valentine is the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks will play third base and left field for the Mets, whose
spring training tickets are selling at their highest rates since
the 1994-95 players strike. Last spring, Brooks went 1 for 22,
though he struck out only four times. The Padres star Tony Gwynn
left him a note at the end of camp telling Brooks he could have
made it if he had started younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could hit some balls out now and then in batting
practice,'' Padres General Manager Kevin Towers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a pretty good feel of the strike zone and didn't swing
at a lot of bad pitches. His arm got sore because he hadn't played
a lot, but it was strong when he started, and he took good routes
in the outfield and hit the cutoff guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a speed demon, but he went 100 percent down the line.
The ball could already be at first, and Garth would still be
running as fast as he could through the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   For Brooks, who has sold 97 million albums, the hardest thing
about baseball is remembering he is not giving a concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gig is to pull the people in,'' Brooks said. ``Here, if you
hear one of them, you're gone, and I never got over that. As soon
as I stepped out on the deck, it's like, `This is the show.' So I'm
so wound up by the time I get up there; all I'm thinking is
mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is going to sound stupid, but I probably plan to
strike out more this year because I'm going to be swinging. I'm
trying to be a ballplayer this year, instead of trying just not to
strike out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
