<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-815&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGHTENING ADMISSIONS IN CONDOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More and more often, condominium boards in New York
City are acting like co-op boards in screening potential buyers,
according to brokers, lawyers and managing agents, a pattern that
seems to conflict with one of the primary reasons that condominiums
frequently sell for more than similar co-ops.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason for the disparity in price, they say, is that
co-op boards have the power to reject potential buyers for just
about any reason other than one that would be deemed
discriminatory, making them more difficult to sell. In addition,
they say, co-ops are more likely to have constraints on subletting
_ with policies and rules ranging from the imposition of time
limits and sublet fees to outright prohibitions against the
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the premium that condominiums command in the
marketplace, however, there seems to be a growing number of
condominiums whose boards are beginning to act more like co-op
directors than condominium managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm finding a tremendous push on the part of some condominiums
to be more like co-ops,'' said Ronni Lynn Arougheti, president of
Heron Ltd., a Manhattan property management company. ``With the
market for apartments so hot, condominium boards are trying to be a
little more particular about who buys into the building. And if
they're not sure whether a particular buyer is financially
qualified, they'll usually ask for some backup proof of the buyer's
finances.''
</P>
<P>
   Arougheti, who is also a lawyer, said that until fairly recently
it would have been unusual for a condominium board to demand such
information from a buyer. That, she said, is because condominium
boards generally have only limited power to block a sale.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Arougheti said, in most cases the only thing a board of
managers can do when confronted with a sale they would rather not
see consummated is exercise its ``right of first refusal'' whereby
the condominium association may buy the apartment from the seller
on the same terms and conditions that had been offered by the
buyer.
</P>
<P>
   While the right of first refusal is a formidable tool, it is
also an expensive one; most condominiums are hardly in a position
to block sales they don't approve of by buying apartments they
don't really need. How, then, could a condominium board of managers
use the right of first refusal to control who buys into the
building?
</P>
<P>
   ``By taking so long to make up their minds that moss grows on
the contract,'' said Frederick W. Peters, president of Ashforth
Warburg Associates, a Manhattan real estate brokerage firm. He
explained that most condominium bylaws give the condominium board
the right to ask for financial information from a potential buyer
so that it can make an informed decision about whether or not to
exercise its right of first refusal.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, in recent months boards have been asking for
increasing amounts of information and taking increasing amounts of
time to examine it. And that, he said, can stretch some deals to
the breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some people, the whole point of buying a condominium is
not having to worry about going through an admissions committee,''
Peters said, adding that the increased scrutiny alone was enough to
discourage some potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what has now begun to emerge with this new trend is that
boards will ask for all this financial information and then take so
long to act on the package that the contract expires. We try to
persuade people to comply with their requests, but frankly, it's
absurd, and the buyers are frequently and understandably furious.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur I. Weinstein, vice president of the Council of New York
Cooperatives and Condominiums, agreed that some condominiums
appeared to be trying to exercise greater control over admissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that in exercising its right of first
refusal, most condominium boards have the power to inquire into the
finances of the proposed purchaser,'' Weinstein said. ``And some
do, in fact, make the same kinds of inquiries that a co-op board
would make because their concerns are basically the same.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Weinstein said, it is probably more important
for condominiums to ferret out financially shaky potential
purchasers than it is for co-ops, because it is more difficult for
a condominium association to collect unpaid common charges when a
unit owner defaults than it is for a co-op to collect maintenance
charges in the same circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   That, he said, is because when a condominium unit owner defaults
on his common charges and mortgage, the owner's lender, rather than
the condominium association, must be paid first. With a co-op,
Weinstein said, the co-op corporation must be paid before the
shareholder's lender.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression is that more condominiums have been burned by
nonpayers than co-ops,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some condominiums have sought to extend their control even
beyond the admissions process to the controversial issue of
subletting, said Weinstein.A condominium can adopt rules regulating subletting the same
way that a co-op can,'' he said. For example, he explained, a
condominium could conceivably amend its bylaws to impose maximum
time limits on sublets or even prohibit them entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, the method that has been used to control
sublets has been for the condominium to exercise its right of first
refusal to rent the apartment from the owner and then sublet it to
an acceptable tenant,'' Weinstein said. ``But there's nothing that
would prevent a condominium association from amending its bylaws to
require approval of any tenancy in the building.''
</P>
<P>
   Errol A. Brett, a Manhattan co-op lawyer, said that he has seen
some condominiums take yet another page from the co-op playbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Condominiums have started to realize that they really have no
way of raising money when they need it,'' Brett said, explaining
that since condominium associations own no property that they can
mortgage, the usual method for raising cash is to impose an
assessment on unit owners. ``But condominium boards have noticed
that co-ops have this wonderful little thing called a flip tax,''
he said, ``and now the condominiums want a flip tax too.''
</P>
<P>
   A flip tax _ a charge imposed on a co-op shareholder when a unit
is being sold _ can range from a couple of hundred dollars to many
thousands of dollars, depending on the formula used to calculate
the payment. For example, Brett said, in a recent condominium
conversion he negotiated, the tenants who purchased apartments
agreed to pay a 15 percent flip tax to the condominium association
when they sell their apartments.
</P>
<P>
   For existing buildings, he said, a condominium association would
have to amend its bylaws to initiate a flip tax _ a change that
usually requires a two-thirds majority of unit owners.
``Condominiums have traditionally never had flip taxes,'' Brett
said. ``But money's the name of the game in this town, and nobody
likes to do an assessment when money is needed. So for some
condominiums, a flip tax might make all the sense in the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
