<HEADLINE>
OFF TO CAMP? FORGET BEDROLL, TAKE BANKROLL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERRICK, N.Y. _ ``Now, you mentioned something tropical,''
Laurel Barrie said into the phone. ``Something along the lines of
Belize or Puerto Rico?''
</P>
<P>
   Across the small office, Barrie's colleague Ronni Bergman was
telling another client, ``Irene, when you see these waterfronts,
your eyes will absolutely bug out.''
</P>
<P>
   These women were not scouting locations for ``South Pacific,''
or even for honeymoons. They were talking summer camp. Remember the
bulky footlockers, the squeaking oarlocks, the ``best friends'' for
life (or eight weeks), the rivers of bug juice and calamine? Camp
might as well be college now, with the expense, the finely tuned
themes, the agonizing selection process.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the phones are ringing at the headquarters of Camp
Connection, the Century 21 of summer camps. Actually, it's just a
small office attached to Barrie's vinyl-sided house here. But so
many people want help planning their children's summers that Camp
Connection is about to expand, right into Barrie's den.
</P>
<P>
   Barrie sits at the intersection of two powerful trends, more
kids and more money. The office is an echo chamber of motherly
advice, gentle nudging and eye-rolling patience, all delivered in a
zesty South Shore Long Islandese.
</P>
<P>
   Here Barrie explains that she never talks to parents when
children are present. ``You tell me what parent is going to say in
front of their kid, `He thinks he's a great athlete and he's
not,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Or what about those former ``hippie'' parents who remember
summers of joyous experimentation? ``They say, `I had the best time
but my kid better not be able to do those things.'''
</P>
<P>
   Barrie went to summer camp, as did her children, who are now
grown, and she met her husband working at a camp owned by his
parents. She's pretty much heard it all when it comes to parental
anxiety and quirky kids.
</P>
<P>
   But some cases are memorable, like the ``white food girl,''
whose mother insisted she would eat only things like white bread,
rice and vanilla ice cream. Barrie found a camp that would not make
her eat any polychromatic food. ``She went to camp and survived,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Camp Connection, which is paid commissions to represent hundreds
of camps and summer programs, helps parents pick through a dizzying
dessert cart of possibilities. The list reads like the periodic
table. Lakota and Lokanda and Lohikan and Louemma and Tree Tops and
Timber Tops and Tall Pines and Tall Oaks and Watitoh and Watonka
and Waukeela and Wekeela.
</P>
<P>
   For teen-agers there are four- to eight-week travel trips around
the country. Community service trips whisk older teen-agers to
economically depressed but exotic locations like Indian
reservations or Thailand, where they build houses or provide child
care and also hike or go sightseeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really the first time they're giving back,'' Barrie said.
``They're coming home with callused hands.'' All for thousands of
dollars. These programs are gaining popularity, she said, because
``there's a lot of money, and parents are not pushing their kids
out of the house at 16 to work.'' Summer programs can cost $6,000
or more for eight weeks and, like the ordeal of picking a college,
families often tour camps a year before. ``Really, college is
easier,'' Barrie said. ``You're restricted by SATs. You're
restricted by grades. You're restricted by price.'' With camp, the
only limit is your imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Take last week's case of the fourth-grade football fanatic.
Barrie told the young Steve Young's mother that contact football
camps lasted only a week to keep children from being pulverized.
``It's terrible,'' she sympathized over the phone, ``but they're
doing it to protect the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrie told her that there's one week in New York, another in
Orlando, Fla., another in Washington, and so on. ``I guess you can
fly him all over the country,'' Barrie said, facetiously.
</P>
<P>
   She agreed to get the woman some information. When she hung up,
she rolled her eyes, ever so slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's going to fly him around the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
