<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DeCASTRO-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Nev., Calif., Fla.)  
 OLGITA DeCASTRO, 65, SINGER WITH SISTER GROUP  
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Olgita DeCastro, who performed and recorded with her famous
singing cousins, the DeCastro Sisters, for over 30 years, died Feb.
14 at her home in Las Vegas. She was 65.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was an asthma attack, said her publicity agent, Alan
Eichler Associates.
</P>
<P>
   DeCastro, who was born in Los Angeles, joined the DeCastro trio
in the 1960s, filling in when needed for one or other of her
cousins _ Peggy, Cherie and Babette _ and later becoming a
permanent member of the ensemble when Babette DeCastro retired.
</P>
<P>
   The original trio had their breakthrough hit in 1954, with
``Teach Me Tonight,'' by Sammy Cahn and Gene de Paul. The sisters
came to the United States from Cuba in 1947 and appeared that year
in the film ``Copacabana'' with Carmen Miranda and Groucho Marx.
</P>
<P>
   DeCastro is survived by a brother, Robert, of Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
