<HEADLINE>
ISLANDERS' POWER PLAY IS TOO MUCH FOR DEVILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The New York Islanders' power play,
ranked 26th in the National Hockey League, would not seem much of a
challenge for the New Jersey Devils' penalty-killing unit, which is
the league's second-best. But the Islanders made a mockery of those
statistics Saturday afternoon at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   With two power-play goals _ by the rookies Josh Green and Tim
Connolly _ the Islanders put an end to the Devils' seven-game
unbeaten streak, 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils still have the league's best record at 36-16-7, but
the Islanders, with a nearly mirror-image mark of 17-35-7, have
split the season series, 2-2. The outcome was notable for the
Devils for several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Devils allowed two power-play goals in the first two
chances after holding their opposition to just three in 50 attempts
over the previous 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   _ It was only the second loss in goalie Martin Brodeur's last 22
starts.
</P>
<P>
   _ It was the Devils' second loss in their last 16 home games
(13-2-1).
</P>
<P>
   The two teams showed their dislike for each other from the early
stages. Captain Scott Stevens of the Devils and Steve Webb set the
tone with a fight with seven minutes 29 seconds left in the first
period.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders, who had lost just once in their previous five
games, played with confidence from the outset. They had more jump
in their play and were eager to erase the memory of their previous
visit here, a 4-0 loss on Jan. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Scatchard got the Islanders off to a quick start, scoring
his sixth goal of the season just 4:04 into the game. It came when
he redirected Kenny Jonsson's pass from the left side during a
break that was executed with such speed and perfection that it
caught Brodeur facing the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   Scatchard's goal came on the second shot of the game for the
Islanders, but they enjoyed their lead for a mere 69 seconds before
John Madden tied it from the slot after a pass by Brian Rafalski.
It was the second goal in as many games for Madden, who has 10 in
his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   But late in the first period, the Islanders put on a surprising
burst of special-teams excellence that proved to be decisive. On
their first power play of the game, Connolly took a pass from Mark
Lawrence and scored from close range on the left for his 10th over
the fallen Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, the Islanders got their second power play
and Green scored his fifth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   What made the first session worse for the Devils was that they
failed on two manpower advantages of their own, including a
five-on-three advantage they held for 75 seconds. The Devils were
so inept with the man advantage that it was the Islanders who had
the best chance.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Devils, Brodeur held his ground when Niklas
Anderson broke away after intercepting a pass by Claude Lemieux and
tried to beat Brodeur with a move from left to right.
</P>
<P>
   That brilliant save by Brodeur _ one of only 15 he made Saturday
_ failed to inspire the Devils, who allowed Green's goal with just
1.1 second left before the first intermission to put themselves in
a precarious position.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were the better team in the second period, holding
the Islanders to just three shots in the session while taking 10.
But all the Devils managed was a power-play goal by Jason Arnott
with 1:37 left in the session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
