<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A MONTHLY BOXING SHOW WITH ATTITUDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``If I had Oscar De La Hoya everyone would know who I
am,'' Cedric Kushner said wistfully. His sad eyes and hangdog gray
mustache furthered the sense of deprivation; De La Hoya fights
Derrell Coley on Saturday night at Madison Square Garden and poor
Cedric, like you and me, won't have a piece of the action.
</P>
<P>
   But two nights earlier, just across the street from the Garden,
he will offer up his version of boxing, so retrograde, so socially
incorrect, so true to the sport's intrinsic character that its time
has probably come yet again. It is a monthly evening of booze,
food, cigars, songs, scantily clad women dancing and scantily clad
men hitting each other.
</P>
<P>
   Kushner calls it ``a respectable men's night out.'' It is billed
as ``Heavyweight Explosion'' and occurs again Thursday night at the
Hammerstein Ballroom of the Manhattan Center on 34th Street off
Eighth Avenue. It may be a more rewarding event for anthropologists
than for purist fight fans. I found last month's respectable men's
night out an endearingly sleazy evening of girlie jiggle and
erratic pugilism. Kushner, a realist, took no offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a single guy,'' said Kushner, 51. ``I love to go out with
the guys to a restaurant or a bar and talk nasty. In my heart, I
believe that is what guys like to do.''
</P>
<P>
   We were looking down on Central Park from Kushner's high-rise
living room last week. Calls came from all over the world. Like all
action entertainments, boxing has no borders. Most of the 57
matches he promoted from Tokyo to Biloxi last year have been seen
on foreign television as well as cable here. A former music
promoter, Kushner says he has 35 fighters under exclusive
promotional contract. If only one of them becomes a heavyweight
champion or beats De La Hoya, everyone would know who Kushner is.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he isn't trying to become as powerful as the reigning
warlords, Bob Arum, whom he says he likes, and Don King, whom he
blames for most of boxing's problems. (Everyone in boxing says this
until there is a chance to make a deal with King.)
</P>
<P>
   Kushner has admitted trying to have his fighters boosted in the
ratings of the boxing organizations by paying off officials.
Bribery is not exclusively an Olympic event. In boxing, however, it
has always been factored into the cost of doing business and may
even add to the faux outlaw sensibility that gives soft boys in
ringside seats the testosterone shivers.
</P>
<P>
   Soft boy that I am, I arrived early for last month's show. A DJ
was sampling, Mr. T-type bouncers were guarding the ropes, young
women dressed for the beach were ankling about. I felt young again.
The cream of boxing society held court around the empty ring. There
was Lou DiBella, the HBO booker, a prince of this realm, and LeRoy
Neiman, its Toulouse-Lautrec, an artist whose work seems to adorn
every program and hang above the mantel of every rich athlete.
</P>
<P>
   I must have forgotten that Bert Sugar, boxing's Thucydides, does
not doff his signature hat for the national anthem but rather tilts
it forward to obscure his still ferally handsome face. Meanwhile,
the cheaper seats in the balconies were filling with the families
and neighbors of the boxers, and the hard-core fans, many of them
middle-aged working men with Purple Heart noses.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't seen the yuppie traders right away because they were
downstairs in the VIP room, bonding over food, drink and cigars,
and watching the prelims on closed-circuit TV. They had to be
herded up to their $125 seats to hoot at the dancers and the ring
girls, which brought back memories of bonding in strip clubs before
the mayor closed them down. There is only one x in boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fights are the nucleus of the evening,'' Kushner had told me,
``but atmosphere is as important.''
</P>
<P>
   The fights themselves were mostly second-rate. A top boxer
(Shannon Briggs will be on display Thursday) does not expose
himself to damage in a 2,000-seat arena for a short purse (Kushner
says $20,000 is the most he has paid a main-event fighter, $600 is
an average for the prelims). So there are house pets against tomato
cans and cupcakes, and the occasional solid pro; I liked Monte
Barrett, a local fighter who hammered out a unanimous 10-round
decision. I also liked his tattoos, especially ``In God I Trust''
in illuminated letters across his back. He will be fighting
Thursday, too.
</P>
<P>
   What does it all mean? Beats me. The jiggly women displayed
Internet addresses on their round cards and most of the fighters
who lost seemed as unwilling as I am to take punishment. I called
around vainly for explication until my son read me a paragraph from
Philip Wylie's recently reissued 1942 classic, ``Generation of
Vipers.''
</P>
<P>
   Wylie imagined a future historian writing about pre-World War II
sports thusly: ``The sight of two men hammering each other in this
fashion _ occasionally, indeed, to death _ was doubtless some
psychic compensation to the ordinary man for the formidable and
revolting circumstances in which he was forced to live.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
