<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD TUNE FOR STARKS: NEW CLUB, NO CHANCE 
TAX'S CHILLING EFFECTS 
RADOJEVIC'S FAMILY TIES
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Starks heard that Pat Riley wanted him for a playoff run in
Miami. It was the kind of gossip that made Starks daydream of
having the ball in his hands with the season on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying if I said I didn't think about that,'' said
Starks, the former Knicks guard. ``When your name is on the trading
block, you hear things and you hope for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Starks spoke by cellular phone from the office of the Chicago
Bulls team physician last Friday, moments after he had taken his
physical.
</P>
<P>
   Just like last year, when the Knicks shipped him to the woeful
Warriors for Latrell Sprewell, Starks pulled the shortest straw of
a three-way trade last Wednesday that sent Toni Kukoc to
Philadelphia and Larry Hughes to Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   John Starks, Chicago Bull. The player who once dunked on Michael
Jordan laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, it's strange,'' he said. ``After all the
rivalries over the years we had with Chicago, all of a sudden I end
up in a Bulls uniform. It's a business. I already knew that. It's
just, as a player, from my standpoint, I want to be competing for a
championship. When you think of it in those terms, it's kind of
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   There is still a chance that Starks could be moved by the Bulls
before Thursday's trading deadline. Chicago general manager Jerry
Krause has shipped players in the last year of their contracts.
Starks is in the last year of his deal, and understands that he
probably is not in Chicago's long-range plans.
</P>
<P>
   Miami, Milwaukee, Toronto and Detroit are still looking for
complementary players to vault them past their Eastern Conference
counterparts. For now, Starks can shelve any visions of knocking
the Knicks out of the playoffs with a clutch 3-pointer. He was
scheduled to suit up against the Clippers Saturday night at the
United Center.
</P>
<P>
   Starks just sold his home in Stamford, Conn., and had moved his
family to a rental in northern California to begin the season. At
34, he still believes there are a few seasons left. But the days of
starting at shooting guard and playing 30-plus minutes appear over.
Spurring a playoff team off the bench is the one role he still
covets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no resentment against Golden State,'' he said. ``They
gave me an opportunity. From their standpoint, they got a younger
player with a lot of talent in exchange. It made perfect sense.
Larry Hughes is going to be a great player in this league.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'll get to play here if I stay. But I just hope it works
out where I can have a chance to really compete again.''
</P>
<P>
   Tax's Chilling Effects
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are still listening to offers for Glen Rice, the
Wizards are hoping someone takes Ike Austin off their hands and
Miami has made murmurs about plucking Walt Williams from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But as the trading deadline nears, many of the 29 teams are
showing restraint in regard to pulling off a blockbuster deal. The
reason? With an escrow tax kicking in for the 2001-2 seasons,
owners do not want their teams to take on long-term, exorbitant
contracts that catapult their franchise significantly past the
salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning that season, teams will have to pay into an escrow
account for each dollar over the salary cap. For example, if the
Knicks' composite salaries were $10 million over the salary cap
they would have to deposit an extra $10 million into a fund
negotiated by the players and owners during last year's collective
bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the luxury tax is having an impact several years in
advance as teams prepare for it,'' said John Nash, the Nets'
general manager. ``The thinking is, why make a trade for a guy like
Juwan Howard or Shawn Kemp today when it could cost you millions in
taxes tomorrow?''
</P>
<P>
   Howard and Kemp are among the underachieving players who signed
$100 million deals before the new agreement was in place. In Kemp's
case, the Cleveland power forward is due a combined $47 million in
the final two years of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just looking at the projected stagnant revenue growth and the
escrow threshold, you look at those last two years at $22 million
and $25 million and you ask yourself, `Do you really want to take
that on?''' said Geoff Petrie, the Sacramento Kings' general
manager. ``You've got to figure you're going to be paying tax if
you do something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Orlando general manager John Gabriel said, ``It may impact
future signings even more. Without balloon payments and ways to
offset the cap by reworking deals in certain seasons, you can't be
as creative as you once were. With the restrictions and the tax,
you better know what you're getting.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Rice is clearly the No. 1 commodity on the market, his
stock has fallen enough recently that the potential for the Lakers
swingman to secure the maximum-allowable deal from another team is
beginning to look slim.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Tracy McGrady can sign with any team after the
season, the Raptors' forward is not on the block. Toronto general
manager Glen Grunwald has apparently made a concerted effort to
hold onto McGrady in hopes he will become attached to the franchise
and want to re-sign this summer.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Radojevic's Family Ties
</P>
<P>
   In the NBA, entourages and hangers-on are part of the landscape.
Young players who come into money often share their wealth and new
opulent lifestyle with friends from the neighborhood, if for no
other reason than to repay their childhood loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Alek Radojevic is no different. The 7-foot-3-inch Toronto
Raptors rookie brought his posse to town recently, and it made for
one of the more touching reunions of the NBA season.
</P>
<P>
   Radojevic's posse is his family from Montenegro, an unstable
republic in the former Yugoslavia. In October, his sister, Zeljka,
30, joined him in Toronto. In January, his mother, Ilinka, and twin
brother, Zelimir, 23, left their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   They all fled Montenegro and drove to Budapest, where Radojevic
had arranged for the Canadian Embassy to grant them temporary
visas. Another sister, Ana, who lived in Quebec, moved to Toronto
to be with the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I always wanted, for every one to be here with
me,'' Radojevic said. ``The visas run out in a few more months, but
I'm doing everything in my power to keep them here. It is bad
situation in my country right now. I don't want them to go back.''
</P>
<P>
   Radojevic has yet to play in a NBA game. He underwent surgery
for a herniated disk in his back in January. That has not stopped
him from setting milestones.
</P>
<P>
   Playing for a Kansas junior college for a season after coming to
the United States, Radojevic went from being potentially drafted
into the Serbian army and fighting in Kosovo to being drafted into
the NBA. He became the highest-drafted Eastern European player ever
last June when the Raptors made him the 12th pick.
</P>
<P>
   Radojevic also won the first arbitration case in the history of
the NBA and FIBA, basketball's international governing body. In a
dispute over whether he was still under contract with a team in
Montenegro, Radojevic and his agent, Marc Cornstein, flew to London
with Jeffrey Mishkin, the league's chief counsel at the time.
Mishkin convinced an independent arbitrator that the contract with
the foreign team was invalid, enabling Radojevic to sign with
Toronto last August.
</P>
<P>
   He will be sitting at the end of the Raptors' bench on Wednesday
when Toronto and Vince Carter come to Madison Square Garden. With
his family safe at home in Toronto watching, Radojevic will not
play. But he has already proved how big and strong you have to be
to play in this league.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
