<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-GAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAREDEVILS SKIP LUGE TO PROMOTE SKELETON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JIM GOULD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ Jimmy Shea is riding a major adrenaline
high, he says. And it's not from his usual 80 mile-an-hour slide
down a banked ice chute.
</P>
<P>
   Shea, a Lake Placid resident and champion World Cup racer in a
sport known as skeleton, has gone from alternately training and
bartending to being anointed as something of a star for the 2000
Winter Goodwill Games, Ted Turner's made-for-television, five-day
multisport spectacle that concludes Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to more than 250 athletes from 20 countries
competing in such sports as skiing, figure skating, snowboarding,
ski jumping and speed skating, the world's best male and female
skeleton racers from North America and Europe are having their own
two-day, two-heats-each-day fest here at the new $20 million Mount
Van Hoevenberg Olympic bobsled and luge facility.
</P>
<P>
   For Shea, who leads the men's skeleton after Saturday's two
runs, that means national television exposure and likely national
team and individual sponsorship. That means no more duct tape
holding his racing suit and sled together, and no more late shifts
at a few of this resort town's bars and restaurants in between
training sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very, very exciting,'' said Shea, 31, after sharing the
stage at the opening ceremony earlier in the week with Turner, Gov.
George Pataki and other celebrities. ``Still, there's so many
stronger athletes here than me, and they deserve a lot more
recognition. I'm really honored, really I am, and I am just happy
to promote my sport, to make it better for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems to be working. Traditional sliding sports include luge
and bobsled, but skeleton racing is the one that most resembles
children on Flexible Flyers sledding on a snowy neighborhood hill.
The similarity ends there. International skeleton racers ride a
lugelike sled, but unlike luge racers who slide feet first on their
backs to limit the risk of injury, skeleton racers slide headfirst,
face down, their chins a few slim inches from the ice surface.
</P>
<P>
   The skeleton sled's steel runners are also rounded, unlike those
on the luge and bobsled, which are sharpened for maximum control.
At speeds illegal on any highway in the United States, keeping the
sled straight is no small feat on the twisting, mile-long course.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a child's sled, the skeleton sled has no steering.
Skeleton racers, resembling human rockets, slide with their arms
compressed to their sides, adjusting their course with slight
shifts of weight.
</P>
<P>
   Each slider wears only a Lycra speed suit and helmet, although
many wear duct tape on their suits to cover abrasions to shoulders,
elbows and knees. It's no wonder that this sport has a reputation
for attracting racers that are part athlete (note the sprint and
jump start) and part masochist (note the unpadded, concrete
embankments on the ice track).
</P>
<P>
   With no major sponsor or Olympic participation in decades, the
ragged look of skeleton racers has made them stepchildren among
traditional winter sliding sports. ``That is changing,'' Shea said,
``especially with the Goodwill Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting, a producer of the event, is featuring
skeleton on its prime-time telecasts, and used Shea in many of its
promotions for the Games.
</P>
<P>
   This has cemented skeleton's bid for credibility, along with its
recent inclusion as a medal sport in the next Winter Olympics, to
be held in Salt Lake City in February 2002. (Skeleton was dropped
as an Olympic event after the 1948 Winter Games.)
</P>
<P>
   Shea plans to compete for the United States in 2002 in Salt Lake
City. Shea's grandfather, Jack Shea, won two gold medals in speed
skating in the 1932 Winter Olympics, and his father, Jack Jr., was
a Nordic combined skier for the 1964 Olympic team in Innsbruck,
Austria. This would make Shea the first third-generation American
Olympian, according to skeleton officials.
</P>
<P>
   The skeleton at the Goodwill Games is the end of the 2000 season
for Shea. The experience has been uplifting, he said, especially
after a World Cup finish of seventh; he placed first the year
before.
</P>
<P>
   Shea has one more goal here: ``I am going to try to get Ted
Turner on a sled. That would be so cool.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
