<DOCNO> NYT20000219.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2228 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-TEAMGIBBS0220-COX     02-19 2093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-TEAMGIBBS0220-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    He has the cars, the drivers, the crew but not the Cup
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTERSVILLE, N.C. _ The building is a gem set among the piney
woods in the Huntersville Business Park.
</P>
<P>
   Sleek and modern, it would not be out of place as an addition to
Atlanta's High Museum. But this is one of the new temples of
stock-car racing, the Joe Gibbs place.
</P>
<P>
   It has all the trappings of success, including the big mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   A trophy case holds trinkets that Joe Gibbs gathered during his
NFL coaching career: Super Bowl rings, the coat he wore for
induction into the Pro Football Hall of Fame, a leather jacket from
the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Another window displays trophies that Bobby Labonte has won in
the Gibbs-owned No. 18 Pontiac. Another window is filling up fast
with Tony Stewart items _ helmets, photos, trophies and his Winston
Cup Rookie of the Year award. Still another window shows off Gibbs'
cars in drag racing.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the trophy cases: a 160-seat auditorium with a mega-watt
sound system, a break room where the Gibbs race team takes weekly
Bible study with the on-staff chaplain, a health club for both men
and women employees and a picture window overlooking a garage so
spotless you could picnic among the race cars.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing obviously missing is a Winston Cup Championship
Trophy. But that's almost a given. It is here that media sentiment,
if not the general public, already has delivered a loving cup,
anointing Gibbs' team as the powerhouse favorite in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, the boss says; we haven't won anything yet.
</P>
<P>
   Last season's success suddenly has positioned Gibbs as the most
formidable team in Winston Cup. Labonte finished second in the
point standings in 1999, winning five races. Stewart set a Cup
rookie record by winning three times and finished fourth in points.
Gibbs' two Pontiacs won four of the last five races.
</P>
<P>
   It took Gibbs nine years to achieve overnight success.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, everybody pictures this as instant success
for us,'' Gibbs said. ``I just want to say this has been one long,
hard deal. Think about it: This thing is nine years of guts, blood
and hard work, and we still haven't won a championship. I tell
everybody it's amazing, and I'm not bragging, but I won a Super
Bowl the second year I was a head coach.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gibbs certainly likes his chances this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think prior to last year, when we were a single-car team, if
you rated our race team, we could win races but we were not one of
the teams that race in that top three or four every week that's
able to win a championship,'' Gibbs said. ``The highest we finished
was fourth one year. I think what happened last year was for the
first time Bobby's team took a big leap forward in consistency.
Winning races is very important, but being there every week and not
having the big mistakes is just as big. ``I think we've got one of
the best pit crews. Our team won the pit-crew challenge (last
year). You've got to have a great motor program; we think we have
that now. You've got have great crew chiefs, people to run the
program. Great engineering.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, all these little pieces have to be put together, and I
think for the first time last year we showed that we were
consistent enough to say that we can run for a championship. That's
the exciting thing about this year.''
</P>
<P>
   FROM TURF TO TRACK
</P>
<P>
   The pieces have been falling nicely into place for Gibbs' racing
operation since it began with Dale Jarrett behind the wheel in
1992. But the answer to the question _ What's a football coach
doing in stock-car racing? _ goes all the way back to Gibbs'
childhood.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in moonshine country in Mocksville, N.C., grew up
near Asheville. His dad was a deputy sheriff and later the
alcohol-and-beverage inspector for Buncombe County.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days, the deputy sheriff's department was like five
guys having a ball,'' Gibbs said. ``My dad had two major auto
wrecks, and he had to run the radio for six months. He'd take me
down to the office, and I'd listen to them all night. They'd be
laughing and chasing bootleggers all over town.''
</P>
<P>
   His first ride in a fast car came in the first or second grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``He picked me up one day and got a call over the radio that
there was a bus going out of town with a fugitive on it. He went
through town, up on the side of curbs, and chased this bus down. I
think he totally forgot I was sitting back there. I remember being
scared to death.''
</P>
<P>
   The family moved to California when Gibbs was 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out there, in the '50s, it was like the movie `Grease.'
Everybody had a street rod, and everybody was running around town
at the local hamburger joints and at the local drag strips, drag
racing. I got hooked on cars. I had every kind of street rod: a '49
Mercury, I had a '32 Ford Victoria, I had a '37 Chevy, I had a '27
Model T. Then I got off into drag racing.''
</P>
<P>
   His dates with Pat, who eventually became his wife, were
Saturday nights at the Lions drag strip. ``It was just part of the
culture, and I got sucked up into that and loved it,'' Gibbs said.
</P>
<P>
   His other love was football, but Gibbs thought that when he
finished playing at San Diego State he might become a race-car
driver. The school offered him a coaching job. He took it. When he
left for a job at Florida State a few years later, Gibbs sold all
his cars. ``I said, `Well, I guess I'll just be a big race fan my
whole life,' '' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   It was toward the end of his 12-year career as the Redskins'
coach that Gibbs first considered getting into racing as a team
owner. ``My son, J.D., was just coming out of college and he told
me, 'Dad, I don't want to go into coaching,' '' Gibbs said. ``He
was too smart for that; he saw that life.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a life that had consumed Gibbs to the point of physical
exhaustion. He was away from home so much that Pat would make him
audio tapes announcing the latest adventures of J.D. and his
younger brother, Coy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to J.D., 'What do you think about us trying to start a
race team? Could we talk your mother into that?' '' Gibbs said.
``So we started the process of trying to talk Pat into letting us
start a race team.'' An idea five years in the making was put into
place within eight months.
</P>
<P>
   TWO CARS BETTER THAN ONE
</P>
<P>
   The first season, Gibbs was an absentee owner, still coaching
the Redskins. But the building blocks for his race team were being
assembled. Jarrett brought along his brother-in-law, Jimmy Makar,
as crew chief. They didn't win a race in Chevrolets the first year.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, 1993, Jarrett won the Daytona 500 and finished
fourth in points. But the following season, Jarrett fell back to
16th in points and asked out of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was a key part of the equation,'' Gibbs said,
``because I told Dale, `We've got an existing contract. You can't
leave unless I can get somebody we're really happy with.' We did
research and research and research, and it worked out through a
wild set of circumstances that we were able to get Bobby Labonte.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte was driving for Bill Davis, but his future appeared
shaky because of sponsorship problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby's been a crucial part of everything that's happened from
that point on,'' Gibbs said. ``He had not won a race to that point.
The next year, he won three with us, and it's been kind of steady
progress from that point on.''
</P>
<P>
   The next key part to the equation was Gibbs' decision to switch
from Chevys to Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said we were nuts,'' he said. ``At that point Pontiac,
really, was fairly mediocre. We sat down and talked about going to
Pontiac. Our thought was, if we stay in Chevrolets, obviously,
Hendricks is always going to be in front of us. They've won
championships; they deserve to be in front of us. Childress has won
a bunch of championships. So chances are if we stayed in Chevrolet,
the best we could hope for is third, fourth, when it came to
getting resources or being considered for technical things.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we did make a move to Pontiac, there was a chance to maybe
distinguish ourselves and maybe get more resources and put
ourselves in a better position with GM.''
</P>
<P>
   And then the two genius moves: Adding a second car and picking
Stewart to drive it. Gibbs, his son, J.D., Labonte and Makar were
all in on the decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we determined what the advantages of doing it would be,
we all agreed that money wasn't necessarily the No. 1 reason to do
it,'' Makar said. ``We didn't want to create a second team that
would just be a B-team or a No. 2 team. Bobby and I both said if we
are gonna do this, we wanted a team of equal caliber of what we
have today, to help us grow, not for us to grow them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that's when we decided one thing we're going to have to
have is a great race-car driver,'' Makar said. ``We can't settle
for just anybody to put in the car. We made a short list of names
of five or six guys to give to Joe to go after. Tony was very, very
high on the list. We were real fortunate to get him. He was one of
the guys we went after first.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart made the transition from Indy Racing League open-wheel
cars to stocks look easy, although he didn't win any of the 22
Busch races in which he understudied in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adding the second team was a big deal because Bobby's best
finish, I think, had been sixth before that point,'' Gibbs said.
``With the addition of Tony, the two-team thing has helped both
cars. It's helped Bobby. You've got two drivers; you've got two
crew chiefs; you've got two crews, (and) you've got more resources
to solve problems every week when you go to the race track.
</P>
<P>
   'WHOEVER CAN WIN, WINS'
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs contends that his two-car operation is unlike others; it's
an equal opportunity situation. ``We decided to have both of them
under one roof. Both teams are here, both crew chiefs sit next to
each other down there. Both drivers know they get the same cars
built by the same people. Most of the people in this building work
on both cars. They don't work on one car. It's not separated. Only
the road crews are separate. Bobby and Tony know they get the exact
same motor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there's some differences based on the driver's
capabilities and feelings in the car, but I think what's different
about us is we try to make it really one team. We try to make sure
we don't have the in-fighting. Now, they're both very competitive.
There are no deals; (when) it comes down to the end, whoever can
win, wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs experienced that first-hand last season at Homestead, when
Stewart tapped Labonte's side on his way to the checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were both going for it,'' Gibbs said. ``They'd run one
and two all day, and Bobby at that point happened to be leading,
but Tony had led up until then and had led the most laps. He goes
in first; his pit crew did a great job. When he came out of there,
he didn't see cars, he didn't see nothing, he was just going for
it. Both of them hit out on the race track and scared me to death.
I think it shows the competitive spirit of both these guys. I don't
think either one of them is going to let somebody else win a
race.''
</P>
<P>
   BILLS COME FAST, TOO
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs marvels at how his new life has fallen into place. He got
out of coaching because it was pulling him away from his family.
J.D. is the company president; he and Coy will race some in the
truck and Busch divisions, and Pat gets to a lot of races. ``We've
got two grandbabies just arrived on the scene, a 2-year-old and a
6-week-old,'' Gibbs said. ``All those things for me in this life
are much better than what football could be.''
</P>
<P>
   What's different is the business pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happened in motorsports is the race owner is the
hardest job to try and make a living,'' Gibbs said. ``I think any
race owner will tell you that. People say, 'Well, you've got this
big building.' And I say, 'Yeah, I've got a lot of debt because of
this big building.' The sweat's trying to pay this off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won Atlanta a year ago and won $125,000. The pro golfer
that week won $370,000. I took 14 people to the race track and
probably spent $200,000. That's an example of the inequities. I
knew what it was when I got in it, but I'm saying this is a
scramble.
</P>
<P>
   But Joe isn't complaining. ``I tell everybody, `` Gibbs said,
``if something happens to me tomorrow, just put on the tombstone:
'I had a ball.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
