<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2229 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLYMPICS-PRESIDENT-NY     02-19 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-PRESIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYDNEY IS LAST HURRAH FOR SAMARANCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By JOHN SHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Juan Antonio Samaranch left Sidney on
Friday, apparently convinced that the 2000 Summer Games here would
be ``the greatest Olympics ever'' and thus a monument to his 20
years as president of the International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney program of 28 sports, 292 events, 635 sessions and
10,200 athletes will make it the largest Olympics ever.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch's tenure officially ends in July 2001, but in effect
it ends at Sydney's closing ceremony on Oct. 1. Samaranch, 80, will
have little or nothing to do with the 2002 Winter Olympics in Salt
Lake City or the 2004 summer games in Athens, where preliminary
work is also under way.
</P>
<P>
   This past week as he looked around Sydney's main Olympic site,
the 110,000-seat Stadium Australia, Samaranch had reasons for
confidence some 200 days out from the opening ceremony there on
Sept. 15. The $425 million stadium, the largest in Olympic history,
and a dozen other new facilities nearby, are ready for competition
after months of testing by athletes, spectators and organizers in
pre-games meets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sydney could run the games tomorrow,'' said Dick Pound of
Canada, the Olympic committee's vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Committee officials are projecting a similarly rosy outlook
about the financial future of the Olympic movement and developments
in drug detection tests for competitors in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is in place to have an excellent games,'' said
Jacques Rogge, the IOC's chief coordinator. ``For for the first
time, everything is ready six months in advance. That is a
record.'' Making his sixth visit to Sydney in three years, Rogge
said finishing downtown transportation and recruiting temporary and
volunteer workers are the main tasks left.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there have been some stumbles, including recent problems
with ticketing and the budget. Sydney's minister for the Olympics,
Michael Knight, made a financial point about a possible $20 million
revenue gap by greeting Samaranch at the airport with a minibus,
rather than the usual stretch limousine.
</P>
<P>
   The shortfall, about 1 percent of the overall $2 billion budget,
could shrink or spread, depending on ticket sales, which have been
slowed by computer and management errors.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch, a target for several years of criticism about
financial misconduct within his ``Olympic family,'' urged
journalists here not to exaggerate IOC and Sydney problems. ``Tell
the truth, and the truth here is that the news is good,'' he
declared.
</P>
<P>
   The best news of the week for the committee was the return to
the Olympic financial fold of the John Hancock insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   Its president, David D'Alessandro, has been the most critical
corporate advocate of change in the committee's structure and for a
cleanup of its corruption-prone system of inspecting cities
competing to stage Olympic events.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, D'Alessandro, an Olympic sponsor since 1993,
suspended a $20 million television agreement with NBC, the main
Games broadcaster, saying, ``Corporations should keep the IOC's
feet to the fire on reform and withhold new sponsorships until we
see what the reforms are.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, D'Alessandro turned down the heat.
</P>
<P>
   He renewed a $50 million agreement with the IOC as a global
sponsor through the 2004 Games. He also resumed negotiations with
NBC for spots on its Sydney coverage, which the network says has
already attracted $750 million in advertising, about $80 million
more than for the Games in Atlanta four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro thinks the committee, which forced out 10 members
and censured others for accepting gifts from aggressive promoters
of Salt Lake City's bid, has changed.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement the committee released here, D'Alessandro said:
``For the IOC to regain confidence it had to become more democratic
and accountable. The IOC has listened to voices for change and
addressed the issues. It deserves credit for this progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch said the Hancock renewal was a ``testament to the
reforms we made last year.'' These include new procedures for
choosing IOC members, eight-year terms for members and elimination
of member visits to bidding cities.
</P>
<P>
   John Hancock is the fifth sponsor to sign up for the 2002-4
program. The others are Coca-Cola, Visa, Time Warner and Sema
Computers.
</P>
</TEXT>
