<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 02/19/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) GREENVILLE, S.C. -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- SC-REPUBS-6 -- Sen.
John McCain and his wife, Cindy, being greeted by his supporters as
he arrives to speak at the Veterans of Foreign Wars Leadership
Conference in Greenville on Saturday. McCain and George W. Bush
battled in the pivotal South Carolina primary Saturday, each
seeking an edge in a tight Republican presidential race. (Chang W.
Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- CAR-DAYTONA-2 --
Dale Jarrett has qualified for the pole position in Sunday's
Daytona 500, the initial Winston Cup race of the season. Jarrett,
at 43, embraces what a superior support system can do for a driver.
He won his Winston Cup title at 42, after 16 years of trying. ``If
you don't have that team around you, it doesn't matter how good you
are,'' he says. (Rick Runion/The Lakeland Ledger)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- CAR-DAYTONA-1 --
Dale Jarrett says he is eager to begin defense of his NASCAR
Winston Cup Series championship. And why not? Jarrett qualified for
the pole position in Sunday's Daytona 500, the initial Winston Cup
race of the season. (Rick Runion/The Lakeland Ledger)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- BBN-METS-MORA -- Melvin
Mora, who had 31 regular-season at-bats last year, made a splash
with the Mets in the playoffs. He was hailed as a hero upon his
return to his native Venezuela, where he played ball in the
off-season. (G Paul Burnett/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- BKN-NOTEBOOK -- John
Starks, now a Chicago Bull, has gone from one sagging team to
another. Just like last year, when the Knicks shipped him to the
woeful Warriors for Latrell Sprewell, Starks pulled the shortest
straw of a three-way trade last Wednesday that sent Toni Kukoc to
Philadelphia and Larry Hughes to Golden State. ```No question, it's
strange,'' says Starks, 34, of his playing for a team against which
he had battled so hard for years as a member of the New York
Knicks. (Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- NY-APOLLO-STRIKE --
Stagehands at the Apollo Theater in Harlem are threatening to
strike on the eve of a Democratic presidential debate. Charles
Richardson, right foreground, a shop steward, says he was fired
because of his union activities. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- BANK-LOST-BOX -- Alla
Kozirovskaya holds a photograph of her mother, Yelizaveta Krush,
and a rent receipt for a safety deposit box holding heirlooms from
her. The bank, Dime, says it has no record of her having a box.
(Philip Greenberg/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) TAMPA, Fla. -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- BBA-YANKS-RIVERA -- New
York Yankees pitcher Mariano Rivera after being told that he lost
his arbitration case. ``It's good for me either way,'' he says.
``I'm happy with the Yankees.'' Rivera, who saved 45 games in 49
chances last year, is arguably the best closer in baseball today.
(Gary I. Rothstein/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) TAMPA, Fla. -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- BBA-YANKS-JETER-2 -- New
York Yankees infielder Derek Jeter takes batting practice during a
light workout in Tampa on Friday. Jeter has gained 18 pounds since
the end of last season, pushing his weight to 203 pounds. ``I'm
trying to get stronger,'' Jeter says. ``I'm not trying to win any
body-building contests.'' (Gary I. Rothstein/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) TAMPA, Fla. -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- BBA-YANKS-JETER-1 -- New
York Yankees infielder Derek Jeter takes batting practice during a
light workout in Tampa on Friday. Jeter has gained 18 pounds since
the end of last season, pushing his weight to 203 pounds. The
additional strength should translate into more bat speed. (Gary I.
Rothstein/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- COLISEUM-DEMOLISH-2 -- The
New York Coliseum is about to be torn down. But more than a
structure will disappear in the next six months. Demolition workers
are taking the first big chunk out of the physical legacy of Robert
Moses, the sovereign master builder who transformed New York, for
better and worse, in midcentury. (Angel Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- COLISEUM-DEMOLISH-1-B&AMP;W --
The Coliseum is a relic of the reign of Robert Moses, the master
builder who transformed New York in midcentury. Its opening in 1956
warranted a stamp. Ten years later, a cake. Today, it is about to
be torn down. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- BIRD-COUNT -- Aline Euler
of Bayside, Queens, is one of thousands of bird-watchers
participating in the Great Backyard Bird Count this weekend,
collecting statistics about which species are showing up at
feeders, lawns and bushes around the United States and Canada.
Observers count the number of birds they observe and submit their
numbers to a Web site, www.birdsource.org, which shows a running
tally, with breakdowns by state and province. (James Estrin/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- OLD-MURDER -- Robert
Bierenbaum and Gail Katz in a 1982 photo, before their marriage
that year. Dr. Bierenbaum reported her missing in 1985; he is now
accused of killing her. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) SAN JOSE, Calif. -- Feb. 19, 2000 --
SILICON-VALLEY-POOR-2 -- Homeless passengers - many of whom have
full-time jobs - who need to catch a bumpy night of sleep can use
$3 all-day passes for repeat runs on the No. 22 bus on its 26-mile
circuit, but they must wait 10 or 15 minutes between trips. In
Silicon Valley, stock option millionares bid on houses as though
they were buying Van Goghs but, at the same time, more and more
working people are becoming homeless. (Thor Swift/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) SAN JOSE, Calif. -- Feb. 19, 2000 --
SILICON-VALLEY-POOR-1 -- The No.22 bus in California's Silicon
Valley provides a bumpy night of sleep for some of the area's
homeless, many of whom have full-time jobs. With all the new money
floating around, the most expensive housing market in the country
and the densest concentration of investment capital in the world,
there is no other place in the country that offers a starker
example of the growing gap between the rich and poor. (Thor
Swift/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. -- Feb. 19, 2000 --
ENVIRONMENT-LAWSUIT -- Rae H. Ely of the Green Springs land trust,
a nonprofit group of preservationists that is being sued after
decades of aggressively using the courts to help create a
11,000-acre land trust of 18th century working farms and Civil War
plantation houses. The trust was set up 30 years ago as a federal
National Historic Landmark. ``We're fighting for our survival,''
says Ely, a founder of the trust. (Shana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BET SHEMESH, West Bank -- Feb. 19, 2000 --
WESTBANK-BEES-2 -- Israeli beekeepers Roni Feldman, left, Zeev
Varner and Ziv Feldman prepare to inspect a hive near Bet Shemesh.
Theft of cars and of agricultural products, from tractors to bees,
increased sharply after the Palestinians started taking control of
territory in the West Bank and Palestinian thieves became able to
disappear into Palestinian-ruled land without fear of apprehension.
(Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BET SHEMESH, West Bank -- Feb. 19, 2000 --
WESTBANK-BEES-1 -- Israeli beekeepers say the theft of hives, which
the government has largely ignored, threatens their work and
Israel's future. Roni Feldman, left, Zeev Varner and Ziv Feldman
inspect a hive near Bet Shemesh. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- CATS-CLOSING -- After almost
18 years, $380 million in sales and untold gallons of makeup,
``Cats,'' the longest-running production in Broadway history, will
close June 25. The move will make the Andrew Lloyd Webber musical,
which has played at the Winter Garden since Oct. 7, 1982, just a
memory. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- OBIT-WATERMAN -- Guy Waterman
and his wife, Laura, avid mountain climbers, wrote four books that
seek to encourage wilderness ethics and conservation. Waterman died
on Feb. 6, when he climbed to the top of Mount Lafayette, a
5,249-foot peak in the White Mountains in northern New Hampshire,
and sat down to die in below-zero temperatures. He was 67 and lived
in East Corinth, Vt. (Ned Therrien/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) GREENVILLE, S.C. -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- SC-REPUBS-5 -- Gov.
George W. Bush and his wife, Laura, right, in Greenville on
Saturday. Bush and Sen. John McCain battled in the pivotal South
Carolina primary Saturday, each seeking an edge in a tight
Republican presidential race. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) GREENVILLE, S.C. -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- SC-REPUBS-4 -- Sen.
John McCain and his wife, Cindy, began Friday in Greenville. McCain
and George W. Bush battled in the pivotal South Carolina primary
Saturday, each seeking an edge in a tight Republican presidential
race. (Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MOUNT PLEASANT, S.C. -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- SC-REPUBS-3 --
John McCain and George W. Bush battled in the pivotal South
Carolina primary Saturday, each seeking an edge in a tight
Republican presidential race. Voters cast their ballots early, like
Diane Bowers at Mount Pleasant, with her son, Matthew. (Wade
Spees/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CHARLESTON, S.C. -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- SUB-SC-REPUBS-2 --
Amid a heavy turnout, voters found some polling places closed
Saturday in South Carolina's primary, with signs giving directions
to other stations. Many precincts were combined for voting, like
this one at a home for the aging in Charleston. (Wade Spees/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) MOUNT PLEASANT, S.C. -- Feb. 19, 2000 -- SC-REPUBS-1 --
Charles and Nina Mariani fill out a poll as voters line up Saturday
at a presidential primary polling place in Mount Pleasant. Amid a
heavy turnout, voters found some polling places closed, with signs
giving directions to other stations. (Wade Spees/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
