<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2271 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-SC-TALES0220-COX     02-19 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-TALES0220-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A bumpy ride for journalists
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John McCain was feeling two things when he got back
aboard his campaign bus last week for a ride into Atlanta. He was
feeling good after a well-attended event at a park on the shores of
Lake Keowee near Seneca, S.C. And he was feeling hungry.
</P>
<P>
   And, soon, both those feelings had gone. A pork barbecue
sandwich took care of the hunger. Questions from two experienced
Atlanta journalists, WSB's Bill Nigut and The Atlanta
Constitution's Cynthia Tucker, sparked the mood change.
</P>
<P>
   Nigut and Tucker, not regular riders on the Straight Talk
Express, got what has become a rare glimpse of the candidate's
famous temper.
</P>
<P>
   With the whine of the bus motor as background noise, Tucker
prefaced a question by saying the Arizona senator was an
``ultra-conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Good move journalistically. Bad way to break the ice with a
candidate seeking the votes of political moderates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's insulting to the people of Arizona to say I'm
ultra-anything,'' McCain replied.
</P>
<P>
   In short order, Nigut attempted to draw McCain into a discussion
about school vouchers, which McCain supports.
</P>
<P>
   Nigut, Atlanta television's pre-eminent political voice, is
nothing if not insistent. So he presented one counterargument, then
another and another.
</P>
<P>
   It did not take McCain long to accuse Nigut of being on the side
of teachers unions, which oppose voucher programs.
</P>
<P>
   He began one comment with a sarcastic ``My dear friend.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Nigut said, ``I'm trying to clarify ...''
</P>
<P>
   McCain broke in, ``You're not doing very well at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it was Nigut's turn to get steamed, and it showed in his
face. Brighter shades of red may not occur in nature, but Nigut's
voice at least did not betray any irritation.
</P>
<P>
   By this point, McCain's staff had taken note of the increasingly
unpleasant atmosphere in the back of the bus. They soon summoned
the candidate to the front of the bus, away from the reporters.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned after several minutes, McCain's mood was much,
much better. And, an hour after that, when the ride ended in
Atlanta, he apologized for being rude.
</P>
<P>
   `GEORGE E.' TAKES REVENGE ON NIT-PICKERS
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign has acknowledged that their candidate has been
retooled and repackaged for the crucial South Carolina primary. Now
it looks like he has been renamed.
</P>
<P>
   The daily schedule passed out on the press bus every evening
looked a bit different Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trip of Governor George E. Bush to Charleston, South
Carolina,'' said the headline.
</P>
<P>
   And the attached schedule was for the coming to an end rather
than for the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The press corps, which never makes a mistake, was ruthless in
holding the errors up for on-bus
</P>
<P>
   ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   Last laugh, of course, went to the campaign staff. The 6 a.m.
baggage call for the next morning was not a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   CLEMSON RALLY HAS LANGUAGE ALL ITS OWN
</P>
<P>
   For Clemson football fans, it would have been a familiar sight.
Loudspeakers thumped out ``Tiger Rag'' as cheering fans spelled out
the school's name. A supportive gantlet of students formed a
welcoming line for the arriving stars, who made their way through a
thick haze generated by a smoke machine.
</P>
<P>
   Those weren't linebackers and running backs who got this
treatment Wednesday night, but Rep. Lindsey Graham, Gary Bauer and
the big star of the evening, Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign hoped to attract younger voters to the
primary, and this rally at Clemson's amphi- theater was aimed
squarely at the young.
</P>
<P>
   ``In two more days, guys, we're going to rock their world,''
Graham told the mostly student audience.
</P>
<P>
   McCain slyly thanked the students for taking time from ``your
heavy academic duties'' and promised the ``patriotic young South
Carolinians'' they would be the ``foot soldiers'' of a movement to
clean up Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Join us. It's great fun,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Some students already on board wore a T-shirt that might have
puzzled outsiders, but would also be familiar to Tiger fans.
</P>
<P>
   With a pawprint outlined in red, white and blue, it said,
``Pawsitively McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   FREEDOM OF SPEECH _ FOR SOME, AT LEAST
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you in the news media?'' Gov. George W. Bush asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not,'' Samuel T. Ross-Lee said. ``I am a Christian
minister.''
</P>
<P>
   So unwound a testy exchange between Bush and Ross-Lee at a
campaign event Tuesday in Irmo. The exchange highlighted Bush's
ongoing discomfort with some of the thornier questions he gets from
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Ross-Lee wanted to discuss Bush's stance on the Confederate
flag. Bush repeated his position that the people of South Carolina
should decide whether to stop flying the flag from the Capitol.
When Ross-Lee pressed Bush, the
</P>
<P>
   overwhelmingly white audience shouted him down and Bush told him
to sit down.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, in answer to another question, Bush
applauded the First Amendment. ``Freedom of speech ... gives a
chance for everybody to stand up and state their opinion,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Melanie Reel, 37, said she was on the fence before the exchange,
but is now thinking of voting for John McCain. ``For Bush to tell
him to sit down really bothered me,'' Reel said. ``The way he asked
the question was very clear and I don't think Bush was being very
clear in his answer.''
</P>
<P>
   UNACCUSTOMED MOOD IS SIGN OF THE TIMES
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina Election Commissioner Jim Hendrix braked Friday
driving past the Statehouse, a usually placid site transformed by
Bush and McCain supporters shouting and waving campaign signs.
</P>
<P>
   Motorists honked horns in a blast of anxious excitement in the
showdown for South Carolina's Republican presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is the most amazing thing I've ever seen,'' Hendrix said.
''Usually we don't see that much enthusiasm. It has been amplified
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Stacked one upon another, as high as campaign workers could
reach, placards transformed utility poles around Columbia into
totem poles of red, white and blue. Street corners were planted in
signs.
</P>
<P>
   People plastered cars and vans in signs. Bush placards decorated
a Buick Roadmaster at the polling place at Irmo Middle School,
where voters began arriving as early as 6:30 a.m. to stand in line.
</P>
<P>
   First in line was C.W. Bowman, 53, who had arrived an hour
before the polls opened and waited in his pickup truck drinking
coffee until poll workers arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writers, Mark Sherman, Jena
Heath, Tom Baxter and Chris Burritt contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
