<SLUG> BC-RAC-FOUNTAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH YIELD STARTS FAST ON ROAD TO DERBY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ High Yield, a well-traveled son of Storm Cat
who traveled from California to Florida this week, won the Fountain
of Youth Stakes Saturday and took the lead among this season's
3-year-old horses traveling the tortuous road to the Kentucky
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   The colt, trained by D. Wayne Lukas, withstood pressure from
Hal's Hope, the surprise winner of the Holy Bull Stakes last month,
and drew clear by 3 1/4 lengths, winning for the third time in 10
career starts. Hal's Hope finished behind him, three lengths in
front of Elite Mercedes, third by the length of his neck over
Greenwood Lake, who made up 20 lengths to finish fourth.
</P>
<P>
   They still have a long way to go before the Derby at Churchill
Downs on May 6, and no dominant horse has emerged. But High Yield,
with Pat Day riding him for the first time because Jerry Bailey and
Corey Nakatani were committed elsewhere, heads for Louisville with
the proper seasoning and pedigree. He seems a little like Cat
Thief, last year's star of the Lukas barn, who ran frequently, lost
frequently but won some big ones. High Yield ran second in his last
two starts and third in the Breeders' Cup Juvenile and the
Champagne, and had not won since the Hopeful at Saratoga last
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only beat the horses that show up, and a lot of them
didn't show up,'' Lukas said. ``But we represented the West Coast
horses very well. We'll keep him in the East now. He'll be an East
Coast horse. He'll go to the Florida Derby. We know where we want
to go. We just have to pull it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas has won the Kentucky Derby four times, and three times in
the last five years. Now he is back with a star colt, High Yield,
and a star filly, Surfside. And he said, ``We know our way around
Churchill Downs.''
</P>
<P>
   High Yield led most of the way after breaking from the fourth
slot in the gate, with Hal's Hope right on his heels, a length and
a half back after half a mile and three lengths back after
three-quarters of a mile. Then he challenged High Yield as they
turned for home, but High Yield, clinging to the fast lane along
the rail, shook him off and won in a driving finish.
</P>
<P>
   He covered the mile and one-sixteenth in 1:42 2/5, paid $6.80
for a $2 bet as the favorite and earned $120,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been on him before,'' Day said later. ``But Wayne
said he was sharp. There was some other speed in there but Wayne
said if we broke well, to go on with it; don't give up what comes
easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The day was generally a coming-of-age tailored for 3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   In an allowance race called the Unbridled, with the purse raised
to $75,000 to attract horses who might not be ready for the
Fountain of Youth, Nick Zito scored with his 8-1 shot, Bare
Outline, a colt owned by William Condren and ridden by Corey
Nakatani.
</P>
<P>
   He outran the favorite, Tahkodha Hills, by a length and a
quarter, while Grundlefoot, aiming for the Kentucky Derby, finished
fourth and Wayward Ways pulled up lame leaving the far turn.
</P>
<P>
   In a later allowance, Cot Campbell's Dogwood Stable unleashed
its prodigy, Trippi, who won his second straight with exceptional
speed. The colt, a son of End Sweep and grandson of Forty Niner,
won his debut last month by nearly five lengths. And he won his
second start by more than nine lengths, displaying the breakaway
power of his namesake, the onetime running star of Georgia
football, Charley Trippi. He is trained by Todd Pletcher, and Jerry
Bailey has been his jockey in both winning starts.
</P>
</TEXT>
