<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2273 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-NHLEAST0220-COX     02-19 1381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLEAST0220-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inside NHL: A quick look at last week's big stories in the NHL
and what to watch for during this week.
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Top teams in the Eastern and Western conferences
</P>
<P>
   EASTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   1. New Jersey: The Devils lost only twice in a span of 14 games
amid stories of the team being sold and possibly moved. We assume
this means coach Robbie Ftorek will not be fired after all.
</P>
<P>
   2. Toronto: Finally hit a slump (four-game losing streak). But
better that the young Leafs go through this now than when the
playoffs start.
</P>
<P>
   3. Philadelphia: General manager Bobby Clarke has added Keith
Primeau and Gino Odjick. But one player keeps this team from being
a powerhouse: goalie John Vanbiesbrouck.
</P>
<P>
   4. Florida: Goalie Trevor Kidd is on the verge of returning to a
team few have been able to slow down. If Kidd regains form,
Panthers will challenge for the conference lead.
</P>
<P>
   5. Ottawa: The Senators jumped to an 11-4-1 start and have been
a .500 team since. There is no indication they will try to move
holdout Alexei Yashin before the trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   6. Washington: The Capitals may have been on the verge of being
dismantled until their recent run. After a 3-1 loss to the
Thrashers on Jan. 6, the Caps went 14-2-2.
</P>
<P>
   7. Pittsburgh: Ivan Hlinka will replace Herb Brooks, who
replaced Kevin Constantine, who may resurface in Minnesota. Jaromir
Jagr may be great but Penguins aren't going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   8. N.Y. Rangers: They began playing up to their talent level
(nine wins in 10 games) about the time coach John Muckler was
supposed to get fired, but they've had two bad games since the
break.
</P>
<P>
   WESTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   1. St. Louis: Continuing to win despite the absences of injured
stars Pierre Turgeon and Al MacInnis. The Blues have a league-best
19-8-2 road record after winning Friday.
</P>
<P>
   2. Detroit: Reason to be nervous: Goalie Chris Osgood is only
8-8-2 since returning from a broken hand. But general manager Ken
Holland said to forget about the trade rumors.
</P>
<P>
   3. Dallas: Considering this team's injury problems, it's amazing
the Stars have one of the league's five best records. Dallas is 9-2
since a 3-1 loss at Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   4: Colorado: Injuries to Peter Forsberg, Joe Sakic and Co. have
resulted in only 25 goals in a 12-game span (3-6-3) before a 5-5
tie with New Jersey on Thursday. But Forsberg is back.
</P>
<P>
   5. Phoenix: A familiar problem has returned to the Coyotes:
goal-scoring. But that's what happens when Keith Tkachuk sprains an
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   6: Los Angeles: After fast start, the Kings dropped to .500 last
month and looked like they were destined for also-ran status. But
they've won six out of seven.
</P>
<P>
   7. Edmonton: How does Glen Sather keep doing it with a
shoestring budget? The Oilers went 3-0-2 on a recent trip,
including a win vs. the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   8. San Jose: Sharks are sinking fast. They've won only four of
14 _ those against the Mighty Ducks, Lightning, Thrashers and
Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE RISE
</P>
<P>
   _ Mighty Ducks winger Teemu Selanne: He had a 12-game
point-scoring streak (seven goals, 14 assists) entering the weekend
for Anaheim and passed the 700-point plateau last week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Islanders forward Mariusz Czerkawski: Something positive on
Long Island. He has seven goals, 12 assists and 41 shots on goal
during a 12-game point streak.
</P>
<P>
   _ Edmonton goalie Tommy Salo: Unbeaten in his past six starts
and has allowed two or less goals in eight of his past nine.
</P>
<P>
   FREE-FALLIN'
</P>
<P>
   _ Edmonton's Alex Selivanov: He has two goals in his past 54
games and was lectured by coach Kevin Lowe last week for lackluster
play.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kings defenseman Aki Berg: Los Angeles general manager Dave
Taylor went to great lengths to sign the free agent from Finland in
the offseason. But Berg's play has been erratic and coach Andy
Murray even has made him a healthy scratch of late.
</P>
<P>
   BEST GAME
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the kind of game typical of a New Jersey-Colorado
meeting. But the teams played to a 5-5 tie Thursday night in New
Jersey in the game of the week _ something for tie-knockers in the
league office to take note of. ``It was the kind of game you don't
see too often in the league any more,'' Peter Forsberg said. ``It
was a great game to be watching.''
</P>
<P>
   WORTH NOTING
</P>
<P>
   Dallas' Jere Lehtinen's most recent surgery on his ankle means
he won't return until April 2 at the earliest. But Stars general
manager Bob Gainey denies he is pursuing either Mark Messier or
Doug Gilmour to fill a hole up front.
</P>
<P>
   This is what you call playing for a contract: Kirk Mueller was
signed by Dallas for a base salary of only $190,000 _ exactly 10
percent of what he earned last season ($1.9 million). But he will
earn more than $200,000 in playing time incentives and has been
signed to a $750,000 extension. ``We brought him in on kind of a
let's-see-what-you've-got left-in-the-tank tryout,'' assistant GM
Doug Armstrong said. ``Obviously, there's quite a bit left.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey goalie Martin Brodeur, on trade rumors that have the
Devils moving Brendan Morrison, Lyle Odelein or others and
importing Teemu Selanne: ``(GM) Lou (Lamoriello) has built an
empire here. If it's not going to make us better, he's not going to
move guys just to move them or get a big-name player. When you're
going good the way we are, it's hard to judge and say you have a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Darcy Tucker, traded from Tampa Bay to Toronto, should cash in
several incentive bonuses he never would have reached with the
Lightning. They include: $40,000 for finishing third in the
conference up to $90,000 for first; $15,000 to $100,000 for each
playoff round won, leading up to the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Stars goalie Ed Belfour on the Stanley Cup hangover: ``Everyone
knows how short the summers are for a Stanley Cup champion team and
guys don't train too much in the summer. There's a lot of
celebrating. So I think when we come to training camp, most of us
aren't too motivated. Sometimes it can lead to a slow start. We got
off to a slow start and, adding to that, we had all of the
injuries. It took us a while to get back in the groove.''
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING BACK
</P>
<P>
   _ The Flames, who built an improbable winning record because of
their overtime success (10-0-1), have lost four in a row in
overtime and were winless in 10 consecutively overall (0-9-1)
</P>
<P>
   _ Rangers coach John Muckler tried to play three defensemen
every time Florida's Pavel Bure was on the ice, with Brian Leetch
shadowing the Russian star. But Bure scored anyway and the Panthers
won easily 3-0. Bure said: ``I was just trying to pull Leetch out
of the zone to create more room for my teammates. Calgary played
against me the same way in the 1994 playoffs. It basically became a
four-on-four game.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Kings' Luc Robitaille scored his 545th goal moved him past
his boyhood idol, Maurice ``Rocket'' Richard into 18th on the NHL's
career list. Robitaille's immediate reaction: ``This will never
sink in.''
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   _ Nashville defenseman Jan Vopat might be forced to retire
because of a rash that players have nicknamed ``The Gonk.'' The red
blotches on Vopat's skin, which have baffled doctors, bring
swelling, itching and bleeding. ``It's very frustrating,'' Vopat
said. ``It's one thing if you break your leg because you say, `OK,
I'll be back in a couple of months.' But with this, I can just hope
that it changes.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida, which talked to the Thrashers about defenseman Darryl
Shannon before passing on him, is now focusing on Vladimir
Malakhov, who is out of favor in Montreal. Malakhov was suspended
briefly by the Canadiens after skiing when he was supposed to be
rehabbing from a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   _ Panthers goalie Trevor Kidd, coming back from a dislocated
shoulder, will start his minor-league conditioning assignment today
with a start for Louisville (AHL) in Hershey, Pa. It will be his
first start since Dec. 11, before he was injured in a skills
competition. His first start likely will be at Carolina on
Thursday. ``I told him going down is for the peace of mind for
himself and for me,'' GM Brian Murray said. ``It's just different
than practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
