<SLUG> BC-SC-BUSH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORM MESSAGE SAID KEY TO TEXAN'S SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ The news was good Saturday, but there were no
early celebrations in the George W. Bush camp. Even Bush, learning
of his substantial lead after the first wave of exit poll results,
gave the mildest possible reaction: He settled down for an
afternoon nap.
</P>
<P>
   But as the votes were being counted it was clear Bush and his
aides felt buoyed by the preliminary South Carolina primary
results, which showed Bush ahead among registered Republicans and,
perhaps just as important, indicated he had somewhat neutralized
support among Independents and Democrats for his chief opponent,
Senator John S. McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Six days after his surprisingly large loss in the New Hampshire
primary, Bush burst back onto the campaign trail with a slew of new
campaign posters and the retooled message of ``reformer with
results,'' which he delivered tirelessly straight through Saturday
afternoon. The problem in New Hampshire, Bush said, was that he
allowed McCain to claim the ``reform'' title. He also vowed not to
``be defined'' by his opponent, as he felt he had been.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, aides said Bush had clearly reclaimed the mantra of
reform for himself, and had succeeded in conveying his track record
of change in Texas. Aides even began to recast the New Hampshire
loss as a blessing in disguise, having forced Bush to hone his
ideas into a campaign platform with which people could identify.
</P>
<P>
   ``People looked at him and saw how he handled adversity, and saw
how he passed through this test, and liked it,'' senior adviser
Karl Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   Rove said McCain had not helped himself any with a negative
campaign ad comparing Bush to President Clinton. That ad, he said,
was a ``substantial'' mistake. ``And it's a stain that can't be
easily washed away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rove and other Bush aides refused to concede that their own ads
about McCain may have affected the outcome. Since last week, only
Bush was running ads about his opponent. McCain had pulled his
negative ads, saying he thought the tenor of the race had gone too
far. Bush, along with several outside groups such as the National
Right to Life Committee, had been running ads that mentioned McCain
by name, and in several cases, cast him as an outright hypocrite.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rove insisted, Bush's success was attributable to the
candidate himself.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what made the difference between New Hampshire and South
Carolina, Rove said: ``Bush returning to his roots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran in 1994 as a candidate who desired to make four big
changes, four big reforms, he talked about it endlessly, used the
word `reform' endlessly,'' Rove said. ``I think that was a big part
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove delivered news of the early exit poll results to Bush at
1:40 p.m. Saturday, as the Texas governor was resting in his room
at the Columbia Sheraton. Bush asked whether Rove thought the
numbers would hold up. Then, Rove said, Bush ``settled down for a
power nap.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the afternoon, Bush went for a 5-mile run with two of
his media advisers, Mark McKinnon and Matthew Dowd. When Bush
returned to the hotel, he sat down for a speechwriting session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 1915EST &QL; 
