<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-REPUBS-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ANALYSIS: BUSH WON BY STEALING McCAIN'S MESSAGE  
(rk) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Shortly after President George Bush lost his
re-election bid in 1992, George W. Bush told a friend that his
father ``should never have let Bill Clinton dictate the terms of
debate.''
</P>
<P>
   When his turn came, the younger Bush did not make the same
error. Having been trounced by Sen. John McCain of Arizona in the
New Hampshire primary, having been branded as the stick-in-the-mud
candidate, Bush came to South Carolina, recast himself as a
hard-nosed conservative, as an outsider and as a reformer who gets
results. McCain, the Texan and his surrogates suggested, was a bit
too liberal, too Beltway-bound and too flaky.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, in other words, stole McCain's clothes.
</P>
<P>
   He righted his campaign, regained the momentum he enjoyed before
New Hampshire and re-emerged as a strong favorite to win the
Republican presidential nomination. Severely wounded here, McCain
will have a chance to rebound in the voting on Tuesday in Michigan,
where the ideological coloration of the electorate may be more
favorable to him, and he has vowed to fight on in what could
develop into a drawn-out struggle, not unlike the one between
Ronald Reagan and Gerald Ford in 1976. But the electoral calendar
grows more favorable to Bush as it moves through March.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates, a survey of voters in Saturday's Republican
primary suggested, were seen as reformers, but when they were
pitted against one another, Bush was seen as the more effective one
_ precisely as he had portrayed himself in a late blitz of
television commercials here.
</P>
<P>
   Other commercials flailed away at McCain's advocacy of campaign
finance reform. Nearly half the voters said that the senator says
one thing and does another when it comes to campaign finance, and
they were mostly Bush backers. That was a second building block of
the governor's victory.
</P>
<P>
   A third was his apparent success in capitalizing on a major
error by McCain, an intemperate commercial in which he compared
Bush to President Clinton. By election day, voters were more likely
to see McCain than Bush as an unfair aggressor, even though McCain
had come into the state with a reputation as a proponent of cleaner
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's television blitz, which dangerously depleted his
treasury, appeared to have paid off among those who made their
voting decisions in the frantic final hours of the campaign here.
About a third of the voters told interviewers as they left the
polls that they made up their minds in the last week or so, and
most went to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   For McCain, the critical failure was an inability to broaden the
electorate sufficiently. Knowing that he was trailing Bush among
the state's unusually conservative Republican voters, he made an
unabashed appeal to Democratic and independent voters to cast
ballots in the Republican primary, hoping that the absence of a
Democratic primary would make it easier to attract those groups.
</P>
<P>
   He vowed last week to create ``a new Republican party'' in South
Carolina by bringing thousands of new voters into the primary.
</P>
<P>
   But relatively few Democrats crossed over. McCain got eight out
of ten of their votes, but they constituted less than a tenth of
the electorate, not enough to have a major impact. Likewise among
independents, who constituted about a third of those who cast
ballots Saturday. McCain took about twice as many of their votes as
his principal rival.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Republicans accounted for only a slightly smaller
percentage of the electorate than they did four years ago, marking
a signal lack of success for McCain's efforts. The electorate was
nearly all white, more than half male and older than most, with
four voters in ten over 60.
</P>
<P>
   One important element in the relatively modest crossover vote
was the decision by black voters, who form the backbone of the
modern Democratic Party in this state, to resist any suggestion
that they vote in the Republican primary. Only 1 percent of the
voters were black, in a state where blacks make up a quarter of the
electorate in general elections. They told interviewers earlier
this week that the two candidates' had forfeited any claim on their
support by refusing to condemn the flying of the Confederate flag
over the state capitol building in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after his loss in New Hampshire, Bush boldly
announced that South Carolina was ``Bush country.'' His aides
calculated that the same party organization that carried his father
to victory in 1986, originally assembled by former Gov. Carroll
Campbell, would do the same for him. They proved prescient. Voters
told interviewers that they prefer a candidate who is loyal to the
Republican Party and has ties to its local leaders, and they
overwhelmingly saw Bush as embodying that.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also succeeded in portraying himself as the more reliable
foe of abortion in a state where opposition to abortion is strong.
Nearly two-thirds of the most vehement anti-abortion voters went to
Bush; in New Hampshire, competing in a more crowded field, he got
one-third.
</P>
<P>
   Although he did not gain the upset he had hoped for here, McCain
rode his New Hampshire victory to something approaching parity with
Bush in financial terms. Now, with only two days to campaign, he
will go after the conservative white voters known as Reagan
Democrats in the counties clustered to the north of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan has a long history of backing protest candidates and
insurgents, like the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who won the 1988
Democratic caucuses here. Its Republicans are less conservative
than South Carolina's. And Gov. John Engler, who used to talk about
providing an asbestos wall there to protect Bush, has been sounding
a much different note lately.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody in Michigan, the governor said the other day, likes to be
taken for granted and to be told that one candidate is a certain
victor.
</P>
<P>
   But Michigan is followed by a big group of primaries on March 7,
the most important of which, New York's and California's, are
effectively closed to all but Republican voters. Among the big
states voting on that day, only Ohio's is open _ a considerable
advantage for Bush. Then on March 14, Texas, his home base, and
Florida, where his brother Jeb is governor, will cast their votes.
As the nation's second and fourth largest states, they will wield
considerable influence at the Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   Had McCain won here, none of those details would have mattered
nearly as much. As he himself exulted this week, ``If we win here,
I don't see how we really can be stopped.'' But he could not bring
it off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 1947EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
