<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2283 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-JARRETT0220-COX     02-19 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-JARRETT0220-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Champion begins quest for repeat with respect, confidence and a
revamped crew.
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The post-race victory lap around Atlanta
Motor Speedway was pleasurable. So was the special red-carpet tour
of New York City. He appeared on the David Letterman show and was
the keynote speaker at the NASCAR banquet in front of a national TV
audience.
</P>
<P>
   But winning the 1999 Winston Cup championship didn't really sink
in with Dale Jarrett until he was lying on his couch on a lazy
Sunday afternoon in January. Jarrett, a self-proclaimed golf
fanatic, was in awe watching Tiger Woods in the middle of his
remarkable winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gosh, Tiger is great'' Jarrett said to his wife during a
commercial break. ``Wouldn't it be an incredible feeling to be on
top of your game and on top of your sport like that?''
</P>
<P>
   Several seconds of silence followed at the Hickory, N.C.,
residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Dale . . . ,'' Kelley Jarrett said slowly, ``You are in
your sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it took Jarrett nearly two months to comprehend his
celebrated accomplishments of last year. The Ford No. 88 driver had
such a dominating run that by mid-August most Winston Cup drivers
had given up on trying to catch him.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the trophy as champion of stock-car-racing's top circuit
was long overdue. Jarrett was the second-oldest NASCAR driver to
capture the title at age 42. He and his father, Ned Jarrett, a
two-time champion himself, joined Lee and Richard Petty as the only
father-son pairs to win Winston Cup titles.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett finally was able to revel in the achievement during the
last month, but everything changes today when the engines are
cranked at the Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's kind of a strange feeling,'' Jarrett said. ``Everything
we accomplished and as good as we were last year, none of that
makes a difference anymore on Feb. 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the only difference now is that other people look at
us differently. Heck, we look at ourselves a little differently. We
walk with a little higher kick in our step and a little bit more
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Jarrett has bagged the elusive title, the big question
is: Can he repeat as Winston Cup champion?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to win a championship every year, and it's really
hard to do it two years in a row,'' said Terry Labonte, who won
titles in 1984 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you've seen a few guys who were able to do it two and
three years in a row, like Dale (Earnhardt) and Jeff (Gordon).
There is no reason Dale (Jarrett) can't do it, because they have
got a great team.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Jarrett's championship run last year ended Gordon's
two-year streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've won a championship, you have to deal with a lot
more responsibility,'' Gordon said. ``You have got a lot of eyes on
you and your team. But at the same time, you've got a championship
team that knows how to win a championship, because they have done
it before.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Yates Racing, owner of the No. 88 team, has refused to
rest on last year's success and made a couple of bold moves to keep
the operation moving forward at full speed. Yates hired veteran
Ricky Rudd to drive the No. 28 Ford, with Rudd expected to be an
ideal teammate for Jarrett in knowledge and experience. Rudd is a
proven winner, even though his streak of at least one victory per
season for the past 16 years ended last season.
</P>
<P>
   In an even bigger move by Yates, he worked quietly behind the
scenes to hire away five members of Gordon's famed ``Rainbow
Warriors'' pit crew.
</P>
<P>
   So can Jarrett, who turned 43 during the offseason, repeat? ``I
think our chances are very good to repeat in 2000,'' crew chief
Todd Parrott said. ``But the competition is incredible, and it is
just going to get better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett says there are 15 drivers capable of winning this year.
He thinks he is on the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``The success (of last season) has bred us into wanting more
success,'' Jarrett said. ``Once you have tasted it, you want more
of it. I told the people at R.J. Reynolds that I wasn't going back
to New York (if I didn't repeat). It wouldn't be any fun if you
didn't win.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
