</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS BEAT PACERS, 87-73  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was just the cellophane-thin Reggie Miller, but
upon the slightest contact, Chris Childs' upper body suddenly and
violently buckled out like a question mark, his head snapped back
and he hit the floor in a heap.
</P>
<P>
   A whistle cut in, and a foul was called on Miller. As the
Madison Square Garden crowd mocked its favorite foil from Indiana
Saturday, Childs bounced to his feet and all but cried out,
``Makeup!'' He had just out-acted one of the greatest flops on
Broadway, just upstaged the theatrical Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a call he normally gets,'' Childs said. ``He got a
taste of his own medicine on that one.''
</P>
<P>
   It was just one isolated moment of a third quarter, just one
more time when a crafty and undaunted team completely unnerved the
Pacers to such an extent that they never recovered as the Knicks
overwhelmed them, 87-73. It was a reminder of Game 6 from the
Eastern Conference finals last year, a flashback to when the
short-handed Knicks were held together with rubber bands and glue
but managed to hitch a ride on Allan Houston's supernatural touch
to advance to the finals.
</P>
<P>
   It was happening again. The makeshift Knicks, playing without
Charlie Ward and Marcus Camby, leaned on Houston as he turned a
7-point game at the half into a blowout by the end of the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   After a quiet half buried beneath foul trouble, and after making
the Knicks' big backcourt look less than threatening, Houston began
to exploit his mismatch with Indiana's Mark Jackson and defy Miller
to guard him as he let the jumpers fly. He hit his first five shots
of the third quarter and scored 13 of his 19 points during a 22-10
run the Knicks used to take a 70-53 lead into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers had no way to counter. Miller was being chased by
Childs _ who gave the big lineup a break and pushed the Knicks to
perform better _ and came unglued. Instead of his usual comeback,
Miller was shaken by how the officials had turned on him. All the
while, Houston kept demoralizing the Pacers, just as he did last
June.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get going like that, it just feels like you can pick
your shot,'' said Houston, who finished 9 for 14 from the field and
had 3 turnovers as the part-time point guard. ``You just don't feel
like you're going to miss.''
</P>
<P>
   As spectacular as Houston was on offense, the Knicks' defense,
leaning on the craftiness of Childs and the interior presence of
Patrick Ewing, were able to hold the Pacers to their lowest point
total of the season and held them to 34.2 percent from the field.
Perhaps if Rik Smits had played, the outcome would have been
different. But the Knicks simply built a lead and wouldn't let go.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the Knicks had lost big leads in the fourth
quarter. And on Christmas Day in Indiana, they blew a lead early.
This time, the Knicks (31-19) held firm in one of their most
impressive victories of the season and pulled into a tie with Miami
for the Atlantic Division lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't just want to keep up with them,'' said Latrell
Sprewell, who was partly responsible for keeping Miller to a quiet
16 points. ``We want to leave Miami behind.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks found the matchups they wanted with the big lineup at
the start of the game but, incredibly, their bulky size lacked
rebounding. With Smits out with a sore back, the 6-foot-9 Austin
Croshere was left to start against Ewing, and Dale Davis was
lurking around Kurt Thomas. Somehow, Croshere and Davis found their
way to every loose ball and gave their team a stream of
second-chance points.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment was over for the first half. Houston was in foul
trouble and the flow was out of sync, so a change toward tradition
was made. With 4 minutes 51 seconds left in the first quarter and
the score tied, Childs came into the game and showed how efficient
a point guard can be. With 6 assists in 17 minutes, Childs led the
Knicks to a 46-39 lead at the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the coach wants,'' said Childs, who had nine assists
off the bench. ``By no means am I happy with a big lineup, but I'll
do whatever it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Even take up acting.
</P>
<P>
   The second half gave the big lineup another chance. And Houston
erupted for 13 third-quarter points as he exploited his size over
Jackson in the post.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers had no answer for Houston. All Miller could do was
get Sprewell in foul trouble midway through the quarter. Even then,
the Knicks had Childs to turn to. Houston was cloaking Jackson,
Childs was chasing Miller and Davis couldn't make up for the
offensive void left by Smits' absence.
</P>
<P>
   The ragged Pacers, slow to recover in defensive transition,
watched as Larry Johnson turned a fast-break layup into a 3-point
play by finishing his shot and giving the Knicks a 68-52 lead with
1:34 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after Childs drew the foul on Miller by flopping on
contact, the Pacers came unglued as the crowd got into it. The
Pacers, who scored only 3 points in the last six minutes of the
third quarter, found themselves in an unlikely hole, 70-53, at the
end of the period. Miller just shook his head in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Childs was taking him. Although Childs is not as solid and
error-free as Ward, he plays tougher defense and can push the ball
to Sprewell's liking. When Childs walked on the floor in the first
half, he took over the tempo of the game and guided the Knicks on a
22-9 run.
</P>
<P>
   It helped that Miller, Croshere and Jackson weren't on the floor
during most of the Knicks' second-quarter run. Once they began
trickling into the game, the Pacers, who had scored only a single
field goal in six minutes, started finding their offense. Miller,
jumping and leaning into Sprewell and Houston, went to the
free-throw line, and the Pacers were quickly within 35-28.
</P>
<P>
   Childs wasn't flustered. He kept pushing the ball and creating
opportunities for the Knicks and himself, hitting a 3-pointer with
4:31 to put the Knicks back up by 10 points. But in another letdown
to end the first half, John Wallace, who picked up the offense, was
beaten in transition for two layups by Rose as a part of a 9-0 run
by the Pacers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 2003EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
