u s BC-BKN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-19 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASKETBALL COLUMN: A SHOOTING STAR AND A FALLING STAR  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ During player introductions at the All-Star Game last
week, Allan Houston walked through a pillar of smoke and under a
scaled-down model of the Golden Gate Bridge. He emerged on the
other side to a loud and prolonged ovation. It was the type of
applause reserved for perennial All-Stars, not first-time party
crashers. Houston looked at his teammates sheepishly, offering up a
``Who, me?'' shrug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little surprised by it, but then you remember that we
were on TV last year during the finals and people got to know us a
little better,'' the Knicks shooting guard said Saturday afternoon.
Someone surmised Latrell Sprewell's counterculture following may
have pushed many fans to embrace Houston nationally, a good cop-bad
cop dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might be it, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The reception for Reggie Miller, meanwhile, was measured and
lasted perhaps a few seconds. Miller has always done the
incarnation of evil proud, playing the villain to the hilt. But it
wasn't about that. Instead of respecting his longevity, the crowd
at the Arena in Oakland seemed to be contemplating the merits of
Miller, as in, Reggie is still considered among the game's great
players? Come on.
</P>
<P>
   Blame the power of television, which kept showing those replays
of Houston's jump shot sailing over Miller in the Eastern
Conference finals last June. Maybe it's a combination of one
player's emergence as a prime-time force and another's decline in
the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Anyhow, sometime over the last year Houston became the premier
shooting guard in the conference and maybe all of the National
Basketball Association. And Miller time expired. Somewhere between
New York's pulsating Game 6 victory and Saturday afternoon at
Madison Square Garden, NBC wanted to talk to Allan instead of
Reggie.
</P>
<P>
   Like last June, the game belonged to Houston and the Knicks
after halftime. They won 87-73, closing the gap for best record and
home-court advantage in the Eastern Conference. They won because
Houston got off 14 shots with ease, and exerted his presence in the
third period _ and because Miller worked hard to take 11 shots and
could not steal New York's spirit like he once did routinely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie ain't 30 no more,'' Larry Johnson said. ``You just have
to know. You ain't 30. What is he, 33, 34?''
</P>
<P>
   Miller is 34. Houston, 28, found a rhythm in the third quarter
not unlike the rhythm Miller once knew. He made a couple of long
jumpers, and suddenly felt like he was shooting by himself in an
empty gymnasium. He spliced his smooth release in with a strong
drive to the basket, releasing a pretty floater over the Pacers
front line that never touched the rim.
</P>
<P>
   Miller tried to front him. Jalen Rose tried to sag off and give
him space. Mark Jackson tried to bang him. And he kept scoring,
until the Knicks had a 15-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand, they think they're throwing me off by
putting different people on me,'' he said. ``The way I look at it
is, it gives me confidence. If three different people are guarding
me at different times, it means I'm giving them trouble. That's
just inspires me.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Riley recently said Houston may be the best shooting guard
in the game now that you-know-who is gone. Eddie Jones and Ray
Allen can argue and compare numbers. Allen Iverson and Kobe Bryant
have more talent, even though shooting guard is often not their
natural position.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is no argument when it comes to his counterpart in
Indiana. Miller is still capable of scoring in bunches, getting to
the free throw line because he knows more about positioning and
pushing off than anyone still active that does not live in Utah.
Reggie is still a money player, one of greatest of his era.
</P>
<P>
   But in stature and performance, Houston keeps creating a
distance between himself and a guy who once loved to tweak him by
saying, ``John Starks is still the best shooting guard the Knicks
have.''
</P>
<P>
   He hit 6 of 7 shots in the third quarter for 13 of his game-high
19 points. When he finished rising up over his defenders, the
Knicks had run away from Larry Bird's Pacers just as they had last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it comes from a strong belief in yourself,'' he said.
``Sometimes I feel, nobody is going to be able to stop me if I have
that kind of belief. No matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   It all looked so familiar Saturday. Houston faces up Miller on
the left wing. Stares him down. Squares. Fires. Scores.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked if Saturday felt like Game 6 at all. ``A little
bit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A little bit? A lot. Saturday could mean nothing and everything
in a few months. Who's to say where the Knicks and Pacers go from
here. Yet there is no denying one ongoing development: With each
arching jump shot, Allan Houston has become the player Reggie
Miller used to be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
