<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-PRICES-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCERN GROWS OVER RISING GAS PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ When Robin Gant of
Leavenworth, Kan., recently pulled his Lincoln Town Car into a gas
station, he had a pretty good idea of what he was about to see.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sure enough, he was right. The price of super unleaded gasoline,
the grade he prefers, had hit $1.50 per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like every time I turn around the price is going
up,'' Gant said.
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone. According to a survey released Friday by the
AAA Automobile Club of Missouri, the average Kansas City area price
of regular unleaded gas _ the most popular grade _ had soared to
$1.36 a gallon. gallon. In fact, it equals the record price set in
1981, when an oil embargo drove prices up.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly some effects of higher fuel prices are rippling
through the economy. But this is not 1981. Adjusted for inflation,
a gallon of gas that cost $1.36 a gallon in 1981 would go for $2.42
today.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the economy and consumers today are in better
financial shape. In 1981, 5 percent of household budgets were
devoted to buying motor fuel. That percentage has since dropped to
about 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not as big a deal for the economy as it was 20 years
ago,'' said Dave McDermott, regional economist for the Bureau of
Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if current gas prices hold, it will cost an extra $300
annually to fuel the average vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't blame people for being upset,'' said Mike Right, a
spokesman for AAA.
</P>
<P>
   Who's to blame? OPEC.
</P>
<P>
   Last year members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries agreed to reduce production 7.5 percent. Since then OPEC
members and other oil-producing countries have shown remarkable
discipline in hewing to the cuts, driving crude oil prices from
about $12 per barrel to more than last week's price of $30.
</P>
<P>
   If OPEC ministers decide next month to boost oil production,
then gas prices are expected to decline. If they do not, some
analysts predict, gas could reach $1.70 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The economic effects of higher gas prices have already cropped
up, and more are likely if prices stay at these levels or go
higher. For example:
</P>
<P>
   - Several airlines and trucking companies now have fuel
surcharges to recoup the higher fuel costs. Others are considering
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   - Independent truckdrivers have been hit hard. Unable to pass on
the increasing fuel costs, many have simply stopped taking jobs.
</P>
<P>
   - State highway departments are beginning to see higher bids for
repaving roads because of price increases for asphalt, a
petroleum-based product. If that continues, some road projects
could be curtailed.
</P>
<P>
   - The company that operates Kansas City's largest cab fleet and
shuttles to Kansas City International Airport plans to make a
decision in the next month about whether to boost fares because of
higher fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   - Even Wal-Mart, the world's largest retailer, expressed concern
last week that high oil prices could hinder efforts to hold the
line on prices of consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
   For average drivers the price increases have already gotten
their attention.
</P>
<P>
   Gant, the Leavenworth resident, commutes to his job in Kansas
City and has to fill his car's fuel tank twice a week. His weekly
gas bill has increased more than $20, and he's not happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see the government step in and do something,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of gas-guzzling sport-utility vehicles have been
particularly hard- hit by higher prices. If you own a Ford
Expedition with a 10-cylinder motor, for example, it will cost you
more than $20 extra to fill its 44-gallon tank.
</P>
<P>
   If gas prices do not decline, says AAA, expect to see some
drivers curtailing vacation plans this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of some tourist destinations say that gas prices have
their attention even though they are hoping that prices will
decline by the time summer vacations begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a topic under discussion here,'' said Lisa Rau, a
spokeswoman for Silver Dollar City, near Branson.
</P>
<P>
   Although higher gas prices are having some effect, they do not
come close to wreaking the havoc they did 20 years ago, many
economists say. In part, that is because oil simply does not play
the central role in the economy that it once did.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981 oil accounted for about 9 percent of expenditures in the
Gross Domestic Product of the U.S. economy. In today's increasingly
information-age economy it is 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Keeton, senior economist for the Federal Reserve Bank in
Kansas City, said one concern was that increases in gas prices
would ultimately fuel broad-based price increases in a wide range
of other products.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, then inflation is a worry. But factors such as
continued improvements in worker productivity so far are mitigating
the effect that gas prices are having on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no sign this is happening,'' Keeton said.
</P>
<P>
   Energy prices rose a sizable 1 percent in January, the Labor
Department reported Friday. But the surge in gas and other energy
costs such as heating oil was blunted by the steepest decline in
clothing prices in 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, inflation at the consumer level rose a mild 0.2 percent
in January. Still, some economists are bracing for fuel-driven
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really the lull before the storm,'' said Donald
Ratajczak, director of Georgia State University's economic
forecasting project. ``There's no question that February's numbers
will be eye-openers.''
</P>
<P>
   All kinds of businesses are on alert.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Lukas, owner of Lukas Liquors Superstore in Overland Park,
said that if gas prices stayed at current levels, he would not be
surprised if brewers tried to reduce their discounts on beer.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers also are monitoring sales of sport-utility vehicles.
Inventories of unsold sport-utilities have begun to build, although
the reason may have more to do with too many models competing for
the consumer.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Wolfe, president of Wolfe Automotive Group, said a few
customers were asking about fuel economy. That could change for the
worse by this summer if prices do not decline, he said, but so far
it has not had much effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty insignificant'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The effect has been more noticeable on companies that rely more
on motor fuel for their operation.
</P>
<P>
   Many airlines are adding a $20 surcharge to round-trip tickets
to cover the extra fuel costs. (Vanguard Airlines of Kansas City
has not added the surcharge, saying it is relying on conservation
measures.)
</P>
<P>
   Yellow Corp. of Overland Park, Kan., has added a surcharge to
freight bills to cover the higher costs of diesel fuel it uses in
its trucks. Currently the surcharge adds 4 percent to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   `We're not happy about taking this step, but it's a reasonable
solution,'' said Roger Dick, a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Some independent truckers have gone so far as to turn their rigs
back over to the finance company, said Todd Spencer, executive vice
president of the Owner-Operator Independent Drivers Association in
Grain Valley, which has 47,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the drivers are just going home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer's group would like to see a law that would allow
independent truckdrivers to automatically add fuel surcharges when
diesel prices escalated.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say they expect fuel prices to go down in the next
few months. OPEC ministers will meet next month to considering
boosting oil production.
</P>
<P>
   Julian Lee, a senior analyst at the London-based Center for
Global Energy Studies, expects a production increase. OPEC does not
want to risk an economic slowdown in Western countries that would
dampen oil consumption.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are looking to produce oil for those countries into the
distant future,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   If production is not increased, consumers can expect to see an
effect that will go beyond the additional cost of filling gas
tanks.
</P>
<P>
   When the Missouri Department of Transportation recently opened
bids for some repaving projects, two came in over budget because of
the rising cost of asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   The department has not had to curtail any projects yet. But if
oil prices do not decline this year and bids continue to come in
over budget, the department may have to rethink some projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It obviously could have some effect'' said Dale Ricks,
assistant district engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Some businesses say they are at a critical point in deciding
whether to raise prices to reflect the higher fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   Bill George Jr., president of Metropolitan Transportation
Services Inc., said his company had already raised rates for
out-of-town bus trips. In the next month the company will decide
whether to raise rates on other services to reflect the higher fuel
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The company also operates taxicabs, shuttles to KCI and a
limousine service. The company uses a million gallons of fuel a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a serious issue for us,'' George said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
