<HEADER>
A2291 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-IDITAROD-RACE-2TAKES-     02-19 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IDITAROD-RACE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY MAN TAKES CIRCUITOUS ROUTE TO THE LAST GREAT RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN BORMANN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It would have been
easy for David Straub to stay in Kansas City, where his friends and
relatives lived, where he worked for the family business. But his
heart was not in it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   His thoughts were of sled dogs and a great race thousands of
miles away. And so, four years ago, he left the comfortable and the
familiar and moved to Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Next month Straub, 39, will stand on a sled drawn by 16 dogs and
live his dream by competing in the Iditarod.
</P>
<P>
   The Iditarod, which some call the last great race in the world,
has become Straub's purpose, his passion. His dogs have become his
love, and a one-room cabin his home.
</P>
<P>
   The journey has not been easy. He lives a solitary life, working
as a carpenter in the summer and training dogs in the winter. He
trains them as long as 17 hours a day, rotating dogs on small teams
every few days.
</P>
<P>
   He depends on propane for heat and light, and a generator for
electricity. His visits back to Kansas City are limited to
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   He has overcome an accident in which three of his dogs were
killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were tough times,'' he said. ``I just held (the dream)
close to me and kept after it.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, Ernie Straub Jr. of Shawnee, Kan., is more surprised
than anyone that his son would grow up with a dream to race dogs
across Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't knock it. I've got to give him credit for his
fortitude,'' the elder Straub said. ``I'd be miserable living in a
shack just one day without utilities and no shower, but power to
him. He does without a place to live, clothing, and every modern
convenience. Every nickel and dime he makes goes to the dogs. He
does without himself.'' A dream begins
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, David Straub bred dogs for show, and he traveled
around the Midwest to competitions where he could show off his
Samoyeds and an Alaskan husky _ both breeds used in sledding.
</P>
<P>
   ``You start working with sled dogs and after a while you just
start reading about the Iditarod. We started tooling around.'' He
hooked his dogs up to a three-wheeled cart and rode around
Westport.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Bishop Miege High School, he worked for
veterinarians to learn more about dogs. He eventually joined the
family business, Straub Construction, as a carpenter, but spent his
spare time working with his dogs. He sneaked away at lunch to read
the newspaper's latest Iditarod update.
</P>
<P>
   When city living became too cramped, he moved his dogs to rural
Warrensburg, Mo. But it wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always talking sled dogs, and it was a little funny
when somebody was talking sled dogs in the middle of July,'' said
David De Feo, a Merriam, Kan., veterinarian and former employer.
``I remember one of his dogs died, and I thought we were going to
lose David. He was a walking zombie for a couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   He developed a four-year plan to move north, but it became a
three-month plan when his father got wind of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father took me out to lunch, and he said if I wanted to
move to Alaska, there was no use waiting four years, to put my
place on the market and go,'' Straub said. ``It was pretty great to
have somebody's support.''
</P>
<P>
   Now his father says he has never seen his son happier, despite
the hardships.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's persevering and paying a terrible price, in my way of
thinking, to live his dream, but he's got to do what he wants. He's
got to be happy. As a parent, you've got to want whatever makes
your children happy,'' his father said. A tragic turn
</P>
<P>
   Straub's most difficult day came in December.
</P>
<P>
   His team was traveling a familiar trail alongside the highway
when the young lead dogs guided the group up and onto the road.
Straub used voice commands to stop the team, but it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the same split second an 18-wheeler rolled through the
middle of the team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The accident killed three of his dogs and injured a fourth, and
it almost broke his spirit.
</P>
<P>
   He lost Mickey, a veteran lead dog who was to have guided the
team through the Iditarod. Straub had opted to place Mickey farther
back in the team that day to train younger lead dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I could do was drag everybody off the highway and ask for
a rescue,'' he said. ``It's hard to take a deep breath and go on
after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Months afterward, when he talks about the accident, his voice
still shakes and the tears still flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shook up everybody,'' he said, referring to the dogs.
``It's like coming up to a red light and everybody runs it.''
</P>
<P>
   News of the accident rippled through Alaska and prompted mushers
from the area to offer him their extra dogs. Straub, however,
decided that if he was to continue, he would have to promote one of
the 32 dogs he had raised from pups. The reshaped team finished two
races, the requirement to qualify for the Iditarod. Once mushers
complete an Iditarod, they are qualified forever.
</P>
<P>
   Straub signed up for the race even before he had qualified; in
June 1999 he was the first to arrive at the race headquarters with
his $1,750 check, earning him the No. 1 position on the entry list.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean his team will leave Anchorage first. Instead,
it is considered prestigious because he will be the first to draw
for position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's demonstrative of his enthusiasm and commitment to this
race, to physically come here to Iditarod headquarters and camp
here for a couple of days,'' said Stan Hooley, executive director
of the Iditarod Trail Committee. ``He's one of the wide-eyed folks
that's living out a dream, and we commend him for that.'' An Alaska
legend
</P>
<P>
   The Iditarod is large in Alaskan lore.
</P>
<P>
   The route dates to 1929, when Nome was hit by a diphtheria
outbreak. Supplies of serum were back in Anchorage, and the only
two planes in Alaska had been disassembled for the winter.
Volunteers using dog sleds rushed the medicine from town to town
until they reached Nome.
</P>
<P>
   Their route is, for the most part, the same route used for the
race.
</P>
<P>
   Teams travel at their own paces, and mushers set their own
schedules. If it's hot _ 30 degrees _ they may choose to race at
night.
</P>
<P>
   While training, Straub's dogs start the day with a warm broth.
Every hour they stop and get an ``ice cookie,'' a bite of frozen
broth. After three or four hours they get chunks of meat _ usually
lamb, beef or turkey. They go another three or four hours with the
ice cookies, and at the end of the day they get more meat. Before
bedtime they get a warm stew made with meat and dry dog food.
</P>
<P>
   Their feedings in the race will be similar but will depend on
their strength during the day.
</P>
<P>
   The dogs will guide Straub through the route using instinct and
smell. Along the route Straub will stop at 18 checkpoints where
veterinarians will ensure that the dogs are not being mistreated
and that mushers are following race rules. Straub also will pick up
1,400 pounds of meat for the dogs, dog booties, fresh straw and
other supplies that have been flown to the sites ahead of time. At
some checkpoints Straub will be offered sleeping shelter, but in
other areas he expects to sleep near the trail, next to his team.
</P>
<P>
   The perils are innumerable. In past years moose and other wild
animals have attacked dog teams. Temperatures dive as low as 60
degrees below zero. Strong winds can produce whiteouts for days,
and thin ice is always a concern.
</P>
<P>
   Hooley said 10 percent to 15 percent of the mushers will drop
out or be disqualified before they reach Nome. Those who brave the
elements to finish have historically been considered heroes in the
state of Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iditarod is far and away the event that Alaskans enjoy the
most and support in a very big way. It's just a very exciting
time,'' Hooley said.
</P>
<P>
   Finish or not, Straub said, he'll come away with an even greater
respect for the race's history and the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found a love for Alaska. When I'm out on these trails I just
imagine what it was like years ago,'' he said. ``It really feels
like home up here.''
</P>
<P>
   It also will be a time to grow closer to the dogs he loves and
considers his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, I'll just be out camping with 16 of my best friends,''
he said. ``I'm pretty nervous, but there's no turning back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
