<DOCNO> NYT20000219.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2295 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GARTH-BASEBALL0220-C0     02-19 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARTH-BASEBALL0220-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Garth trades his guitar for a baseball bat
 &HT;    EDS: MOVING ON SPORTS AND ENTERTAINMENT WIRES
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ If nice guys really do finish last, then
Garth Brooks is way deep in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   Best-selling country singer and all-around good guy Brooks
traded in his black cowboy hat for a New York Mets baseball cap and
his guitar for a black bat Saturday as he began five weeks of
spring training with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   But he brought his country fans with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love you, Garth,'' chimed a quartet of female admirers as
he fielded ground balls at third. Several hundred fans lined the
fences of Thomas J. White Stadium to see Brooks play out Year 2 of
his baseball fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is not to embarrass major league baseball or the New
York Mets,'' said the 38-year-old singer/third baseman/first
baseman before beginning a 2 1/2 hour workout.
</P>
<P>
   He booted only one at third and, while playing first, flipped
several ground balls with his glove to pitchers playing first.
``Ooooh,'' said the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Average,'' pronounced longtime Mets fan Pat Lowe, wearing a
fisherman's hat festooned with dozens of Met pins and buttons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a wannabe. It's a little fantasy camp for him,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing No. 1 on his back, Brooks stepped into the batting cage
after slugger Mike Piazza had ripped several over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to throw him to the wolves right away. We're gonna
find out,'' teased Mets coach John Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   Swinging right-handed, Brooks missed the first pitch, took the
second and drilled the third hard on the ground between shortstop
and third base.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks wasn't ready for the next pitch and mumbled, ``Sorry.'
Then he dribbled one foul and said, ``My fault.'' A few pitches
later, ``My fault'' again.
</P>
<P>
   His new teammates scolded him for apologizing. The pitcher let
up a bit and Brooks rocketed a few shots to the fence. Then he took
a turn left-handed. He tired quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry about it, dude,'' said catcher Todd Pratt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to peak out early,'' said Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did that about 8 this morning,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Superfan Lowe re-assessed her opinion: ``Not bad at all. Pretty
good for a country superstar.''
</P>
<P>
   Before wind sprints, Brooks paused against a fence to sign
autographs, shooing photographers away. He stayed an hour, signing
balls, rosters and baby bibs, long after most of the Mets had gone
inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the best manners of any player I've ever seen,'' said
Mets General Manager Steve Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   But manners isn't what brought Brooks to camp. Brooks''
2-year-old Touch 'Em All Foundation, which provides money to
children's groups, will benefit from the singer's stay in camp.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are donating $100,000, which is being matched by
eSuperstars.com, an Internet charity auction site represented by
Mets Manager Bobby Valentine. Players also make donations based on
their performances. Last year the charity raised $1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Mets wouldn't have gone along had not players like
Robin Ventura and Al Leiter encouraged it, and had not the San
Diego Padres, where Brooks spent spring training last year, been
convinced it wasn't merely a publicity stunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole goal here is that people see my respect for the game
is unequaled, and my love for the game is equal to any fan's on the
other side of the fence,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   His second goal is to improve last year's spring batting average
of .045 (1-for-22). ``I probably will strike out more this year
because I'm going to be swinging. I'm trying to be a ballplayer
this year, instead of trying just not to strike out.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he didn't want to be a distraction to the players.
Saturday's workout brought fans who didn't know Piazza from pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Moore and her sister-in-law Debbie Beck left Coral
Springs at 5 a.m. so they could be there in the Thomas J. White
Stadium parking lot when Brooks arrived in his blue Chevy king cab
truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was friendly,'' Moore said. ``He said, 'Hi,''' which was
remarkable since Brooks arrived in town at 3:30 a.m. Saturday after
finishing the score for a new movie. The film, ``Frequency'',
features a fantasy sequence involving the '69 world champion Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've shot two rolls of film already,'' Moore said, ``most of
them butt shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore has been to six Brooks concerts and zero major league
games. Until this spring.
</P>
<P>
   So, how did Mets Manager Valentine assess Brooks' performance?
``Garth brought a lot of energy. He seemed to enjoy it and he
seemed to fit in,'' the manager sit diplomatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a stand-up guy that sings a song. Maybe some of that
goodness rubs off. It's probably good for the other guys to see how
that works.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 2017EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000219.0241 </DOCNO>
