</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-MCCAIN0220-COX1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain campaign urging primary cross-over in Michigan
 &HT;    (EDS: fixed headline)
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ Two separate efforts _ one by Sen. John McCain's
presidential campaign committee _ have begun in Michigan urging
Democrats to cross party lines and vote for McCain against Texas
Gov. George W. Bush in Tuesday's Republican presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the Dayton Daily News obtained a post card the McCain
campaign in Michigan sent to a registered Democrat here in Flint,
urging Democrats to support McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, state Rep. LaMar Lemmons III, a black Democratic
lawmaker from Detroit, is helping lead an effort to persuade
Democrats to vote for McCain to punish Republican Gov. John Engler,
leader of Bush's Michigan campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can vote in the GOP primary and Democratic and
independent voters are considered crucial to McCain's efforts to
defeat Bush. Polls have shown Bush leading among likely Republican
voters, but McCain with a lead among all likely voters, including
Democrats and independents.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Democrats will chose their national convention
delegates in caucuses March 11 and neither Vice President Al Gore
nor former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley is on Tuesday's primary
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The post card sent to Democrats by the McCain committee says,
``The Democrats are not holding a presidential primary in Michigan.
But you can still make your vote count by voting in the Republican
primary on Tuesday, Feb.22.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Make your voice heard by voting for the one candidate
committed to reform. John McCain will reform the current
disgraceful and corrupting system of financing campaigns,'' the
card continues.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. John J.H. Schwarz, a Battle Creek Republican and
McCain's Michigan chairman, said that the cards are consistent with
McCain's invitation to ``Republicans, independents and like-minded
Democrats'' to support him
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz said that he did not know how many of the cards have
been mailed. He also said that he hoped that the cards would help
counter some of the Bush campaign's negative ads targeting McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Lemmons said that Engler, a third-term governor, has mistreated
Democrats, particularly Detroiters. He cited Engler's role in
replacing Detroit's elected school board with an appointed board
among other abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our chance to retaliate,'' Lemmons said. ``We
(Democrats) are in a minority. African-Americans are in a double
minority.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemmons said that fliers are being sent to Detroit-area churches
in predominantly black neighborhoods urging people to vote for
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Responding specifically to questions about Lemmons' campaigns,
Susan Shafer, Engler's deputy press secretary, said that they would
only re-energize the Republican base.
</P>
<P>
   ``When folks read these kind of things, it re-energizes them and
rejuvenates them as Republicans. We are deciding who are candidates
are going to be, not Democrats and independents. This is a
Republican primary,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
