<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2301 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-SC-PRIMARY-BOS &LR;      02-19 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-PRIMARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH COASTS TO EASY WIN IN SOUTH CAROLINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH AND CURTIS WILKIE AND  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ George W. Bush capitalized on an outpouring
of Republican support Saturday to win the South Carolina primary by
a decisive margin, dashing Senator John McCain's dream, after his
New Hampshire victory, that his reformist appeal would trigger a
huge turnout of Democrats and independents here.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls and early returns suggested that Bush's victory
margin would be 10 percentage points or more. McCain called Bush
shortly after the polls closed at 7 p.m. to concede defeat. And he
sought to buck up his disappointed army of supporters: ``We have
just begun to fight, and I cannot wait for the next round.''
</P>
<P>
   The see-sawing Republican nomination battle now shifts to the
Michigan primary on Tuesday, with the pressure on McCain to run
strongly there, and in his home state of Arizona on the same day.
It was a dramatic turn of events after McCain upended the GOP race
with his landslide win in New Hampshire, which enabled him to
arrive here tied in the polls with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I'm relieved, but relief is not the right word,''
Bush told reporters. ``I'm excited and energized.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did we win, we did so in convincing fashion,'' Bush
added. ``It's an embrace of a message that's conservative and
compassionate and an embrace of a messenger who is a reformer who
has gotten positive results and will do for America as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The yawning 18-day gap between New Hampshire and South Carolina
slowed McCain's march and gave Bush time to regroup and retool his
strategy. In the end, Bush was saved by the much-discussed South
Carolina ``firewall,'' kept aflame by the Republican Party base
that listened to the Texas governor's argument that McCain was
spending too much time appealing to Democrats. After all the talk
about Democratic crossover voters, McCain was hurt by the small
size of the Democratic turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls showed that 61 percent of the vote came from
Republicans, 30 percent from independents and only 9 percent from
Democrats. While McCain was strong among independents and
Democrats, he could not overcome the flood tide of Republicans,
two-thirds of whom backed Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's overt appeal to Democrats may have backfired,
motivating many conservatives to turn out against him.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was also hurt by other factors. The black voter turnout
was only 1 percent. And McCain, who made much of his days as a
Vietnam prisoner of war, barely won the veteran vote, by 49 percent
to 47 percent, according to the exit poll.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who lost in New Hampshire with what aides described as a
soft, lackluster effort, won here after waging a much tougher kind
of campaign, blasting McCain with harsh advertisements that
questioned the senator's conservative credential and accused the
Arizonan of trying to take away tax breaks for contributions to
churches.
</P>
<P>
   Radio talk show host Alan Keyes was running a distant third
place as the early returns poured in.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls conducted by the television networks and the
Associated Press showed that Bush won the vote of self-described
religious conservatives by a 3-to-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were not for the massive negative campaign run against
us, primarily in the religious conservative community, we would
have carried the state,'' McCain campaign manager Rick Davis told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to Bush ads that said McCain's tax plan would
limit the deductibility of church contributions, a charge refuted
by McCain. But McCain has long had trouble with religious
conservatives, with Christian Coalition founder Pat Robertson
saying that McCain was unfit to be president because his campaign
finance plan would hurt organizations such as antiabortion groups.
</P>
<P>
   Voting was marred early in the day by reports that some polling
places in black neighborhoods were not open. McCain political
director John Weaver vowed to ``raise hell''' with a formal
complaint about the poll closings.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain barely had time to digest the outcome of the
race before moving early Sunday to Michigan, which along with
McCain's home state of Arizona holds its primary on Tuesday. Then
the campaign will unfold rapidly, with elections in Virginia and
Washington on Feb. 29 and many states on March 7, including New
York, California, and Massachusetts. McCain has said he will
participate at least through those contests.
</P>
<P>
   The key to McCain's success has been his ability to attract
non-Republicans, but that effort fell short in South Carolina, a
state heavily populated with veterans. McCain said several weeks
ago South Carolina was a ``must win.'' But more recently, McCain
has said South Carolina only has to be close and perceived as a
win, enabling him to raise money and continue the march to Super
Tuesday. Saturday's outcome left both those goals uncertain at
best.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's day unfolded in contrast with his New Hampshire
experience. Senior advisor Karl Rove, who had delivered the bad
news about the New Hampshire exit polls, Saturday arrived with good
news from the first wave of exit polls just after 1:30 p.m. Bush
later went for a 5-mile run and took a nap.
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon, Bush aides were confident the early
indicators had proven true, and jubilantly heralded the numbers as
evidence the ``retooled'' Bush strategy had worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think South Carolinians and Republicans in general learned a
lot about Bush'' after the New Hampshire primary, Rove said.
``People in this state saw him fight for what he believed in, and
saw him stand by his convictions. And they appreciated that,'' Rove
said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, when it was clear voters had turned out in
droves, Bush campaigned in Spartanburg before returning to his
hotel in Columbia. ``That is good news,'' he said of the high
turnout. ``Our whole focus has been on increasing the turnout,
convincing Republicans and like-minded Democrats to come out and
support us.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the polls closed, Bush appeared ebullient. After
meeting with voters Saturday morning at a polling place in
Spartanburg, the Texas governor told reporters: ``I'm enthused
about my chances. . . . I'm going to come out of this state feeling
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he acknowledged a few days ago that his campaign had
spent much of the $70 million he raised in contributions last year,
Bush said he was satisfied fund-raising would pick up again on the
strength of a strong showing in South Carolina. ``People like to
back a winner,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a blue windbreaker and accompanied by his wife, Laura,
Bush said he made adjustments in South Carolina following his
defeat in New Hampshire 18 days ago. ``I got defined somehow as the
insider,'' he said of McCain's antiestablishment campaign. ``I told
people coming down here I wasn't going to let that happen'' in
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   During the intense struggle here, Bush began portraying himself
as a ``reformer with results'' and hammered McCain with a barrage
of combative commercials that called attention to the Arizona
senator's Washington connections.
</P>
<P>
   Election day had a bizarre start for Bush. After eating pancakes
and bacon and greeting breakfast customers at the Ham House outside
Spartanburg, Bush was being interviewed by a TV reporter outside
the cafe when a dump truck pulled alongside him. Ignoring a police
officer's order to move, the driver dumped a large load of manure
nearby. After donning a pig's mask and shouting, ``Meat is murder!
Pork is death!'' the man was taken into custody.
</P>
<P>
   He was believed to be an animal rights activist rather than a
McCain partisan.
</P>
<P>
   As the suspect was led away, Bush said, ``I sure am glad I had
my bacon for breakfast this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the day, McCain expressed confidence that he would win,
appealing to the Veterans of Foreign Wars spring meeting in
Greenville to commit ``to one more mission'' in turning out the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   As the polls opened at 7 a.m., McCain officials said they were
disturbed by reports, coming from poll-watching volunteers in
Greenville County, that polling places in predominantly Democratic
African-American neighborhoods had not opened and voters were being
directed to a less convenient location. Republican officials later
said that more than a score of polling places that lacked
volunteers were closed and ``consolidated'' with other venues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Reporters Anne E. Kornblut, traveling with Bush, and Mary Leonard,
traveling with McCain, contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 2022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000219.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2304 &Cx1f; ttj-z
b p BC-SC-PRIMARY-3RDLD-WRIT     02-19 1458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-PRIMARY-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     BUSH DEFEATS McCAIN IN SOUTH CAROLINA, EXIT POLLS SHOW   
 &HT;     (EDS: New material in grafs 6-7, with McCain defiant.)   (For
use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL And DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLSTON, S.C. _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush decisively revived
his flagging front-runner campaign for the Republican presidential
nomination, exit polls showed Saturday, fighting off a scrappy
challenge by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., in the South Carolina
primary and catapulting their bitter struggle into big state
showdowns beginning with Michigan on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls showed that Bush rode to victory on a tidal wave of
GOP voters who turned out in record numbers across the
predominantly conservative piedmont region to overwhelm McCain's
less-than-expected support among many non-Republican voters who
could legally vote in the open primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's victory was projected on the basis of interviews
conducted by Voter News Service as voters left their polling
places.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great moment and I'm excited,'' Bush told reporters
shortly after 7 p.m. when the polls closed and exit polls projected
his win. ``This will have a very positive effect in Michigan.``
</P>
<P>
   Bush took a phone call from McCain at 7:08 p.m. conceding the
race. ``I'm very
</P>
<P>
   Grateful for the phone call,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on how far he has come since his defeat in the Feb. 1
New Hampshire Primary, Bush said: ``I fell down in the snow (in New
Hampshire, but) I knocked the snow off my suit and came down
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Stung by the size of his loss, McCain struck a defiant tone in
his concession speech before flying to Michigan. He vowed to go
forward with his reformist crusade, ``to offer voters a choice
between a record of reform and an empty slogan of reform, a choice
between experience and pretense.''
</P>
<P>
   He wished Bush ``a good night's rest.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain added: ``He's going to need it, my friends, for we have
just begun to fight. And I cannot wait for the next round.''
</P>
<P>
   The exit polls showed that 9 percent of those voting Saturday
were Democrats. Of those, 82 percent supported McCain and 16
percent said they voted for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The polls also showed that 31 percent of voters were
independents. Of those, 34 percent were for Bush and 61 percent
were for McCain. That's a much bigger-than-expected margin for
Bush. In New Hampshire among independents, McCain got 61 percent
and Bush got 19 percent. Among Democrats in New Hampshire, Bush got
10 percent and McCain got 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   CNN projected turnout at 600,000, more than double the 276,000
who voted in the 1996 South Carolina Republican Primary.
</P>
<P>
   Religious conservatives went for Bush 3-1, exit polls showed.
Unlike New Hampshire, Bush tailored his South Carolina message to
fit ``the pro-life agenda,'' said Randy Tate, former executive
director of the Christian Coalition now with Voter.com, a
politics-oriented website. ``These are the issues that motivate the
grassroots activists to walk the precincts,
</P>
<P>
   and bring the Reagan Democrats out to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   By winning here in a southern state that has voted reliably
Republican in eight of the last 10 presidential elections, Bush
energized a campaign that had been stunned by McCain's upset
victory in New Hampshire's Feb. 1 primary. The Bush win helps him
allay campaign donors' anxieties, stem threatened defections by
worried Republican office holders and stun McCain's momentum.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who had hoped to parlay his come-from-behind victory in
New Hampshire into a second upset here, came away from the contest
with ample evidence that he appeals to the independents and
Democrats who can vote in 16 of the next 24 GOP presidential
primaries. McCain vowed to carry on with his populist insurgency at
least until Super Tuesday, March 7, when New York, California and
Ohio join 13 less populous states to hold primaries and caucuses
that could settle the struggle for the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's triumph in an 18-day slugfest stemmed in part from a
shift in strategy from being a tax-cutting ``compassionate
conservative'' who lost to McCain by 19 percentage points in New
Hampshire to becoming a ``reformer with results'' who ardently
courted the state's religious and social conservatives and
challenged McCain's proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spoke at conservative Bob Jones University where
inter-racial dating is prohibited and he refused to challenge the
GOP platform's call for an absolute ban on abortions, even though
he favors exceptions to save the mother's life or to end
pregnancies that result from rape or incest.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's turn to the right risked alienating the
middle-of-the-road voters who often decide the outcome of the
industrial state primaries that lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Whit Ayres, an Atlanta-based Republican pollster who is not
working for any GOP presidential candidate, said the victory
enables Bush to retain ``the mantle of the front-runner,'' adding:
``It's a tremendous boost for Bush. It allows you to say that once
again, the nomination is Bush's to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's victory is expected to help entice a sorely needed
infusion of campaign donations into a fast-spending juggernaut that
has already spent more than $50 million of the $68 million in
donations. He heads into Michigan where three-term Gov. John Engler
has vowed to deliver the state to Bush. Bush's hand is also
strengthened in follow-on contests in Virginia and Washington on
Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sabato, professor of government at the University of
Virginia, said Bush's victory may be seen in hindsight as ``the
turning point that enabled Bush to go on to victory,'' adding:
``This is too big a victory for McCain to spin.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Ballenger, editor of the influential Inside Michigan
Politics newsletter and a radio talk show host, said the magnitude
of Bush's victory in South Carolina could discourage turnout by the
independents and Democrats that McCain is counting upon to keep him
competitive in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their attitude now might be 'Why bother to vote?''' Ballenger
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain showered South Carolina's 2.1 million registered
voters with more than $5.9 million worth of often hard-nosed
campaign ads during the longest presidential primary campaign in
state history. Previously, South Carolina held its primary just
four days after New Hampshire's.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &LR;  &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina has a 20-year history of picking Republican
winners. The GOP winner in South Carolina has never failed to go on
and capture the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls showed Bush built his win on a healthy core
Republican turnout.
</P>
<P>
   About 61 percent of voters Saturday identified themselves as
Republicans. Among them, 68 percent said they voted for Bush and 26
percent said they voted for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also did better than expected among independents, who along
with Democrats were free to cast ballots in the state's Republican
primary. Exit polls showed that fewer independents and Democrats
turned out than McCain had hoped for. Just 30 percent of the voters
were independents and 9 percent were Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Bush managed to carry 35 percent of the independent voters _ a
far stronger showing among independents than Bush scored in New
Hampshire where he won only 19 percent of the independents.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``played to win rather than playing not to loose, like in
New Hampshire,'' said Ayres, adding that Bush had succeeded in
shifting voters' focus away from McCain's heroic biography as a
Navy pilot and prisoner of war in Vietnam to his policy proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain's agenda is much less compelling to Republican
audiences, whether its taxes or campaign finance reform,'' Ayres
said. ``This is going to buck up the Bush forces big time.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain complained early in the day that state GOP officials had
failed to open many precinct-voting stations where Democrats and
independents lived, including 21 polling stations in Greenville
County. South Carolina law requires party officials to staff
polling places. Of the state's 1,700 polling places, 1,454 were
open _ twice the number that were open for the 1996 GOP
presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just disappointing that anyone anywhere in South Carolina
is deprived of the ability to vote,'' McCain said. ``That's just
not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   State GOP officials consolidated 21 polling places in Greenville
County at the last minute, requiring voters to travel to
alternative sites. ``From the reports we're getting everywhere,
everything is goingsmooth,'' said state GOP director J. Sam
Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell and Dan Freedman can be reached at
202-298-6920.)
</P>
</TEXT>
