<HEADLINE>
ON EVE OF BURUNDI TALKS, REFUGEES TELL OF ESCALATING VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUKOLE REFUGEE CAMP B, Tanzania _ This is the story Hamu
Ncongera tells.
</P>
<P>
   He was collecting firewood in the forest near his village,
Murama, in northeastern Burundi on Feb. 12 when soldiers of the
Tutsi-led army arrested his father and two of his brothers. The
Ncongeras were accused of killing Tutsi. Last Sunday, Hamu's mother
tried to bring food to her husband and sons in prison. She was too
late. They had already been executed. The boys were 18 and 12 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   Hamu, 15, and his only remaining brother, Salvadore, 19, arrived
at this refugee camp last Monday. Their mother was captured as they
fled into Tanzania. They fear the worst. The younger brother looks
bewildered, the older one angry.
</P>
<P>
   Hamu's story is not unique. Nor is it insignificant to a region
rent by the chaos of overlapping wars.
</P>
<P>
   As Nelson Mandela, Africa's elder statesman, jumpstarts
Burundi's stalled peace process Monday, refugees trickling into the
string of camps on Tanzania's western frontier tell of escalating
ethnic violence and persecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attacks by soldiers are happening every day,'' Hamu said,
standing under a blue UN tarpaulin during an afternoon hailstorm.
</P>
<P>
   The talks are critical. The deterioration in Burundi mirrors a
serious breakdown of the peace process in neighboring Congo, where
several foreign armies and splintered rebel groups are fighting
either for or against the government, and could fan the flames of
war into Tanzania and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the urgency of the crisis, President Clinton plans
to address the Burundi talks, to be held in Arusha, Tanzania, via
satellite.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as rebels operating from inside eastern Congo think
they can overthrow Rwanda, Uganda, and Burundi by war, they won't
talk peace,'' said Jan van Eck, a consultant to the Arusha talks
from the Center for Conflict Resolution in Cape Town. ``Burundi is
increasingly becoming subject to what is happening in the region.''
Congo and its allies want ``to mount a rebellion in Burundi to
force the war into Rwanda.''
</P>
<P>
   Slightly larger than Massachusetts, Burundi shares the same
combustible ethnic politics as its northern neighbor, Rwanda, where
militant Hutu killed an estimated 800,000 Tutsi in a swift
genocidal spree in 1994. In both countries, Hutu make up about 85
percent of the population, Tutsi about 14 percent. The other 1
percent are pygmies.
</P>
<P>
   Burundi has battled to overcome ethnic violence since
independence in 1962, but never more so than during the past seven
years, after Tutsi army paratroopers raided the presidential palace
in October 1993, and rounded up and killed several prominent Hutu
politicians, including President Melchior Ndadaye. Hundreds of
thousands of Burundians have fled or been killed in continuous
ethnic attacks since, as both groups have struggled for power and
built territorial strongholds throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Regional leaders launched a peace initiative in 1996 with former
Tanzanian president Julius Nyerere as mediator. That process
sputtered along inconclusively until Nyerere died last October. The
talks were beset by the repeated splintering of parties.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela now breathes vital new life into the talks. Gathering
the 18 recognized negotiating parties to an initial meeting last
month, the former South African president made it clear he would
hear all, but tolerate no bickering. ``The daily slaughter of men,
women, and children is an indictment against each and every one of
you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into the first round of formal talks, Mandela has
already made one significant structural change by inviting
previously excluded armed rebel factions to participate. Those
groups undermined a June 1998 cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is Burundi's devastated economy. The country
faces massive poverty and popular discontent partly because of
Nyerere's insistence that donor countries disengage from Burundi
until a settlement was reached.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-government groups, as well, say there can be no peace
without punishment of those guilty of genocide.
</P>
<P>
   A UN Security Council resolution on Burundi, adopted Jan. 19
after Mandela addressed the body, reiterated those concerns by
condemning attacks against civilians; calling on neighboring states
to stem border insurgencies and arming of rebel factions. The
resolution also encouraged donor countries to resume economic aid.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest stumbling block, however, remains the war in Congo,
where Zimbabwe and Angola have backed President Laurent Kabila in
quashing a rebellion sponsored by Rwanda and Uganda. Initially,
Kabila and his allies said the 19-month war would end when they had
pushed Rwandan and Ugandan troops out of Congo. Now they talk with
increasing vehemence about toppling the ``Tutsi regimes'' of
Burundi and Rwanda, as well as ``Tutsi-supporting'' Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its denials, there is strong evidence, van Eck said,
that Zimbabwe is funneling arms to Burundian rebels inside Congo,
dealing a significant blow to a faltering cease-fire signed last
July by the belligerents. Meanwhile, the United Nations is
considering plans to deploy 500 observers to salvage the
cease-fire, protected by 5,000 UN troops.
</P>
<P>
   With foreign soldiers preparing ethnic-based rebel movements for
war, the outcome of Mandela's talks this week on Burundi may
indicate whether there is still hope of averting a humanitarian
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that everyone in Burundi is expecting that the
whole war in the region will engulf all of Burundi,'' van Eck said.
``The antagonism between the countries fighting in Congo is such
that an escalation of the war is probable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
