<SLUG> BC-MUBARAK-LEBANON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGYPTIAN LEADER PAYS SURPRISE VISIT TO BEIRUT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ In the first visit of an Egyptian president here in
nearly a half-century, Hosni Mubarak Saturday made a surprise call
on his Lebanese counterpart to offer support for the fight against
Israeli occupation in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The landmark expression of support followed the escalation of
the conflict along the Israel-Lebanon border, the last Arab-Israeli
warfront.
</P>
<P>
   One diplomat here described Mubarak's visit as ``symbolism, but
important symbolism'' aimed at expressing a unified opposition
among Arab leaders to Israel's avowal last week to strike at
civilian infrastructure if Hezbollah fighters in south Lebanon kill
any more Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Israel staged punishing airstrikes on
Lebanon, destroying three power stations and wounding 20 civilians
in retaliation for Hezbollah attacks on its soldiers occupying
southern Lebanon. Hezbollah guerrillas have killed seven Israeli
soldiers in a series of attacks since Jan. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon maintains that Israel's retaliatory strikes, which
knocked out power to half the nation and prompted angry protests in
Beirut's streets, violated a 1996 agreement.
</P>
<P>
   That accord, which followed a large-scale Israeli air war in
which more than 100 civilians were killed, established rules for
the conflict that ban attacks on civilian areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Continuing attempts by Israel to ignore this understanding
will not lead to changing it but will lead to an unlimited
escalation,'' Mubarak and Lebanese President Emile Lahoud said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has defended the attacks and vowed to continue them,
saying Hezbollah is operating out of civilian areas, which would
also be a violation of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak and Lahoud ``stressed the right of the resistance to
fight the Israeli occupation until liberation and said the
resistance is a result of the occupation and not a reason for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Their statement also emphasized the urgency of reviving
Israeli-Syrian peace talks, which were suspended in January. It
expressed support for Damascus's demand that Israel return the
occupied zone in Lebanon and the Golan Heights, which it captured
from Syria in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   There is a delicate web of diplomacy between Israel, Lebanon,
and Syria, which has 35,000 troops stationed in Lebanon. Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak has vowed to honor last year's campaign
promise to pull Israeli forces out of the 9-mile deep ``security
zone'' inside Lebanon by July. Many analysts in the region said
that for an Israeli pullout to be successful it must be
accomplished in the context of an Israeli-Syrian agreement on the
Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak and Lahoud called the Israeli return of the occupied
zone and the Golan Heights a ``primary foundation of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak's visit was the first of an Egyptian president since
Lebanon gained independence in 1943.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons have much to do with strained relations between
Egypt and Lebanon and Lebanon's long, tortured history of civil
unrest through the decades, including its 1975-90 civil war. The
last visit to Lebanon by an Egyptian leader was in 1952, although
Gamal Abdel Nasser met with Lebanon's president six years later in
a tent between Syrian and Lebanese border posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mubarak's visit to Lebanon is a sign of our solidarity with
the Lebanese people,'' Mubarak political adviser Osama Baz told
Reuters. ``But also, Mubarak is sending a message to the government
of Israel to respect Lebanon's sovereignty and the security of its
people. He is telling them, enough is enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
