<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST WHAT THE CLIPPERS NEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO - To the watchdogs of timing and incongruity, the
Clippers' hiring of ex-Lakers great Kareem Abdul-Jabbar for
tutorial work may seem as strategically twisted as recruiting
Richard Petty to change a tire on your tractor.
</P>
<P>
   Doomsday reactionaries probably wonder why if low-post wisdom is
required wasn't the NBA's all-time leading scorer hired sooner?
That one's easy. Abdul-Jabbar wasn't hired earlier, because
teaching Michael Olowokandi and his seemingly disinterested cronies
was the responsibility of Chris Ford. Now Ford's a goner.
</P>
<P>
   Through the vapor of Ford's departure, we salute Clips GM Elgin
Baylor for bringing in Kareem and Dennis Johnson as potentially
enlightening influences on the Clippers' itchy young talent.
</P>
<P>
   What's in it for Abdul-Jabbar, a Hall of Famer with six
championship rings? The opportunity to stick his tootsie through
the NBA's coaching door. Why did it seem so difficult for one of
the game's greatest players to cross that coaching threshold? Maybe
the reluctance to take up Abdul-Jabbar on his frequent
sideline-seeking overtures had something to do with a
well-established and vigorous allegiance to privacy.
</P>
<P>
   But his commitment to teaching the sport he frequently
transcended was validated when Abdul-Jabbar spent a season on a
reservation, coaching Native American players at the high-school
level. He has written a book, done the tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end,'' Abdul-Jabbar said of that teaching experience,
``it was more about life than basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   It must have had something to do with the approach of the coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life was full,'' he said of his post-retirement existence.
``It wasn't like I was pining away for basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   His eager return has been motivated, in part, by a
disintegration of the sport's on-court integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamentals aren't being translated,'' Abdul-Jabbar
pointed out. ``The game has lost something. It's the money in the
pro game. Kids don't stay in college and learn the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's killing the college game and hurting the pro game at the
same time. Hopefully, through teaching, I can be part of the
solution. We've got to figure a way to get that back.''
</P>
<P>
   Even trickier is his gig with the Clippers, who hope
Abdul-Jabbar can replicate something they've never had.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry-mandering
</P>
<P>
   Most barstool sharpies in the City of Big Mikes regard Jerry
``Crumbs'' Krause as a man with a plan - and a donut.
</P>
<P>
   If we postpone its trip into Jerry's jowls for a few moments,
our donut can represent the points Krause usually scores with
cry-hard Chicago fans.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan shows promise. The plan has legs. The plan has
invited the Windy City to inhale and pause since the biggest Mike
of all bagged his last jumper in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the plan: Just demolish it (team) and they (free agents)
will come.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so Krause - personnel dictator of the Chicago Bulls - hardly
cuts a romantic path to rival the rah-rah theatrics of Kevin
Costner. If he chose to wear a helmet through this minefield of
criticism, the funny, little rascal (Krause, not Costner) could use
a hammock as a chin strap.
</P>
<P>
   But Krause also should receive some applause for dragging the
Bulls back to the curb of eventual contention.
</P>
<P>
   Krause will have enough cap room this summer to handle Siamese
twins and has banked four first-round selections in the next two
drafts. One of those was acquired from Golden State in last week's
three-cornered deal that sent Toni Kukoc to Philly. The pick
originally was linked to Michael Jordan's Washington Wizards, who
will keep it if the selection falls among this season's top three.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, the Bulls have it - without restrictions -
for the 2001 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's conceivable that it could be the No. 1 pick in the 2001
draft,'' said Krause, taking a big swing at MJ's rebuilding skills
while speaking at last Wednesday's Goodbye Kukoc press conference.
</P>
<P>
   As for the seduction of two top-shelf free agents to team up
with hot rookies Elton Brand and Ron Artest, Krause said. ``We will
be out there (market) and out there with force. We plan to sell
free agents on the fact that Chicago is the greatest sports city in
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Center isn't Noah's Ark, but it does know how to
handle reign.
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   Commish Isiah Thomas spent part of Friday in nearby Gary, Ind.,
where he plans to create another franchise for his beloved CBA. The
Gary Steelheads would be the 10th CBA team, although Thomas - who
purchased the other nine for $10 million - is attempting to buy the
USBL and IBA in his plan to create a baseball-style minor league.
... ``I always promised Toni (Kukoc) that I'd never trade him to a
bad team,'' said Krause, who dangled the 6-foot-11 forward in front
of the Clippers before the draft last summer. ... The Detroit
Pistons' main bargaining chip in their bid to acquire inside help
before the Feb. 24 trading deadline has been starting point guard
Lindsey Hunter. ... University of Minnesota sophomore center Joel
Przybilla (7-1) was suspended last week over academic
transgressions, and has been scouting for an agent to steer him
into the lottery. Przybilla, an accomplished shot-blocker with very
raw ball skills, had 33 points and 14 rebounds in his last Gopher
appearance - a victory over Indiana. ...
</P>
<P>
   The latest ``next Shaquille O'Neal'' is Eddy Curry, a 6-11,
270-pound junior at Thornwood High in Chicago's south suburbs.
According to one NBA scout, Curry ``is an almost frightening
package of strength and agility, when his age is considered.''
According to the hoop grapevine, Curry may skip college and declare
for the draft after his senior year. ... Clippers assistant coach
Dennis Johnson said younger brother Joey, a skywalking legend in
his days at Banning High, had a 52-inch vertical. If you're
skeptical, it only means you never saw Joey play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
