<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2313 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-SC-REPUBS-ART-840(2TA     02-19 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-REPUBS-ART-840(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGE
</HEADLINE>
  
 BUSH CLAIMS VICTORY IN SOUTH CAROLINA AS McCAIN VOWS TO CONTINUE (ART ADV:  Photos  NYT1-5 and NYT26 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Gov. George W. Bush pronounced himself the
victor in the South Carolina primary Saturday, reclaiming his spot
as the unmistakable front-runner for the Republican presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain called Bush Saturday evening to concede the
race. But the senator vowed to persevere as his advisers insisted
that the governor's conservative stands would not play as well in
the states ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Riding a record primary turnout, Bush rallied Republicans across
the state, undermining McCain's efforts to attract independents and
Democrats like those who helped McCain win convincingly in New
Hampshire on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited and energized,'' Bush said in his hotel suite.
``This is a big victory. This campaign ignited and united the
Republican base.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's victory was wide and deep; he captured the majority of
nearly every demographic group. Most significant, Republicans
rallied to him in large numbers. And the reformer mantle that Bush
appropriated from McCain after the senator's stunning triumph in
New Hampshire 19 days ago paid off. Voters told pollsters Saturday
that they liked Bush's reform message and they suggested that
McCain was too much of an outsider.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had staked his prospects on the expectation that
independents and Democrats would flood to the polls and support him
overwhelmingly. In fact, estimates based on surveys of voters found
that turnout was heavy, and may have doubled the 276,000 who voted
in the primary here four years ago. And independents and Democrats
did turn out in larger numbers than in 1996, and those who did
largely backed McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people heard my message loud and clear,'' a jubilant Bush
said in an interview Saturday night with CNN. Conceding that his
campaign in New Hampshire was lackluster, he said, ``I did better
as a candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said McCain had called to congratulate him. ``He was
gracious,'' he said. ``After tonight, it's going to be a good
contest. I think I'm going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the polls closed, a jubilant and no doubt relieved,
Bush attributed his victory to his belief that his reform message
had sunk in. ``Early in the primary season, I got defined,'' he
told reporters. ``I told people I wasn't going to let that happen
in South Carolina.'' He added, ``My message, that I'm a reformer
with results, has taken hold.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was particularly welcomed by Bush because before New
Hampshire he was as much as 20 points ahead of McCain in polls
here, but more recently the race was neck and neck, with the
senator even outpacing Bush in some surveys.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's advisers, already looking to the next contests,
asserted that Bush's hardline conservative message in South
Carolina would put off voters as the race turns quickly on Tuesday
to primaries in Michigan and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ralph Reed and Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell ought to be
congratulated,'' said John Weaver, McCain's political director.
``He ran the kind of campaign he needed to win in South Carolina.
But that's not the kind of campaign you need to win the nomination
_ and certainly not the general election.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a telling concession, Rep. Lindsey Graham, McCain's
most prominent supporter in this state, lamented how poorly the
senator had performed among Republicans. ``Our base just fell
apart,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By appearing to win comfortably here, Bush is better positioned
in Michigan and Arizona, the senator's home state. McCain now faces
enormous pressure to show that his win in New Hampshire was not an
anomaly. But the voting here was particularly distressing for
McCain because South Carolina was one of the few remaining states
where independents and Democrats could vote in the primary. Now,
most of the voting is in states where only Republicans can
participate; and in many of those states Bush has the backing of
the governors.
</P>
<P>
   Though he limped out of New Hampshire, Bush engineered a
comeback here by displaying a scrappy determination to work for the
nomination that was never apparent in the earlier contests.
Throughout last year, Bush swamped his rivals in the polls _
effortlessly it seemed _ and forced most of them to quit the race.
Had McCain won South Carolina, that might have given him an
important lift that could have led some Bush backers to begin to
defect. Yet Bush's conquest came at a price: He overwhelmed McCain
by pouring more than $3 million in an advertising blitz, and in so
doing continued to deplete what had been a flush treasury. McCain's
threat also forced Bush to abandon his long-promised posture of
never stooping to attack commercials.
</P>
<P>
   And, in appealing to conservatives in this state on issues
ranging from abortion to whether the Confederate flag should fly
over the state Capitol, Bush took a sharp turn to the right. He
abandoned his strategy of hewing to the middle of the road, a move
that McCain's advisers were quick to note Saturday night could
haunt the governor in a general election.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   But it seemed clear that his barrage of commercials worked to
Bush's advantage. Of the voters who were interviewed Saturday by
the Voter News Service, a consortium of television networks and the
Associated Press, about a third said they waited until the last
week or so to decide who to vote for, and most of them backed Bush.
Voters were more likely to say that McCain had unfairly attacked
Bush than they were to say that Bush was the one attacking McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In a heartening sign to Bush as the voting moves to a more
varied electorate, Bush won the majority of support of nearly every
demographic group, including men, women, rich and poor, young and
old. Even veterans _ whom McCain had targeted in an all-out turnout
drive _ split their vote between McCain and Bush. More than a third
of voters said they considered themselves members of the religious
right, and more than two-thirds of those voters backed Bush. If
religious conservatives were removed from the mix, McCain would
barely have won.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that Bush's drumbeat of reform and
leadership, as well his emphasis on moral values, meant a lot when
voters decided who to support.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush and McCain were viewed as reformers, Bush was seen
by voters as more of one. Voters were not convinced that McCain has
been true to his word on the issue of campaign finance, a subject
Bush hammered McCain on in his advertising. Nearly half the voters
said McCain says on thing but does another on campaign finance _
and they voted overwhelmingly for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what issue played the greatest role in their decision,
voters said it was moral values, and they mostly backed Bush. Among
those who cited Social Security and Medicare, McCain was more
popular. But the issue of tax cuts was low on the list of voters'
priorities, even though Bush made it a centerpiece of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush succeeded in being portrayed as a reformer, McCain
was viewed as a man who stands up for his beliefs. That is the
character trait that voters said they cared most about, and more
than have of those voters backed McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, voters said they considered Bush more of a leader _ and
a more potent rival against the Democrats in November.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, Bush's chief strategist, attributed the results
Saturday to a return to the roots of 1994 gubernatorial campaign,
when Bush talked about reforms he favored _ and spoke in specific
terms. He also said voters were impressed with a tougher, more
assertive Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of these guys are going to come out of here with roughly
equivalent positives and negatives, and yet Bush is going to come
out of here with a substantial win,'' Rove said. ``And I think it's
because people looked at him and saw how he handled adversity, saw
how he passed through this test, and liked what they saw.'' He
added, ``People wanted to see, if you care about something, are you
somebody who is going to fight for it?''
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-eight percent of voters in the primary were white, more
than half were men and more than four in 10 were over the age of
60. Nearly half said they had college degrees; three in 10 served
in the military. Blacks were virtually nonexistent in the voting,
even though in general elections in 1996 and 1998 they made up a
quarter of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The voters here are more conservative than most; nearly a
quarter described themselves as very conservative, and another four
in 10 called themselves somewhat conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly six in 10 of the voters Saturday want abortion to be
against the law to varying degrees and they voted heavily for Bush.
Nearly six in 10 said they wanted abortion to either be always
illegal or mostly illegal, and nearly two-thirds of them voted for
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   After his most spirited, jam-packed week on the campaign trail
to date, Bush made only two public appearances Saturday, dropping
by Tommy's Country Ham House in Spartanburg for breakfast and then
visiting a nearby polling site at an elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to come out of this state feeling great,'' Bush said
to a dense huddle of reporters who surrounded him outside the
elementary school before the polls closed. ``When you win a state
like South Carolina, you get a bump.''
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter reminded Bush that he had also voiced optimism
before New Hampshire, he said, ``I was optimistic in New Hampshire.
``I'm really optimistic today.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's extremely good cheer was reflected in a slightly
different answer he gave minutes later to the question of what he
felt about the outcome in his gut.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my gut,'' Bush said, ``I feel three pancakes and bacon.''
That was what he had eaten at his previous stop at Tommy's Country
Ham House. Inside, Bush mingled merrily with voters.
</P>
<P>
   But he had a different kind of experience outside the
restaurant. A protester with the People for the Ethical Treatment
of Animals, who was dressed as a pig, drove by in a white dump
truck and deposited a pile of cow manure on the street near Bush,
and was then carted off by the police as he shouted, ``Meat is
murder!''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he thought of the protest group, Bush said, ``I'm
glad I had my bacon for breakfast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
