<HEADLINE>
GORE SEES SOUTH CAROLINA AS VICTORY FOR DEMOCRATS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Mass. _ Even before results of the South Carolina
primary were known, Vice President Al Gore declared the day a
victory for Democrats, saying that Gov. George W. Bush and Sen.
John McCain had badly hurt each other in the hotly contested
Republican race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty clear that they have done a lot of damage to one
another,'' Gore said at a news conference after a
town-meeting-style campaign event here.
</P>
<P>
   He also harshly criticized the two Republicans for not
supporting the removal of the Confederate battle flag from the
South Carolina statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither of the two major Republican candidates had the guts to
take on bigotry and call for the removal of the Confederate flag,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore brushed aside questions about his Democratic opponent,
former Sen. Bill Bradley, whose campaign has been stumbling lately,
and instead used the interest in the vote in South Carolina to hit
the Republicans on abortion, education and the environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
