</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-BUSH0220-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A nap, a run and a victory for Bush
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Judging from his grin, Gov. George W. Bush's
key political adviser, Karl Rove, knew it was all over five hours
before the polls closed in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Cell phone glued to his ear, Rove walked into a restaurant at
the Columbia Sheraton, leaned over a table of reporters grabbing
lunch and dropped the first exit polls numbers: 52 percent Bush, 42
percent McCain.
</P>
<P>
   From that moment on, the Sheraton, ground zero for the Bush
campaign, buzzed with the heady sensation of victory. The
jubilation was large part relief, an expression of how deep the
worry had been and how much was riding on this primary. Would Bush
emerge with his frontrunner crown golden or would he see it all
topple, one domino at a time, as voters here and in upcoming
primary states decided he wasn't born to win the White House after
all?
</P>
<P>
   If Bush was anxious, he didn't show it. He made a prediction in
the morning that would ring overwhelmingly true hours later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to win,'' he told reporters trailing him
through Tommy's Country House, in Greenville. ``The last couple of
days there's been an unusual amount of enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   The enthusiasm was palpable hours later in the Sheraton ballroom
where the victory celebration included three fully- stocked bars, a
hot buffet (main course, hot dogs) and a country band. Brown County
Commissioner Steve Adams was one of the revelers. He arrived in
Columbia Tuesday and joined a band of about 30 Texans here to help
get out the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've built signs,'' he said. ``We were waving them out at
intersections. They've used us about as good as you can use help
and it's working out. These numbers are incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   David Miner, a North Carolina state representative and Bush
Pioneer _ one of the fundraisers who has netted at least $100,000
for Bush _ didn't want to use the word relieved to describe how he
was feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident that the governor will be the nominee of the
Republican party and that he will go on to defeat Al Gore in
November,'' he said. ``The only concern was the 18-point deficit we
had in New Hampshire and the coverage McCain was getting.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush got the news that his chances looked good at about 1:40
p.m., when Rove came to see him in his suite. Rove said his boss
was in bed ``in near total darkness,'' getting ready to take a nap.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'Great, will they hold?''' Rove told reporters later.
</P>
<P>
   Assured that victory was likely, Bush said, ``I'm going to take
my power nap.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he went running along the Congaree River with media
advisor Mark McKinnon and resumed the work on his victory speech
begun earlier that day. Speechwriter Mike Gerson and policy chief
Josh Bolten had emailed ideas in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Communications director Karen Hughes was taking a nap when the
phone rang and she was summoned to Bush's suite. There she found
Bush, still red-faced from his run, dressed in shorts and a T-shirt
with a towel draped around his neck. Also there were Laura Bush,
Rove, aides Ari Fleischer and Mindy Tucker and finance chief Don
Evans, the man most responsible for Bush's record-breaking $70
million in contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was steady,'' Hughes said. ``He was just as gracious in
victory as he was in defeat in New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe he knew he wouldn't have to face defeat again _ at
least not in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   At a local pancake house Bush spent about 45 minutes shaking
hands, holding babies and signing his name to everything from
folded newspapers, scrap paper and waitresses' order pads. Then he
sat down to a breakfast of pancakes with butter and syrup, bacon,
coffee and orange juice. Laura Bush had grits and a biscuit,
scrambled egg and ham sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   He later called the unusually high voter turnout, ``good news.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole focus has been on increasing the turnout, convincing
Republican and like-minded Democrats to come out and support us,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy worked.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
