<SLUG> BC-R-SC-REPUBS-ART-840(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING for all needing)  
 BUSH CLAIMS VICTORY IN SOUTH CAROLINA AS McCAIN VOWS TO CONTINUE (ART ADV:  Photos  NYT1-5 and NYT26 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Gov. George W. Bush pronounced himself the
victor in the South Carolina primary Saturday, reclaiming his spot
as the unmistakable front-runner for the Republican presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain called Bush Saturday evening to concede the
race. But the senator vowed to persevere as his advisers insisted
that the governor's conservative stands would not play as well in
the states ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Riding a record primary turnout, Bush rallied Republicans across
the state, undermining McCain's efforts to attract independents and
Democrats like those who helped McCain win convincingly in New
Hampshire on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited and energized,'' Bush said in his hotel suite.
``This is a big victory. This campaign ignited and united the
Republican base.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's victory was wide and deep; he captured the majority of
nearly every demographic group. Most significant, Republicans
rallied to him in large numbers. And the reformer mantle that Bush
appropriated from McCain after the senator's stunning triumph in
New Hampshire 19 days ago paid off. Voters told pollsters Saturday
that they liked Bush's reform message and they suggested that
McCain was too much of an outsider.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had staked his prospects on the expectation that
independents and Democrats would flood to the polls and support him
overwhelmingly. In fact, estimates based on surveys of voters found
that turnout was heavy, and may have doubled the 276,000 who voted
in the primary here four years ago. And independents and Democrats
did turn out in larger numbers than in 1996, and those who did
largely backed McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people heard my message loud and clear,'' a jubilant Bush
said in an interview Saturday night with CNN. Conceding that his
campaign in New Hampshire was lackluster, he said, ``I did better
as a candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said McCain had called to congratulate him. ``He was
gracious,'' he said. ``After tonight, it's going to be a good
contest. I think I'm going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the polls closed, a jubilant and no doubt relieved,
Bush attributed his victory to his belief that his reform message
had sunk in. ``Early in the primary season, I got defined,'' he
told reporters. ``I told people I wasn't going to let that happen
in South Carolina.'' He added, ``My message, that I'm a reformer
with results, has taken hold.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was particularly welcomed by Bush because before New
Hampshire he was as much as 20 points ahead of McCain in polls
here, but more recently the race was neck and neck, with the
senator even outpacing Bush in some surveys.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's advisers, already looking to the next contests,
asserted that Bush's hardline conservative message in South
Carolina would put off voters as the race turns quickly on Tuesday
to primaries in Michigan and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ralph Reed and Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell ought to be
congratulated,'' said John Weaver, McCain's political director.
``He ran the kind of campaign he needed to win in South Carolina.
But that's not the kind of campaign you need to win the nomination
_ and certainly not the general election.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a telling concession, Rep. Lindsey Graham, McCain's
most prominent supporter in this state, lamented how poorly the
senator had performed among Republicans. ``Our base just fell
apart,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By appearing to win comfortably here, Bush is better positioned
in Michigan and Arizona, the senator's home state. McCain now faces
enormous pressure to show that his win in New Hampshire was not an
anomaly. But the voting here was particularly distressing for
McCain because South Carolina was one of the few remaining states
where independents and Democrats could vote in the primary. Now,
most of the voting is in states where only Republicans can
participate; and in many of those states Bush has the backing of
the governors.
</P>
<P>
   Though he limped out of New Hampshire, Bush engineered a
comeback here by displaying a scrappy determination to work for the
nomination that was never apparent in the earlier contests.
Throughout last year, Bush swamped his rivals in the polls _
effortlessly it seemed _ and forced most of them to quit the race.
Had McCain won South Carolina, that might have given him an
important lift that could have led some Bush backers to begin to
defect. Yet Bush's conquest came at a price: He overwhelmed McCain
by pouring more than $3 million in an advertising blitz, and in so
doing continued to deplete what had been a flush treasury. McCain's
threat also forced Bush to abandon his long-promised posture of
never stooping to attack commercials.
</P>
<P>
   And, in appealing to conservatives in this state on issues
ranging from abortion to whether the Confederate flag should fly
over the state Capitol, Bush took a sharp turn to the right. He
abandoned his strategy of hewing to the middle of the road, a move
that McCain's advisers were quick to note Saturday night could
haunt the governor in a general election.
</P>
