<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2321 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-SC-MAIN-0220-COX     02-19 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-MAIN-0220-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush gains momentum with key victory in South Carolina
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C _ In the most critical win of his political
career, Texas Gov. George W. Bush reinvigorated his presidential
campaign Saturday by sacking Arizona Sen. John McCain in South
Carolina's GOP primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is counting on the big win _ exit polls indicated about a
14 point margin _ to help him regain momentum sapped from his
high-dollar campaign by McCain's surprise landslide victory in the
Feb. 1 New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   Commentator Alan Keyes finished a distant third and was not a
significant factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited and energized,'' Bush said as he watched election
returns in his hotel room where McCain called to concede eight
minutes after the polls closed. ``This campaign ignited and united
the Republican base.''
</P>
<P>
   By early afternoon, Bush, just before his afternoon nap and run,
was told by top strategist Karl Rove that South Carolina has
performed as the ``firewall'' Bush was counting on to block the
McCain surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have now won four of the five contests: Iowa, Alaska,
Delaware and South Carolina, and it puts us in good shape now,''
Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   University of South Carolina political scientist Blease Graham,
who has been watching politics here since 1970, was surprised by
the ease of Bush's victory. ``McCain might keep running, but I
really think this makes an uphill battle even steeper for him,''
Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   But the McCain camp believes Saturday's victory by Bush, which
included a heavy boost from religious conservatives, will be
hard-pressed to re-create in Michigan on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether he can run as a Dixiecrat in Michigan,
but we'll find out,'' said John Weaver, McCain's political
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I congratulate Governor Bush on his victory here and wish him
a happy celebration and a good night's rest,'' McCain said at a
post-election rally. ``He's going to need it, my friends, for we
have just begun to fight and I cannot wait for the next round. I'm
going to fight with every ounce of strength that I have, but I'm
going to keep fighting clean. I'm going to keep fighting fair. And
I'm going to keep fighting the battle of ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, McCain raised concerns about the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidation of Republican primary polling places across South
Carolina caused voter confusion and prompted McCain to demand an
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign complained that precincts that were supposed
to be open were closed. The Arizona senator demanded ``a full
investigation'' after discovering the Pond Branch voting precinct
in Greenville was closed.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, NAACP President Kweisi Mfume said representatives
of the civil rights group had received complaints Saturday morning
that some polling places in heavily black areas were closed. He
said he would send a representative to South Carolina to
investigate the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to take a look at these complaints to see if any
violations occurred,'' Mfume said at the NAACP's annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Bush believes the win in South Carolina _ a state that has
backed the eventual nominee since it began holding primaries in
1980 _ will relegate New Hampshire back to its traditional role as
political freak show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell down in the snow,'' Bush said of his New Hampshire
loss. ``I knocked the snow off my suit and came down here.''
</P>
<P>
   The theory will face quick tests. Voters in Michigan and Arizona
go to the polls Tuesday. While McCain is favored in his home state,
a Bush win in Michigan could deeply tarnish the sparkle of his sole
remaining real challenger for the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates had reason to expect good things for them in
South Carolina, where 37 delegates were up for grabs. For Bush,
it's a state that traditionally goes with the establishment
candidate and where his father always ran well.
</P>
<P>
   For war-hero McCain, it's a state with a high veteran population
and a GOP primary open to all, with no Democratic primary. In New
Hampshire, Democrats and independents were a major part of the
McCain coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Voter News Service exit polls here showed that 30 percent of the
voters identified themselves as independents, and McCain was backed
by 61 percent of them. But Bush built up a huge advantage (68
percent to 26 percent) among Republicans, as well as 67 percent
among those identifying themselves as members of the ``religious
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's big turnout was seen as a potential boost for McCain.
But, according to early results from exit polls, Bush picked up a
third of the Democratic and independent vote, a much better result
than he had in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polling also showed 61 percent of the voters viewed Bush as
the ``real reformer,'' compared to 54 percent who said McCain
deserves that tag.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's primary was only the second contest between Bush and
McCain. The Texas governor won the Iowa caucuses and Delaware
primary, but McCain campaigned in neither state. McCain won big _
by 19 points _ in the New Hampshire primary that stripped Bush of
his prohibitive frontrunner status and wiped out his lead in South
Carolina polls.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's camp says it will now take the fight to Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign manager, Rick Davis, told reporters, ``We'll
be up and running hard when we wake up in Michigan. Clearly, we're
going to have to sell really hard and really fast our reformer's
message.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding McCain's defeat, Davis told reporters, ``If it were
not for the massive negative campaign run against us, primarily in
the religious conservative community, we would have carried the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush disagreed. ``I think it's more than social conservatives''
that carried the day in South Carolina,'' he said. ``I united the
party. I brought elements of the party together. I convinced the
people of this state that I have an agenda that is positive and
hopeful and that I'm a reformer who has good results when given a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
