<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S.C. Bush supporters seek to limit who votes
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Republican state legislators angered by John
McCain's appeal to Democratic and independent voters are pushing a
bill to end open primaries in South Carolina. Most of the sponsors
of the legislation in the state's House are supporters of George W.
Bush. An identical bill was also introduced in the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something is wrong with the process,'' said GOP state Rep.
Harry Cato, a sponsor of the bill introduced Wednesday amid growing
concern by Bush strategists.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's backers accused Democrats of encouraging party members to
vote for McCain, figuring he'd be an easier opponent in November
for likely Democratic presidential nominee Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The active Republicans and the active Democrats have always
respected one another's primaries,'' said Cato, a Bush supporter.
``That way, the independents out there can vote either way.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I do not think I've seen that in this primary,'' he said.
``Each party ought to be able to nominate its candidate without
interference.''
</P>
<P>
   But another of the bill's sponsors, Republican Tracy Edge, said
the partisanship that spurred the bill will probably make it a hard
sell in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bush were getting the (Democratic and independent) votes,
nobody would be crying foul,'' said Edge, a McCain supporter.
``There is some hypocrisy going on.''
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina's GOP adopted the open primary 20 years ago at
the urging of Republican strategist Lee Atwater. He convinced
leaders that they could build the party in South Carolina and
bolster its national importance by holding an open primary earlier
than other states.
</P>
<P>
   It worked in 1980, as Democrats and independents helped
Republicans elect Ronald Reagan as president. But McCain's adoption
of the strategy drew criticism from Bush's backers, prompting
charges of hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   In a Saturday editorial, The State newspaper in Columbia, which
has endorsed Bush, called open primaries ``an important tool for
building the Republican Party in South Carolina. It is hypocritical
to say they are a bad idea now.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hendrix, executive director of the South Carolina Election
Commission, said he believes voters would resist legislation
requiring them to register by party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thought is that it is not anybody's business whether they
are a Republican, Democrat, independent or whatever,'' Hendrix
said.
</P>
<P>
   University of South Carolina political scientist Blease Graham
said he believes that sentiment will hurt the bill in the
Legislature. ``The open primary speaks to the sense of the South
Carolina voters being recognized,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What core Republicans have to do is build a coalition with
independents,'' Graham said. ``While that may wreck the unity of
the South Carolina Republican Party, it probably a good tactic
nationwide.''
</P>
<P>
   In Columbia, voters expressed mixed views Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Describing himself as an independent, Stanley Dubinsky said he
felt entitled to vote in the Republican primary. He voted for
McCain, but said he's not sure whether he'd vote Republican or
Democrat in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is sort of like free trade,'' Dubinksy, 47, said as he left
the polling place. ``The more open the process, the healthier it is
for everybody involved.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fred Moore, a Republican supporter of Bush, said he favors
an end to the open primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand the validity of having a Republican primary
or a Democratic primary if you are allowing crossovers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
