<HEADER>
A2323 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-R-SC-REPUBS-ART-2NDTA     02-19 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SC-REPUBS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (REPEATING for all needing) 
CHARLESTON, S.C.: general election. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But it seemed clear that his barrage of commercials worked to
Bush's advantage. Of the voters who were interviewed Saturday by
the Voter News Service, a consortium of television networks and the
Associated Press, about a third said they waited until the last
week or so to decide who to vote for, and most of them backed Bush.
Voters were more likely to say that McCain had unfairly attacked
Bush than they were to say that Bush was the one attacking McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In a heartening sign to Bush as the voting moves to a more
varied electorate, Bush won the majority of support of nearly every
demographic group, including men, women, rich and poor, young and
old. Even veterans _ whom McCain had targeted in an all-out turnout
drive _ split their vote between McCain and Bush. More than a third
of voters said they considered themselves members of the religious
right, and more than two-thirds of those voters backed Bush. If
religious conservatives were removed from the mix, McCain would
barely have won.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that Bush's drumbeat of reform and
leadership, as well his emphasis on moral values, meant a lot when
voters decided who to support.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush and McCain were viewed as reformers, Bush was seen
by voters as more of one. Voters were not convinced that McCain has
been true to his word on the issue of campaign finance, a subject
Bush hammered McCain on in his advertising. Nearly half the voters
said McCain says on thing but does another on campaign finance _
and they voted overwhelmingly for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what issue played the greatest role in their decision,
voters said it was moral values, and they mostly backed Bush. Among
those who cited Social Security and Medicare, McCain was more
popular. But the issue of tax cuts was low on the list of voters'
priorities, even though Bush made it a centerpiece of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush succeeded in being portrayed as a reformer, McCain
was viewed as a man who stands up for his beliefs. That is the
character trait that voters said they cared most about, and more
than have of those voters backed McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, voters said they considered Bush more of a leader _ and
a more potent rival against the Democrats in November.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, Bush's chief strategist, attributed the results
Saturday to a return to the roots of 1994 gubernatorial campaign,
when Bush talked about reforms he favored _ and spoke in specific
terms. He also said voters were impressed with a tougher, more
assertive Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of these guys are going to come out of here with roughly
equivalent positives and negatives, and yet Bush is going to come
out of here with a substantial win,'' Rove said. ``And I think it's
because people looked at him and saw how he handled adversity, saw
how he passed through this test, and liked what they saw.'' He
added, ``People wanted to see, if you care about something, are you
somebody who is going to fight for it?''
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-eight percent of voters in the primary were white, more
than half were men and more than four in 10 were over the age of
60. Nearly half said they had college degrees; three in 10 served
in the military. Blacks were virtually nonexistent in the voting,
even though in general elections in 1996 and 1998 they made up a
quarter of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The voters here are more conservative than most; nearly a
quarter described themselves as very conservative, and another four
in 10 called themselves somewhat conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly six in 10 of the voters Saturday want abortion to be
against the law to varying degrees and they voted heavily for Bush.
Nearly six in 10 said they wanted abortion to either be always
illegal or mostly illegal, and nearly two-thirds of them voted for
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   After his most spirited, jam-packed week on the campaign trail
to date, Bush made only two public appearances Saturday, dropping
by Tommy's Country Ham House in Spartanburg for breakfast and then
visiting a nearby polling site at an elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to come out of this state feeling great,'' Bush said
to a dense huddle of reporters who surrounded him outside the
elementary school before the polls closed. ``When you win a state
like South Carolina, you get a bump.''
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter reminded Bush that he had also voiced optimism
before New Hampshire, he said, ``I was optimistic in New Hampshire.
``I'm really optimistic today.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's extremely good cheer was reflected in a slightly
different answer he gave minutes later to the question of what he
felt about the outcome in his gut.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my gut,'' Bush said, ``I feel three pancakes and bacon.''
That was what he had eaten at his previous stop at Tommy's Country
Ham House. Inside, Bush mingled merrily with voters.
</P>
<P>
   But he had a different kind of experience outside the
restaurant. A protester with the People for the Ethical Treatment
of Animals, who was dressed as a pig, drove by in a white dump
truck and deposited a pile of cow manure on the street near Bush,
and was then carted off by the police as he shouted, ``Meat is
murder!''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he thought of the protest group, Bush said, ``I'm
glad I had my bacon for breakfast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
