u p BC-SC-REPUBS-TURNOUT-1ST     02-19 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-REPUBS-TURNOUT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAROLINIANS, HOPING FOR CHANCE TO PLAY KINGMAKER, FLOCK TO SUPPORT
BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (UPDATES with complete rewrite) 
 (rk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAK GROVE, S.C. _ The sidewalk leading to the Oak Grove Civic
Club is about 30 feet long, and at 7 a.m. it was packed with people
waiting for the doors to open so they could vote. Unfortunately for
Sen. John McCain, most of them were there to vote for Gov. George
W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Election workers at this suburban Columbia polling place, and at
many others around the state, said they had never seen such a heavy
turnout for a Republican presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   That large number of voters was supposed to benefit McCain,
because of his support among independents and Democrats. What had
not been widely predicted, however, was that the turnout would be
so great in polling places like this one, a heavily Republican
suburb that cast twice as many votes for Bob Dole in 1996 as for
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   People here said they showed up in such large numbers not
because they dislike McCain, but because they wanted to nominate a
man they saw as having the best chance of defeating Vice President
Al Gore, who they assume will be the Democratic nominee, and whom
they generally despise.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush is a decent, moral man, and he can win,'' said
Margie Coker, who was wearing a T-shirt that said, ``Yes, I believe
in God.'' Elizabeth Whitehead, a friend, added, ``He'll make the
best president of the bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 40 percent of the precinct's 2,681 registered voters
showed up to vote Saturday, said Grady Merritt, the Republican
chairman of the precinct, who said he could not recall a similar
turnout in a primary. That kind of enthusiasm was spread throughout
the state, where there were long lines at hundreds of polling
places _ mostly in the heavily Republican areas where Bush did
best.
</P>
<P>
   J. Sam Daniels, the executive director of the state Republican
Party, said the overall turnout was unprecedented, possibly as much
as 400,000. Exit polls suggested the number could even approach
500,000. In the 1996 primary, 276,000 people voted.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dire predictions of Bush supporters, the throng of
voters was not due to Democrats causing political mischief. Surveys
of voters showed that fewer than 10 percent were Democrats, about a
third independents, and about 60 percent Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   McCain clearly succeeded in adding attention and excitement to
the race _ nearly a third of those who voted said they had never
before participated in a Republican primary. But he was not able to
draw enough crossovers to counterbalance an enormously heavy
turnout of Republican Party regulars.
</P>
<P>
   That was clear, for example, in Forest Acres, a suburb of
Columbia that is mainly Republican but has large numbers of
independents and Reagan Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The turnout there was so heavy early in the day that nearly a
quarter of the 1,600 registered voters in one neighborhood had
voted by 10:20 a.m. But most of the people standing in line at
midday said they were voting for Bush. A neighborhood like this was
crucial to McCain's hopes, but not enough Democrats or independents
voted.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a lawsuit brought earlier this month by Democrats,
who charged that the Republican Party had closed many polling
places in black and other Democratic areas in 1996, there were
hundreds more polling places open this year than ever before. The
suit was settled earlier this week when the Republican Party agreed
to provide volunteers or pay state workers to open every possible
polling place. But the large number of inexperienced poll workers
caused problems throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   In Greenville, a conservative bastion of Bush support, 21
polling places were closed because volunteers failed to show up,
Daniels said. Infuriated members of the McCain campaign said some
of the precincts were in Democratic areas and charged that they had
been deliberately kept closed to suppress McCain votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had thought the court had clearly dictated that all polling
sites should be open,'' McCain said on his bus Saturday morning.
``I believe there should be a full investigation. I don't know what
to say. It's so disappointing to hear this.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels said only three of the closed polls were in black or
Democratic areas.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Greenville, however, there were few reports of
problems. In Lexington County, a suburban area west of Columbia,
voting was substantial even in Democratic areas. At the Brookland
United Methodist Church in West Columbia, a traditionally
Democratic area, workers had anticipated about 139 voters for the
whole day, based on past turnouts in Republican primaries. But by
noon, there had already been 120 voters.
</P>
<P>
   At the North Bamberg precinct 50 miles south of Columbia, Ronny
Maxwell, the Republican volunteer poll manager, said at 1 p.m. that
nearly 300 people had voted, but he only had enough ballot slips
for 399 voters. He had to call the countyan to deliver 100
more ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout was much lower in black areas, although there was a
trickle of voters in the community center in Martin Luther King Jr.
Park near downtown Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   According to polls, only 1 percent of the voters in the state
were black, although black voters constitute about 25 percent of
the state's electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters said they were excited by all the attention given
the race, and the sense that their decision could make or break
either of the two leading candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a change, it got a little exciting around here,'' said
Jerry Bradley, a builder who voted Saturday afternoon at Oak Grove
accompanied by his young daughter. ``I never really felt like I had
much of a choice before.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he enjoyed thinking about it for a while, and then
settled on Bush.
</P>
</TEXT>
