<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-ADVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD FRICTION CREATES HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ As much as they like to disagree, drivers
of the Chevrolet Monte Carlo and Pontiac Grand Prix seem to be in
accord about one thing: Sunday's 42d running of the Daytona 500 is
not going to be a fair fight against the Fords.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since pole-sitter Dale Jarrett and outside pole Ricky Rudd
dominated qualifications in their Ford Tauruses, the General Motors
camp has complained long and loud about NASCAR's new shock/spring
rule.
</P>
<P>
   It claims the rule, implemented to smooth out the rough ride at
superspeedway venues through mandated shock and spring settings,
puts its cars at a competitive disadvantage against the Fords. Dale
Earnhardt, the seven-time NASCAR Winston Cup champion, was incensed
about the way his car handled in traffic in his 11th-place finish
in Thursday's Gatorade Twin 125s; he fumed that Ford's box-to-wire
victories in both qualifiers ``was the worst racing I've seen at
Daytona in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   GM drivers fear Sunday's race will be a complete drag.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such an unbalanced field right now,'' said Richard
Childress, Earnhardt's car owner. ``We told (NASCAR officials) all
along this car has a lot of drag on it. We went to them and asked
them, and they've made their decision. We're just going to have to
go with what we've got. I've been in this business 30-something
years, and you're not going to overcome drag. The only thing that
will overcome drag is horsepower. We've got restrictor plates and
you can't get the horsepower through the restrictor plates.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Helton, NASCAR's chief operating officer, said NASCAR
was not about to make any changes to the shock/spring rule before
the Daytona 500, ``because we don't want to create a moving
target,'' he said. Further, they pointed to the racing that took
place in last Sunday's Bud Shootout as proof positive that Chevys
and Pontiacs could compete with the Fords.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have front springs, swaybar, trackbar, there are a lot of
things you can do to still help your car if it's not driving right,
so I really don't understand their complaint,'' said Jarrett, who
dented a rear bumper in a mishap during a Happy Hour practice
session Saturday. ``Half of it, it seems like they're blaming us
for their car having a lot of drag and, the last I checked, we
didn't build their cars. They submitted them. We worked on our cars
and made a good car.''
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Marlin led for much of the Shootout and was challenged
by Jeff Gordon, the defending Daytona 500 champion. But it was
Jarrett, who won the 25-lap qualifier in a runaway, who came from
the back of the pack with the aid of drafting help from Pontiac
driver Bobby Labonte to win on the last lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cars ride better, they're softer and bounce around,''
Gordon said. ``They're nothing like they were when they were
beating us up. They've gone from one extreme to the next. We need
to be somewhere in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that Chevys and Pontiacs are unable to negotiate
corners at full speed because of a push and, as a result, are
forced to lift on the throttle. When the GM cars are relegated to a
single-file draft, making it difficult to move up in the field, it
enables Fords to make a clean breakaway from the pack, such as the
one Bill Elliott made in his victory in the Twin 125s.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 20 laps into the race, the handling goes away where you
can't turn,'' Gordon said. ``The track warms up and the tires warm
up. You're just hanging on, and you have to lift. You just go up
there and wait for the car to run and try to keep your momentum and
try to stay on the throttle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time Daytona turns into a handling racetrack, you're going
to see a poor race.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, some would say, an unfair fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind going to a gunfight if you've got a Colt .45, but
I've got a .22 revolver,'' said Felix Sabates, the head of Team
Sabco. ``I figure, with my .22, I'm going to be able to get you
anyway. If you go to a gunfight and guys have bazookas and you've
got a wooden knife, that's not too good. Basically, they've got
bazookas and we've got wooden knives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
