</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-OLAZABAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLAZABAL REKINDLES DRIVE AND SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The situation was desperate enough in late 1999 that he took
himself out of the lineup at the Ryder Cup, but perhaps not as
severe as it was a few months earlier, when, he said, ``I was maybe
hitting three or four fairways.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, said Jose Maria Olazabal, things were not very good
in late 1998, either, unless you compared it with 1995-96, when he
couldn't play and wasn't sure he would ever walk again. That was
the low point.
</P>
<P>
   For the proud, determined Spaniard, physical and mental
challenges have made this difficult game even tougher, though his
spirits have never dimmed. He draws strength from within, from the
countless friends who have encouraged him, and from four glorious
days in Augusta, Ga., last April.
</P>
<P>
   ``The memories of hard times, what I had to go through in my
life. To be able to talk about this and be in position to do what I
like to do most _ play golf _ is very, very special,'' said
Olazabal, who overcame two years of foot problems and an inability
to drive the ball straight to win his second Masters in 1999. In
tribute to his courage, Olazabal was voted the Ben Hogan Award for
overcoming serious injury to contribute to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never forget that my entire life,'' he said. ``From the
very bottom of my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his Masters win in 1994 was special (``It is always
tougher to win that first major''), but the '99 triumph was more
enjoyable. And quite shocking. ``I was not playing very well and
was not confident,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Champions Dinner before the tournament, Gary Player
sensed something was wrong and approached Olazabal. Olazabal told
the truth: He wasn't playing well, and his confidence was low.
</P>
<P>
   Player, a three-time champion at Augusta and one of the true
sporting marvels of our time, is a man of many qualities, intensity
being near the top. He told Olazabal to trust his swing because it
was a great swing, and to believe in himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was spontaneous,'' said Olazabal, ``like you have a little
chat. Not long. Perhaps three to five minutes. But it was the way
he said it. Like he was a man on a mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal opened with a 70, then shot a 66, and everything seemed
to click.
</P>
<P>
   ``Player had built confidence in me, and it changed my
approach,'' said Olazabal, whose third-round 73 kept him in the
lead. When he went bogey-bogey-bogey starting at the third hole of
the final round, Olazabal turned to his caddie and said, ``I think
we're throwing this tournament away.'' Again, he dug deep. Again,
he overcame adversity.
</P>
<P>
   A birdie at the par-3 sixth stopped the bleeding. He got to the
turn with three straight pars, then shot 33 on the back for a
two-shot win. When Greg Norman rolled in an eagle putt at the 13th
to threaten Olazabal's lead, the Spaniard never blinked. He knocked
down his birdie putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely the turning point,'' said Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal rode out of Augusta with another green jacket, but some
old problems accompanied him. He played badly in ensuing weeks,
broke his hand in frustration at the US Open, then perhaps
exercised poor judgment by rushing back for the British Open. Never
a great driver, he got even worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no confidence. I just couldn't hit a fairway,'' he said,
at one point calling his Masters triumph ``an oasis in the
desert.''
</P>
<P>
   The woes plagued him throughout the rest of the season, and at
33, he still has much to learn.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he were resigned to a career of bad driving, he said,
``I will never accept that. I think I am pointed in the right
direction now. I have made a couple of changes in my swing, with my
grip. There is no reason why I cannot be a good driver.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Olazabal has played twice in Australia. His driving
wasn't bad, but his irons, he said, were awful. This week he will
be in Carlsbad, Calif., for the Andersen Consulting World Match
Play event, then he will play in the Dubai Desert Classic. Warmups
at The Players Championship and the BellSouth Classic will usher
him into Augusta, which should help rekindle his spirited game.
</P>
<P>
   Rising to the challenge
</P>
<P>
   For now, it will be the victory that ended Tiger Woods's streak,
but Phil Mickelson's effort at the Buick Invitational may go down
as the turning point in his career. As gifted as any player who has
come into the game in the last 25 years, Mickelson had lost much of
the spotlight to three players who arrived on the stage after he
did _ Woods, David Duval, Justin Leonard _ and increasingly he was
being asked not about his successes but his failures. Mickelson won
on Tour as an amateur in 1991 and through 1996 had nine victories.
And though he knocked off four more wins in 1997-99, Mickelson took
a back seat to Leonard (three wins, including a British Open and
TPC), Duval (11 wins, including a Tour Championship and TPC), and,
of course, Woods (15 wins, two majors). Unlike those players,
Mickelson had to face questions about his inability to hold it
together down the stretch, particularly in big events. His
final-round scoring average in 1999, for instance, was 72.5, 134th
on Tour, which prompted a reporter to ask Mickelson if there were
any reasons for it. ``I don't know, and I don't care,'' he snapped.
Much was made of his closing 65 at the NEC Invitational last
August, but overlooked was the fact that Mickelson bogeyed two of
the final three holes to lose by one to Woods. He also shot these
final-round numbers at marquee events in 1999: 78 at the Mercedes,
80 at Phoenix, 82 at TPC, 77 at the PGA Championship, 78 at the
American Express. Two weeks before the Buick, Mickelson led the
Phoenix Open standing on the 10th tee of the final round, then
proceeded to shoot 40 and tumble to T-10. Indeed, Mickelson had to
play with those thoughts in his head down the stretch at San Diego,
in addition to matching whatever Woods did in front of him, but he
was equal to the challenge and deserves credit. He conceded his
work ethic slipped a bit in 1999, but a more devoted practice
schedule ushered him into the new year, one he hopes can push him
back into the stifling spotlight to which he is accustomed . . .
Arnold Palmer on Woods: ``I marvel (at his) ability to release
through the ball. I have not seen a player _ maybe Nicklaus, maybe
Player, but I'm not sure if I've ever seen anyone _ release the
club through the ball with the clubhead speed that Tiger does.''
</P>
<P>
   Coast to coast
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that the Doral Open signaled the start of the PGA
Tour season, back when events out West were bypassed because of
their desert locales, celebrity fields, and small purses. That has
changed. The Buick Invitational had a decent field, and this week's
Nissan Open is jam-packed with the game's best. PGA Tour
commissioner Tim Finchem said recently he used to be asked all the
time about ideas for getting better players out West, but now he
faces questions about improving the first two stops in Florida _
the Doral and the Honda Classic. The best American players are
skipping the Doral, so the attractions will come from an
international pool, including defender Steve Elkington, Norman,
Jesper Parnevik, Vijay Singh, Ernie Els, Bernhard Langer, Nick
Price, and Retief Goosen, the South African who will be making a
rare start in the United States. Doral officials announced that
Nicklaus and John Daly are also committed, though most top
Americans are resting for the Bay Hill-TPC-Masters run . . . Part
of the problem, of course, is having so many options. Last week,
the Buick Invitational in San Diego attracted a nucleus of big
names, but so did the Australian Masters (Norman, Stuart Appleby,
Sergio Garcia, amateur sensation Aaron Baddeley), and the Malaysian
Open (Langer, Goosen, Padraig Harrington, Per-Ulrik Johansson) . .
. It isn't often that you shoot 82 and still make the cut, but
Robin Byrd did just that at the Australian Masters in Melbourne. He
got through the 36-hole cutoff with a 69, but fell back with a
74-75 weekend . . . While most of Europe's big names (Olazabal,
Harrington, Lee Westwood, Darren Clarke, Paul Lawrie, Miguel Angel
Jiminez) are either in the United States or preparing to be here
for the Andersen Consulting World Match Play event that starts
Wednesday, the Algarve Portuguese Open is going on with a field
devoid of stars. Ian Woosnam is one noteworthy entrant, and another
that raises interest is Ronan Rafferty. The Northern Irishman is
attempting a comeback at age 36 after missing nearly two years with
a variety of thumb and wrist problems . . . Onetime PGA Tour player
Bob Lohr had his own woes at last week's Buy.com event. The night
before the final round, he injured his right hand. He would have
withdrawn, but he would not have earned a paycheck if he did. So
Lohr basically played one-handed, shot 98, and finished last.
Still, he earned a check, and even though it was for just $1,200,
every penny counts in today's pro golf world.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the blocks
</P>
<P>
   Bob Lendzion, the longtime pro at the Quechee Club in Vermont,
made a nice splash in his debut as a card-carrying member of the
Senior PGA Tour by finishing T-17 to earn $17,050 at the Royal
Caribbean Classic. Last week, Lendzion opened with a 76 and never
recovered at the Ace Group Classic in Naples, Fla., finishing 20
shots behind the winner, Lanny Wadkins . . . With the Women's
Australian Open on deck, some top LPGA Tour players skipped this
week's Hawaiian Ladies Open in favor of arriving Down Under a few
days earlier. Kelly Robbins, for one, wasn't crazy about what she
discovered when she got to the Yarra Yarra course in Melbourne: a
layout of just 5,938 yards. ``It's playing a little short right
now,'' said Robbins, who needed her driver only a few times. A
particular annoyance is a par 5 that measures but 422 yards.
``You're seeing courses shortened by choice, not because of the
weather.'' . . . The University of Rhode Island finished sixth in a
16-team field at the recent Bridges All-American Intercollegiate
tournament in Bay St. Louis, Miss. Senior Michael Sims opened with
a 69 and led URI with a 218 total for 54 holes, finishing sixth in
the individual race. Josh Hillman of Greenfield (223), Jim
Salinetti of Stockbridge (224), Mike Carbone of Brewster (231), and
Justin Thompson (241) rounded out the URI scoring . . . James
Dodson, who has authored a couple of must-read books if you are a
golf fan, will be guest speaker March 9 when the Massachusetts Golf
Association holds its 38th annual spring conference. Dodson, a
columnist for Golf Magazine who lives in Maine, wrote ``Final
Rounds,'' which so impressed Winnie Palmer that it led to ``A
Golfer's Life,'' Dodson's collaboration with Arnold Palmer. The
conference will be held at the Westin Copley Place Boston; for
information, call 781-449-3000 . . . Bob Ruszala of Hickory Ridge
in Amherst is the new president of the Golf Course Superintendents
Association of New England. He becomes the first president in 30
years from the western end of the state . . . Joe Concannon, a
colleague who died at age 60 last week, was a man of modest desires
but extravagant generosity. For some 30 years, he wrote about golf
for the Globe, and it was a perfect fit _ a man of dignity and the
most honorable of sports. That he died too young is a given; that
he gave everything he had to his profession and to his countless
friends is what should be remembered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
