<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS HAVE FROZEN UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Slightly more than three weeks remain before the NHL's March 14
trade deadline, and it looks like the Bruins will remain in ``Stand
Pat'' mode during what little time is left of the season.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so let me ask, is that all there is to a fire? I mean, the
whole thing goes up in flames and everyone _ that especially means
you, fans of Hub hockey _ is supposed to sit around here and wonder
what next cool gimmick will pop up on the Vault's Jumbotron?
</P>
<P>
   Is that where we are in 2000? Everyone thinking, ``Sure, it
stinks, but so what?'' If so, the Boston hockey fan has become
nearly as faceless and apathetic as the product.
</P>
<P>
   Great Game. Good Guys.
</P>
<P>
   Dreadful Results.
</P>
<P>
   What, and no one cares?
</P>
<P>
   Pat Burns remains behind the Boston bench, despite owner Jeremy
Jacobs shaking down the thunder a few weeks ago from Buffalo. A
remark of equal significance that got little media attention was
captain Ray Bourque's recent support of Burns. To fire Burns now
would be wrong, noted Bourque, saying, ``Believe me, you can bring
anyone in here and they can't do a better job than Pat.''
</P>
<P>
   That says the captain believes the product, as constituted here
in February 2000, just isn't good enough. That would make Burns the
right coach but the Bruins just a bad, untalented team, factoring
in all the variables (holdouts, injuries, bad trades, bad bounces,
poor acquisitions, etc).
</P>
<P>
   Is that stating the obvious? Sure. But at some point the paying
customers will recognize what's before them _ just as they did when
they vacated Foxborough in the pre-Parcells days _ and that could
leave Causeway Street just a lonely pothole at the edge of the Big
Dig (don't get me started).
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the Bruins trying to market a club that missed the
playoffs for a second time in four seasons and no longer has
Bourque on the back line. Tough sell. No one knows for certain
whether Bourque will retire after this season, but why, other than
money, would he want to subject himself to such frozen water
torture one more time? What a 40th birthday party that would be in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Could the waves of boos that cascaded in the Vault last Saturday
night, in the late stages of a 5-1 humbling at the hands of the
Panthers, be the recognition that vox populi finally is getting,
shall we say, edgy?
</P>
<P>
   In the nearly 28 years that have passed since the Bruins won the
Stanley Cup, there have been bad teams here, but never so bad and
so unentertaining with such little promise. That's the horror.
They've now crossed into Celtic-like insignificance, just a bunch
of suits with familiar logos, filling up arena dates, their best
games ending in (yahoo!) ties. They don't even have a towel-wagging
M.L. Carr type to whip the crowd into a frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday night in New York, a 5-2 loss had some momentary
tension and competitiveness in the second period. But by and large,
it was a classic ho-hum mail-in job that would bring tears even to
that Fred Creighton-led team of 1979-80 (no barnburner itself).
That team at least had gumption, brothers Milbury, McNab, and
O'Reilly jumping into the MSG stands for a rumble because a fan had
the audacity to yank Stan Jonathan's stick out of his hands. Now
they go into MSG, get mugged by the ``Czechmates'' (Petr Nedved,
Radek Dvorak, and Jan Hlavac), and everyone in Black and Gold acts
like a New York tourist _ just glad to escape alive.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Messrs. Harry Sinden and Mike O'Connell have taken
their ``Stand Pat'' approach to new heights. While the product has
chugged and sputtered along to 18 wins _ fewest in the Northeast
Division and more than only the Islanders, Lightning, and Thrashers
_ the front office hasn't done a single thing to add to the product
since the Dec. 7 acquisition of Marty McSorley. Nothing, for almost
three months.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago, prior to the All-Star Game, I thought
they might deal for help on the penalty-killing unit (Coach
Jacobs's stated sore spot) and provide Burns &AMP; Co. with the
slightest booster shot to make a run at a playoff spot. But,
nothing. Meanwhile, the Bruins have gone 0-2-2 since the All-Star
break, and it's taking on the look of the post-Thanksgiving 3-12-8
massacre and that 0-5-4 start in October.
</P>
<P>
   It's fine for Jacobs to criticize the product. Ownership has its
privileges. Jacobs writes the checks. However, when he pinpointed
the PK as the single most troubling issue, and flogged the coaching
staff, then Sinden and O'Connell owed it to Burns and, more
important, the fans to find some help.
</P>
<P>
   True, Burns was slow to alter his approach, finally implementing
a slightly upbeat forecheck only after weeks of horrible results.
But it has been clear here since at least early December that the
front office has had to add to the roster. Burns was slow. The
front office was stationary.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell and Sinden decided to stand pat, leave the coach _ and
the roster _ in place, and the result is a bizarre, struggling, and
often inept product.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket to ride
</P>
<P>
   Michal Grosek, Buffalo's Cam Neely wannabe, is the Sabre most
likely to be ditched as the trade deadline approaches. Head coach
Lindy Ruff benched Grosek for one game and suited him up against
the Oilers last Sunday only because Curtis Brown had the flu. But
Ruff didn't give Grosek a shift against the Oilers _ reminiscent of
the Neely-Kevin Stevens incident here . . . The Buffalo front
office continues to snuff out rumors that Dominik Hasek will be
dealt, even after his recent decision to play at least one more
year. But for a small-market club that could lose $12 million or
more this season, one that lost in the Cup finals last year even
with Hasek, the Sabres no doubt will be peppered with proposals
over the next three weeks. Philadelphia could come calling with an
offer too good to refuse . . . If Bob Corkum's salary demands
hadn't been so high last summer, the Rangers would have signed him
before ex-Bruin Tim Taylor. But Corkum, formerly of UMaine, balked
at the Blueshirts' offer of $1 million-plus per year, allowing
Taylor to jump to the head of the line. Corkum ultimately landed in
LA for a two-year hitch worth $700,000 this year (pro-rated) and
$800,000 next year _ only a touch better than the $675,000 he made
in Phoenix last season . . . He's 35 now, but Brian Bellows, last
seen with the Capitals last season (17-19_36), might be a help to
someone down the stretch. According to his agent, ex-Bruin Brian
Lawton, Bellows is home in Minneapolis, remains in shape, and is
looking for offers . . . The Neely Foundation, run by brothers Cam
and Scott Neely, opened a new wing at the New England Medical
Center last month for cancer patients and their families. Since
opening its doors in August 1997, the foundation has hosted
500-plus families. Donations to the Neely Foundation can be sent to
30 Winter Street, second floor, Boston 02108 . . . The Rangers
moved defenseman Brian Leetch up front on the Nedved-Dvorak line
against the Panthers last week, in hopes of neutralizing Pavel Bure
. . . Isn't it about time for Esa Tikkanen to show up on an NHL
roster? Tikk is back in Finland playing for Jokerit with ex-Bruin
Dmitri Kvartalnov . . . Ivan Hlinka, head coach-to-be in
Pittsburgh, might recruit old pal Thomas Gradin, once a teammate in
Vancouver, as an assistant coach with the Penguins. Gradin is now
the Canucks' chief scout in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   No deal with the Devil
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the Devils will make a deal or two, but one won't be
the acquisition of Teemu Selanne from the Ducks. ``That's so out of
whack, it has to be addressed,'' said Anaheim GM Pierre Gauthier,
responding to the rumor. ``That's a total fabrication.'' . . . Word
around Phoenix is that the Coyotes will deal little-used blue liner
Deron Quint, ex- of Tabor Academy and the 30th pick overall
(Winnipeg) in the '94 draft . . . The Stars had a lot to work with,
but Dallas management, after purging the roster of veterans Dave
Reid, Pat Verbeek, Benoit Hogue, and Craig Ludwig, did some
admirable on-the-run patching after realizing some rookie
shortcomings. To wit: the additions of Kirk Muller, Dave Manson,
Scott Thornton, and Sylvain Cote. Muller's good work earned him a
boost in this year's salary and a guarantee for next season. He
jumped from a pro-rated $300,000 this year to a pro-rated $650,000
and he picked up an added year at $750,000 . . . Brett Hull
returned to the Dallas lineup wearing a full shield after surgery
on his broken nose. Stuck at 603 goals, the Golden Brett needs
seven more strikes to reach his dad's total of 610. Brett,
comparing his style with Bobby's: ``I just lumbered around the ice,
so I kind of developed a style, a stealth mode, I guess I'd call
it. I would just weave my way in and out of holes. My dad gave me a
piece of advice very early. He said, `The farther you think you are
out of the play, that is when you are the closest to it.' I said
that to Wayne Gretzky one time and he agreed wholeheartedly with
it. We are different that way, but in the same sense I think that
the personality I got from him helps you score goals because you
have to know you can score.'' . . . Hard, hard times for hockey
lovers, losing both Charles M. Schulz and his beloved ``Peanuts''
gang last weekend. I know he wouldn't fit the classic definition,
but Schulz would be a fitting inductee for the Hockey Hall of Fame.
The Elmer Ferguson Award _ bestowed upon the (Lawrence)
Eagle-Tribune's Russ Conway last year _ is given ``in recognition
of distinguished members of the newspaper profession whose words
have brought honor to journalism and to hockey.'' Now, find me a
more honorable character than Woodstock, hockey stick in hand,
twirling around his frozen birdbath. Good grief, stickhandling was
an art in those days, wasn't it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
