<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-USSOCCER-GOLDCUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US BOOTED OUT OF GOLD CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Colombia gained some revenge. And most of the failings
of the United States national soccer team development system were
exposed in the quarterfinals of the Gold Cup Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia eliminated the US on penalty kicks, 2-1, after playing
to a 2-2 tie over 120 minutes in 85-degree temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia was seeking to compensate for a disastrous World Cup
'94 elimination by the US, and succeeded because of a spectacular
left-footed Gerardo Bedoya drive from 25 yards that zipped past
Brad Friedel's outstretched hand in the 82d minute to tie the
contest.
</P>
<P>
   On penalty kicks, Andres Mosquera and Gonzalo Martinez beat US
goalkeeper Brad Friedel, while Eddie Lewis was the only one among
five Americans to convert.
</P>
<P>
   The US squandered the lead twice, but Colombia coach Luis Garcia
simply outmaneuvered US coach Bruce Arena with substitutions. Arena
should not take all the blame, though, since he had no one on the
bench to match Colombia reserves Mayor Candelo and John Wilmar
Perez.
</P>
<P>
   After Jovan Kirovski departed in the 27th minute with a broken
foot, the US midfield play dropped off. And, though the US remained
dangerous on the wings with Cobi Jones and Lewis crossing to Brian
McBride and Eric Wynalda, the team simply did not have enough
variety to unbalance Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   The US defense, led by Robin Fraser, contained Faustino Asprilla
after he scored in the 24th minute to match McBride's 21st-minute
header. But Fraser, Jeff Agoos, and Eddie Pope had to work much
harder than the Colombian defenders. This allowed Garcia to refresh
the Colombian midfield with creative players. And, by the second
half and 30 minutes of extra time, Colombia's ability to control
possession and keep the US off balance was crucial.
</P>
<P>
   This was the earliest elimination of the US from the continental
championship since the tournament was relaunched in 1991 as the
Gold Cup. The US has a 16-3-2 record in the Gold Cup and had failed
to reach the finals only on 1996, after falling to Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't lose the game, and it's certainly not the end of the
world,'' Arena said. ``But we lost two leads and we should be able
to protect the lead with 10 minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The roster limits were low for some strange reason. You can't
play a tournament like this with 18 players, and with the gate
receipts from these games they should be able to pay for two more
players. It must have been 85 degrees out there and we don't have
the fitness right now because our league is not playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colombians were committed to attack in the first half, and
Bonner Mosquera caught Friedel off his line with a 40-yard blast
off the bar in the sixth minute. Asprilla pressured Friedel and
blocked his clearance wide of the net five minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   But the US had chances, mostly thanks to Jones's threatening
runs on the left side. Bedoya, the Colombian left back, matched up
well with Jones, and when in doubt, simply felled Jones just
outside the penalty area. And the US nearly capitalized on Lewis's
free kicks, one of which was nearly headed in for an own goal and
another was tipped over the bar by Miguel Calero.
</P>
<P>
   The US took the lead as Wynalda found Jones on the right and
Jones chipped a perfect ball for McBride to head past Calero from
15 yards. Three minutes later, Bedoya slammed down Jones. And the
Colombians, seemingly inspired, scored soon after as Frankie Oviedo
found Hector Hurtado with a 40-yard through ball, and Asprilla
finished Hurtado's square ball.
</P>
<P>
   The US's Richie Williams hit the post five minutes into golden
goal extra time, and Asprilla's free kick hit the post in the 108th
minute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 2114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
