<HEADER>
A2334 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-HOUSTON-     02-19 2030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-HOUSTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON'S CASSERLY STARTING FROM SCRATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you hail from New Jersey and matriculate at Springfield
College, you can end up many places, but one of them is not usually
atop a Brahma bull.
</P>
<P>
   Charley Casserly tried his best to avoid that fate this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The new general manager and director of football operations for
the Houston Whatever They End Up Being Called, has been in Texas
for a little more than a month trying to create an organization
that will turn Bob McNair's huge investment into an NFL franchise
worthy of his massive commitment. But before Casserly had time to
do that, there was a bull to deal with first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to the rodeo,'' said the former general manager of
the Washington Redskins. ``My family is coming in (from Virginia)
and we're the grand marshal of the parade, so I've got to go out
and buy some Western gear. I have no idea what that entails, but
they're taking me to a Western shop and the manager is supposed to
help me.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me I could ride on a horse, a bull, or in a covered
wagon. I voted for the covered wagon. I told them unless they
wanted me to have the shortest tenure of any general manager in NFL
history, they better put me in the wagon.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus begins the latest chapter of an NFL management career that
began in 1977 in an $8-a-night room at the YMCA in Alexandria, Va.,
a place Casserly ended up after Redskins coach George Allen took
him up on an offer he made to all 28 NFL teams. Unable to move from
a high school coaching job in Massachusetts to the college ranks,
he would work in any capacity.
</P>
<P>
   As an unpaid intern, Casserly went to the Redskins and didn't
leave for 22 years, working in the scouting department under Bobby
Beathard that built the heart of Washington's first Super Bowl
team. Eventually he became assistant general manager in 1982 under
Beathard and took over in 1989 after Beathard moved to San Diego.
He built a team that won Super Bowl XXVI in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In good years and bad, the Redskins remained a Casserly creation
until Daniel Snyder took over last year, buying the team from the
estate of Jack Kent Cooke. Although loyal to the Redskins, Casserly
knew his days were numbered once Snyder took over, but he put
together a draft day trade that landed Champ Bailey and enough
first-round picks over the next couple of years to allow the new
owner to rebuild into a champion again.
</P>
<P>
   That might have been easier had Casserly been retained, but he
was not and spent the past season out of the league for the first
time in three decades. Because McNair is a smart businessman,
Casserly didn't stay out long.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to the NFL Jan. 19 after weighing job possibilities,
but now that he's back, what will he do for a team that won't begin
play for two years?
</P>
<P>
   ``We joined the BLESTO scouting combine and I brought in Mike
Maccagnan as our scout for them until we can switch him to pro
scouting (which he did for Casserly in Washington for six years)
and hired Chuck Banker as director of pro scouting (also from
Washington),'' Casserly said. ``We brought Chuck in sooner than I
expected, but Carolina had offered him a job so we did it ahead of
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us will be at the combine later this month. We're
getting boxes of tape and ordering our video equipment so we can
look at player tape by March as well. Then we'll bring in a salary
cap analyst because, even if we're without players, we have to keep
up with the (cap) trends.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last five weeks and for the foreseeable future,
Casserly's biggest job will be visiting training facilities
throughout the league. He's designing his team's practice complex,
which will adjoin the state-of-the-art stadium McNair is building
in downtown Houston. For a guy who has spent most of his life
evaluating talent, evaluating architecture and design is a bit of a
change. For the moment, that is Casserly's job, and it's better
than bull riding.
</P>
<P>
   In the end though, his job in Houston will be what it was in
Washington: finding players he can win with. According to Casserly,
it's a job that will begin long before his team takes its first
snap in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be scouting, but not picking players,'' Casserly said,
``because we'll have a shot at 70 percent of the players in April's
draft. That many will be cut in four years or in the expansion
draft or become free agents. You make your decisions on players on
their history, not on one year, so we'll be able to have three
years of scouting on a lot of guys by the time we're in the
business of selecting players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll reconstruct this year's draft and by the time we're
done, we'll have a college report on every player so when we're on
the clock in 2002, we'll have a full three years of scouting
reports to evaluate players on.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the thought of that moment two years down the road that
led Casserly to Texas in the first place. To have taken a job with
an existing NFL team would have been to inherit problems not of his
making.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the jobs available to me were interesting, but what I
appreciated about Houston was we're starting from scratch,''
Casserly said. ``It's the challenge of building from nothing that I
liked. You have the chance to hire all your own people and build a
team in a town where football is king. Everybody here is a football
fan, so there's no question we can sell out every week if we can
give them a team that wins.''
</P>
<P>
   That is Casserly's job, one he did with regularity in
Washington. Now he's in an unfamiliar town in an unfamiliar job _
trying to find football players. That isn't all bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``What problems we have we will have created ourselves,''
Casserly said. ``I do think the climate for an expansion team has
changed dramatically from when Carolina and Jacksonville came in.
Teams do a much better job now of keeping their own players. I know
when I looked at the (expansion) list Cleveland had to draw from,
there wasn't a lot of talent there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The draft is your foundation. That means it takes 3-5 years to
build a team, but that, in the end, will be our foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   If it is, McNair's Houston team has its cornerstone in the guy
who'll be doing the draft _ as long as they can keep him off those
bulls.
</P>
<P>
   The Stat Pack
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made in Green Bay of the fact that the Packers had
a 1,000-yard rusher, two 1,000-yard receivers, and a 4,000-yard
passer. While that may be true, it doesn't reveal a more important
statistic. In five of the Packers' eight division games, they
scored only one offensive touchdown. ``So much for stats,'' said
general manager Ron Wolf. The Packers expect tight end Mark Chmura
to be back at full strength, which should come as good news to
Brett Favre. The quarterback relied on Chmura to get his offense
out of trouble . . . You have to hand it to Georgia Frontiere,
because she certainly did to Dick Vermeil. The departing Rams coach
was given a $2 million farewell bonus, which will be paid at
$500,000 a year for the next four years. In exchange, Vermeil will
serve as a consultant, if asked. Actually, it's a good deal for the
Rams. If St. Louis fired Vermeil, it would have cost $3.9 million
to buy him out. Instead, the Rams get a Super Bowl trophy and save
$1.9 million for rewarding a good guy who earned the money . . .
Rams right tackle Fred Miller had more than the 24 million reasons
to sign with Tennessee. He had the memory of six false starts and
two holding penalties against the Titans' Jevon Kearse last Oct.
31. Miller made $429,000 last season, which means he just got a
raise of more than 10 times last year's pay . . . You've got to
give Frank Gansz credit. He quit the Rams last week because at 61
he was tired of living in St. Louis while his wife was raising
their three grandchildren in Atlanta. He lived alone in St. Louis
for three years, commuting to Atlanta when he could. Reportedly, he
told assistant coach Jim Hanifan the day he quit, ``Simply stated,
this is not a way to live.'' Gansz had been offered a contract
extension but never signed. Some felt he was looking for work.
Actually, he just wanted to go home . . . Mike McCarthy must have
done a hell of a job last week. Seven days after being hired by Jim
Haslett as the Saints' quarterbacks coach, he was promoted to
offensive coordinator. It was a promotion that came six weeks after
he was fired as part of Ray Rhodes's staff in Green Bay. McCarthy
has never been an offensive coordinator in 13 years as a coach. He
will run the West Coast offense similar to the way the Broncos use
it with Terrell Davis . . . Speaking of Denver, sportswriters there
have to be in mourning now that loquacious Shannon Sharpe has
landed in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   A good spread
</P>
<P>
   Despite arbiter Sam Kagel's ruling that Barry Sanders must repay
the Lions $5.58 million of an $11 million signing bonus, it will
have little impact on Detroit's salary cap. If Detroit spreads the
money out, as Kagel suggested, the Lions would be hit with $3.83
million (because of a $1.75 million payment already made) this
year, but would have an additional $1.913 million in cap room in
2001 and $1.83 million the following two years . . . Is it
fraternization to coach in the Pro Bowl? Only 10 days after the
Tampa Bay staff handled the NFC team, Vikings center Jeff Christy
jumped ship and signed with the Bucs for $17.5 million over five
years. That means the end for Tony Mayberry, whom the Patriots
tried to lure years ago when he was a restricted free agent . . .
Apparently, Dan Rooney likes to get his employees from close to
home. He replaced ex-Steeler ballboy turned director of football
operations Tom Donahoe with Kevin Colbert, who went to a local
Pittsburgh Catholic school whose alums include Rooney and his
former boss with the Lions, Ron Hughes. Colbert was the Lions'
director of pro scouting the last 10 years . . . A week to the day
after naming defensive tackle Norman Hand its franchise player, the
Chargers removed the tag last week. Hand now may find that the
Chargers' original offer of just under $4 million a year is more
than he can get elsewhere. If it works out, Beathard would have
made a brilliant business move by stalling Hand for a week, saving
$4.73 million on the cap, then freeing him when it was too late to
get the $5 million a year he hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   It's elementary
</P>
<P>
   Just before he signed a deal with the Panthers, Atlanta pass
rusher Chuck Smith flatly stated what he had to offer. ``They need
defense,'' Smith said. ``That's where I come in. I bring another
element to the table.'' Apparently Carolina agreed because it
handed him a five-year, $21 million contract a day later . . . Some
guys don't think too clearly. Detroit pass rusher Robert Porcher
reportedly turned down a five-year, $35 million deal that included
a $12 million signing bonus from the Lions. So what happened next?
Detroit slapped the franchise tag on him, meaning he gets $4.25
million next year, the average of the top five defensive ends. ``No
way I can play for that,'' Porcher said. He should go talk to Joey
Galloway . . . Every year you say free agency can't get any
nuttier, and then a guy like Phillip Daniels is signing with the
Bears for $24 million, which included an $8 million signing bonus,
the highest in Chicago history. What has the 26-year-old Daniels
done to justify the cash? He had a career-high nine sacks last
season. He has averaged barely five sacks in four years in the NFL.
Maybe he's ready to blossom. The Bears had better hope so, or
somebody is going to pay, and it won't just be the guy writing
Daniels's check. But that's not the half of it. Ever hear of
Orpheus Roye? He just jumped from Pittsburgh to the Browns for a
reported five-year, $25 million deal after a four-sack season. The
Browns say he's an emerging player. He'd better emerge into Reggie
White to justify that cash. ``How many guys who get these contracts
play better for their new team?'' asked Titans executive Jeff
Diamond. The answer is not many. But they never learn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
