<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2335 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-GAMACHE-     02-19 1442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-GAMACHE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMACHE PLAYS MATCHMAKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fortunately for Joey Gamache, Jimmy Glenn's bar isn't far from
HBO's offices.
</P>
<P>
   One day last August, the two-time world champion happened to be
walking into the joint in Manhattan owned by his trainer when he
noticed HBO's building just up the block, and on the spot he
announced he was going in to see HBO Sports executive Lou DiBella.
What came from that unscheduled meeting was one last chance for a
tough battler from Maine to climb into boxing's big-time.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Gamache will step into the ring at Madison Square
Garden against another former champion down on his luck, Arturo
Gatti. The difference is that Gatti has become the darling of HBO
because he produces ratings. The fact that Gamache understood why
he produced those ratings is what landed him the fight in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went over to HBO's office and Lou said he'd see me,''
Gamache recalled. ``I told him me and Gatti would make a great
fight. It's two guys who cut and bleed and fight like hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him it was a perfect matchup of a boxer against a
slugger. Lou said he'd see if he could make it, but he told me
Gatti had to beat Reyes Munoz first. I told him a guy I just beat
in April knocked Munoz out in two rounds. Gatti took care of him in
one, so here we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite that easily. First Gamache returned to Maine,
where he still works putting up drywall when he's not on the road
boxing in some of the sport's more obscure outposts. Once there, he
sent HBO a tape of one of his most recent wins, followed up with a
second trip to New York when he didn't manage to see DiBella, then
sent another letter and tape along with one more assurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he wouldn't be sorry if he gave me the
opportunity,'' the 33-year-old Gamache said. ``I wasn't embarrassed
to do it. These days in boxing, you've got to rely on yourself. I
got a good manager (New York legend Johnny Bos), but I was the one
who could leave the lasting impression. I couldn't blame them if
they'd given the shot to someone else because there are plenty of
fighters deserving of it, but I stayed after DiBella and he gave me
the shot. I respect that. I wasn't embarrassed to go ask for the
fight. I needed them to know I wasn't finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamache appeared to be just that two years ago, after he lost a
bloody battle with Julio Cesar Chavez and announced his retirement.
He said if he could no longer compete at the elite level of the
sport, there was no point in going on. But after a seven-month
layoff and a failed restaurant venture in Maine that cost him a lot
of money he'd earned with his blood, Gamache decided to let Bos
take him on the road for one last try at the bright lights. After
nine straight wins, he has landed such a night at Madison Square
Garden, which will be rocking with Oscar De La Hoya fans and
attract a large cable television audience.
</P>
<P>
   But more than the number of people who will see him fight,
Gamache knows it is what he does in that ring that will determine
what future he has left.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't win this, there's no tomorrow,'' Bos said. ``This
is the seventh game of the World Series for Joey. But he's made for
Arturo's style. It's the right fight. Funny thing is, if we win
easy it's not as good for Joey as if we win close. Beat him close
and we get a rematch and Joey can get paid. Beat him easy and who
wants to watch it again?''
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the dilemmas of boxing, a sport in which you can
penalize yourself if you're too dominant almost as much as you can
if you're dominated. Gamache understands that, because the sport
has been his life for more than 20 years, yet when he thinks of
Gatti (30-4), he thinks not of style points or future paydays.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks of winning and bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely there's no tomorrow for me if I lose,'' said
Gamache (55-3). ``Gatti's not an easy fight. He turns everything
into a war, and I've been known to bleed. You have to be careful
with him because he's so easy to hit you can find yourself drawn in
and hitting him longer than is wise and then he gets you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is the final chapter of my career. But I wanted to
come back for one more chance to go out the right way. If I win,
that would do it. Or maybe I'd fight once more.''
</P>
<P>
   They all do until there has been one too many nights, and
Gamache knows he is approaching that evening whether he wins Friday
or not. But he fought his way back to the main stage from places in
which the halls are small and the money smaller. He fought for one
thing. He fought for this night with a guy who bleeds as much as he
does and knows how to make you bleed, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``People pay to see him bleed, not to see him box,'' Gamache
said. ``He doesn't fight off his skills, he fights off his
emotions. Because I can box and still have good legs, it gives me a
good chance if I don't get caught up in things. I think most people
are saying, `If Joey has anything left, this is a winnable fight.'
That's all I was looking for _ a chance to get back there one more
time.''
</P>
<P>
   That chance comes in six days. What Joey Gamache does with it is
anyone's guess, but win or lose he knows this. He got there. One
more time.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz No. 1 at being No. 1
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea heavyweight John Ruiz got unexpected good news last week
when it was announced that he'd been elevated to the No. 1 ranking
by the World Boxing Association, thus making him Lennox Lewis's
mandatory challenger in two of the three major organizations. Ruiz
already holds the World Boxing Council's No. 1 ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz (35-3, 26 KOs) now is entitled to the next title shot at
Lewis if the champion successfully defends his crowns against
Michael Grant April 29. Ruiz would likely get that shot in July,
probably in England, because the winner must defend the WBA title
next. Lewis had refused to do so because Henry Akinwande, whom he
already defeated in stinker of a match, had been long kept in the
top spot for no reason. The WBA finally came to its senses and
elevated Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   Evander Holyfield is No. 2 in both organizations, and rumors
continue to float that Ruiz and Holyfield could fight later this
spring on Showtime in a boxoff to determine the true No. 1
contender. Ruiz's manager, Norman Stone, would rather force Lewis
to fight Ruiz before Grant, but that simply will not happen. The
rules says he's entitled to, but business says it's Grant-Lewis at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ruiz is where he could only dream he might get one day.
He's six months from becoming the first New England heavyweight in
decades to fight for a world title.
</P>
<P>
   Short jabs
</P>
<P>
   The reason Junior Jones didn't get the shot with Prince Naseem
Hamed supposedly is that he wanted 10 first-class air tickets to
London. Another source said that although Hamed was willing to pay
Jones the $500,000 he wanted, ``it was a rough contract.'' That
means that if Jones won, it tied him up like a mummy. Hence no
fight . . . It now seems more and more likely that Mike Tyson will
journey to Milan to fight Lou Saverese in April. New Jersey wanted
the fight for a while, but word is Italian promoters have gone over
the top for it . . . Tyson would still like a June or July fight
with Shannon Briggs before going after a big-money bout . . . Among
the Olympic hopefuls in Tampa last week was a most unusual story.
In 1992, Joseph Pastorello was a fullback at Air Force Academy who
was Most Valuable Player in the Liberty Bowl. Personal problems led
him to leave school after three years, but the 27-year-old
Pastorello decided to give boxing a try in 1995. Four years later,
he was named to the US team for the Pan-Am Games and he finished
second in the US Challenge this year to reach the Olympic trials.
Unfortunately, his story ended there when he failed to qualify for
the boxoffs in two weeks . . . Derrell Coley seemed pretty
confident last week, although one has to wonder why. Coley will be
in the ring with De La Hoya at Madison Square Garden, and few think
he'll come out a winner. Many, in fact, believe he may come out
early. Yet Coley said blithely, ``De La Hoya says he's going to
make it a rumble, but I seriously doubt it. Everything he says he's
going to do, he doesn't.'' . . . De La Hoya fired 77-year-old
training adviser Gil Clancy, effectively blaming him for the Felix
Trinidad loss, and then tried to claim he wanted to retain Clancy
but the rest of his ``corner'' outvoted him, 4-1. Since when does
the guy signing the checks get outvoted?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
