<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2336 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CAR-DAYTONA-YATES-BOS     02-19 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-YATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YATES'S TEAM BUILT FOR SPEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The garage area at Daytona International
Speedway was bustling last Thursday as race teams prepared for the
start of the Gatorade Twin 125s. But the scene was a little more
subdued at the Robert Yates Racing camp, where everyone on Dale
Jarrett's crew seemed to go about their business with an aura of
quiet confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Winning a NASCAR Winston Cup championship does that for you. It
breeds confidence. It brings a new sense of respect from your
peers. And ultimately, it leads to a higher level of expectation.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, there's another neat perk: preferred parking for your
hauler in the NASCAR Winston Cup garage.
</P>
<P>
   But those were hardly the reasons Robert Yates, owner of
Jarrett's No. 88 Ford Quality Care Taurus and Ricky Rudd's No. 28
Texaco Havoline Ford, invested so much blood, sweat, and tears in
winning his first championship last year with Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   It had more to do with a desire to be the best.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was drag racing at Shuffletown Dragway in Charlotte,
N.C.; building Ford engines for several NASCAR teams; or striking
out on his own as a car owner in 1988, when he bought the
Ranier-Lundy Racing team, Yates has never strayed from that
principle.
</P>
<P>
   In 370 starts on the Winston Cup circuit, Yates has accumulated
42 victories, 26 poles, 173 top five finishes, 237 top 10 finishes,
and $32,866,394 in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sort of pinching ourselves that we had a good team the
first couple of years,'' Yates said of his partnership with
Jarrett, which resulted in a Daytona 500 victory in 1996. ``We sort
of took it for granted at first. We've always been serious, but
we're even more focused on it now. We like that feeling of being in
the hunt all the time for a championship and winning races.''
</P>
<P>
   During the offseason, Yates, 56, took measures to ensure that
his team became even more formidable. When Jarrett and Rudd won the
pole position and outside pole, respectively, to give Yates a
front-row sweep for Sunday's 42d Daytona 500, it was evidence that
the best had gotten better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like the luckiest guy here,'' Yates said. ``I'm very
fortunate. All my life, Daytona has been like the big deal and
still is. Daytona is where you came and showed your new cars, your
power, and who did their homework during the winter months. There's
all this anxiety, and then you show up here and, boom, you're on
the front row.''
</P>
<P>
   Yates rescued Rudd after the veteran driver lost his Tide
sponsorship and was forced to liquidate his Rudd Performance
Motorsports team.
</P>
<P>
   When Rudd brought crew chief Michael McSwain along with eight
other employees to the Yates team, they were astounded at what they
found.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential of this team is unbelievable,'' Rudd said. ``I
feel like we are prepared better than I've ever been prepared on
any race team I've been on in many, many years. The chemistry is
there to do great things. We might have had one first-stringer (on
the pit crew), but the Yates organization has first-stringers at
every position, not only with the pit crew but the guys hanging the
bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Yates knew he made a good move when he brought in Rudd to
replace Kenny Irwin in the 28 car. Many drivers _ from Robby Gordon
to Ernie Irvan to Irwin _ have failed to live up to the potential
of its original occupant, the late Davey Allison.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great guy, a good family man,'' Yates said of Rudd, for
whom he built engines during their days together on the defunct
DiGard Racing team. ``I've known him and worked with him, and he's
certainly the guy I've always scanned on my (radio) scanner,
because every season he's always a threat to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have the opportunity to hire somebody like that, you
know that if you don't win it's not the driver, and we needed that.
We needed that so we could sort of rule out what the problem was.
Kenny was certainly learning, and we put a lot of work and,
sometimes, heartache into it. I'm sure he'll have a good career and
create a lot of excitement for the fans, but the 28 team needs to
win some races.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, addressing an area of need on the 88 team, Yates bolstered
Jarrett's pit crew by luring away five members of Jeff Gordon's
``Rainbow Warriors.'' He continued his oversight of the Yates
engine program headed up by his son, Doug, and developed the
redesigned 2000 Ford Taurus into a rocketship that launched Jarrett
to victory in last Sunday's Bud Shootout and Rudd to a triumph in
his 50-lap heat in the Twin 125s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd think we'd be extremely lucky if we won a championship
with the 28 team, but I'd like to believe over time _ over a short
period of time _ we can get to where we feel like we can,'' Yates
said. ``I think it's just a matter of time and getting some
positive results. I'm excited about it and I'm looking forward to
it, but this deal here with the 88 team is pretty polished.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the pieces are in place, is Robert Yates Racing capable
of becoming a championship-caliber team year in and year out? Can
it make a dynastic run?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that you mention it, that's what we're really trying to
do,'' Yates said. ``I remember the Wood brothers and Pettys. I
remember working for Junior Johnson, and we didn't have a dynasty
going, but we created one. I left there to go to DiGard, and we won
one-third of the races and had a real strong deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really about the people you work with or attract or align
yourself with. I'd like to think we have the makings of that kind
of dynasty with (crew chief) Todd Parrott and Dale Jarrett. I'd
like to have the 28 team be in that same elite status. But it's
tough to have that now, because the money's so equal.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, are the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the DiGard and Petty days, shoot, they had
everybody outclassed,'' Yates said. ``I remember when you couldn't
go in the garage and see a Wood brothers manifold. You couldn't
look and see if they were running the right cubic inches. Now it's
hard to get a monopoly or a dynasty going, because you can't
establish a competitive advantage over anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But with Jarrett on the throne as defending Winston Cup champion
and Rudd riding shotgun as a proven veteran, and both in
Ford-powered mounts, Yates appears to have his team poised to
become great.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you beat us, you're going to have to run awfully good,''
said Jarrett. ``I think we have the total package now.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that explained why everyone was working so feverishly
elsewhere in the garage: Yates Racing has given people a lot of
catching up to do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
