<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTONOTES-CRASH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FENCE SAVED DAY AND DAYTONA FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ It is the worst nightmare of every race
promoter and track operator: a spectator fatality.
</P>
<P>
   When Geoffrey Bodine was involved in a horrific 13-truck crash
midway through Friday's inaugural NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series
race at Daytona International Speedway, there were initial fears
that Daytona had joined Michigan International Speedway and Lowe's
Speedway in Charlotte, N.C., in the sad fraternity of tracks struck
by fan fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, a CART race at Michigan was marred by three
spectator deaths and six injuries when a tire and wheel assembly
were sent flying into the stands. Last year, three fans were killed
and eight injured in a similar accident at an Indy Racing League
event at Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Both were open-wheel racing events.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's accident involved trucks, which have no exposed
suspension parts. And that may have been Daytona's saving grace.
</P>
<P>
   When Bodine's truck catapulted into the catchfence near the
trioval, it sent a ball of flame and small debris spraying into the
grandstands. There's no telling how many fatalities there would
have been had major truck parts been involved, but a major
catastrophe was averted when the fence prevented Bodine's truck
from careening into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Nine spectators were treated for injuries, and five were taken
to a local hospital, including two who were admitted for surgery
(for a facial laceration and a fractured arm). That was relatively
small damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that the systems did their job,'' said track
president John Graham. ``The vehicle systems did their job and
prevented serious, serious injury to the driver, and the fence
system did its job and kept the accident on the track.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham said the accidents at Michigan and Charlotte prompted
Daytona officials to review their fencing systems, but they
determined that no changes were necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Bodine, amazingly, survived the crash. He suffered a concussion,
a mid-back fracture, multiple lacerations and bruises, and a
fracture, laceration, and burns to his right wrist. He remained in
intensive care Saturday, in serious but stable condition, at
Halifax Medical Center. No surgery is expected.
</P>
<P>
   That should have been the good news that allowed track officials
to enjoy a peaceful night's sleep _ not the fact that, as Graham
intoned so callously, the track staged what it considered to be a
successful inaugural truck event on its high-banked superspeedway
before 80,000-100,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike track officials at Michigan and Charlotte, Daytona should
consider itself lucky that it didn't have to bury any of its fans.
</P>
<P>
   Power shared
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Mike Helton was appointed NASCAR's chief operating
officer and introduced as Bill France's hand-picked successor to
take over day-to-day duties of the sanctioning body. It was a
significant move in that France, president of NASCAR since 1972,
appeared to finally delegate some of his authority. More important,
it was the first time in NASCAR history that responsibility was
bestowed upon someone outside the France family.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, questions have arisen about the health of the
66-year-old France. He disclosed at the end of last season that he
was undergoing treatment for an unspecified form of cancer. And
while the news of France's illness was certainly distressing to
NASCAR's hierarchy, it has not put a damper on the future of the
sport, which kicks off its 2000 season with Sunday's Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR is poised to reach out to new markets, sponsors, and fans
when its $2.47 billion television package with NBC, Fox, and Turner
Sports kicks in next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a busy year, and I'm not sure if it's just because I
ended up being chief operating officer or it's just the fact it's
been a busy year,'' said Helton. ``I do know it's been rewarding
from learning a deeper part of the business and understanding all
the business elements has been rewarding for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the challenges of '99 didn't necessarily come from me
being chief operating officer as much as it was the TV package,
because that effort was consuming a lot of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always love, personally, getting to keep my hand in the
garage area and being involved in the competition side of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Building his business
</P>
<P>
   When Michael Holigan, star of his own syndicated TV show on
house construction, agreed to a three-year deal to sponsor the No.
25 Hendrick Motorsports Chevrolet driven by Jerry Nadeau. It
represented a breakthrough of sorts in NASCAR sponsorships: the
dot.com company. Holigan, who caught the racing bug when one of his
TV sponsors, DuPont, invited him to a NASCAR race at Texas, saw an
opportunity to enhance his business. Holigan plans to bring
together vendors, suppliers, and merchandisers of home building
materials with home builders, developers, and general contractors
in a big event-type setting and expose them to a new trade matrix
he is designing with a major computer design company that will
bring online builders and their suppliers. ``This year I'm going to
entertain 4,000 builders and they're going to represent almost
200,000 housing starts across the nation,'' Holigan said. When he
brought his partners to meet with Hendrick Motorsports
representatives to discuss the price of a sponsorship, which
Holigan said ranged from $10 million to $12 million, ``They
immediately tried to justify the price by explaining how the money
would be spent. But one of my partners, who is a part-owner in the
Texas Rangers, turned to me and said, `Hey, that's what we pay a
mediocre pitcher.' With this new TV deal, I can already see that
we'll be getting a return on our investment and I predict that,
before the end of my three-year sponsorship, I will start a two-car
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Tempers flare
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect Tony Stewart and Robby Gordon to be cutting each
other any breaks in Sunday's Daytona 500. The two drivers were
involved in a tussle in the garage area Wednesday afternoon.
Stewart, who claimed his Pontiac was pinched by Gordon into the
grass, clipped Gordon's rear and sent him spinning during a
drafting run. When Gordon approached Stewart in his garage stall,
the two exchanged words. Stewart then gave Gordon a dismissive wave
and punctuated it with a push, which prompted Gordon to retaliate.
The drivers were separated by Stewart's crew members, one of whom,
Jason Shapiro, was fined $2,000 by NASCAR officials for being a
detriment to the sport when he shoved Gordon and struck the driver
in the chin . . . Scott Ford, an 11-year-old from North Reading,
Mass., got an unexpected bonus when he showed up for Friday's truck
race at Daytona and was chosen in a random drawing as the honorary
grand marshal of the race . . . The CART FedEx Series was dealt a
huge blow when car owner Tony Bettenhausen Jr., 48, was killed in a
plane crash last Monday near Leesburg, Ky., along with his wife,
Shirley, and two other team members, Russ Roberts and Larry Rangel,
while en route to Indianapolis. ``This tragedy comes as an absolute
shock to everyone in the CART community,'' said CART CEO Andrew
Craig. ``Tony and Shirley were deeply intertwined in the fabric of
CART racing and their loss is even more profound because of the
fact that along with them perished two individuals of equal
character and integrity.'' The Bettenhausens leave two teenaged
girls . . . Target-Chip Ganassi Racing, which has won the last four
CART titles, announced that it will field entries for defending
CART champion Juan Montoya and Jimmy Vasser for the 2000
Indianapolis 500. ``Racing in the Indy 500 is a dream for any owner
or driver,'' Chip Ganassi said. ``It's disappointing for us and for
our fans we haven't been here in four years, but it's good to be
back. I'm just excited to give Jimmy, Juan, and Target the
opportunity to race at the Brickyard.'' Defending IRL champion Greg
Ray, who was at Daytona participating in the IROC series opener
Friday, said he welcomed Target-Ganassi Racing's return to Indy.
``I think it's going to be exciting,'' he said. ``I think whenever
you compete in a race of that magnitude you want the world's best
drivers to be there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
