<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-BAXTER0220-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Victory may be sweet, but it comes at a cost
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Any judgment of the price George W. Bush paid
to win the South Carolina Republican primary has to be tempered
with the realization that this was a contest he couldn't afford to
lose.
</P>
<P>
   Anything less than a solid victory would have been a disaster
for Bush, who came here with his back to the wall after his
stunning loss to Sen. John McCain in New Hampshire. But for Bush,
who turned the tables on McCain Saturday, this was still a costly
victory.
</P>
<P>
   To win this contest for 37 convention delegates, Bush threw open
his campaign coffers, went negative and mimicked his rival's
rhetoric and platform. He put out a quickly cobbled together
campaign finance reform plan that will be subjected to heavy
scrutiny down the line.
</P>
<P>
   In two weeks of frenzied campaigning, he uttered enough
malapropisms to give comedians material for months: Expect to hear
a lot of cracks about ``raising the pie higher.'' He embraced the
religious right, which could incur more costs in future primaries
such as that in Michigan on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most troubling for his long-term prospects, his campaign
here left the implication that independents and Democrats _ whose
votes he would need to win in November _ weren't welcome in this
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did, however, slam the brakes on the steadily rising
expectations that had built around McCain since New Hampshire. He
not only won, he did so with the sort of heavy turnout that was
supposed to work in McCain's favor. And his margin of victory was
almost as surprising as McCain's in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said many times in the past couple of weeks that the
American people were getting the chance to see how he performed
under pressure. Now there will be an opportunity to watch how
McCain behaves under similar circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The two words McCain will regret most from this campaign are
``like Clinton.'' He probably would have faced a harsh attack even
if he hadn't run the controversial ad comparing Bush to the
Democratic president. But he momentarily lost the moral high
ground, and when he unilaterally disarmed, as he put it, he did so
in the face of an awesome arsenal of negative media still aimed at
him.
</P>
<P>
   Nor can McCain afford to make another switch in strategy in the
primaries ahead. He has put himself squarely on the high road, and
for better or worse he can't afford to take another detour.
</P>
<P>
   While it got far less attention, Steve Forbes' decision to drop
out after the Feb. 8 Delaware primary was also a heavy blow to
McCain's prospects. Almost all the extra air time Bush purchased in
the past two weeks had been originally reserved by Forbes. Forbes
probably would not have siphoned off enough conservative votes to
deny Bush a victory, but he would have shaved off enough to make it
less impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, McCain's campaign may have erred in putting its entire
stake back on the table after his New Hampshire victory. This state
was always a long shot for him, and he may suffer from allowing the
impression that anything else was the case.
</P>
<P>
   What impact Bush's win has on Tuesday's primaries in Michigan
and Arizona remains to be seen. But for next month's races in
Georgia, Florida and other Southeastern states it has huge
implications.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Atwater is gone, but his old friends Warren Tompkins and
former Gov. Carroll Campbell helped deliver an Atwater-style
victory: not very pretty, but deadly effective.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
