u s BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     02-19 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMOR US WITH AN EXTENSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Jimy Williams is beginning his fourth season
managing the Red Sox. If you want perspective for that statement,
think of ``Cats'' and its lengthy run on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Really, did you expect Williams to be here this long? He is a
member of Boston's Coaching Class of 1997, which also includes Rick
Pitino, Pat Burns, and Pete Carroll. In '97, a lot of people
guessed Williams would be the group's first casualty. Now it's just
the opposite: He should be given a four-year contract extension
immediately. I would consider him for a three-year deal based
solely on his comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The man is an amazing mimic of comedian Jonathan Winters. I
think the similarities, beyond the initials ``J.W.,'' are more than
coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage Winters: He once parked in a handicap parking space and
a woman said, ``Hey, you're not handicapped.'' He replied, ``Madam,
can you see inside my mind?''
</P>
<P>
   Vintage Williams: Saturday, he was asked if he is one of those
managers who sits around and draws up potential lineups on napkins.
``I don't ever use napkins,'' he said. ``I always wear old clothes
when I eat.''
</P>
<P>
   The dry humor is not the only reason Williams's one-year
contract should be extended. If you ever want to evaluate a manager
or coach, ask yourself the following introductory question: How
does he/she handle talent?
</P>
<P>
   Williams is a master at this. The Sox have made the playoffs in
back-to-back seasons. They hadn't done that since Babe Ruth had a
locker at the four-year-old Fenway Park. Williams lost Mo Vaughn
from his lineup last year _ for nothing _ and still squeezed 94
wins out of his team. Sometimes he is like your best friend; he can
keep a secret. Sometimes he is like your sensitive neighbor; he
complains when the music is blaring and orders players to use
headphones in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   It would be naive to think that all of his players agree with
his rules. But most understand that he is not trying to be their
buddy. He doesn't take credit for Nomar Garciaparra and Pedro
Martinez. He doesn't care if his image is not featured prominently
on a game telecast.
</P>
<P>
   It's not surprising that the clubhouse he runs is similar to the
very professional one in Atlanta. His friend, Bobby Cox, has said
that the Sox should give Williams a five-year deal. Even I wouldn't
go that high. Five years? That's an NBA contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'm OK,'' Williams said when asked about his contract
Saturday. ``I'm all right.''
</P>
<P>
   When a radio reporter spoke highly of him, he said, ``You should
be my agent.'' Another reporter rattled off his accomplishments and
told him he had ``leverage'' because of them. Williams said he
never thought of using his leverage.
</P>
<P>
   I guess Dan Duquette could argue that there is no reason to
extend Williams more than a year. Maybe he believes that the
current system has worked fine, and that changing it would disrupt
the flow as well as cost the Sox more money. Duquette knows that
Bob Kraft is still paying Carroll, even though Bill Belichick is
the Patriots' coach. He knows the power of Pitino's contract.
Against that backdrop, why reward Williams with a multiyear deal?
</P>
<P>
   That leads to another important managing/coaching question: How
do they match up with their contemporaries? I think we all have to
agree that the best manager in the game is Joe Torre. You can talk
about the excessive Yankee payroll if you want, but I have a hard
time arguing with three World Series titles in four years. Williams
is not Torre, but he is a notch above Tony La Russa and Lou
Piniella. No one would have suggested this 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But based on what I've seen of Williams, I think he would find a
way to make the playoffs if he had Ken Griffey, Alex Rodriguez,
Edgar Martinez, and Randy Johnson as part of his core. (Piniella's
Mariners had just that in 1997 and most of '98.) I think he would
do fine with Mark McGwire's 65 home runs, Ray Lankford's .306
average, and Kent Bottenfield's 18 wins. (That's what La Russa had
last year.)
</P>
<P>
   The eccentric man doesn't like it when people talk about him
this way. He says he doesn't hit, throw out runners, or throw
strikes. He's just another guy, he tells you. So you switch the
subject and ask about his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like he gained a few pounds,'' you say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, maybe he's been lifting aluminum foil all winter,''
Williams replies.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows what that means? Who knows where Winters got the idea
of portraying a middle-aged alien ``baby'' on TV? Williams is a
Winters fan. The more you see the manager's work and the more you
hear of his stories, the more you understand. Additional years of
his quirks? That would be a good thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
