</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-SPRINGTRAINING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAIT TILL THIS YEAR? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ These are giddy times for the Red Sox. The
American League Manager of the Year, Cy Young Award winner, and
batting champion, all under the same dugout roof. Applause,
applause for Jimy Williams, Pedro Martinez, and Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   A big winter's trade landed Carl Everett, a switch-hitting
center fielder who can run and hit and throw and has
middle-of-the-order power.
</P>
<P>
   The farm system is spitting out prospects, Japanese and Korean
pitchers (Tomo Ohka, Sunny Kim, and Jin Ho Cho), Dominican third
basemen (Wilton Veras), and catchers from Peabody (Steve Lomasney).
</P>
<P>
   A native son, Carlton Fisk, is going into the Hall of Fame, a
quarter-century after starring in perhaps the greatest World Series
ever played, while another native son, Rick Asadoorian, pride of
Whitinsville, Mass., was their No. 1 pick in the amateur draft and
already is hearing his name linked to the young Tony C.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket sales are reported to be booming, even at 45 bucks a pop,
the radio shows and chat rooms are already humming with Sox talk,
and kids and their grandparents are ticking off the days to Opening
Day.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Dan Duquette, architect of the first Sox team to
make back-to-back postseason appearances in 83 years, is back to
being a smart guy again. So is CEO John Harrington, who last July
hosted the best All-Star show ever, though right now he could use a
little help with his pet stadium project.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox haven't been in a World Series since 1986. They haven't
won one since 1918, the year Ted Williams was born. Teddy Ballgame,
like Red Sox Nation, is still hanging on.
</P>
<P>
   In 1901, when they were still called the Boston Americans, the
Sox became a charter member of the new American League. Now, in
their 100th season, comes that all-too-familiar cry: ``Could this
be the year?''
</P>
<P>
   Well . . . maybe.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are still the Yankees, aiming to become the first
team since Dick Williams's fighting Oakland A's of the mid-'70s to
win three pennants in a row. For once, George Steinbrenner kept a
pat hand, though the Boss is sure to swing into action at the first
hint of weakness.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians, humiliated by the Sox in October, have beefed up
their pitching. Seattle lost Junior Griffey but has better balance.
Texas loaded up on lefthanders. Toronto has the next great closer
in Billy Koch. And nobody laughs at Oakland anymore.
</P>
<P>
   So where does that leave the Sox, who have won 92 and 94 games
in the last two seasons? The view in February, as pitchers and
catchers assemble Sunday morning under Jimy Williams for their
first official workout of spring, is that they have the talent to
make another run at a pennant.
</P>
<P>
   But here are 10 things that have to go right:
</P>
<P>
   1. Pedro must stay healthy. It all begins and ends on his skinny
right shoulder. Martinez took more time off this winter to rest
after a year in which he broke down once in midsummer, again in
October, and still had a season for the ages. Can he do it again?
Of course he can. All the great ones do. But there's a reason
pitching coach Joe Kerrigan gives him a blow as often as he can.
With an extra day's rest last season, Martinez was 13-0.
</P>
<P>
   2. Older brother Ramon has to be healthy, too. Ramon Martinez's
importance to the staff becomes even greater in the absence of Bret
Saberhagen, who claims to be ahead of schedule in yet another
comeback from shoulder surgery but cannot be counted on for even
the modest 119 innings he gave the Sox last season. Ramon turns
just 32 next month, and while the odometer has been turned back
once on his shoulder, he could be a dominant force in this league
if healthy. The guess here is that he is.
</P>
<P>
   3. Derek Lowe cuts it as closer. His credentials as a setup man
were impeccable and he thrived down the stretch as closer. There's
little wiggle room for the Sox if Lowe falters. Rod Beck has the
credentials but also a creaky elbow. And the rest of the bullpen
has to step up and close down the opposition in the seventh and
eighth innings the way Lowe did.
</P>
<P>
   4. Everett doesn't need a season to acclimate to the American
League. He's played only in the National League, for the Marlins,
Mets, and Astros, and leaves Houston with considerable reluctance.
Even with Houston's Killer B's, Craig Biggio and Jeff Bagwell, a
lot of folks (including former ace Mike Hampton) say Everett was
the team's MVP when it won the NL Central last season. He could
make a similar impact on the Sox lineup.
</P>
<P>
   5. There's a safety net in place if Brian Daubach stumbles. The
Belleville Basher delivered huge hits all last summer, and came
through with two home runs in the playoffs, too, but his slump from
mid-August to the end of the season has raised some alarms. It
should help that with Everett here, he'll be hitting lower in the
order, but if Daubach is overmatched early, the Sox might have to
accelerate Dernell Stenson's timetable to the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   6. The Sox have a fallback plan if Jeff Fassero washes out.
Fassero had elbow surgery to remove bone chips in '98 and followed
that with the worst season of his career, a 5-14 record and a 7.20
ERA. That ERA was the highest among pitchers with 150 innings since
Jim Walkup (7.36) in 1937. Another year of rest and a reunion with
Kerrigan may help, but Duquette is clearly in the market for
another starter. The Twins' Brad Radke would be a great fit.
</P>
<P>
   7. The Sox do a better job of catching the ball. They made 127
errors last season, and while Jose Offerman proved better than
expected at second base, he still had trouble turning the double
play. One scout warned last summer that Garciaparra would get
crushed out there if Offerman doesn't give him more timely and
consistent feeds. With Mike Stanley (11 errors) and Daubach sharing
first base, the right side of the infield is no bargain.
</P>
<P>
   8. John Valentin shows up for the regular season. Valentin was
awesome in October, driving in 17 runs, but he was a .250 hitter
from April to September for the second straight season. He has had
his knee cleaned out and is the type to respond to the challenge
posed by Veras, but it wouldn't be a shock if he were traded.
</P>
<P>
   9. One (or more) of the kid pitchers steps up. Brian Rose is as
strong as he's ever been, Juan Pena is supposedly over his shoulder
miseries, Ohka was unbeaten (15-0) in the minors with a big-league
splitter, and Kim dominated in the Arizona Fall League. At least
one pitcher in this bunch has to deliver, and don't be surprised if
Duquette uses some of the surplus _ along with a tradeable Scott
Hatteberg _ to land a veteran pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   10. Williams keeps the same clubhouse karma that has been here
the last two years. The surprise last season was how well this club
kept its focus after losing Mo Vaughn. There remains a good mix of
strictly-business veterans (Stanley, Darren Lewis, Ramon Martinez)
and old-school younger players (Garciaparra, Jason Varitek, Trot
Nixon).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
