<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-BIRD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRD BUYS IDEA OF OWNING CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Larry Bird has heard about all the back-to-Boston
stories that have surfaced in the last week since he said he wasn't
going to stick around Indiana. He gets a kick out of them.
</P>
<P>
   But there's one scenario that hasn't been mentioned that Bird
said would have him back in Boston in a nanosecond: as the owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could get people together to buy the team in a day,'' Bird
said. ``I could get it done tomorrow. Let's get the ball rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, consider it done. (It is kind of strange to hear Bird
talking in high-finance terms. This is, after all, the same person
who didn't leave a tip after his first meal in New York because he
thought it was overpriced.)
</P>
<P>
   Bird does own a piece of the Pacers, but he said he would gladly
sell if he were able to front a group to buy the Celtics. You can
probably assume commissioner David Stern would love to have Bird
involved in Boston ownership, and Bird made it clear that if it
ever did happen, he would be more like Michael Jordan (active) than
Magic Johnson (investor).
</P>
<P>
   Indiana had hoped Bird would move into its front office next
season, and the invitation still stands. But Bird surprised his
bosses when he said last week in Boston he'd be going to Florida
instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``I'm not really interested in
(Indiana's front office) right now.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he won't return to Boston under the current
ownership, which hardly comes as a shocker. He threw some darts at
chairman of the board Paul Gaston in his last book, and he threw a
few more last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kills me,'' he said, ``is that (Rick) Pitino is taking
all the hits there. Yeah, he's made some moves that didn't work
out. But the reason they're in the state they're in is because of
the owner. He's the one who put M.L. (Carr) in there. When we had a
championship team in 1984, those owners (Gaston's father and two
others) did only one thing over the next five years _ they brought
in DJ (Dennis Johnson). They got (Bill) Walton, too, but he called
them. They knew what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird spent five unfulfilling years as a Celtic ``consultant''
under Dave Gavitt and Carr. Versions differ as to why he left the
team in 1997 to coach the Pacers. Gaston, who became the Celtics'
head honcho in 1992, said Bird always had an open invitation to run
the show. Bird said if that was the case, he never knew about it.
He also said his suggestions and advice were continually ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Gaston was traveling over the weekend; efforts to reach him were
unsuccessful. (He's also smart enough to know you don't get into a
verbal skirmish in Boston with Larry Bird.) He has said in the past
that while he fields many inquiries to sell the Celtics, the team
is not for sale. Last week, he said his objective is to make the
team competitive while running it like a business, adding, ``I know
of no other way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird laughed at that one.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sounds like the Clippers to me,'' he said. Gaston's
Celtics, Bird said, have ``been a cash cow there for years. He
wants people to buy tickets, get good crowds, and make $8
million-$10 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought that the owner of the Celtics wanted to win a
championship, not just be competitive. Tell him I'm ready to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep an eye on Sixers
</P>
<P>
   With the Knicks (Charlie Ward, Marcus Camby) and the Heat (Dan
Majerle) each missing key people, the team to watch in the Eastern
Conference may well be the 76ers. They made a huge deal in getting
Toni Kukoc, and they are not that far off the pace, assuming Kukoc
embraces the move and doesn't go into a sulk. ``In the short run,''
said Nets GM John Nash, ``Philadelphia gets a player who will help
them in the playoffs. He can stretch defenses, and it will be
interesting to see how it works out because he might not be the
defensive player they're accustomed to having at the position.''
They'll get a good test Sunday afternoon from the Lakers. Nash and
his Boston counterpart, Chris Wallace, each think the deal benefits
all three teams. The Warriors got Larry Hughes and Billy Owens (for
a second go-around), while Chicago got a free agent (John Starks)
and a high draft pick. ``Golden State doesn't have its own pick, so
in getting Hughes, they get a guy with two years in the league
who's a talent and ahead of the learning curve,'' Wallace said.
``He's a guy who can make plays and goes to the basket.'' The Bulls
get even more cap room and undoubtedly will spend on someone. The
risk for Philly is re-signing Kukoc. ``I'm not sure Europe is as
big for him as it was for Dino Radja,'' Wallace said. ``From what I
understand, his kids are in school here, and he's a big golf fan.
And while he is a good player, I don't think that the teams
accumulating cap room are doing it necessarily with an eye on
him.'' . . . Just in case you were wondering, statistics guru
Harvey Pollack keeps track of players who have shots blocked the
most, and Antoine Walker was only 15th last year. The stats are not
up to date for this year, however. Walker had 51 shots rejected
last season, according to Pollack's data, well behind league leader
Shareef Abdur-Rahim, who had 106 swatted away . . . Rony Seikaly
has just started jogging and shooting in his attempt to make a
comeback at the age of 34. Seikaly played only nine games for New
Jersey last season and was waived in August. He said he was waived
not because he couldn't play, which was the Nets' contention, but
because he was injured. A grievance is scheduled to be heard early
next month on the matter. Seikaly is working out in Florida and,
according to his agent, Steve Kauffman, wants to get back ASAP.
``He definitely wants to play,'' Kauffman said. ``I know the
perception has been that he doesn't really care, but that is not
true. He's an incredibly competitive person, and he wants to play
badly. He wants to show those people that think that that they're
wrong.'' Kauffman said he's heard from ``a bunch of teams,''
although they know Seikaly is a long way away from being ready to
play NBA basketball. He had a very complicated foot injury _
Kauffman said it's most often associated with ballet dancers _ that
has taken time to heal . . . Going into the weekend, Bird had a
winning percentage of 70.8 in his two-plus seasons as Pacers coach.
That would rank second only to Phil Jackson on the all-time list.
Is there any wonder why Indiana keeps hoping Bird will change his
mind? (He's also third all-time in playoff winning percentage.)
</P>
<P>
   Canada is Carter country
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be nice if Vince Carter at least appeared in a
playoff game before we coronate him as Michael II? Yes, he's a very
nifty player, but let's face it, his popularity comes from the fact
that he's a spectacular dunker. When Carter passed through Boston
last month, a bunch of reporters waited for him after the
shootaround to talk about many things, including the upcoming
Slam-Dunk competition. Carter blew them all off and was insistent
on not talking about the Slam Dunk. Well, on the night of the
competition last weekend, he had Canadian TV viewers riveted,
drawing ratings that approximated those for a Stanley Cup game. The
competition produced the highest rating for any basketball event
ever shown on TSN (the Canadian equivalent of ESPN), with an
average of 610,000 viewers, including a staggering 852,000 during
the final round. To put those numbers in perspective, a normal
Raptors game on TSN usually attracts about 130,000 viewers. ``For
us, anything close to a million viewers is huge,'' said TSN's Chris
Doyle. The largest viewership in TSN's 15-year history came 13
months ago, when 1.8 million tuned in to see the Canadians battle
the Russians in a world junior hockey tournament. The Slam Dunk
competition outdrew even the Calgary-Phoenix hockey game . . . It
didn't take Nets president Michael Rowe long to back off his
promise to travel to all road games so he could ``interface''
better with the team's basketball people. He was not on the
traveling roster for Sunday's nationally televised game in
Minnesota. The game, New Jersey's only NBC appearance this season,
not only will mark Marbury's first return to his beloved Twin
Cities (he has since called the place basically unlivable) but also
will be played on his 23d birthday. ``It's like, let me have a bad
birthday,'' Marbury said . . . Bird's favorite Pacers lineup: Jalen
Rose, Reggie Miller, Austin Croshere, Dale Davis, and Derrick
McKey. ``That's a hell of a lineup,'' he said. ``They can defend
and score.'' Bird said he's glad he won't have to deal with Rose's
impending free agency, but said of Croshere, ``I thought he'd be
this good last year.'' . . . The Mavericks did indeed sell out for
Dennis Rodman's debut. But in the second home game, the one in
which Rodman was ejected, the Mavs drew 11,912 to see Milwaukee.
Undaunted, would-be owner Mark Cuban predicted a much bigger crowd
for Thursday's game with the Pistons, a prediction made prior to
Rodman's suspension. The crowd: 16,241. The Mavs won, as well. They
were 0-2 in their first two games with Rodman . . . Speaking of
anemic support, the Cavs had a shade over 12,000 for their game
against the Nuggets Thursday, extending their non-sellout streak to
26. How bad has it been? The eight lowest crowds in the six-year
history of Gund Arena have come this season . . . Amid swirling
rumors that the Suns are hot after Dikembe Mutombo, both Jason Kidd
and Tom Gugliotta pleaded with the bosses to keep the team intact.
The Suns are starting to get it done at both ends of the floor and
have their roster intact for the first time in a while. Kidd,
however, acknowledged the obvious: ``It's up to the men upstairs.
They're the ones who call the shots.'' Gugliotta has a 15 percent
trade kicker on top of his hefty $8.5 million salary. He has been
mentioned as the major player in the Mutombo rumor . . . The
Nuggets had lost 15 straight road games against Western Conference
opponents until beating the Timberwolves in overtime Tuesday. The
Wolves then had one of those delightful back-to-backs, having to
fly to New York for a Wednesday game. They lost that one, too . . .
The Rockets were fined $5,000 for allowing the halftime ceremony
honoring Clyde Drexler to go for 36 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
