<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SLUMP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS IN COMMON SLUMP WITHOUT A CURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kyle McLaren, who was on the last Bruins team that didn't make
the playoffs (1997), says the current edition, which is in a
struggle for its postseason life, bears no resemblance to the sad
sack club that finished as the worst Boston team in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no similarities at all,'' he said. ``It's a
different team, different style, different coach. It's totally
different. There's nothing the same.''
</P>
<P>
   But McLaren and the rest of the Bruins have had a hard time
putting their finger on what has caused this team to go 18-24-16 as
it prepares to take on the Vancouver Canucks Monday night in the
first of a four-game road trip. To a man, they all thought they
would be in significantly better shape at this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if we'd be first or second in our division, but
I thought we'd be there battling it out and making sure we make it
to the playoffs,'' said McLaren. ``It still frustrates me. I still
wonder why we're not there. The bottom line is we haven't played up
to expectations from ourselves or anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every day I wonder what's going on, especially when
you're 4 points out of a playoff position. It's hard not to think
about what's going on and what we can do to change this thing
around. Every day you come up with new answers, but the bottom line
is we have to win. If you win, it takes care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   True. But with this team, the victories have been few and far
between. They've managed but one strong streak and that lasted a
month, back in late October and November. The rest of the time,
it's been too few wins, too many losses, and a boatload of ties.
That makes this trip _ half in Western Canada, the rest on the East
Coast _ more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not playing as well as we'd like to,'' said McLaren.
``It's a time to come to jell together and play together; we have
to. Everyone is saying it's a big time for us, and it is. It's one
of the biggest trips we've taken so far this year. We need the
points. We need them worse than anybody we're playing against.''
</P>
<P>
   As time has gone on, McLaren said, he isn't sure if the reasons
for their struggles have become any clearer. He said it's more
prudent to deal in cold, hard numbers than in philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it comes down to less wins,'' he said. ``You have to
win games to get into the playoffs. We have 16 ties and 18 wins. If
you turn those 16 ties into five ties and turn the others into
wins, we're right in the hunt. Maybe that's a small answer right
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play hard and the work ethic is there, we just can't finish
the games. It's been a roller coaster season and this is the part
where you want it to go up and keep going up until April.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the wish of players, coaches, and management alike, but
too often with this team, it hasn't equaled the sum of its parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the lineups from team to team and we should beat
teams,'' said McLaren. ``There's no lack of effort or lack of skill
to not beat those teams. We have got to be greedy. We have to hate
every team we play against. We've seen it with some teams, Buffalo
and Carolina. But it has to be there on a more consistent basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have the killer instinct to bury teams when we have
the chance, and sometimes we can't or we don't. It's not for lack
of trying; we've tried. The bounces have not gone our way this
whole entire year. Other teams have had bunches, dozens.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, McLaren said, there's no question that the
sense of urgency can be greater. McLaren realizes what it's like to
sit out the postseason and doesn't want to go through it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our jobs are on the line every night, especially when you're
not in the playoffs,'' he said. ``You don't know who's staying or
who's going at the end of the year. Anything can happen. If we
don't make the playoffs, there are more changes than not.''
</P>
<P>
   With 24 games remaining, McLaren won't concede that the team is
in an impossible situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're in trouble,'' he said, ``but we are
fighting for a playoff spot. I don't think you can write us off. We
realize where we are, and we know we have to pick it up. It's do or
die.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
