<DOCNO> NYT20000219.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2348 &Cx1f; ttj-z
b p BC-SC-PRIMARY-4THLD-WRIT     02-19 1531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-PRIMARY-4THLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     BUSH BEATS McCAIN IN SOUTH CAROLINA; MICHIGAN NEXT  
 &HT;     (EDS: PRECEDES CHARLESTON-dated story.)  
 &HT;     (EDS: New 3rd graf with late numbers; new 4th graf with Bush
victory statement.) ) 
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL And DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush decisively revived
his flagging front-runner campaign for the Republican presidential
nomination, exit polls showed Saturday, fighting off a scrappy
challenge by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., in the South Carolina
primary and catapulting their bitter struggle into big state
showdowns beginning with Michigan on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls showed that Bush rode to victory on a tidal wave of
GOP voters who turned out in record numbers across the
predominantly conservative piedmont region to overwhelm McCain's
less-than-expected support among many non-Republican voters who
could legally vote in the open primary.
</P>
<P>
   With one-third of the vote counted, Bush had 74,083 votes, or 53
percent to McCain's 58,787, 42 percent. Alan Keyes ran a faraway
third at 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's victory was projected on the basis of interviews
conducted by Voter News Service as voters left their polling
places.
</P>
<P>
   In his victory statement at a hotel rally about two hours after
the polls closed, Bush said he was ``honored and humbled by this
huge victory. South Carolina has spoken, and tonight there are only
263 days more to the end of Clinton-Gore!''
</P>
<P>
   Bush took a phone call from McCain at 7:08 p.m. when the Arizona
senator conceded the race. ``I'm very grateful for the phone
call,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on how far he has come since his defeat in the Feb. 1
New Hampshire Primary, Bush said: ``I fell down in the snow (in New
Hampshire, but) I knocked the snow off my suit and came down
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Stung by the size of his loss, McCain struck a defiant tone in
his concession speech before flying to Michigan. He vowed to go
forward with his reformist crusade, ``to offer voters a choice
between a record of reform and an empty slogan of reform, a choice
between experience and pretense.''
</P>
<P>
   He wished Bush ``a good night's rest.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain added: ``He's going to need it, my friends, for we have
just begun to fight. And I cannot wait for the next round.''
</P>
<P>
   The exit polls showed that 9 percent of those voting Saturday
were Democrats. Of those, 82 percent supported McCain and 16
percent said they voted for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The polls also showed that 31 percent of voters were
independents. Of those, 34 percent were for Bush and 61 percent
were for McCain. That's a much bigger-than-expected margin for
Bush. In New Hampshire among independents, McCain got 61 percent
and Bush got 19 percent. Among Democrats in New Hampshire, Bush got
10 percent and McCain got 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   CNN projected turnout at 600,000, more than double the 276,000
who voted in the 1996 South Carolina Republican Primary.
</P>
<P>
   Religious conservatives went for Bush 3-1, exit polls showed.
Unlike New Hampshire, Bush tailored his South Carolina message to
fit ``the pro-life agenda,'' said Randy Tate, former executive
director of the Christian Coalition now with Voter.com, a
politics-oriented website. ``These are the issues that motivate the
grassroots activists to walk the precincts,
</P>
<P>
   and bring the Reagan Democrats out to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush now has won four of five Republican contests _ Alaska,
Iowa, New
</P>
<P>
   Hampshire and South Carolina. McCain has won one, New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   By winning here in a southern state that has voted reliably
Republican in eight of the last 10 presidential elections, Bush
energized a campaign that had been stunned by McCain's upset
victory in New Hampshire's Feb. 1 primary. The Bush win helps him
allay campaign donors' anxieties, stem threatened defections by
worried Republican office holders and stun McCain's momentum.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who had hoped to parlay his come-from-behind victory in
New Hampshire into a second upset here, came away from the contest
with ample evidence that he appeals to the independents and
Democrats who can vote in 16 of the next 24 GOP presidential
primaries. McCain vowed to carry on with his populist insurgency at
least until Super Tuesday, March 7, when New York, California and
Ohio join 13 less populous states to hold primaries and caucuses
that could settle the struggle for the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's triumph in an 18-day slugfest stemmed in part from a
shift in strategy from being a tax-cutting ``compassionate
conservative'' who lost to McCain by 19 percentage points in New
Hampshire to becoming a ``reformer with results'' who ardently
courted the state's religious and social conservatives and
challenged McCain's proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spoke at conservative Bob Jones University where
inter-racial dating is prohibited and he refused to challenge the
GOP platform's call for an absolute ban on abortions, even though
he favors exceptions to save the mother's life or to end
pregnancies that result from rape or incest.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's turn to the right risked alienating the
middle-of-the-road voters who often decide the outcome of the
industrial state primaries that lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Whit Ayres, an Atlanta-based Republican pollster who is not
working for any GOP presidential candidate, said the victory
enables Bush to retain ``the mantle of the front-runner,'' adding:
``It's a tremendous boost for Bush. It allows you to say that once
again, the nomination is Bush's to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's victory is expected to help entice a sorely needed
infusion of campaign donations into a fast-spending juggernaut that
has already spent more than $50 million of the $68 million in
donations. He heads into Michigan where three-term Gov. John Engler
has vowed to deliver the state to Bush. Bush's hand is also
strengthened in follow-on contests in Virginia and Washington on
Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sabato, professor of government at the University of
Virginia, said Bush's victory may be seen in hindsight as ``the
turning point that enabled Bush to go on to victory,'' adding:
``This is too big a victory for McCain to spin.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Ballenger, editor of the influential Inside Michigan
Politics newsletter and a radio talk show host, said the magnitude
of Bush's victory in South Carolina could discourage turnout by the
independents and Democrats that McCain is counting upon to keep him
competitive in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their attitude now might be 'Why bother to vote?''' Ballenger
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain showered South Carolina's 2.1 million registered
voters with more than $5.9 million worth of often hard-nosed
campaign ads during the longest presidential primary campaign in
state history. Previously, South Carolina held its primary just
four days after New Hampshire's.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &LR;  &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina has a 20-year history of picking Republican
winners. The GOP winner in South Carolina has never failed to go on
and capture the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls showed Bush built his win on a healthy core
Republican turnout.
</P>
<P>
   About 61 percent of voters Saturday identified themselves as
Republicans. Among them, 68 percent said they voted for Bush and 26
percent said they voted for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also did better than expected among independents, who along
with Democrats were free to cast ballots in the state's Republican
primary. Exit polls showed that fewer independents and Democrats
turned out than McCain had hoped for. Just 30 percent of the voters
were independents and 9 percent were Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Bush managed to carry 35 percent of the independent voters _ a
far stronger showing among independents than Bush scored in New
Hampshire where he won only 19 percent of the independents.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``played to win rather than playing not to loose, like in
New Hampshire,'' said Ayres, adding that Bush had succeeded in
shifting voters' focus away from McCain's heroic biography as a
Navy pilot and prisoner of war in Vietnam to his policy proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain's agenda is much less compelling to Republican
audiences, whether its taxes or campaign finance reform,'' Ayres
said. ``This is going to buck up the Bush forces big time.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain complained early in the day that state GOP officials had
failed to open many precinct-voting stations where Democrats and
independents lived, including 21 polling stations in Greenville
County. South Carolina law requires party officials to staff
polling places. Of the state's 1,700 polling places, 1,454 were
open _ twice the number that were open for the 1996 GOP
presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just disappointing that anyone anywhere in South Carolina
is deprived of the ability to vote,'' McCain said. ``That's just
not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   State GOP officials consolidated 21 polling places in Greenville
County at the last minute, requiring voters to travel to
alternative sites. ``From the reports we're getting everywhere,
everything is goingsmooth,'' said state GOP director J. Sam
Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell and Dan Freedman can be reached at
202-298-6920.)
</P>
</TEXT>
