<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVENTING PRESIDENT MCCLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 ALSO MOVED IN ``A'' CATEGORY 
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ If John McCain becomes the next president of the
United States, the person most responsible will be McCain's mentor,
archetype and political guru _ Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if the mirror sequence from ``Duck Soup'' has come to
life, with Harpo McCain mimicking every move of Groucho Clinton,
making two men who have little in common appear exactly alike. For
instance:
</P>
<P>
   _ Clinton was a Democrat running as a Republican; McCain is a
Republican running as a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   _Clinton came from a small state and wasn't given a chance;
McCain is from a small state and wasn't given a chance.
</P>
<P>
   _Clinton pretended to be an outsider; McCain pretends to be an
outsider.
</P>
<P>
   _Clinton had a bus; McCain has a bus.
</P>
<P>
   _Clinton was a fun guy whose opposition was a stiff; McCain is a
fun guy whose opposition is a stiff.
</P>
<P>
   _Clinton's checkered past was ignored; McCain's checkered past
is ignored.
</P>
<P>
   _Clinton claimed to be bucking the Democratic establishment;
McCain claims to be bucking the Republican establishment.
</P>
<P>
   _Clinton didn't; McCain isn't.
</P>
<P>
   You don't get to be the chairman of the Senate Commerce
Committee, like McCain, if you're ``anti-establishment.'' That's
why the rich guys whose industry he regulates give McCain so much
money.
</P>
<P>
   Also, if you're a third-term member of the most exclusive club
in the world, the U.S. Senate, you ARE an insider, no matter what
you say.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did the same thing. He also realized that outside of
Arkansas, no one cared about his past problems. McCain understands
this, too.
</P>
<P>
   Do you remember what Charles Keating, poster boy for the savings
and loan disaster that cost taxpayers billions, said about the
politicians to whom he'd donated truckloads of cash?
</P>
<P>
   No, you don't. Just as you don't remember the $112,000 McCain
took from Keating, along with vacation trips to the Bahamas and
more.
</P>
<P>
   Keating said, ``One question . . . raised in recent weeks had to
do with whether my financial support in any way influenced several
political figures to take up my cause. I want to say in the most
forceful way I can: I certainly hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   How about this?
</P>
<P>
   Do you remember the study done by ``Congressional Quarterly'' in
1997 that showed McCain voting with Clinton 70 percent of the time?
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Clinton and McCain have agreed on normalizing
relations with Vietnam, on campaign finance reform, on anti-tobacco
legislation and other showy issues that can mask a politician's
true colors.
</P>
<P>
   _Clinton talks like a moderate but is a liberal; McCain talks
like a moderate but is a hard-core conservative.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, McCain told ``The Republic's'' Jeff Barker, ``There are
mavericks that are outside the pale of their party, and they're
always just throwing darts. I have a legislative record. I think if
you look at my voting record, it fundamentally has not changed.''
</P>
<P>
   None of that stuff matters. Clinton and now McCain have proved
the old proverb wrong: Words DO speak louder than deeds.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has patterned his 2000 campaign after what Clinton did in
1992 and 1996, and it just might work.
</P>
<P>
   As for McCain's hero status, it's overplayed. Sen. Bob Kerrey of
Nebraska is a Medal of Honor recipient, a bigger hero, but he
couldn't get elected president. McCain, like Clinton, has something
better going for him.
</P>
<P>
   _The media loved Clinton; the media REALLY love McCain. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reach Montini at Ed.Montini(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8978. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
