u s BC-GLF-NISSAN-1STLD-WRIT     02-19 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NISSAN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUTHERLAND LEADS, BUT WOODS IS LURKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (UPDATES with results of 3rd round) 
 (rk) 
 By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PACIFIC PALISADES, Calif. _ It was difficult enough to dodge the
bumps, footprints and spike marks that made every green at Riviera
Country Club a potential three-putt for bogey or worse. Now, the
leaders of the Nissan Open have another yet familiar factor to
fear.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods moved into the passing lane during Saturday's third
round, carding a 2-under 69 that easily put him within striking
distance of a seventh victory in his last eight PGA Tour
tournaments. Woods finished at 6-under 207 and trailed by three
strokes. He came perilously close to shooting himself out of
contention, but was helped by two late birdies and opponents who
could not take the lead lower than 9-under 204.
</P>
<P>
   David Sutherland, a journeyman who will celebrate his 34th
birthday on Sunday while searching for his first PGA Tour victory,
grabbed first place with a birdie at No. 17, sneaking past a crowd
of marquee names. Among six players at 8-under 205 were Jesper
Parnevik, who shot a second straight 67, and Rocco Mediate, who
fired a 64 and climbed the leader board after surviving the cut by
one stroke.
</P>
<P>
   The logjam continued at 7-under, where 12 players settled after
54 holes. Included were two-time U.S. Open winner Lee Janzen (69),
Fred Couples (68) and Scott Hoch (69).
</P>
<P>
   But the buzz was about Woods, who shook off a poor start that at
one stage put him eight strokes behind. He four-putted at No. 13
for a double bogey _ from 12 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   But Woods pieced together his putting stroke and made five
birdies, including three on the back nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did all right just to hang in there,'' Woods said. ``It all
depends on the weather conditions. The forecast is supposed to be
ugly. If that's the case, I just need to be patient, make a lot of
pars, hit a lot of solid shots and take my opportunities when I
have them.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Woods: ``Other than that, it's not rocket science out
there. I just need to give myself a lot of chances to make some
putts.''
</P>
<P>
   The weather forecast was for rain and some wind. Another
forecast might call for a duel down the stretch between Woods and
Parnevik, the No. 1 and 2 players on this year's tour money list,
who were paired together in Saturday's third round. Both already
own victories. Woods won the Mercedes Championships and AT&AMP;T Pebble
Beach National Pro-Am, and Parnevik won the Bob Hope Chrysler
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Like Woods, Parnevik four-putted a hole, the par-3 No. 4. His
birdie attempt from 25 feet hit the hole, but spun away, leaving
him a four-footer for par. Parnevik missed his next two tries and
took double bogey. Like Woods, he recovered, sinking short birdie
putts on the next three holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect a couple of guys to go low tomorrow, including
myself,'' Parnevik said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he, too, will be watching Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he's playing, he could pretty much shoot zero around
here,'' Parnevik said. ``But anybody who's in the lead isn't going
to be comfortable because you've got so many people near the
lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods began the third round five shots behind. Despite his
rally, he only made up two shots, although it was enough to raise
the other players' attention significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't physically throw him down in the fairway and beat
him that way,'' said Brandel Chamblee, who was one shot from the
lead and will be one of those players looking in his rearview
mirror for Woods. ``But I'm going to do everything I can to beat
him or whoever's up there. I've seen his game, I know what he can
do. Every time you see it, you think there's no way he can do that
again. And then he does it the next week. I'd like to be the one
he's trying to do it to.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamblee will have to get in line. Of 71 players in the
tournament, 29 are within three strokes of Sutherland. The crowd at
the top resulted from unpredictable rolls on the greens, where the
mysteries of poa annua grass led to frayed nerves, especially on
short putts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greens are a little bit doggy,'' said Parnevik, who also
three-putted No. 15 from about 15 feet. ``They're soft and bouncy,
so you have to be firm with your putts, but then you'll get a
little too aggressive and have a bunch of four-footers to look at.
You have to really die the ball in the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutherland, who split time between the regular tour and what was
called the Nike Tour for most of his 10-year career, stayed away
from taking extra putts. Neither of his two bogeys were caused by
miscues around the hole, instead resulting from poor approach
shots. He was in trouble at No. 2, but made a clutch eight-foot
putt to save bogey. His hit a wayward tee shot at the par-3 sixth
hole and failed to chip up and save par. Sutherland carded five
birdies, including a 10-footer at par-5 17th that gave him the
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not exactly Tiger Woods,'' Sutherland said. ``I led a
tournament once and finished second, so I did OK. I've never been
in this position in a tournament of this stature. I won't look at
the leader board until the back nine, about the 16th green.
Hopefully, I'll see something good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
