<DOCNO> NYT20000219.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2351 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GOP-MICHIGAN0220-COX     02-19 1552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-MICHIGAN0220-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP battle moves into Michigan
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Arizona Sen.
John McCain today begin two days of intensive campaigning that will
provide the first real test of their presidential appeal in a
populous, diverse state that mirrors the nation as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates are scheduled to arrive in Michigan early this
morning after leaving South Carolina, which held its Republican
primary Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A poll published in today's Detroit News shows Bush and McCain
in a virtual tie in Michigan, with McCain at 40 percent and Bush at
38 percent. The survey had a 4 percent margin of error and was
conducted with 600 likely voters inclduing Republicans, Democrats
and independents.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's Michigan chairman, state senator John Schwarz, said the
negative attack strategy that Bush used in South Carolina won't
work in Michigan. ``Voters here in Michigan expect a thoughtful,
issue-based discussion not a Dixie mud brawl.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Michigan chairman, Gov. John Engler, said ``It's a very
good night for George Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   He said South Carolina results showed Bush's broad support and
he expects that to continue in Michigan but there'll be no let up
in campaigning. ``This is a very strong win coming back from New
Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan and Arizona have Republican contests Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-eight delegates are at stake in Michigan's Republican
presidential primary, the biggest single-state prize so far. Three
delegates will be selected from each of the state's 16
congressional districts, with the winner taking all in each
district. Ten additional delegates will be awarded to the candidate
who receives the most votes statewide.
</P>
<P>
   The Michigan Republican primary, which also includes
conservative activist Alan Keyes, is open to all voters, much like
South Carolina's vote Saturday. The ballot also includes a
Democratic ticket, but lists only perennial fringe candidate Lyndon
LaRouche. Vice President Al Gore and former New Jersey Sen. Bill
Bradley have chosen to participate in the closed caucuses being run
by the state Democratic Party on March 11.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Secretary of State Candice Miller, a Bush supporter,
projects a turnout of 950,000, 14 percent of the registered voters,
up from the 746,000, 11 percent turnout of four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush and McCain last week slugged it out in South
Carolina, Bush backers here, including his father, former President
George Bush, have concentrated on getting as many Republican voters
as possible to the polls, while McCain supporters openly wooed
independents and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign even sent postcards to Democrats urging them
to vote for the Arizona senator.
</P>
<P>
   Separate from the McCain campaign, Democratic opponents of Gov.
John Engler, head of the state's Bush campaign, are urging
Democrats, particularly black voters in the populous Detroit area,
to embarrass Engler by voting for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Engler, who's mentioned as a possible vice presidential
candidate or a Bush cabinet member, worked to put the Michigan
primary at the beginning of the nominating process in an attempt to
help Bush and to provide a ``firewall'' for the Texas governor in
case he faltered in the early states.
</P>
<P>
   A loss here would be a major ``embarrassment'' for Engler said
James Penning, a political science professor at Calvin College in
Grand Rapids. ``He has a big stake in this. He endorsed Bush early.
He worked hard to change the primary system. ...That's now looking
like a questionable move.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins here would have bragging rights as the candidate
with the broadest appeal as the campaign moves to other major
states, including Ohio, New York and California, for primaries and
caucuses on March 7, which has been dubbed Titanic Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Michigan voters are pretty much a microcosm of the
voters nationwide,'' Penning said.
</P>
<P>
   The primary campaign has reflected the changing nature of
Michigan's Republican politics.
</P>
<P>
   William Milliken, a moderate Republican governor in the late
1970s and early '80s, has endorsed McCain. As governor, Milliken
engineered George Bush's win over Ronald Reagan in the 1980
Michigan Republican primary in which the elder Bush was considered
the moderate alternative to Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning here last week, former President Bush said it was
his 1980 victory in Michigan that prompted Reagan to choose him as
his vice president.
</P>
<P>
   In Warren, Irene Hammond, 65, a retiree from the K-Mart Corp.,
said she voted for the elder Bush twice for president but hasn't
decided whether to back his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say it is tough,'' she said. ``Both men are very
good.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who survived five years as a prisoner of war after his
Navy plane was shot down over North Vietnam, is impressive, she
said. ``You can't take away his real life experience.''
</P>
<P>
   A Republican, she still is irked by Engler's role in the Bush
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Engler but I don't like to have anything shoved down my
throat,'' Hammond said.
</P>
<P>
   Janice Nearon, the Republican chairman in MaComb County,
northeast of Detroit, said she is solidly behind Bush. ``I think
he's more conservative,'' Nearon said.
</P>
<P>
   The county is home to many of the so-called Reagan Democrats who
helped Republicans win three straight presidential elections
beginning in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   At a Lincoln Day Dinner in Flint later on Thursday, the
Republican establishment's support for the Texas governor was
obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Genesee County Republican Party, host of the
dinner, is officially neutral, President Bush delivered a campaign
speech for his son and Bush campaign material was distributed. Not
all the dinner guests had decided to back the Texas governor,
however.
</P>
<P>
   Clifton Stokes, an engineer for General Motors, described
himself as a ``conservative independent'' who hadn't made up his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do like McCain's war record. It really showed lots of
sacrifice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Coons, a grocery store employee, described himself as a
``conservative Christian'' and said he favored Bush. ``Neither one
was my first choice,'' said Coons, 49.
</P>
<P>
   Nor his second.
</P>
<P>
   He first backed former Vice President Dan Quayle and then
publisher Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go with the most conservative candidate who can
win,'' Coons said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the state in Lansing, Jerry Roe, 63, said McCain's
campaign had given hope to Republican moderates, who seldom have
been heard of during Engler's 10 years as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Roe, now a community college professor of political science, was
the state party's executive director when Milliken and George
Romney served as governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't that be awful to have a presidential candidate who
could get independent and Democratic votes?'' Roe asked
sarcastically.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to gauge how many Democrats will come out
Tuesday, particularly if the snow that hit Friday were to return.
</P>
<P>
   In Flint, however, Democratic activist Hal Lawson, a retired
broadcaster and college professor, got his postcard from the McCain
campaign on Friday and has decided to vote for the Arizona senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fascinated by the man. It's really got Bush worried,''
said Lawson, 75, a World War II Army veteran.
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, state Rep. LaMar Lemmons III, a Democrat, said the
campaign he's leading to get Democrats to support McCain really is
directed at Engler.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has treated Democrats, particularly those in
Detroit, unfairly, said Lemmons. He cited Engler's role in
replacing the city's elected school board with an appointed board.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Engler flyers are being distributed at churches in
predominantly black neighborhoods, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The support for McCain, if he were nominated, would not carry
over to the general election, said Lemmons, 43.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be Democrats the next day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to these efforts, controversial Democratic lawyer
Geoffrey Fieger, who represented suicide doctor Jack Kevorkian,
reportedly has created a political action committee that will run
an ad blasting Engler and Bush for their positions on lawsuit
reform. Fieger lost the 1998 gubernatorial election to Engler.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Shafer, Engler's deputy press secretary, said the governor
doesn't take such efforts personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been in this game too long to take it seriously,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has ``a great campaign'' in Michigan with ``great
grassroots support'' all across the state, Shafer said.
</P>
<P>
   Candice Miller, the secretary of state and Bush supporter, said
she does not think the turnout among non-Republicans will be of
``great proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Swift, a self-described moderate Republican who is
coordinating McCain's efforts in Lansing, said he's never seen
anything like McCain's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have an office. We don't have a phone. We don't have
a dime,'' said Swift, 70, an attorney. ``I have 27 voice mails this
morning. They want yard signs. They want bumper stickers. They want
to know how they can help. It's a real fever pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
