<SLUG> BC-SAIL-AMCUP-CAYARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUP IDEAS OVERFLOWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ Paul Cayard got some sand between his
toes in the past couple of weeks, and also a bit of hope about his
future in the America's Cup.
</P>
<P>
   After his 5-4 loss to Prada with AmericaOne in the challenger
finals, Cayard took off with his family to see some of New
Zealand's vacation spots, and now is back among the tens of
thousands of racing fans in Auckland watching the start of the
America's Cup, a spectacle anticipated in this South Pacific port
for nearly five years.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Cayard wanted to be sailing his boat in the match,
but he got nipped in an excruciating series by Italy's Prada.
</P>
<P>
   When it was all over, Cayard sounded bitter. He complained that
a lack of funding early in the campaign, coupled with Prada's $55
million war chest _ flush early, when it counts _ was too much to
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that there were so many US challengers (including two
from his home city of San Francisco) spread the money and talent
too thin and ``kept our country from putting its best foot
forward,'' said Cayard.
</P>
<P>
   So, no America in the America's Cup. It never happened before.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard's emotions have settled down, but he still believes in
his point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without adequate funding from the very beginning, it's
pointless to try and make a commitment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But since the Cup ended for him, Cayard says the responses to
his feelers on keeping AmericaOne going ``give me a lot of
confidence to dig in, though nothing will jell until this (Cup) is
over, or perhaps up to three months.''
</P>
<P>
   The first order of business is to get private donors lined up.
They can act more quickly than corporations, which make such
decisions at the boardroom level.
</P>
<P>
   Since the middle of the last campaign, Cayard, who tried to be
both syndicate manager and skipper, knew he was spread too thin.
The reason he had to handle both ends of ``an incredibly complex
organization'' was simple. It's what everything about the Cup comes
back to: money.
</P>
<P>
   The result: ``I just wasn't the sailor this time around that I
was in '92 or '95,'' he said. ``I had not put in enough time
sailing, with everything else that needed to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Prada campaign got rolling in 1998 with full funding
that gave the team a fast start, Cayard still was sailing the
Whitbread Round-the-World race _ which he won.
</P>
<P>
   Prada's founder and bankroller, Patrizio Bertelli, was able to
offer sailors decent money and, perhaps more important, at least
two years of security.
</P>
<P>
   Bertelli already had signed Francesco de Angelis, once with
Cayard's Whitbread campaign, to be Prada's skipper. But two other
key members of the Cayard team also defected _ longtime friend
Steve Erickson, and Laurent Esquier, a veteran of eight America's
Cups and now Prada's chief of operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people are huge,'' said Cayard, who at the time had
nothing to offer but his dream of a Whitbread/America's Cup double.
``Especially when we got into the finals, those people might have
made the difference. Losing them was a big negative for us and a
big positive for Prada.''
</P>
<P>
   Having enough start-up money also allows a campaign to sign on a
top designer and gather the materials necessary to start
construction. The best example of the latter is perhaps the Cuben
Fiber sailcloth, an exotic ``bulletproof'' lightweight material in
limited supply.
</P>
<P>
   Prada was able to corner the market on Cuben Fiber, at least in
the Cup. Hence, Prada had much better spinnakers than AmericaOne,
which was a great weapon in downwind duels.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard's vision is to be manager of his syndicate, which will
race the Volvo (formerly Whitbread) and then be ready for the next
America's Cup. Cayard says he will not try to fill both roles, as
skipper and manager, again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love sailing,'' he said, ``but if I do it, I have to focus
on it, like (New Zealand skipper) Russell Coutts.''
</P>
<P>
   But managing a complex syndicate also has its appeal. ``I really
like that game,'' Cayard said. ``I have a lot of experience and I
get some satisfaction from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cayard believes the US interests in the Cup would be best served
by just two, perhaps three syndicates, rather than the five that
came to Auckland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course you can't legislate it, but, from my point of view,
getting started earlier is the way to deal with the competition,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   His pick in the America's Cup? ``It makes me smile when I hear
people make predictions,'' he said. ``No one knows better than we
do, especially about Prada. And I don't have a clue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
