<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYANT'S BIG BURDEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Coming home hasn't been the most enjoyable
experience for Kobe Bryant the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, who attended high school here at Lower Merion before
jumping to the NBA in 1996, enjoys plenty of support from old
friends and family when the Lakers play here. But the last two
visits have both ended in Laker losses to the 76ers and
lightening-quick Allen Iverson.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant had the burden of guarding Iverson last year, and watched
him zip around screens to take 36 shots from the field and score 41
points in a 105-90 Sixers victory.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers coach Phil Jackson hasn't divulged who will defend
Iverson today - Bryant, veteran Ron Harper or Derek Fisher, who was
assigned to speedy Darrell Armstrong of the Magic on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But Bryant would welcome the assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really care. I look forward to any challenge, whether
it's guarding Al or guarding whoever,'' he said. ``When I'm on him,
I'm just going to play him. Yeah he's a big challenge, because he's
so little and he's quick. But y'all know me, you know I don't give
a damn.''
</P>
<P>
   In Jackson's mind, Iverson is not one man's burden to bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a team challenge, is what he is, not just an individual
challenge. He challenges the whole team,'' Jackson said. ``He's
very talented, he's resilient, he's determined, he's dogged about
scoring. He's unafraid. There are a lot of things about his game I
like. I don't like his style of play particularly, but that's what
they have to do to make themselves a potent team, and they do a
good job of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson leads the league in scoring at 31.2 points per game and
is also tops in field-goal attempts, 26.4 per game. He might be
able to ease up a bit, now that the Sixers have acquired former
Jackson pupil Toni Kukoc from the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, who beat the Bulls on Tuesday, a day before the
trade, face Kukoc for the second time in six days. He scored 14
points on 4-of-14 shooting in the first meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm glad we had one opportunity to get used to him,''
said Jackson. ``And the next time around, maybe we'll do a little
better job, although we did a pretty good job that game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal trails only Iverson in the scoring
race but isn't concerned with catching him. O'Neal won a scoring
title in 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never really tried to be the leading scorer,'' he said.
``I've got that little trophy at the house. I just play team ball.
He's a phenomenal player. Whatever happens, happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting words: Jackson unwittingly started a feud with Orlando
when he casually referred to it as a ``plastic city'' last week.
The Orlando Sentinel picked up on the comment and stripped a story
about it across the top of Friday's sports section. Jackson was
duly booed during pregame introductions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that all about?'' Jackson remarked about the story.
``Is this a redneck town or something, they have to start a fight
like this?... That's really pretty low stuff, journalistic-wise, if
you ask me. If that's what they need to do to have the fans
respond, that says even more about Orlando than I thought I made a
comment about.''
</P>
<P>
   LAKERS vs. PHILADELPHIA
</P>
<P>
   Tipoff: 2:30 p.m., First Union Center
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: Channel 4; KLAC-AM (570)
</P>
<P>
   Lakers (40-11) update: With three wins to open this six-game
road trip, the Lakers are now 16-2 against the Eastern Conference
and 7-1 on the road against East teams. They've lost three straight
to the Sixers, however, including a 105-90 loss here last season.
</P>
<P>
   76ers (28-23) update: They have been typically inconsistent and
are 4-3 in February. Allen Iverson leads the NBA in scoring (31.2
points per game) but is taking a league-leading 26.4 shots per game
to get it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Howard Beck
</P>
</TEXT>
