<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-MCCAIN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN VOWS TO FIGHT ON  
(rk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Hardly bowed by his double-digit defeat in
South Carolina, a defiant Sen. John McCain vowed Saturday night
that his ``crusade grows stronger'' and pledged that ``we have just
begun to fight and I cannot wait for the next round.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiling, fists clenched and sounding new themes that are likely
to get stronger as the bitter Republican primary battle moves on to
the big-state contests across the nation, McCain promised to keep
``fighting clean'' and drew an implicit but sharp contrast with
Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends I say to you I'm a uniter, not a divider,'' he
said, ``I don't just say it, I live it. I am a real reformer. I
don't say it I live it. And I am a fighter for this country. And I
don't just say it I live it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As this campaign moves forward, a clear choice will be
offered,'' he said. ``A choice between my optimistic and welcoming
conservatism and the negative message of fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Having watched Bush successfully take from him the mantle of
reform here by changing from a ``compassionate conservative'' to a
``reformer with results,'' McCain began a battle to redefine his
opponent once more, this time on his own terms. The voters he said
have ``a choice between a record of reform and an empty slogan of
reform. A choice between experience and pretense.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain walked into a Charleston ballroom to give his concession
speech to the music from Star Wars. But the crowd was small and the
senator's supporters were stunned by the breadth and magnitude of
his loss here much as they were surprised by the broad-based nature
of his 19-point New Hampshire victory just three weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our base just fell apart,'' said Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C.,
as exit polls showed that McCain had done dismally with members of
his own party who flocked to the polls for Bush. At the same time
he failed to draw out the same kind of outpouring of independents
that he had in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   McCain flew on to Michigan Saturday night, hoping to recover his
footing in the larger states that now come center stage in the
Republican nomination struggle. Michigan and Arizona both hold
primaries on Tuesday. The senator's aides predicted his reform
message would have more appeal there and in later primary states
such as California, Washington, Ohio and New York, which do not
have South Carolina's concentration of Christian conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign quickly started trying to paint Gov. George
W. Bush as the candidate of the Christian right. ``Ralph Reed, Pat
Robertson and Jerry Falwell are to be congratulated,'' said John
Weaver, McCain's political director. Referring to Bush, he said,
``We don't know if you can run as a Dixiecrat in Michigan, but
we'll find out.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary results suggested that Republican voters had
believed everything Bush and his conservatives allies had told them
about McCain in a steady barrage of television and radio
commercials and mass mailings. The senator's supporters said he had
been caught in a bind _ weakened by his decision to stop negative
ads but in danger of losing his luster if he had not done so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason people don't unilaterally disarm is that generally
its tough to make it work,'' said Rep. Mark Sanford. But he added
``if you ever got down in the mud with the other guy elbowing as
hard as you could, then frankly you've lost the idealistic God,
country appeal that was the cornerstone of the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver said that despite McCain's vow to avoid negative
advertising throughout the entire primary season, that ``We will
set the record straight and you can do that in a way that's not
negative.'' In an instant sign of how the McCain campaign was now
prepared to fight, the senator's aides immediately distributed a
statement from McCain's Michigan chairman, state Sen. John Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Gov. Bush's negative attack strategy may have worked in
South Carolina,'' Schwarz said, ``Voters here in Michigan expect a
thoughtful issue-based discussion not a Dixie mud brawl.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the last South Carolina campaign day began in
Greenville Saturday morning, there were hints that McCain knew he
was likely to fail in his attempt to draw Democrats and
independents into voting in the open Republican primary to counter
Bush's strength with Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   His tones had a valedictory sound as he begged the veterans to
go out on ``one more mission'' for him and get out the vote. ``When
I'm very old down at the old soldiers home with the feet up on the
railing, I'm going to look back,'' he said. ``and say the South
Carolina experience was an incredible part of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   From the moment he flew into South Carolina propelled by his New
Hampshire victory, McCain had defied the conventional wisdom that a
Republican primary here is won on the right. At times in the past
few days, the senator's tones became so populist and
anti-establishment that he no longer sounded much like a Republican
at all.
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon at a jam-packed gymnasium of the College of
Charleston he didn't just proclaim a crusade, he said, ``We are
starting a revolution.'' Later that night, at an outdoor rally
under the neon lights of the NASCAR cafe in Myrtle Beach, he
shouted, ``We can eradicate evil. We can eradicate differences
between rich and poor''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 2144EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000219.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2463 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MICH-REPUBS-1STLD-WRI     02-19 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-REPUBS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN GOVERNOR PRESIDING OVER HUGE EFFORT FOR BUSH
</HEADLINE>
 (UPDATES thruout with result in South Carolina) 
 (rk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANSING, Mich. _ Having won the Republican primary in South
Carolina, Gov. George W. Bush plans to spend Sunday and Monday
here, seeking to deal another blow to Sen. John McCain's
aspirations in this state's primary on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Saturday night, Gov. John Engler of Michigan, an
early supporter of Bush, said the South Carolina victory will
provide additional momentum here, as he and his allies lead one of
the largest political mobilizations ever in the state. ``There's no
question it's going to be helpful,'' said Engler. ``The size of the
win is really opening eyes in Michigan.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Bush, McCain plans to spend the next two days furiously
campaigning across Michigan. But he has a low-budget operation here
and is relying heavily on media coverage and the Internet to get
his message out, in a showdown that pits the buzz of his popularity
against one of the most formidable political machines left in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Republican owners of small businesses say party officials have
asked to use their offices as phone banks to appeal for Bush
voters. County executives and other local party leaders have been
writing thousands of letters to get out the vote. And Republican
state legislators have been recording radio advertisements for Bush
in their districts.
</P>
<P>
   Engler is hoping that his approach to politics still works. In
an interview last Thursday at his office here, across the street
from the state capitol he said, ``It's somewhat chilling, actually,
to see the McCain campaign be so obsessed with their press
relations and their media strategy that it overwhelms all of the
old, traditional political campaign aspects,'' Engler said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain campaign officials say that 2,000 people have volunteered
over the Internet to help in Michigan, but they have set up only a
handful of phone banks and are hoping that most of the volunteers
will distribute pamphlets, put up signs and make phone calls from
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll concede the organization battle,'' said Michael Hudome,
McCain's top adviser on the Michigan primary.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high here for Engler personally, too. Term limits
require him to leave office at the end of his current term, his
third. And because he has bee a top adviser to Bush there has been
much speculation that he would have a role in a Bush
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Engler predicted on Thursday and again Saturday night that Bush
would win the primary here by four or five percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters say Bush is slightly ahead of McCain here, but that
the outcome will depend on turnout. In past Republican primaries
here, the turnout has tended to be 10 percent to 12 percent of
registered voters, about two-thirds of whom are in the party and
the balance of whom are Democrats, independents and Republicans who
vote only occasionally. McCain can win if he can increase turnout
to 15 percent _ close to one million people _ by attracting more
independents, Democrats and Republicans who vote infrequently, said
Ed Sarpolus, a pollster here at EPIC/MRA, which does polling for
media organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 100,000 voters on Tuesday will be Republicans who seldom
vote in primaries but will vote for Bush at the request of the
Engler organization, Sarpolus estimated. That could be roughly
equal to the number of Democrats who vote in the Republican
primary, he added.
</P>
<P>
   A few liberal Democrats have urged their supporters to vote for
McCain to punish Engler for stripping Detroit of some its control
over schools and courts. But Michigan's Democratic leaders have
disavowed this tactic, and pollsters have predicted that the effect
would be statistically insignificant. Engler has tried to galvanize
his supporters by attacking the limited Democratic efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats will hold caucuses in Michigan on March 11.
Republicans in Arizona will, like those in Michigan, hold their
primary on Tuesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Engler has spent his 10 years as governor, as well as most of
the 1980s as president of the state Senate, assiduously attending
fund-raisers and other events for Republican chairmen in each of
Michigan's 83 counties. He is also a feared figure in state
politics, with a reputation similar to that of Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani of New York for remembering his friends and punishing his
enemies in budgets and other legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Engler has been using all his influence to make sure that
local Republicans organize the grass-roots effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is when the Engler machine, or establishment, kicks in,''
said L. Brooks Patterson, Oakland County executive. ``We have
resources, I think, that McCain doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Gil Cox, the chairman of a large law firm in Troy, Mich., said
that he had agreed to a request from Oakland County Republicans to
turn over the firm's headquarters this weekend to volunteers who
would make phone calls asking Bush supporters to make sure they
voted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been asked to do this for local races, but this is the
first time we've been asked for a presidential race,'' Cox, a
Republican, said. His firm, Cox, Hodgman &AMP; Giarmarco, represents
many Michigan cities in liability cases, including cities with
Democratic administrations. But Cox said that the decision to help
had been made, ``because it's a good thing for the community'' to
increase voter turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan's secretary of state, Candice S. Miller, said she had
arranged for 560 volunteers to work this weekend in shifts on 300
phones at local businesses to get out the vote for Bush in Macomb
County in Detroit's northeastern suburbs, her political base.
``We're approaching this not as if this were a presidential
campaign but as though there were county commissioner campaigns all
over the place,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the McCain campaign has 25 volunteers who will be
making calls from their homes in Oakland and Macomb Counties, two
of Michigan's three largest counties.
</P>
<P>
   There is a precedent for Engler's activity. William G. Milliken,
a moderate Republican who was Michigan's governor from 1970 to
1982, campaigned energetically at the last moment for Bush's father
in the Republican primary in 1980 and essentially cast the primary
as a referendum on himself.
</P>
<P>
   Despite trailing Ronald Reagan in Michigan polls by up to 12
percentage points several days before the vote, Bush won the
primary by 25 percentage points. The victory helped him secure the
vice presidential nomination at the Republican convention eight
weeks later in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Milliken, who remains one of the most popular politicians in the
state despite 18 years in retirement, endorsed McCain on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
