<SLUG> BC-SC-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH GETS HIS POLITICAL SWAGGER BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ On the Sunday after Gov. George W. Bush limped
out of New Hampshire, two of his aides were deep into a telephone
conversation, searching for a new sales pitch that would put some
swagger back into their campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Karen P. Hughes, turned almost instinctively to the
kind of alliteration she often favored.
</P>
<P>
   ``A reformer with results, Hughes said to Ari Fleischer, the
other aide, who liked what he heard.
</P>
<P>
   By the next day, the phrase was emblazoned on banners, atop the
campaign's news releases and prominent in Bush's public comments.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two weeks later, as Bush and his advisers savored an
emphatic victory in South Carolina, they attributed much of their
success to this change of direction. The exit polls from Saturday's
Republican primary here affirmed that judgment, showing that more
South Carolinians thought of Bush as a reformer than they did
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers said that they had not simply co-opted McCain's
message of reforming government. They had found a slogan that
signaled that Bush could boast a record of the kind of
accomplishments so rare in the bitterly partisan halls of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminded people of successful governors from outside the
Beltway,'' said Fleischer. ``There's no secret there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush folded variations on the word ``reform'' into his victory
speech Saturday night a half dozen times.
</P>
<P>
   He called his triumph ``the victory of a messenger who is a
reformer with results,'' Bush told hundreds of cheering supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reform agenda,'' he added, ``stands in stark contrast to
the current administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers divined all sorts of good news not only in the
margin of Bush's victory, but also in the shape of it.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had beaten McCain handily among younger voters and women.
He had lost to McCain among independent voters by much less than he
had in New Hampshire. And despite a barrage of commercials harshly
criticizing McCain, more voters said that McCain had run a negative
campaign than said that Bush had.
</P>
<P>
   The data also held a piece of potentially bad news: that when
Christian conservatives, an enormously influential bloc of voters
in this state, were removed from the equation, McCain came out on
top.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush and his advisers were busy embracing an emotional high
that contrasted sharply with the depths they felt only two weeks
ago, when they were quickly retooling the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six days after New Hampshire, we were smiling, but we were
gritting our teeth,'' said Tucker Eskew, a spokesman for the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday morning, the Bush campaign had completely recaptured
its confidence, and Bush was unequivocally guaranteeing victory
just hours after the polls opened.
</P>
<P>
   He was so calm that he had almost begun a midafternoon ``power
nap,'' as he called it, before his chief strategist, Karl Rove,
came into his fifth-floor suite at the Sheraton with the first exit
polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great,'' Bush told Rove, as Rove recalled. ``Will they hold?''
</P>
<P>
   Rove assured him they would.
</P>
<P>
   Rove then contacted Bush's father, the former president, in
Texas, who had been anxiously calling the governor's advisers all
day long.
</P>
<P>
   Bush woke before 3 p.m. and went outdoors to exercise: three
miles of running, two of walking. Advisers said that he was still
in his workout clothing, a white towel around his neck, when the
campaign's senior officials convened in his suite to sketch out his
victory speech.
</P>
<P>
   A band played the rock song ``Taking Care of Business'' as Bush
entered a ballroom to deliver those remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We come roaring out of South Carolina,'' Bush told the crowd,
``with a new energy in this campaign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
