<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAFEAT0220-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    76ers new talent is hard to beat
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA That noise you hear is from the quivering knees of the
Indiana Pacers, New York Knicks and Miami Heat. That trio of teams
had been expected to battle it out for the Eastern Conference
championship.
</P>
<P>
   But last week's acquisition of Toni Kukoc made the Philadelphia
76ers legitimate contenders _ and scary.
</P>
<P>
   Not so much because the Sixers have added a multi-talented, 6-11
forward with a championship pedigree. But because once Kukoc gets
acclimated to coach Larry Brown's scheme and playing with all-star
guard Allen Iverson, his presence will help exploit the other
clubs' weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, facing Philadelphia mostly required paying special
attention to Iverson, the NBA's No. 1 scorer. But with Kukoc
opening the floor with his perimeter game and creating for others
with his passing, look for Theo Ratliff to be more of a defensive
and rebounding force, for center Matt Geiger to assert muscle
inside _ for all of the 76ers' play to rise.
</P>
<P>
   That's the magnitude of a player who knows how to play. At the
same time, Kukoc makes the Pacers' depth less of an issue, the
Knicks' confidence less effective and the Heat's defense less
daunting.
</P>
<P>
   All three of the teams were seriously flawed. On any given
night, New York can perform like a group of stumblebums. Losses to
Boston, the Hawks and the Warriors are examples. Indiana has had
the experience and talent for the last three years but has found
,ways to lose. Last year's conference finals loss to the Knicks,
despite having home-court advantage and Patrick Ewing out injured,
is an example.
</P>
<P>
   As for Miami, it has grown weary of coach Pat Riley's strong-arm
tactics and lacks enough offense to be successful in the playoffs.
Last year's loss as the No. 1 seed to New York, the eighth seed, in
the first round, is an example.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the 76ers have the reliable scorer to go with Iverson.
Larry Hughes was Iverson's partner, his ``Flight Brother.'' But
Hughes was a rookie who had flashes of spectacular play. Kukoc is a
cunning passer whose size creates mismatches no matter what
position he plays.
</P>
<P>
   In short, when the three-team deal was proposed, Hughes had to
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're trading for a player who has won championships and
played with the greatest players in the league (in Michael Jordan
and Scottie Pippen), his championship experience will help us
tremendously,'' Philly general manager Billy King said.
</P>
<P>
   The wild card in the deal for the Sixers is Iverson. He has to
accept Kukoc's talent and feed off of it. Iverson probably won't
have to hoist 30 or so shots while his teammates stand around and
watch. The quality of his attempts should increase, meaning that
his scoring average should not suffer, while the production of
others should increase, making the team better.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for Allen Iverson, I think he is a very, very good
player,'' Kukoc said. ``His record speaks for itself. It's always
nice to have teammates around who can finish a play when you pass
to them. Allen is probably a player you could call an easy assist
because he is such an outstanding finisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, I'm going to be a player who will try to
score, as well,'' Kukoc said. ``And Allen can help there, too,
because he can discourage a double-team when I go inside to try to
use my height advantage. It's always good to have an outside and
inside attack. The team itself is very talented and has a lot of
potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Kukoc said he wanted to finish his career in Chicago, but he
could not hide his excitement about what being a Sixer could mean.
``I'm happy to be going to a much better team,'' he said. ``It's a
winning team that has an excellent chance not just to make the
playoffs but to advance deep into the playoffs. We'll just have to
wait and see what this deal does for all sides.''
</P>
<P>
   The sides most concerned are Indiana, New York and Miami. And
they have every reason to be.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
