<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLREA0220-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    St. Louis on a Blue streak
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _You can't go anywhere without seeing a hat, T-shirt or
a pennant commemorating the St. Louis Rams' improbable run through
the NFL last season. Signs of the relocated franchise's first Super
Bowl victory are as obvious as the Arch.
</P>
<P>
   It will be up to four months before the city's hockey team
learns if it can match the Rams' postseason success and win its
first Stanley Cup. But this much is certain: A Blues NHL title will
not create nearly the number of dropped jaws that quarterback Kurt
Warner did this season.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody already knows the Blues are solid.
</P>
<P>
   ``They built that club to the point now where they're a
legitimate contender for the Cup _ they've got everything,'' said
Thrashers coach Curt Fraser, whose team was drilled by the Blues
4-1. ``They're big, they're fast, they have guys who can finish
like (Pavol) Demitra and (Pierre) Turgeon. They have great guys on
defense like (Al) MacInnis and (Chris) Pronger. They're the total
package.''
</P>
<P>
   Making it through the Western Conference playoffs with Dallas,
Detroit and Colorado won't be easy. But the Blues have the best
record in the conference and, similar to the Stars and Red Wings,
are deep in forwards who play well at both ends of the ice. The
biggest question is how young goalie Roman Turek holds up as the
first-time starter of a playoff team.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues last made the conference finals in 1986 (losing to
Calgary in seven games). They reached the Stanley Cup finals their
first three seasons, when all six expansion teams were placed in
one division, the West, and the winner faced the champion of the
East's ``Original Six.'' Montreal (twice) and Boston swept St.
Louis all three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Blues general manager Larry Pleau, in his third season after
eight years with the Rangers and 17 with Hartford as player, coach
and general manager, and coach Joel Quenneville both have gained
respect in the league. Pleau has built a team that sent five
players to the All-Star Game _ Demitra, Turgeon (who couldn't play
because of an injury), Turek, MacInnis and Pronger. Quenneville, an
aide on Colorado's Stanley Cup team in 1995-96, will get Canadian
Olympic team consideration if the NHL goes to Salt Lake City in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit coach Scotty Bowman said last week, ``I think they'll
take a guy like Joel. He was in Colorado when they won. He built a
team up in St. Louis. They play hard every night. Any time you get
a team to play like he does, that's the trick.''
</P>
<P>
   There was foreshadowing for this season. The Blues upset Phoenix
in the first round last season and took Dallas to six games, losing
two of four overtime games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to know what to expect,'' Pleau said. ``Fortunately
some of the moves we've made have worked. We brought in a guy like
(Slovakian center) Michal Handzus, and he's been a piece of the
puzzle. We wanted to better ourselves in goal scoring, goaltending
and be more consistent, and we've done that.''
</P>
<P>
   It has impressed the veteran MacInnis, who played on a Cup team
in Calgary and barely survived the Mike Keenan era in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great indication of the job Larry and Joel have done,''
he said. ``They came in with a game plan to build the organization,
build the assets and have a deeper team. We've had injuries, but
we've been able to stay on top of the standings.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
