<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY SEEKS TO GET A PUSH IN NORTHWEST
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley's struggle to keep his
presidential campaign alive seems to hinge increasingly on this
state's primary.
</P>
<P>
   Washington holds a nonbinding vote on Feb. 29 that will be the
only Democratic contest before the so-called Super Tuesday
primaries in 16 states on March 7. Having lost to Vice President Al
Gore in both Iowa and New Hampshire, and trailing badly in polls in
almost every state including Washington, Bradley views this state
as a critical proving ground where he must regain some of the
political momentum and media attention he has lost over the last
month, his advisers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens here if he beats Gore is that it will resonate
across the country that this is a race,'' said Mayor Paul Schell of
Seattle, who is helping Bradley here. ``This is where he's going to
make a stand. I think he's decided that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is planning to lavish his time and resources on
Washington in the coming week. He has also sent more than 20 aides,
including some of his most seasoned organizers, to the state. By
next weekend, his aides said, the full-time paid staff will
probably grow to 30 people.
</P>
<P>
   The group includes many of Bradley's top political aides from
Iowa and New Hampshire, including Mark Longabaugh, his state
director in New Hampshire, and Robert Becker, who was his political
director in Iowa. Two of Bradley's senior advisers, Margy Heldring
and Gretchen Crosby, have also moved to Seattle to talk about
Bradley's record and agenda, particularly his plan to extend
private health insurance to almost all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley himself is expected to spend most of the coming week
campaigning along the Pacific Coast and in heavily Democratic
cities like Tacoma and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is also preparing an advertising campaign for local
radio stations and newspapers to promote his health care plan as
well as his endorsement by The Seattle Times, the state's largest
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The vote on Feb. 29 will not be used to select delegates to the
Democratic convention. That will be done on March 7 in party
caucuses, where Gore is expected to excel because he has the
support of most party officials and labor unions, groups that tend
to dominate the caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley's advisers are less concerned with delegates than
public relations, and they view Washington as one of their last
chances to reverse perceptions that the Bradley campaign is
foundering. A win here on Feb. 29, they say, could build the kind
of excitement they need to go into the March 7 primaries with some
sense of positive movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want this state to be able to send a message to the rest of
the country,'' Bradley told a group of about 75 supporters Saturday
morning outside a health clinic in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has acknowledged that he must win some states on March
7, when New York, California, Ohio and 10 other states will select
30 percent of the Democratic delegates. But while Bradley once
talked of trying to contest Gore in almost every state, his
campaign is trying to focus its efforts on certain states to ensure
that he gains enough victories to justify staying in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's advisers say that in addition to Washington, they are
counting on doing well in New England, particularly Connecticut, in
New York, where Bradley played pro basketball for 10 seasons, and
Missouri, where he was born.
</P>
<P>
   Victories in those states, combined with a strong second-place
showing in California, would help insulate Bradley against pressure
from other Democrats to drop out of the race. Performing well on
March 7 is also important because on March 14 the campaign turns
south, to Florida, Texas, Tennessee and several other states where
Gore is considered the heavy favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's advisers say they think he can do well in Washington
in part because independents _ a group he does better among than
Gore does _ are allowed to vote in the Feb. 29 primary. Thanks to a
booming high-tech economy, there is also a large population of
well-educated, higher income residents here, and polls have
consistently shown that such voters tend to support Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   During less than 24 hours in Seattle, Bradley focused on the two
issues his aides think are most important to Washington voters: the
environment and health care.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting with more than 800 people on Friday, Bradley talked
proudly about his work on environmental issues in the Senate, which
earned him an 84 percent favorable voting record from the League of
Conservation Voters, compared with a 64 percent rating for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And Saturday morning, he appeared outside a health clinic to
promote his health care plan. ``I didn't come new to the health
care debate since I've been running for president,'' he said. ``In
16 years in the Congress, he did not introduce one health care
bill,'' he added, referring to Gore.
</P>
</TEXT>
