<HEADLINE>
IRANIAN REFORMERS AHEAD IN CRITICAL VOTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ Initial ballot counts Saturday in Iran's pivotal
parliamentary elections showed reformist candidates who back
President Mohammad Khatami poised for a landslide victory.
</P>
<P>
   State television said results have been declared for 168 of the
290 seats, but it did not give the affiliations of the elected
lawmakers. But the official Islamic Republic News Agency said about
67 percent of those seats _ or about 112 _ went to reformists, 25
percent were won by hard-liners and the rest were taken by
independents.
</P>
<P>
   If the reformers win, Khatami would become the next speaker of
the Parliament. He would replace Ali Akbar Rafsanjani, who had so
few votes by Saturday evening that it appeared he could lose his
parliamentary seat.
</P>
<P>
   Results, however, were preliminary and an official count was not
expected for at least a week because ballots are being counted by
hand. A runoff is set for sometime in March.
</P>
<P>
   But the electric atmosphere in cosmopolitan Tehran, where the
core of Khatami's supporters live, suggested they expected his push
for greater freedoms and democracy to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic,'' said Mahmoud Motevalian, a journalist and
political commentator. He added that he hoped Khatami's Islamic
Iran Participation Front would dominate Parliament ``so we can have
some change.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first election-related violence, meanwhile, two people
were killed and 15 injured Saturday in the southwestern town of
Shush, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble started when one group accused the winning candidate
of bribing people to vote for him, IRNA reported. It was not clear
whether the conflict stemmed from political differences or local
tribal rivalries unrelated to the conservative-reformist struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Police fired tear gas and bullets in the air to quell the
rioters, who set fire to cars and hurled stones, IRNA said. It
confirmed the 15 injuries but did not report any fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear to which camp the victorious candidate, Jassem
Sayeri, belonged.
</P>
<P>
   Sporadic violence also was reported in the towns of Boroujen,
Boldaji and Gandoman in central Iran. Supporters of two losing
candidates burned tires and smashed windows of the governor's
office and shops, witnesses said. No injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   The election is seen as a critical juncture that could determine
the country's direction for a generation. Since his election in
1997, Khatami has tried to move Iran toward democracy and respect
for human rights and the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, he has come up against powerful conservative rivals
who have tried to halt change. If reformers win the Parliament,
analysts have predicted, they could give Khatami the backing he
needs to confront the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a movement from the grass roots up,'' said Habibollah
Peyman, a reformist. ``We believe that very soon this social
movement will win.''
</P>
<P>
   At the core of this election is the question of how much
influence Iran's Shiite Muslim religious clerics should maintain
over public life and to what extent the country should open its
borders to new ideas and other nations.
</P>
<P>
   Young people fed up with the decade of the ``government of God''
telling them what to wear and what music to listen to have come out
in force behind Khatami's reformers. They hope to curb the
influence of the mullahs _ the clerics who control key aspects of
government _ and open up to the West.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative voters worry that Western influence will corrupt
the morals of young people and entice them away from the strict
lifestyle of fundamentalist Shiite Islam that has guided Iran since
the mullahs overthrew Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the mullahs have become increasingly unpopular and
are blamed for driving the country into ruin _ and political
isolation. Iranians, conservative and reformist, cite Iran's
economy as one of their biggest grievances. Both camps also favor
importing products and ideas from the West, although conservatives
would rather limit this contact to science and technology.
</P>
<P>
   Rafsanjani, as one of the most visible supporters of the
conservative government, seems to have borne the brunt of much of
the public's wrath. Despite the fact that he heads a reformist
party that includes a few respected liberals, he is not well-liked.
</P>
<P>
   He is associated, foremost, with corruption, the killing of
several dissident writers and failing to put an early end to Iran's
eight-year war with Iraq. Many voters said they suspect his
reformist rhetoric is merely show.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
