<HEADER>
A2593 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-SC-BUSH-HNS &LR;      02-19 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH NOTCHES A BIG WIN IN SOUTH CAROLINA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ George W. Bush triumphed Saturday in the
hard-fought South Carolina Republican presidential primary,
reclaiming leadership in the battle for his party's nomination and
leaving suddenly testy insurgent John McCain to regroup for quickly
approaching contests.
</P>
<P>
   With three-fourths of the precincts counted, Bush, the Texas
governor, led with 54 percent to 41 percent for McCain, a senator
from Arizona. Alan Keyes, a former Reagan administration official,
was stuck at about 5 percent of what was clearly a record turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after the polls closed, Bush declared he was ``excited
and energized.'' He later told supporters in a Columbia hotel
ballroom he was ``honored and humbled by the huge victory.'' He
barely mentioned McCain and targeted President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore, the leading contender for the Democratic
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only 263 days more to the end of Clinton-Gore,''
Bush declared, returning his focus to the general election, where
it had been until a tightening Republican race, highlighted by his
loss to McCain in New Hampshire, diverted his attention.
</P>
<P>
   McCain quickly called Bush to congratulate him but then hammered
the governor in a statement to supporters in a North Charleston
hall. Without mentioning Bush by name, McCain caustically
criticized his opponent's hard-edged campaign in a combative
statement that contrasted with Bush's gracious concession speech in
New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not take the low road to the highest office in the
land,'' McCain said. ``I want the presidency in the best way, not
the worst way.'' In an obvious allusion to Bush's retooled claim to
be ``a reformer with results,'' McCain said he had ``a record of
reform'' not ``an empty slogan of reform.'' McCain contended that
he offered ``a choice between experience and pretense.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush expressed no regrets about his aggressive campaign against
McCain in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand by what I did,'' Bush said in a CNN interview. ``I
defended myself.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Bush aide called McCain's concession ``a bitter speech.
You can learn a lot about a man in defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign manager, Rick Davis, signaled the task ahead:
``Clearly, we're going to have to sell really hard and really fast
our reformer's message.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he hoped Bush would get a good night's sleep,
because ``he's going to need it, my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   After their election night statements, Bush and McCain flew
immediately to Michigan for whirlwind tours in advance of the
campaign's first primary in an industrial state.
</P>
<P>
   Public-opinion polls taken immediately after New Hampshire gave
McCain an edge in Michigan despite Bush's backing by the Republican
establishment, including Gov. John Engler. But a new Detroit News
survey published Saturday showed the race a dead heat, with McCain
at 40 percent to Bush's 38 percent. A week ago, McCain led 43
percent to 34 percent in the same survey last week, indicating
definite movement toward Bush.
</P>
<P>
   If McCain loses in Michigan, ``it would be the equivalent of
`Dead Man Walking,'`` said Randy White, former executive director
of the Christian Coalition. McCain would begin to ``completely
unravel'' and ``it would be very difficult for him to recover,''
said White, now director of Republican affairs for Voter.com, a new
political Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who remains the Republican front-runner in national
surveys, scored solidly across South Carolina with conservatives,
who backed him 2-1 over McCain, and with the religious right, who
favored him 3-1, according to exit polls for news organizations.
Self-identified Republicans backed Bush by more than 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Bush split veterans about evenly with McCain, whose history as a
prisoner of war in Vietnam is at the center of his campaign
persona. McCain drew most strongly from independents, moderates,
Democrats and newcomers to the Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   The balloting, in generally sunny, warm weather, was open to all
registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   The primary was the 2000 campaign's first test in the South and
the first major confrontation for the principal candidates since
McCain electrified the Republican race as he drubbed Bush by 19
percentage points in the New Hampshire primary Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, South Carolina proved to be a firewall for a
hard-pressed favorite of the Republican establishment, much the
same function it served for Bush's father in 1988 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had earlier won caucuses in Iowa and Alaska and the primary
in Delaware, states where McCain chose not to compete actively.
McCain's sole success was in the Granite State.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had counted on a victory in South Carolina to propel him
through Tuesday's voting and to set the stage for a further assault
against Bush on March 7, when more than a dozen primaries are on
tap, including California and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona also holds a primary Tuesday with Michigan, and after
trailing Bush in polls last fall, McCain now shows a substantial
lead in surveys of likely voters in his home state.
</P>
<P>
   McCain complained as voting progressed in South Carolina that
the state Republican Party, which administered the primary,
violated terms of a legal agreement by not advertising in advance
that some polling places in traditionally low GOP turnout areas
were to be merged with nearby precincts. A black Democratic state
legislator had challenged the GOP plan to keep some polling places
shuttered, and early last week a U.S. district judge approved a
merged-precinct plan provided notice was given.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he would ask for ``a full investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina voting came after two weeks of attacks from
both major candidates, in which each compared the other to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign was crowned with a finger-waving face-off Tuesday
night in which Bush and McCain, with only Keyes sitting between
them, accused each other of low blows, hypocrisy and childishness.
As throughout most of the weeks since the campaign moved south, key
issue differences on the tax system, federal spending and budget
surpluses were subsumed in often personal charges and
countercharges.
</P>
<P>
   Negative ads filled the airwaves, harsh campaign calls poured
into homes and quickly retooled fliers landed in mail boxes and on
windshields outside politically active churches.
</P>
<P>
   McCain withdrew his negative television commercials for the
final week, but not before the campaign became one of the nastiest
in South Carolina history.
</P>
<P>
   Republican strategists fear that the South Carolina campaign may
be best remembered for the sniping video footage that it has
bequeathed to Democrats for use in the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, shocked by his poor showing in New Hampshire, arrived in
South Carolina looking almost befuddled, an unaccustomed state for
the usually super-confident Texan. After a huddle two weekends ago
with top aides in Austin, he emerged as a combative competitor,
sounding on the stump like a circuit preacher. And he had a new
slogan _ ``A reformer with results'' _ intended to show that McCain
wasn't the only guy in the race with new ideas and that Bush was
the only candidate with a record of executive achievement as the
governor of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had to prove he had fire in the belly,'' said White. ``He
had to show he had more than `inevitability.' The more clearly
George Bush got his message out there, ... the better he did.''
</P>
<P>
   All three candidates kept up their pleas for voters to turn out
even as the polls opened. Bush and McCain both predicted victory in
campaign-closing appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to win,'' Bush said as he breakfasted on
pancakes and bacon at Tommy's Country Ham House in Greenville, the
upstate hub of conservative Republicans at the heart of his South
Carolina campaign. ``The last couple of days, there's been an
unusual amount of enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
