<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAGGERED BUT DEFIANT, MCCAIN TAKES AIM AT MICHIGAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH CHARLESTON, S.C. _ John McCain was staggered by a hard
right to the chin in South Carolina, but he remained on his feet
Saturday as he headed to Michigan, where he needs to bounce back
Tuesday to keep his presidential hopes alive.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding defiant, the Arizona senator vowed to continue his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Congratulating George W. Bush on his victory, McCain also
advised the Texas governor to get a good night's rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to need it, my friends, for we have just begun to
fight, and I cannot wait for the next round,'' McCain told his
cheering supporters before leaving South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's campaign had received a strong boost from his
decisive Feb. 1 victory over Bush in New Hampshire. But his loss in
this more conservative state, where his maverick style met stiff
opposition from religious fundamentalists and most of the
Republican establishment, transferred the momentum for the
Republican nomination back to the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's rediscovered political life also may rejuvenate his own
fund-raising and cool McCain's ability to raise cash before a rash
of key coast-to-coast primaries within the next three weeks,
beginning Tuesday in Michigan and McCain's home state of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has raised about $70 million, holds a huge lead in
fund-raising but already has spent more than $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (McCain) has to win decisively in Michigan. It can't be
close,'' said Jeffrey Tulis, a government professor at the
University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. John Schwarz of Battle Creek, McCain's Michigan
chairman, welcomed the opportunity to help put the senator's
campaign back on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Governor Bush's negative attack strategy may have worked
in South Carolina, Michigan is different,'' Schwarz said. ``Voters
here in Michigan expect a thoughtful issues-based discussion, not a
Dixie mud brawl.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as he flew north Saturday night for a
middle-of-the-night rally in Dearborn, Mich., McCain faced more bad
news. His once-strong lead over Bush in Michigan has evaporated,
and the two are now in a statistical tie, according to a poll
published in today's editions of the Detroit News.
</P>
<P>
   A similar survey showed McCain with a nine-point lead in
Michigan about a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Another recent poll indicated McCain has a huge lead in Arizona,
a state he also must win, mainly because he is expected to carry
his home state. But Bush has been endorsed by a number of Arizona
officeholders, including Republican Gov. Jane Hull.
</P>
<P>
   Cary Covington, a political science professor at the University
of Iowa, said a victory in Arizona wouldn't necessarily do McCain
much good but a loss in his home state could be devastating.
</P>
<P>
   Covington said a loss in Michigan, the most populous state yet
to hold a nominating primary, may not end McCain's campaign on the
spot but would be ``more of an indicator of how he's going to do on
Super Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   The Super Tuesday lineup March 7 includes primaries in numerous
states, including California and New York.
</P>
<P>
   The senator also predicted that his campaign would become
unstoppable if he won in South Carolina. But that wasn't to be,
thanks in large part to a heavy turnout of religious and social
conservatives, who, according to early exit polls, voted for Bush
by a 3-to-1 ratio.
</P>
<P>
   McCain indicated that he will deliver the same message in
Michigan, where the Republican establishment headed by Gov. John
Engler is strongly backing Bush, much like most of the Republican
powers in South Carolina supported the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   Tulis, the UT Austin professor, said Michigan _ with its mix of
Republicans, Democrats and independents _ could prove particularly
important in deciding the GOP nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls indicated that veterans in South Carolina split their
votes between Bush and McCain, despite McCain's strong overtures to
former military people. The former Vietnam War POW urged a veterans
group in Greenville on Saturday to make ``one more mission for me''
and turn out their vote.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
