<HEADER>
A2605 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-TESSERACT-AZR &LR;      02-19 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESSERACT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE SCHOOL COMPANY IS BEING WATCHED ACROSS THE U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By HAL MATTERN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Tesseract Group calls its academically rigorous
and high-priced private schools ``Harvards for children.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents at the company's Ahwatukee campus say it has seemed more
like an impoverished inner-city school lately.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its nearly $8,000-a-year tuition, the 2-year-old school
hasn't had enough money for classroom supplies, parents told
Tesseract's top executive Thursday night at a sometimes emotional
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Money has been so tight that the school couldn't afford the
postage to mail report cards home recently.
</P>
<P>
   And the school has been operating all year without a budget.
</P>
<P>
   Tesseract's crisis is being watched closely nationwide for what
it says about the future of for-profit public schools and charter
schools, two of the biggest developments in education over the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm embarrassed. I'm truly embarrassed,'' John Golle, founder,
chairman and chief executive officer of the Tesseract Group, told
parents at Thursday's meeting. ``I promise that the problems will
be fixed immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Golle, the man credited with creating the for-profit school
industry, has been making a lot of promises and apologies lately.
</P>
<P>
   After $14 million in losses over the past two years, Tesseract
is selling assets and shedding staff. Its stock, which peaked at
$48.50 a share in 1993, is now worth pennies.
</P>
<P>
   Parents of its 6,000 students are being assured that Tesseract's
private, charter and pre-elementary schools will stay open.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tesseract is up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is we tried to grow too fast, too soon without
enough capital,'' Golle said. ``It didn't work. It was poor
management execution.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst may not be over: A change in state law will cost
Tesseract's charter schools $6 million in state funding, or 16
percent of the company's 1999 revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nationally, charter school supporters are skittish about
Tesseract's problems,'' said Mary Gifford, director of the center
for market-based education at the Goldwater Institute and a member
of the state Board for Charter Schools.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford said Arizona's charter school movement, the largest in
the nation, with more than 360 schools, ``is strong enough to
endure this.'' Ten percent of the charter schools are run by
for-profit companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Mary Hartley, D-northwest Phoenix, said Tesseract's
problems foreshadow what's eventually going to happen to other
for-profit charter school companies in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``They eventually are going to have the same experiences,''
Hartley said, adding that such schools have to cut corners to make
a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale-based Tesseract, formerly based in Minnesota and
known as Education Alternatives Inc., shook up the education
establishment in the early 1990s when it was hired to manage
failing public schools in Dade County, Fla.; Hartford, Conn.; and
Baltimore. It was the first private, for-profit company to take
over a public school system. &QL; 
Tough industry
</P>
<P>
   The experiment was less than successful, however, and Tesseract
no longer has contracts to run traditional public schools. Even so,
the company's experience opened the door to a new industry that
continues to expand.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen for-profit ``education management organizations''
operate traditional public schools and charter schools across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them also are losing money. Edison Schools, the largest
such company, lost $38 million last year and is projecting losses
of close to $60 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts and industry executives say the business is
capital- and labor-intensive and that profit margins are razor
thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of money to get these things started,'' said
Bill Coats, founder of the Leona Group, a privately held Michigan
company that runs charter schools in Detroit and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Coats, who plans to open a separate Arizona company soon to
oversee the Leona Group's 13 schools here, said his firm has
succeeded by growing slowly and watching its cash flow carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to generate as much cash as you spend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Bailey, a securities analyst at Merrill Lynch who
follows Edison, said she doesn't expect Tesseract's problems to
hurt the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question there are some lessons to be learned from
a pioneer,'' Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   But she said Merrill Lynch analysts are predicting that
for-profit companies could capture as much as 10 percent of the
$360 billion now being spent annually on public schools. &QL; 
Tesseract's future
</P>
<P>
   Whether Tesseract will be part of that growth is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   The company's financial problems stem from a variety of factors,
some of them out of the company's control, said Golle, who retired
as CEO three months ago only to return after a management shake-up.
</P>
<P>
   The company's spending spurt, including the purchase of the
Sunrise preschool chain for $13.5 million in 1997 and the opening
of several charter schools and two new private schools, contributed
to the tight finances, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tesseract poured $5 million into two new West Valley charter
schools last year, expecting to be reimbursed by the developer. But
the money never materialized, and one of the schools sits
unfinished, mired in litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Golle said the company's delayed second-quarter earnings report,
which will be released this week, will show a positive cash flow at
all of its school sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst is behind us,'' Golle said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Tesseract parents are skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a comedy of errors,'' said Michael Chilton, who has
a daughter in fourth grade at the private Ahwatukee school. ``I
don't understand how they think the same people who caused the
problems are going to fix them now.'' &QL; 
More bad news
</P>
<P>
   There still are some storm clouds on the horizon. Tesseract's
state funding for its charter schools will decrease by nearly $6
million, about half of this year's state funding, after June 30,
when Arizona's formula for funding pupil transportation changes.
</P>
<P>
   The law allows charter schools that are sponsored by traditional
public school districts to charge the state up to $1.95 per mile
for transportation, either for busing students or reimbursing
parents for driving their own kids.
</P>
<P>
   But some schools have abused the system by giving parents as
little as 5 cents a mile while collecting the entire $1.95 from the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Tesseract, whose charter schools are sponsored by the Snowflake
Unified District in northern Arizona, is collecting $6 million in
transportation funds this year, or about $4,400 a student.
</P>
<P>
   After June 30, charter schools will get a flat rate of $174 per
student for transportation funding. If their enrollment remains the
same, Tesseract's charter schools will qualify for just $240,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what the impact is going to be,'' Golle said.
</P>
<P>
   _-Reach the reporter at Hal.Mattern &LR; ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8652.
</P>
</TEXT>
