<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA NO MATCH FOR ARIZONA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. - It was easy to see this coming, especially for
those who witnessed the final minutes of UCLA's practice Friday
afterno on at McKale Center.
</P>
<P>
   The workout didn't so much end as fizzle. After shooting free
throws, several players wandered to nearby gymnastics equipment for
a few laughs. Jerome Moiso and Ray Young tumbled. Ryan Bailey tried
vaulting - he's no Mary Lou - and Dan Gadzuric howled.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Moiso was asked if the two-hour workout had
been productive.
</P>
<P>
   He paused, then smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``No comment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With preparation like that, it's little wonder UCLA committed 17
turnovers in the first half, played invisible defense and watched
No. 4 Arizona steam to a 99-84 victory before 14,532 Saturday in
McKale that was much worse than the score indicated.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats jumped to a 21-point halftime lead and extended it
to 25 midway through the second half before play turned ragged.
They dominated with two reserves playing major minutes and without
center Loren Woods (back spasms), the leading candidate for Pac-10
player of the year honors.
</P>
<P>
   If possible, UCLA appeared less prepared to face Arizona than it
did Arizona State, which beat the Bruins by 29 points Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get swept by 20 points in the desert, it works on
your character and it hurts,'' UCLA forward Rico Hines said.
``Nobody's used to losing. We're asking ourselves, `What's going
on? What's wrong?' We just have to go back to the basics when we
get to practice Monday. You begin to question how good you are.''
</P>
<P>
   There's an easy answer for that: not very.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have lost six of their last seven games, their worst
skid since 1984, when they lost six of seven late in the year and
did not make the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   They are two defeats from their first losing record in
conference play since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, they set a school record for most points allowed
in back-to-back games (203).
</P>
<P>
   And here's the biggie: at 13-11 overall and 4-8 in conference,
they must win five of their last six to reach the 18-victory
plateau that probably would secure an NCAA bid.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins still have a one-game margin for error, which means
they don't have to win at Stanford in two weeks. However, they must
beat the Oregon and Washington schools in Pauley Pavilion, then win
at Cal. Possible? Sure. Probable? Not the way they're playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to forget this loss and get four of our next
six or five of our next six,'' said forward Jason Kapono, who led
the Bruins with 27 points. ``We've got to squeak out some wins some
way.''
</P>
<P>
   First, they must find their passion. They didn't have it
Thursday and they didn't have it Saturday. They let Arizona reserve
forwards Justin Wessel and Luke Walton push them around in the low
post. They were beaten to loose balls. They were beaten up and down
the court.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps losing seven games by 12 points or more has crushed
their confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess losing all those games...they look kind of frustrated,
'' Arizona forward Michael Wright said. ``Some of them didn't seem
to care.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins also must make better use of their practice time.
Instead of preparing for Arizona's offense, coach Steve Lavin
focused on correcting mistakes in Friday's workout. Whatever he
said didn't register, because the Bruins committed 17 turnovers in
the first half and took more bad shots than an intramural team.
Arizona turned both the bad shots and the turnovers into easy
baskets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the first half is when we lost the game,'' Lavin said.
``We didn't have the necessary poise and composure. We had a lot of
unforced (turnovers). We turn the ball over at such a rapid rate
that we can't set our defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two biggest things are turnovers and shot selection. We
don't even get a chance to play defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Arizona devoted its 75-minute practice to UCLA's
attack. Coach Lute Olson instructed his players to overplay the
passing lanes, deny entry passes into the post and double-team UCLA
forward Moiso whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats executed perfectly, smothering Moiso (five points)
and intercepting passes all over the court. (Point guard Jason
Gardner had seven steals.) Quicker, tougher and better prepared,
Arizona never ne eded Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The coaches) said it was a 50-50 chance (Woods would play),''
said Arizona guard Gilbert Arenas, a Grant High alum who scored 23
points Saturday. ``We just thought we had to go out there and play
harder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
