<HEADLINE>
S.C. MAY GIVE BUSH ARIZONA BOOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
   
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ George W. Bush's solid win in South Carolina could
give him a boost in Arizona's Republican primary on Tuesday, said
Jaime Molera, an aide to Gov. Jane Hull, Bush's top supporter in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this gives Bush a shot,'' Molera said. `But it will be
tough, no doubt,'' he added, noting McCain's comfortable lead in
public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rep. Sue Gerard, R-Phoenix, a McCain supporter,
acknowledged that she was disappointed by Saturday's result.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought McCain would have a strong showing in South
Carolina,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard also said Bush ran so far to the right to win South
Carolina that he will lose support among the GOP mainstream in
other parts of the country as the primary season continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a few years ago, Bush was considered to be a moderate
Republican,'' Gerard said. Now he's far-right. It seems to me he's
just telling people what they want to hear. That's one of the
reasons I don't support him.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix public opinion pollster Earl de Berge said he didn't
think the South Carolina defeat will have a strong effect on
McCain's prospects elsewhere. He cited the ``intensely
conservative'' character of the GOP in South Carolina and the
strong role played there by the Religious Right, which came out
strong for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is always: Does it deter other people from voting,
will it make them think that they've lost and there is no point in
going forward,'' de Berge said. ``I don't see that coming out of
this. I think the troops will rally.''
</P>
<P>
   State Senate President Brenda Burns said McCain should not be
discouraged by Saturday's result.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you consider that so much support has turned toward John,
I expect he will have a strong showing here and that it will be a
great launching pad for him for March 7,'' said Burns, citing the
date of this year's Super Tuesday cluster of primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush was the clear front-runner from the beginning, and John
was barely a recognizable name around the country,'' she said.
``Now, there is virtually no one who hasn't heard of him, and he is
generating a tremendous amount of support.''
</P>
<P>
   Molera said he expects Bush's surge will continue, in part
because of negative Republican reaction to the McCain campaign's
efforts to appeal to Democratic and Independent voters. Democrats
and Independents played a major role in McCain's double-digit
victory in New Hampshire on Feb. 1 and helped McCain in South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans are angry that McCain is using Democrats to try to
win Republican primaries,'' Molera said. ``I think they'll say,
`Wait a minute. We need a real Republican candidate to have a clear
choice against Gore.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gerard called McCain's campaign good for the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's really exciting,'' she said, noting that until
recently it appeared inevitable that Bush would emerge from the
crowded primary field to carry the GOP standard in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone should ever be anointed,'' Gerard said.
``A few months ago, nobody thought McCain had much of a chance. But
now it's just Bush and MCain, and you don't hear those other names
any more.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 2330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
