<DOCNO> NYT20000219.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2611 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-AHEAD-AZR &LR;      02-19 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AHEAD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN FOCUSES ON MICHIGAN VOTE; VICTORY IN ARIZONA APPEARS
ASSURED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER AND KRIS MAYES  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ After spending most of his money in the New
Hampshire and South Carolina primaries, John McCain moves into the
relatively uncharted waters of Michigan, where George W. Bush has
an organizational armada lying in wait.
</P>
<P>
   But regardless of what happens in Michigan, McCain's candidacy
has a life raft in the Arizona primary on Tuesday, the same day as
Michigan's.
</P>
<P>
   Because polls indicate McCain has a commanding lead in his home
state, he is concentrating instead on the Midwestern state.
</P>
<P>
   He was to fly to Michigan on Saturday night for a rally in
Dearborn after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   McCain will hold rallies and town hall meetings all over
Michigan, and he won't come to Arizona until Monday night. He will
remain in Phoenix for Tuesday's voting.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan may not be as conservative as South Carolina, and that
could help McCain because the newly re-established front-runner,
George W. Bush, has staked out the party's right wing. McCain
surged in the polls in Michigan after he beat Bush in New Hampshire
on Feb. 1, creating the prospect of a tight race, maybe the closest
one yet.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain will have to overcome a huge organizational
disadvantage by relying more than ever on his staples: positive
media coverage and lots of personal campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Bush won the endorsements last year of Michigan Gov. John
Engler, five of the six Republicans in the Michigan congressional
delegation (Steve Forbes won the other), and the lion's share of
the state GOP legislators.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the task before McCain was evident in a visit last
year to Michigan: Not a single member of Congress or the state
Legislature was in his traveling party. During his travels, McCain
sat in the back of a sports utility vehicle with a couple of
advisers and some ham-and-cheese sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has since picked up a smattering of official GOP support,
and his poll numbers surged after New Hampshire, apparently because
Michigan voters believed he had a serious chance. It remains to be
seen whether McCain's South Carolina loss on Saturday will dampen
that enthusiasm for his candidacy in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're up right now, so depending upon what happens after
today, we start in a very good position in Michigan'' because of
the success in New Hampshire, McCain campaign manager Rick Davis
told ``The Arizona Republic'' Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   With only three days between primaries, McCain won't have the
luxury of being able to hold scores of town meetings as he did in
New Hampshire. Voters in that state got to know him intimately, and
his small-town political style worked well.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Davis sees a positive side to the shortness of time
before the next round.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is that Bush doesn't have the time to put down the
kind of negative campaigning in Michigan that he has been
performing here (in South Carolina) for the past 18 days,'' Davis
said.
</P>
<P>
   But if McCain stumbles in Michigan, he may be in danger of
stalling out just before the crucial California primary on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   A loss in Michigan would likely mean ``he is going to lose some
of the power in the argument that he can bring new people into the
party, that he can rebuild the Reagan coalition,'' said Sherry
Bebitch Jeffe, a political scientist at Claremont University in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be an awful lot of establishment Republicans in
California who will be breathing a little easier.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final days of the South Carolina primary, Bush motivated
Republicans to go to the polls by claiming that Independent and
Democratic supporters of McCain were trying to infiltrate the GOP
election.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush camp has also made that argument in Michigan, which
allows crossover votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be useful to Bush in that he can then go into Michigan
and make the same pitch: Don't surrender the Republican Party,''
Bebitch Jeffe said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the chief architects of Bush's triumph in South Carolina
predicted that it will only strengthen the campaign's second line
of defense in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to boost him in Michigan. For that matter, it's
going to boost him in Arizona,'' former South Carolina Gov. Carroll
Campbell said. ``I think you are going to now see McCain diminish
as a competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   For McCain, the only certain victory on the horizon is back
home, where the only question about Arizona's primary is the margin
of a McCain victory.
</P>
<P>
   In an ``Arizona Republic'' poll released Friday, McCain led by
23 percentage points. Unlike South Carolina and Michigan, Arizona's
primary is closed to crossover voters. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-00 2337EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
