<DOCNO> NYT20000219.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-19 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-R-SC-REPUBS-1STLD-WRI     02-19 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SC-REPUBS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGE
</HEADLINE>
 
(REPEATING for all needing)  
 BUSH CLAIMS VICTORY IN SOUTH CAROLINA AS McCAIN VOWS TO CONTINUE(UPDATES thruout) 
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT1-5 and NYT26 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Gov. George W. Bush surged to victory in the
South Carolina primary Saturday, reclaiming his spot as the
unmistakable front-runner for the Republican presidential
nomination. But Sen. John McCain vowed to persevere, warning that
if Bush was nominated, the Republicans would lose in November.
</P>
<P>
   Riding a record primary turnout, Bush rallied Republicans across
the state, overwhelming McCain's drive to attract independents and
Democrats like those who helped the senator in his stunning victory
in New Hampshire on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   But in a surprisingly combative concession speech here Saturday
night, McCain showed no sign of yielding as the race quickly turns
to contests in Michigan and Arizona on Tuesday. In a clear stab at
Bush and what he called a ``negative message of fear,'' McCain
declared that he would offer ``a choice between a record of reform
and an empty slogan of reform, a choice between experience and
pretense.''
</P>
<P>
   In his victory speech in Columbia about an hour later, Bush
looked right past the man who had threatened to unhinge his
campaign in New Hampshire nearly three weeks ago and set his sights
on Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Carolina has spoken _ and tonight there are only 263
days more to the end of Clinton-Gore,'' he declared. ``My reform
agenda stands in stark contrast to the current administration.''
</P>
<P>
   His only mention of McCain came near the close of his speech,
when he thanked him for a tough fight and lumped him with Alan
Keyes, the former State Department official who also ran.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to commend two tough competitors, Senator John McCain
and Ambassador Alan Keyes,'' he said. ``I want to thank their
supporters for their hard work in fighting for a cause in which
they believe.''
</P>
<P>
   With 85 percent of election districts reporting at 10:30 p.m.
Saturday, Bush had drawn 253,772 votes (54 percent); McCain had
194,728 (41 percent); and Keyes, 22,255 (5 percent). Bush's support
was wide and deep; he captured the majority of nearly every
demographic group. Most significant, the reformer mantle that he
appropriated from McCain after the senator's stunning triumph in
New Hampshire seems to have paid off. Voters told pollsters
Saturday that they liked Bush's reform message and they suggested
that McCain was too much of an outsider.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had staked his prospects on the expectation that
independents and Democrats would flood to the polls and support him
overwhelmingly. Officials estimated that that the turnout was
indeed huge, more than double the 276,000 who voted in the primary
here four years ago. And independents and Democrats did turn out in
larger numbers than in 1996, and they largely backed McCain. Still,
their numbers were not significant enough to carry McCain even
close to Bush, who locked up loyal Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The results were particularly welcomed by Bush because before
New Hampshire he was as much as 20 percentage points ahead of
McCain in polls here; for weeks, the race was neck and neck, with
the senator even outpacing Bush in some surveys. In his speech
Saturday night, McCain looked upbeat, but spoke the words of a
politician unwilling to yield. He even suggested Bush's advertising
barrage was out of bounds. ``I am going to keep fighting clean,''
he said. ``I am going to keep fighting fair.'' McCain's advisers
were even more blunt. They asserted that Bush's hardline
conservative message in South Carolina would put off voters in the
upcoming contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ralph Reed and Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell ought to be
congratulated,'' said John Weaver, McCain's political director.
``He ran the kind of campaign he needed to win in South Carolina.
But that's not the kind of campaign you need to win the nomination
_ and certainly not the general election.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a telling concession, Rep. Lindsey Graham, McCain's
most prominent supporter in this state, lamented how poorly the
senator had performed among Republicans. ``Our base just fell
apart,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By winning comfortably here, Bush is better positioned in
Michigan and Arizona, the senator's home state. McCain now faces
enormous pressure to show that his win in New Hampshire was not an
anomaly. But the voting here was particularly distressing for
McCain because South Carolina was one of the few remaining states
where independents and Democrats could vote in the primary. Now,
most of the voting is in states where only Republicans can
participate; and in many of them Bush has the backing of the
governors. Though he limped out of New Hampshire, Bush engineered a
comeback here by displaying a scrappy determination to work for the
nomination that was never apparent in the earlier contests.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Throughout last year, Bush swamped his rivals in the polls _
effortlessly it seemed _ and forced most of them to quit the race.
Had McCain won South Carolina, that could may have given him an
important lift that could have led some Bush backers to begin to
defect.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bush's strong showing came at a price: He overwhelmed McCain
by pouring more than $3 million in an advertising blitz into this
state, and in so doing continued to deplete what had been a flush
treasury. McCain's threat also forced Bush to abandon his
long-promised posture of never stooping to attack commercials. And,
in appealing to conservatives in this state on issues ranging from
abortion to whether the Confederate flag should fly over the state
Capitol, Bush took a sharp turn to the right.
</P>
<P>
   He abandoned his strategy of hewing to the middle of the road, a
move that McCain's advisers were quick to note Saturday night could
haunt the governor in a general election.
</P>
<P>
   But it seemed clear that the barrage of commercials worked to
Bush's advantage. Of the voters who were interviewed Saturday by
Voter News Service, a consortium of television networks and the
Associated Press, about a third said they waited until the last
week or so to decide who to vote for, and most of them backed Bush.
Voters were more likely to say that McCain had unfairly attacked
Bush than they were to say that Bush was the one attacking McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In a heartening finding for Bush as the voting moves to a more
varied electorate, Bush won the majority of support of nearly every
demographic group, including men, women, rich and poor, young and
old. Even veterans _ whom McCain had targeted in an all-out turnout
drive _ split their vote between McCain and Bush. More than a third
of voters said they considered themselves members of the religious
right, and more than two-thirds of those voters backed Bush. If
religious conservatives were removed from the mix, McCain would
barely have won.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that Bush's drumbeat of reform and
leadership, as well his emphasis on moral values, meant a lot when
voters decided who to support. Although Bush and McCain were viewed
as reformers, Bush was seen by voters as more of one. Voters were
not convinced that McCain has been true to his word on the issue of
campaign finance, a subject Bush hammered McCain on in his
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half the voters said McCain says one thing but does
another on campaign finance _ and they voted overwhelmingly for
Bush. Asked what issue played the greatest role in their decision,
voters said it was moral values, and they mostly backed Bush. Among
those who cited Social Security and Medicare, McCain was more
popular. But the issue of tax cuts was low on the list of voters'
priorities, even though Bush made it a centerpiece of his campaign.
Although Bush succeeded in being portrayed as a reformer, McCain
was viewed as a man who stands up for his beliefs. That is the
character trait that voters said they cared most about, and more
than have of those voters backed McCain. Even so, voters said they
considered Bush more of a leader _ and a more potent rival against
the Democrats in November.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, Bush's chief strategist, attributed the results
Saturday to a return to the roots of 1994 gubernatorial campaign,
when Bush talked about reforms he favored _ and spoke in specific
terms. He also said voters were impressed with a tougher, more
assertive Bush. ``Both of these guys are going to come out of here
with roughly equivalent positives and negatives, and yet Bush is
going to come out of here with a substantial win,'' Rove said.
``And I think it's because people looked at him and saw how he
handled adversity, saw how he passed through this test, and liked
what they saw.'' He added, ``People wanted to see, if you care
about something, are you somebody who is going to fight for it?''
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-eight percent of voters in the primary were white, more
than half were men and more than four in 10 were over the age of
60. Nearly half said they had college degrees; three in 10 served
in the military. Blacks were virtually nonexistent in the voting,
even though in general elections in 1996 and 1998 they made up a
quarter of the vote. The voters here are more conservative than
most; nearly a quarter described themselves as very conservative,
and another four in 10 called themselves somewhat conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Bush's aides said his father, former President Bush,
was so nervous about the voting that he called them several times
to find out the latest intelligence. Rove said he alerted Gov. Bush
about the encouraging exit polls Saturday afternoon and then called
the candidate's father to brief him. The former president, Rove
said, uttered the word ``relieved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
