<SLUG> BC-WIN20-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TOPS MCCAIN IN S.C.; WIN HALTS SENATOR'S MOMENTUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES AND JEFF BARKER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ With the help of religious conservatives, Texas
Gov. George W. Bush regained his political footing, brushing back
John McCain's challenge on Saturday with a 13-point victory in the
South Carolina GOP presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's decisive victory, which followed McCain's upset win in
New Hampshire on Feb. 1, didn't settle the outcome of the race by
any stretch, but it halted McCain's momentum heading into Tuesday's
Arizona and Michigan primaries.
</P>
<P>
   McCain pumped his fist and told cheering supporters at a North
Charleston convention center that he would fight on and that ``you
don't have to win every skirmish'' to win the Republican
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But while his demeanor was upbeat, McCain's words _ indirectly
cutting at Bush _ suggested a belief that the Texan won by running
a dirty campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Without attaching Bush's name to his harshest accusations,
McCain variously sought to link his rival to ``the negative message
of fear'' and ``an empty slogan of reform.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to take the low road to the highest office in
the land,'' McCain said. ``I want the presidency in the best way,
not the worst way.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who has said his foreign-policy credentials and war
record make him the best qualified candidate, said the race
amounted to ``a choice between experience and pretense,'' adding
that ``I'm a real reformer . . . I don't just say it _ I live it.''
</P>
<P>
   The tone of McCain's speech stunned Bush's aides, who accused
McCain of demonstrating a ``lack of graciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable,'' said Karl Rove, Bush's campaign manager.
``The tone, the lack of graciousness. I think we saw the real
McCain tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who suffered an overwhelming defeat to McCain in New
Hampshire, badly needed to re-establish his credentials as the
front-runner with a victory in the Palmetto state.
</P>
<P>
   He did so by defeating McCain by 11 points, 53 percent to 42
percent. Alan Keyes received 5 percent. More than 600,000 people
voted, twice the number who have ever participated in the South
Carolina primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ignited a record turnout, a huge outpouring of Republicans
from all across the political spectrum,'' Bush told a packed
ballroom of supporters. ``Tonight is the beginning of the end of
the Clinton-Gore era.''
</P>
<P>
   Fully a third of GOP voters who went to the polls Saturday
called themselves part of the Religious Right, and Bush won
two-thirds of their votes. Bush also drew strong support from
another core GOP group, abortion-rights foes, who made up 60
percent of the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, one of the key elements of the McCain strategy
failed him. The Arizona senator split the veterans' vote down the
middle with Bush. McCain had been banking on a much stronger
showing in that group.
</P>
<P>
   Bush took a majority in virtually every demographic group, with
McCain getting an edge only among those who described themselves as
liberals, low-income or over 75 years old. Democrats were eligible
to vote, but not as many showed up to vote for McCain as the
Arizonan had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though we fell a little short tonight, our crusade grows
stronger,'' McCain said in his speech.
</P>
<P>
   When the results came in, McCain called Bush to congratulate him
in a phone call that lasted less than a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides were also elated and relieved at the outcome,
thankful that the midcourse correction made by their candidate paid
off.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign manager attributed the South Carolina win in
part to the ability to make quick changes to counter McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talked about it endlessly, used the word reform endlessly,
and I think that was a big, big part of it,'' Rove said. ``The
second part of it was Bush saying, `I'm not going to allow myself
to be defined.' We didn't allow him to define us here (on Social
Security).''
</P>
<P>
   The candidate also ran ads responding to claims by McCain that
Bush would spend nothing to shore up Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``People looked at him and saw how he handled adversity. They
saw how he passed through this test and liked what they saw,'' Rove
said. ``I think they saw somebody who was willing to set the record
straight with regard to what he was proposing and what he was
advocating and willing to defend it.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain campaign manager Rick Davis said in an interview that
Bush's negative ads prevented South Carolina from seeing the real
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what they (South Carolina voters) got to see was the
negative campaign that George Bush ran. They had to cut through all
this smoke that Bush put out, and that was what obfuscated the view
of John McCain,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's team claimed that part of their victory could be
pinned on McCain's decision to go on the attack after weeks of
invoking the Republican party's 11th Commandment against negative
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was telling (that) John McCain . . . said
something like, `When your enemy hits you, you hit him back even
harder to make them know there will be a price to be paid,' '' Rove
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the people of South Carolina, Republicans or
Americans in general, like this attitude that you treat your
political opponents or competitors as enemies. We've had seven
years of the politics of personal destruction where, if you oppose
somebody, they are your enemy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
